<SLUG> BC-LOST-SHEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST SHEEP ON THE LAM IN THE CITY GETS A BREAK
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On most mornings, Sgt. Joseph T. Kersting brings the
tools of his trade to patrol the streets of East Harlem: a
plexiglass shield, an electronic stun gun, a life preserver, a rope
and a heavy-duty fire extinguisher.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, that rope got a workout: a sheep was loose, dashing
through traffic on Franklin D. Roosevelt Drive in Manhattan in a
mad spectacle that drew police officers, an agent of the American
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, and some
commuters in hot pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how the animal made its way onto the highway. One
theory is that it escaped from a slaughterhouse at 126th Street and
Amsterdam Avenue, then journeyed crosstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were pretty shocked,'' the sergeant said, acknowledging
that he himself was stunned when he saw the sheep trotting down
Second Avenue near East 120th Street. ``It's not that common to see
a sheep running down the FDR.''
</P>
<P>
   With their emergency lights flashing but no sirens, they chased
the young sheep down Second Avenue. ``A couple of civilians tried
to help us and no one could stop the sheep,'' the sergeant said.
</P>
<P>
   At East 96th Street, they were joined by the ASPCA agent, Tina
Salaks, who had been sitting in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The sheep ran up the exit ramp from the northbound lanes of the
FDR Drive, heading south toward Carl Schurz Park, then entered the
tunnel under Gracie Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant; his partner, Officer Larry Lopez; and Salaks _
aided by a commuter _ were able to trap the sheep in the southbound
lanes of the tunnel. He was bundled into the back of a patrol car
and taken to the ASPCA on East 92nd. After a thorough checkup by
ASPCA veterinarians, the 49-pound sheep was soon happily munching
sweet hay and grain. The sheep, named Franklin for the highway
where he made good his escape, will most likely live out his years
at Green Chimneys, a sanctuary for abused animals in upstate New
York, said Valerie Bedziner, a spokeswoman for the ASPCA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
