<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-JEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO COURTS NEW YORK'S JEWISH VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days before the Salute to Israel Parade, Rep.
Rick Lazio, the Republican candidate for Senate, met with Jewish
community leaders Friday, seeking support from a constituency that
traditionally favors Democrats but which might swing toward either
candidate in November.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong meeting with about 25 leaders at an office
building in Midtown Manhattan, Lazio said he explained his
positions on a number of concerns among Jewish leaders, including
support for moving the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem to
recognize the city that Israel claims as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after the meeting, Lazio said he had also told the
gathering that he could not take a position on whether Jonathan
Pollard, convicted of spying for Israel, should be granted
clemency, because Lazio said he lacked access to government
information in the case. He did say he would support a presidential
review of the case.
</P>
<P>
   On another topic, Lazio said he told the meeting that he would
accept an endorsement from the Independence Party, even though its
presidential candidate might be Pat Buchanan, who has been
criticized by Hillary Rodham Clinton and others for remarks they
consider anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lazio and Clinton, the Democratic candidate for Senate,
plan to march in the Salute to Israel Parade on Fifth Avenue in
Manhattan on Sunday. New York's Jewish voters may prove to be a key
constituency in the Senate election.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Democratic candidates in New York can count on support
from Jewish voters. But Lazio's predecessor in the Senate race,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, enjoys strong backing in the Jewish
community. And Clinton has angered Jewish leaders with her support
for an independent Palestinian state and by her visit last year to
the West Bank, where Yasser Arafat's wife, Suha, made remarks
implicating Israel in the poisoning of Arab women and children.
</P>
<P>
   On some issues, Lazio said he stated positions similar to those
of Clinton. For instance, she too has called for moving the U.S.
Ebassy, which would bolster Israel's claim to Jerusalem, control of
which is claimed by Arabs and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's support for moving the embassy is qualified: she
supports legislation that would allow the administration to delay
the move if it determines a delay would help the Mideast peace
process. Lazio said he believed the sovereignty of Israel is
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for America to demonstrate to Israelis and to
the world that we stand four-square behind Israel and the
sovereignty of Israel,'' he said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not stated a position on clemency for Pollard, the
American convicted of passing secrets to Israel. Pollard is serving
a life sentence, which Jewish groups and an increasing number of
politicians call too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Friday she would ``work on'' forming an opinion
before the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said, ``I haven't had the kind of secured briefing that
people need to make that kind of judgment'' on whether Pollard
should be freed. But he called on the next president, within six
months of taking office, to open a comprehensive review of the case
to determine whether clemency is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he faced several questions about his possible
association with the Independence Party, the New York State
affiliate of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he told those gathered that he found Buchanan a
``divisive force in American politics'' but that he would still
accept an endorsement from the party, even if Buchanan's name was
on the ballot with his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be making very clear that I accept the votes of the
Independence Party voters but I do not accept any support from Pat
Buchanan,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Honlein, executive director of the Conference of
Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations, who attended the meeting,
which was organized by George Klein, a founder of the Republican
Jewish Coalition, said Lazio's stance on Buchanan might cause
trouble with Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Friday she would never appear on a ballot with
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his record of anti-Semitic comments, his record of
intolerant and prejudicial remarks are ones that I don't want to be
associated with,'' she said. Some present at the meeting with Lazio
said they would probably support him. ``He's like Al D'Amato, but
without the passion,'' said one participant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
