</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS PLAY THEIR BEST AGAINST   THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Yankees have mastered their sport three
of the last four years, and truth be told, the two-time defending
World Series champions get bored with the regular season. A series
in Detroit is like homework for them. What they love are the big
tests, which is why they can flunk a pop quiz against the Oakland
Athletics and then come back and stifle the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's human nature to rise to challenges, David Cone said
before Orlando Hernandez hushed the Atlanta bats Friday night in a
5-2 victory capped by another save by Mariano Rivera, the star of
last year's four-game Series sweep of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee drove in all but one of the Yankees runs with an
early three-run homer and a late double; Ledee has four runs batted
in in each of his last two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees understand what big games are all about, know the
difference between those and mundane May contests. After playing
inconsistently for two months, they will be filled with adrenaline
in the days ahead: Roger Clemens faces Atlanta's Greg Maddux
Saturday, in the first duel of pitchers with a combined nine Cy
Young awards.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing a three-game series here Sunday against the best
team this season so far, the Yankees will play the Montreal Expos,
the Mets, the Boston Red Sox and the Chicago White Sox at Yankee
Stadium, then the White Sox and the Red Sox on the road. Seven
straight series against teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Vizquel, the Cleveland shortstop, said recently that the
Yankees always played their best baseball against the best teams,
like ``they have something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (5-4) had something to prove. He had not won since
April 23, had missed his last start with a strained muscle in his
back, and yet El Duque pitched against the Braves the way he did
last October, when he shut them down in the first game of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a cap so new that he has not had time to curl the bill
to his liking, Hernandez got ahead in the count, threw mostly
fastballs the first time through the batting order and used his
slider with more effectiveness the next time around, always keeping
the Braves hitters off balance. He allowed four hits, one walk and
one run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez had something to prove. Manager Joe Torre made a
point of chatting with the first baseman hours before the game; it
was an attempt to soothe Martinez, who is on a pace to drive in 83
runs, woeful production for an American League first baseman in
this era.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez frets when he is not hitting home runs, but Torre
reminded Martinez that he drove the ball to center and left-center
when he was at his best.
</P>
<P>
   There was one out when Martinez batted in the fourth inning, and
with the count at 3 and 2, Kevin Millwood looked in for a sign from
catcher Javy Lopez. Fastball inside, Lopez signaled, but Millwood
did not want to throw that. Curveball inside, Lopez signaled. No,
Millwood indicated.
</P>
<P>
   As Lopez gave another sign, Martinez stepped out, tired of
waiting, then stepped back in, and when Millwood finally agreed
with Lopez and threw a fastball high and outside, Martinez smashed
it against the center-field fence, a double. Driving the ball
through the middle is what Martinez does best.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada reached a full count, as well, then ignored a
changeup that was just a fraction high for ball four. Ledee was
next and with two runners on base, Millwood did not want to dawdle;
he wanted to pump a fastball past Ledee for strike one.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee hammered this fastball, however, lifting it high toward
right field, where Brian Jordan slowly retreated, looking up at and
reaching for the wall with his gloved left hand until he bumped
into it. Jordan could go no further.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the ball landed in the seats, Clay Bellinger and then
Derek Jeter each threw up both hands in the Yankees dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, who would lose his job if the Yankees traded for a
slugger today, rounded the bases and smiled a bit as teammates
congratulated him, but it was not until he returned to left field
for the bottom half of the fourth inning that he appeared to really
relax.
</P>
<P>
   Warming up before the Braves batted, Ledee played catch with the
relief pitcher Jason Grimsley, and when Grimsley began firing his
nasty sinker and slider, Ledee laughed and waved a finger across
his throat _ cut that out, please.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball was fun again for Ledee, who has something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   But all the Yankees seemed more intent, more focused, facing
three weeks of big games, big challenges.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
