A3492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ILLEGAL-FUNDING-NYT &LR;      06-03 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLEGAL-FUNDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MAN PLEADS GUILTY TO ILLEGAL CAMPAIGN DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A New Jersey political donor with mysterious
sources of income and connections that reached into the White House
and both political parties pleaded guilty in federal court in
Friday to charges of illegally channeling $53,700 into the 1996
campaign of Sen. Robert Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   The donor, David Chang, 57, of Cresskill, N.J., pleaded guilty
to five misdemeanor election-law violations by making contributions
to the campaign that exceeded individual limits, by making illegal
corporate donations and by making contributions using other
people's names.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, who was raised in South Korea and served on the
Torricelli campaign's finance committee, also pleaded guilty to one
felony count of obstructing justice by trying to persuade a
potential witness to lie to a grand jury investigating accusations
of campaign finance violations in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before Judge Alfred M. Wolin four days before Chang
was to go on trial on election-law, tax, perjury and other charges
that could have sent him to prison for decades, Chang, as a
condition of his plea, also agreed to cooperate with the Justice
Department's investigation of campaign violations.
</P>
<P>
   Chang could be sentenced to 15 years in prison and fined up to
$250,000 under federal sentencing guidelines, but prosecutors said
he might be sentenced to as little as two years if he provides
``substantial cooperation,'' as outlined in his plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea came one day after a Korean-born businessman,
Cha-Kuek Koo, also pleaded guilty in federal court in Newark to
election-law violations by making illegal contributions to the
Torricelli campaign and by aiding Chang in making secret
contributions in the name of other people.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, a Democrat, has not been accused of any wrongdoing.
While he has called Chang a friend, the senator has insisted that
he was unaware of the improper contributions to his campaign, which
have since been donated to charities. Among 25 people accused of
election-law abuses by the Justice Department's Campaign Financing
Task Force, Chang and five others from New Jersey have admitted
wrongdoing, but none of them have implicated the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, whose fund-raising skill led to his appointment as
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, raised
$9.2 million to defeat Rep. Richard Zimmer in the 1996 Senate race.
The senator did not comment Friday on Chang's plea.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe David Lowell, a lawyer for Torricelli, said in a statement
that the Justice Department ``has confirmed that neither the
senator nor anyone in the campaign are the focus of any
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang made no statement after entering his plea. He remains
under house arrest, pending a bail hearing on Monday. His lawyer,
David Schertler, told The Associated Press that he would not
comment on what other information Chang might provide the task
force.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, who was born in Beijing and raised in South Korea where
his family moved when he was a boy, reportedly attended the
University of London, worked in the oil business in the Middle
East, came to New York in the early 1980s and has become a
naturalized American citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Although he operates commodities trading and export businesses
in Bergen County, they have never posted a profit, according to
Justice Department investigators, and Chang's only sources of
income have been wire transfers from unknown sources in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chang lives in a $1.25 million home, drives a Rolls-Royce,
has run up huge business debts and gambling losses, and has given
nearly $300,000 to U.S. election campaigns since 1993 _ $240,000 to
Democrats and about $50,000 to Republicans, according to
investigators and election records.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the nation's most prolific campaign donors, Chang
reportedly has had dinner at the White House, private discussions
with President Clinton, flown on Air Force One and personal
references from former President George Bush. He also has a history
of prior campaign violations, including illegal contributions in
1992 to a California representative, Jay Kim, who later pleaded
guilty to accepting $133,000 in donations from Korean corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Federal laws prohibit political donations by corporations and
individuals amounting to more than $2,000 to a candidate during an
election cycle. They also bar secret reimbursements to so-called
``straw donors'' _ a way of hiding political contributions by the
person making the reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chang and Koo admitted making such contributions. Chang, in
his plea, acknowledged that he had reimbursed Berek Paul Don, a
former Bergen County Republican leader, and Don's former law
partner, Carmine Alampi, for $11,000 they had contributed to
Torricelli's campaign in their own names. Don and Alampi pleaded
guilty last year to related charges.
</P>
<P>
   Chang admitted that, as a member of Torricelli's campaign
committee, he had collected $21,000 from donors and had illegally
reimbursed them with money from one of his corporations, Bright &AMP;
Bright, based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   Chang said he also used $1,700 from the same corporation to pay
for flights for the Torricelli campaign _ an allegation
Torricelli's aides have denied, saying that Bright &AMP; Bright was
reimbursed for all flights it paid for. Chang also admitted that he
gave Koo $20,000 to reimburse other donors.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors agreed to drop other charges in the latest of
several indictments, they noted in court papers that they
anticipated filing additional charges against Chang ``with respect
to payments made to a certain former government employee.'' They
declined to provide details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
