<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FLORIO-ADBOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: TAKEN FROM THE HEADLINES
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This 30-second commercial, titled ``Best,'' was released
Thursday by former Gov. Jim Florio in his bid for the Democratic
Senate nomination against Jon Corzine. The commercial is running on
television stations in New York City and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER _ The Campaign Group.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN _ At the sound of a whip crack, the commercial
opens with grainy, colorless, slow-motion videotape of Corzine in
an impromptu news conference with several microphones thrust before
him. He is holding his left hand up, palm out toward the camera, in
a way that makes him look uneasy and defensive. Headlines flash
onscreen, obscuring his face: ``Your prying eyes,'' ``Corzine
lawyer put detectives on Florio.'' The nameplates of The New York
Times, The Star-Ledger and The Philadelphia Inquirer are shown
against an outline of New Jersey and the words, ``Reject Jon
Corzine.'' An editorial from The Record, in Hackensack, is quoted
from beneath the headline, ``Buying an election.'' The ad cuts back
to the tape of Corzine, now above a giant label, ``$35 million,''
and the appeal ``Show Jon Corzine New Jersey is not for sale.''
Finally, the newspaper logos are shown beneath The Inquirer's
editorial headline, ``Democrats, vote Florio,'' and a quotation:
``Jim Florio is the better choice.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT _ Narrator: ``Jon Corzine's campaign has sunk to a
new low, using private detectives to spy on his opponent. Come on,
Corzine. And that's why, from The Times and Star-Ledger in North
Jersey, to The Inquirer in the South, newspapers are urging voters
to reject Jon Corzine. The Record: `Make no mistake about it,
Corzine is trying to buy his way into the Senate.' Tuesday, show
Jon Corzine New Jersey is not for sale. For Democrats, Jim Florio
is the better choice for Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY _ The commercial accurately quotes from the newspaper
articles and editorials it cites.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD _ Florio, trailing in the polls and outspent by more
than 15 to 1, has done his best in the last week to make Corzine's
record-shattering spending the overriding issue in their Senate
contest.
</P>
<P>
   News accounts that have appeared in the past few days recounting
Corzine's heavy-handed use of private investigators to explore
Florio's background have been a boon to the Florio campaign, as
have been endorsements by the largest newspapers circulating in New
Jersey. This commercial wastes no time in exploiting such favorable
publicity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
