<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CONFERENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER STATE GOVERNORS AGREE TO SEEK ILLEGAL
IMMIGRATION  SOLUTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The governors of the border states of Mexico and
the United States agreed Friday to look for long-term solutions to
illegal immigration problems while promoting immediate efforts to
halt border killings.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration issue rose to the top of the agenda of the 18th
annual Border Governors Conference after a recent spate of violent
incidents at the border, especially in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be challenges to our good neighbor
policy,'' said Arizona Gov. Jane Hull. ``The rush of undocumented
workers crossing in the dark shadows is not a new problem, but one
that is escalating to a crisis level. Tensions and emotions are
running high, and I am concerned for the health and safety of those
on both sides of the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 455 people have died since the beginning of Operation
Gatekeeper, a 5-year-old program that increases the number of
Border Patrol agents along the southern California border. Migrant
rights advocates say the program has forced immigrants to take more
dangerous routes through deserts and mountains to avoid the patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican governors used Friday's closing ceremonies _ and a
large audience of Spanish news media _ as an opportunity to
pressure the U.S. government to make its policies more friendly to
Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no secret that some immigration policies of the U.S.
government has hurt Mexican brothers, and will continue to hurt
efforts for peace and cooperation,'' said Gov. Alejandro Gonzalez
Alcocer, governor of the state of Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   Added into the joint declaration signed at Friday's closing
ceremonies was a committement for three levels of government _
local, state and federal _ to work to improve coordination and stop
the ``unfortunate incidents'' taking place along the border.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the participants agreed the solutions lie with the
two countries' federal governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to take constructive steps, by setting up
programs to educate people who cross the border about the laws they
have to follow,'' said Gov. Gray Davis, who hosted the two-day
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Davis praised President Clinton for including $2 million in his
budget to help implement some of the projects agreed to at the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull, a Republican who has endorsed Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, said she has been frustrated with the administration and the
lack of movement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply concerned that private citizens will take the law
into their own hands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made only a brief appearance Friday, choosing to skip the
closing session and press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor stayed largely out of the limelight,
attending the opening ceremonies, at which governors did not speak,
and a 90 minute work session which was closed to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the meetings as he left to fly back to Austin, Bush
said ``We talked about friendship and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Davis, described as cordial in their interaction by
several who saw the closed door sessions, did stop together in the
rotunda of the Capitol to have their picture taken with students
from Golden View Elementary School in San Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   While the discussion on immigration was the focus of many of the
closing speeches, the joint declaration included a number of
recomendations on topics from the environment to educations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the notable provisions include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Expanding the H-2A temporary agricultural workers program so
that migrant workers can help meet America's labor needs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Strengthening the trade relationship by modernizing the ports
of entry and implementing parts of the North American Free Trade
Agreement that allow for easier commerce and transportation across
the border.
</P>
<P>
   -- Working together to fight natural disasters that effect the
region, including forest fires, floods and drought.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pushing cooperation of the state agricultural agencies to
improve plant and animal health and food safety. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
