<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LODUCA WILLING TO LEND A GLOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's not that Los Angeles Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson doesn't think Chad Kreuter can handle the load of
being an everyday catcher. He'd just rather not force it upon him,
which is why Paul LoDuca was recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque and
inserted into the starting lineup against the Angels on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Regular starter Todd Hundley was placed on the 15-day disabled
list with a strained oblique muscle on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter _ in the midst of an eight-game hitting streak, during
which he's batting .346 _ is expected to resume his role of being
Chan Ho Park's personal catcher today and will continue to split
time with LoDuca thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul did a good job for us last year and he's doing a good job
of catching (in Albuquerque),'' Johnson said. ``I could have gone
with Kreuter (Friday), but he'd rather play (Saturday) because
(Saturday) is Chan Ho and he's kind of been catching him and
catching him well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in LoDuca. Rather than put that on
Chad right now _ I think he can handle it _ it's not something we
need to do right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter LoDuca, who made his presence felt right away when he
gunned down Darin Erstad on an attempted steal in the first inning
Friday and hit a three-run homer in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca, who was batting .299 with 22 RBI in 41 games for
Albuquerque, played 36 games for the Dodgers last season, batting
.232 with three homers and 11 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca was focused on winning the backup catcher's job in spring
training this season and was disappointed when Kreuter was
selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough. Of course I was upset,'' LoDuca said while
accepting a barrage of greetings from his old/new teammates. ``I'm
human. Of course I was upset when something like that happens, but
I took it in stride. Todd and Chad are doing great and I'm not
trying to fill their shoes, I'm just trying to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Relief, please: Currently 14th among active major- league
pitchers with 144 saves, Jeff Shaw was temporarily removed from the
closer's spot after blowing the save in Tuesday's 10-5 loss to the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw is suffering from ``dead arm,'' a condition he said does
not result from overuse and can limit a pitcher numerous times
throughout the course of a season.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, fourth in the National League with 11 saves, does not
expect to have an MRI on his ailing right shoulder. He will undergo
a strength test when the Dodgers return June 7 from a three-game
road trip to play the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw did not throw on Wednesday or Thursday but did pitch a
bullpen session Friday. The biggest challenge for him is keeping up
with a new weightlifting regimen to rebuild the strength in his
shoulder. He normally does not lift weights during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Team physician Dr. Frank Jobe) asked if I would take four or
five days off and that's OK,'' Shaw said. ``Then he asked about two
weeks and I said no. I have a very high pain tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he will use Mike Fetters, Antonio Osuna and Terry
Adams, by committee, to close out games until Shaw returns to form.
He will not use Osuna and Fetters in back-to-back games because of
their history of arm problems.
</P>
<P>
   __ Closing in: Eric Karros' second-inning homer Friday gave him
15 this year and moved him to within two of tying the all-time
franchise record for a career, held by Ron Cey (228).
</P>
<P>
   __ Poking fun: Dodgers players were watching the movie
``Slapshot'' in the clubhouse before Friday's game. During the part
of the movie in which minor-league hockey players go into the
stands to fight with fans, F.P. Santangelo remarked, ``Hey, that's
the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo was of course referring to the already-infamous brawl
between the Dodgers and Chicago Cubs fans on May 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
