<HEADER>
A3500 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SFCHR     06-03 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FAA THREATENS TO SHUT ALASKA AIRLINES MAINTENANCE FACILITIES  &HT;     By HENRY K. LEE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ In a move that could ground the airline within
months, federal regulators threatened Friday to strip Alaska
Airlines of the authority to maintain its fleet because mechanics
in Seattle and Oakland failed to properly document repairs.
</P>
<P>
   A special inspection of the airline after January's deadly crash
of Flight 261 found that Alaska employees released planes into
service without the required signatures, improperly delayed repairs
and often could not rely on maintenance records to confirm whether
work was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a paperwork problem,'' Nick Lacey, director of
flight standards for the Federal Aviation Administration, said at a
Washington news briefing. ``Aviation accidents come as a series of
small errors and the inability to detect small errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska must respond to the FAA's findings within seven days. If
the response is unsatisfactory, the agency, pending an appeal by
the airline within 30 days, could shut down Alaska's maintenance
facilities in Oakland and Seattle, effectively grounding five or
six planes a month out of a fleet of 89.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at Alaska's headquarters in Seattle,
airline chairman and chief executive John F. Kelly said the carrier
has already addressed many of the FAA's concerns. Kelly said he
intends to restore public confidence in the nation's 10th-largest
airline, which until recently has enjoyed a reputation for safety
and quality service.
</P>
<P>
   While it was difficult to be ``100 percent in every little
detail,'' Kelly said, ``We've always said we're never perfect, but
we're never going to stop trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said the company's cooperation, skilled personnel and
record of completing repairs _ even if they were not properly
documented _ persuaded the FAA not to immediately shut down the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   However, a maintenance shutdown could devastate the airline,
which has suffered a spate of problems this year, the most serious
of which was the crash of Flight 261 off the Southern California
coast on Jan. 31, which killed all 88 people aboard. The ill-fated
flight was bound for San Francisco from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has grounded other airlines, but the proposed action
would be the first time the agency has sanctioned an airline for
problems associated with major maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The two-week FAA probe in April, known as a ``white glove''
audit, came in response to the fatal crash but renewed concerns
about Alaska's maintenance practices first raised in 1998, when a
federal grand jury in San Francisco began investigating allegations
that airline mechanics in Oakland falsified repair records.
</P>
<P>
   Although the FAA's review of 79 of Alaska's planes found that
all the needed repairs had been completed and that passenger safety
did not appear to be an issue, federal inspectors said they
uncovered 150 instances in which aircraft maintenance was completed
but not properly documented.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey blamed Alaska supervisors for the ``serious'' breakdowns
in documentation and quality assurance, saying, ``We think the root
cause is really management effectiveness and, I think, a certain
amount of sloppiness.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Kelly said: ``Any record-keeping that has not been
done to perfection could be characterized with many different kinds
of adjectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wagstaff of Anchorage, an aviation attorney who has been
closely following the Alaska Airlines situation, said it remains to
be seen how the FAA proposal will affect the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paperwork was out of order, but the maintenance was done _
it's not good, it's not correct,'' said Wagstaff. ``I think Alaska
has taken some very serious hits as far as public relations is
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the way in which Alaska oversees and performs what
is known as ``heavy maintenance,'' or extensive structural
inspections. The carrier's 35 MD-80s undergo heavy maintenance at
Hangar 6 off Earhart Road at Oakland International Airport, while
its 54 Boeing 737s are primarily inspected in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said Alaska would be prohibited from contracting out its
heavy maintenance work. ``It would be illogical for them to
out-source to other companies'' if the airline could not follow its
own procedures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Francois, president of Aircraft Mechanics Fraternal
Association Local 37 in Oakland, declined to comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA probe of Alaska comes as the federal grand jury in San
Francisco continues to investigate allegations that airline
mechanics falsified repair records in Oakland. Since 1998, FBI
agents have seized records for 11 MD-80 planes. The probe grew &LR; 
 &LR; expanded last month to include records for the plane that crashed
January 31.
</P>
<P>
   The crash remains under investigation by the National
Transportation Safety Board, the FBI and the Department of
Transportation's inspector general. The probe has focused on the
possible failure of the jackscrew, a key part of the plane's tail
stabilizer system.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FAA audit has recast the spotlight on Alaska's
Oakland maintenance facility, where the grand jury investigation
began in 1998 as a result of allegations by John Liotine, 37, of
Pittsburg, Calif., a former lead mechanic and Francois' predecessor
who is on paid administrative leave.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has proposed fining Alaska $44,000 and recommended that
three supervisors in Oakland have their mechanic's licenses
revoked, saying the airline operated two planes in an
``unairworthy'' manner. Alaska has denied any wrongdoing and is
challenging the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   At the airline's hangar in Seattle, 64 Alaska mechanics signed a
letter in March accusing maintenance manager Robert Falla of
pressuring them to take shortcuts on repairs. The airline has
denied that any unsafe planes were put into service.
</P>
<P>
   Falla has since been reassigned to a nonsupervisory job and has
been replaced by Kurt Kinder, a former line maintenance supervisor,
Alaska said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Flight 261 crash, Alaska has been plagued by a
series of other problems on flights this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the airline said it plans to fire two pilots for
continuing a flight in March from Portland, Ore., to San Jose with
oxygen masks deployed after they failed to pressurize the Boeing
737 jet. Also in march, a passenger tried to wrestle the controls
from a pilot during a flight from Mexico to San Francisco. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
