<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-EMISSIONS-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOR VEHICLES CHIEF QUITS AMID ACCUSATIONS ON EMISSIONS TESTS
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ The commissioner of the Connecticut State
Motor Vehicles Department, Jose O. Salinas, resigned on Thursday
amid a growing clamor over accusations of fraud in the state's
emissions testing program, which is run by an outside contractor,
Envirotest Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gov. John Rowland, Salinas said he planned to
resign effective June 29. But Rowland, who has been described by
aides as increasingly frustrated with the fraud accusations, asked
that the resignation take effect Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Seymour, a spokesman for the Department of Motor Vehicles,
said the resignation was unrelated to the accusations. Salinas, a
lawyer, decided to return to a post in the attorney general's
office, Seymour said, because ``his first real love was the
practice of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The emissions testing case began in March with the arrests of
three inspectors here who were charged with falsifying emissions
test results in exchange for payments from car owners of $50 to
$60.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth inspector was arrested in April, in Darien, after
officials from Envirotest told state police investigators that he
had sold a passing sticker for $80. The emissions test, required
every two years, costs $20; cars that fail must be repaired and
tested again.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, said he
had received reports of widespread corruption in the emissions
testing program and wrote to Salinas urging a broad investigation
into allegations of bribery, fraud and theft.
</P>
<P>
   That same week, Rowland ordered an independent audit of
Envirotest, which has run the emissions inspection program since
1994 under a 10-year, $25 million contract from the state. The
company, based in East Granby, operates 25 testing stations and
inspects 1.5 million cars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas has not been accused of any wrongdoing and is not a
target of the audit or the state police investigation. But some
people, including Rowland, have questioned whether the Motor
Vehicles Department exercised proper contract oversight. ``The
governor obviously is very concerned about the integrity of the
emissions testing program,'' said his spokesman, Dean Pagani.
Pagani said the governor had instructed the auditors to look at
both the private contractor and the motor vehicle agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is seriously asking whether the management at DMV has done
a sufficient job in overseeing that contract,'' Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud allegations relate to various automobile tests that
are performed by more than 300 employees of Envirotest around the
state, including exhaust-system emission tests and gas-cap tests
that check fuel vapor emissions. The arrested inspectors have been
accused of conducting multiple emissions tests on cars that they
know will pass to generate an extra pass report and sticker for a
car that would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Sanders, a spokeswoman for Envirotest, said the company
had cooperated fully with investigators and was vigilant about
fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
