<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BORDER-CENSUS-$ADV04-     06-03 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CENSUS-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS TALLY BODES WELL FOR BORDER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 4) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Elena Garcia was off driving her school bus
when a census worker came to count her family in Valle Escondido, a
flood-prone colonia near the banks of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was glad when the census worker returned the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we were counted,'' said Garcia, who explained that
her household of five was missed in the 1990 Census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man was real nice,'' she said of the census taker. ``He
read the questions twice and repeated them in Spanish if I had
trouble understanding. And he explained why he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   The census worker who twice visited the Garcia home is among the
1,500 enumerators and hundreds of Spanish-speaking helpers hired to
hand-deliver census forms to hard-to-find residents on the border.
The workers are conducting an unprecedented, door-to-door effort to
count thousands of residents living in substandard border
subdivisions, known as colonias, and other remote communities, many
without addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the first time, we'll have a really good sense of
how many colonias there are. We'll have a good sense of how many
people live there, and what their needs are,'' said Frank Newton,
spokesman for the U.S. Census Bureau's regional office in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The count is significant, because population numbers are used to
determine such things as federal money for public projects and
congressional and legislative districts, which translate into
political power.
</P>
<P>
   The Garcia family, who were nearly flooded out of their
wood-frame home during torrential rains in 1990 and 1994, hope this
census will translate into federal money for much-needed services
in their rural neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need here, the most important thing is the sewage
(system),'' said Garcia, who has snapshots of a neighborhood pig
who took refuge on her front porch during the flood. ``In 1990, the
water came up almost to the windows and we have septic tanks and it
was all coming out. It was ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Census officials estimate that they missed an estimated half
million Texans during the count 10 years ago, and many of those
were Hispanics like the Garcias who live in the 1,800 colonias from
Brownsville to El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   This year, to get a more accurate count, many of the census
workers hired were residents of colonias. A major key, Newton said,
was a $90,000 grant to Texas A&AMP;M's University Center for Housing
and Urban Development, which operates community centers in eight
colonias from Brownsville to El Paso. The center trains residents
to become community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in the four-county Brownsville-McAllen region, the
housing center trained nearly 1,000 colonia residents. Thirty of
those were colonia leaders, known by the Spanish term promotoras,
and all were hired to help census workers interview residents in
the area's 120 colonias.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it wasn't just a government official coming in and talking
to the people; it was one of their next-door neighbors,'' Newton
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau also worked hard to literally put many
colonias on the map, using both promotoras and aerial photographs
to help map unnamed subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, Newton said the census was slightly under 99
percent complete in the El Paso, Laredo and McAllen districts _
among the best in the nation. Early reports from officials along
the Texas border say the census strategy appears to be working.
They note that an accurate count reflecting the tremendous
population growth on the border could have significant political
and financial implications for the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, this census should open eyes especially in South
Texas, where we have had 25 percent to 30 percent growth in certain
counties. I expect the political power in those areas will have
grown considerably,'' predicts State Sen. Eliot Shapleigh, a
Democrat from El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good count to us means power and money,'' he said. ``We
learned our lesson last census that El Paso County would lose
millions of dollars with a bad count.''
</P>
<P>
   A multimedia awareness campaign was launched before the count
that included signs, bilingual television and radio commercials
featuring pitches from elected officials, the Catholic bishop and
other community leaders, said El Paso census official Jesse Acosta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached this like a political campaign,'' said Acosta, a
partnership specialist who has been doing advance work for the
census since 1998. ``The county kicked in $50,000 to help promote
the census. We went out and littered the entire county with signs _
we had signs under every rock. People couldn't miss the census, so
it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are some Rio Grande Valley residents who, although
they agree with the approach taken this year, wonder if the count
is as comprehensive as claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be more wishful thinking than reality,'' said Ray
Gill, an attorney for the Texas Civil Rights Project in San Juan.
``But there has been marked success over the last census (in 1990),
which woefully undercounted folks in the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill and others say many colonia residents are still afraid
that, despite repeated public assurances by census officials, their
immigration status will be reported to Immigration and
Naturalization Service agents. It did not help that Border Patrol
agents were raiding homes in colonias as the census began.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a lot of people who have had experiences
themselves or their families with government agencies, whether it's
the INS, the Border Patrol or state or local police, that have been
extremely negative,'' Gill said. ``People are very distrustful and
very fearful of having representatives of the U.S. government in
their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, census officials were predicting that this year's
count will encompass 99 percent of Texans before the official end
July 7, the most thorough count ever. And this time, colonia
residents won't be left out, Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the work we've done, all the preliminary things to
identify in a legal and geographic sense, where the colonias are,
and working with residents,'' Newton said, ``I've got to believe
we're going to do a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
