<HEADER>
A3510 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKESID-LADN-(SLA     06-03 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKESID-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS PLAN TO GO TO FINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ It began with Damon Stoudamire, a guy so little
that when he tucks in his jersey, the number on his back disappears
into his trunks like some minute T-baller.
</P>
<P>
   It continued with Steve Smith, the former Hawks star turned
Portland Trail Blazers role player, making like an unstoppable
force.
</P>
<P>
   It kept rolling with Rasheed Wallace, pumping fists and jumpers,
and off the bench with Bonzi Wells, and with a seeming army to
bring Shaquille O'Neal crashing down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was over, when the Blazers had pushed the Los
Angeles Lakers into a dangerous final Game 7 with a 103-93 victory
on Friday night, the Blazers were a team brimming with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The team the Lakers thought they had left for dead here last
weekend, now returns to Los Angeles very much alive, very much an
unwanted guest and very much believing it is headed for the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they knew even being up 3-1, this series was far from
over,'' said the Blazers' Scottie Pippen. ``We gave them a couple
of games and they really didn't have anything to hang their hats
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Only six teams in NBA history have ever come back from a 3-1
deficit, but with the Western Conference Finals now tied up 3-3,
the Blazers are convinced they are about to join the historic list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying since Game 1, there is no momentum,'' said
Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy. ``There is no homecourt advantage.
There's only one game at a time and you have to bring it. This
(last) one is going to finalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire did his Mighty Mite thing, sparking the Blazers
early. The Portland point guard had struggled through most of the
series. He played only 15 minutes in Portland's win in Los Angeles
in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Lakers jumped out to a quick lead, Stoudamire
became a near one-man gang. Guarded by Kobe Bryant, and no doubt
aware Bryant was struggling with a sprained right foot, Stoudamire
consistently drove to the hoop. He keyed a 12-2 spurt by the
Blazers that gave them the lead for good, scoring four of the
baskets and passing off for another. He finished with 14 points,
seven rebounds and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damon played a great game tonight,'' Dunleavy said. ``He did a
terrific job. Damon did all the things we wanted him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers act like a team clueless about stopping Smith, who's
been successful posting up Bryant and others throughout the series.
On Friday night, Smith scored a Portland-high 26 points _ nine
coming in the third quarter when the Blazers fought off the Lakers'
only real charge _ scoring from all over the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the heart and soul of our team, along with
Rasheed,'' Pippen said. ``We have a 6-8 guy who can handle the ball
and go to the basket. We have great confidence in each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells is no longer able to slip by as the Blazers' stealth
weapon. He stepped up big in the final quarter to keep the Lakers
in their place. Wells scored 14 of his 20 points in the fourth
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonzi can come in and put up some big-time numbers,'' Dunleavy
said. ``I wouldn't have him there as a go-to guy if he couldn't do
it. He's explosive. He gets on a roll and you ride him, and we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has led the Blazers throughout the postseason, and
Friday he again left the Lakers looking like they had no one to
guard him. Wallace scored 18 points on 6 of 10 field goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3511 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-03 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE USUAL SUSPECTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The winning team wangled glorious performances
out of its peripheral players, got a gritty performance from a
guard who wasn't expected to play much, attacked the boards as if
jet-propelled and did all this and more with a sneer worthy of one
of Jack Nicholson's characters.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, one of the Portland Trail Blazers stole the Los
Angeles Lakers' game plan Friday.
</P>
<P>
   We're sure the culprit would have been caught, had every
Portland player been detained long enough to be fingerprinted after
Game 6 of the Western Conference finals. The trouble was, the Rose
Garden security corps was otherwise occupied, harnessing the
revelers luxuriating in the Trail Blazers' 103-93 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Though we'll never know who absconded with the blueprint that
was supposed to work to the Lakers' advantage, the culprits who
forced a deciding Game 7 Sunday at the Staples Center were easy
enough to identify. After all, there were 20,340 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith assuredly was one of Portland's perpetrators. He
made six of nine shots in the first half and surpassed his series
scoring average of 16.8 points before the game was 36 minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Damon Stoudamire. That rascal looked to be the
ringleader.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10 point guard figured he'd be lucky to log the 15
minutes he had played in Game 5. The Trail Blazers had employed a
bigger lineup to beat the Lakers on Tuesday and it made perfect
sense for them to stick with what had brought them renewed life.
</P>
<P>
   Only Stoudamire saw the flaw in the logic. He came out and
attacked Lakers guard Kobe Bryant, who was hampered by a foot
injury that left his playing status up in the air. He held up all
right on offense _ he finished with a game-high 33 points _ but
Bryant looked as helpless as a hitchhiker on the side of the road
every time Stoudamire drove on him.
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire finished the first half with 12 points, eight more
than his 7-foot-3 teammate Arvydas Sabonis. He also had one blocked
shot in that span, which was one more than the Lakers' seven
footer, Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-point lead the Trail Blazers fashioned in the first half
was a wall the Lakers couldn't quite scale. Every time they got
close to the top, they seemed to lose their footing.
</P>
<P>
   Blame Bonzi Wells. He was another unlikely culprit in the Trail
Blazers' grand theft. He came off the bench to contribute 20 points
_ 12 more than his series average _ and four rebounds, three on the
offensive end. He was leaping as if his life depended on it.
</P>
<P>
   You talk about matchup problems; there wasn't a Laker on this
night who could match Wells' will.
</P>
<P>
   With Smith and Stoudamire and Wells stealing the spotlight,
Scottie Pippen repaired to the shadows. The Trail Blazers put 47
points on the scoreboard and built a lead that stretched to as many
as 15 points before Pippen took his first shot.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen made his presence felt in other ways, collecting five
defensive rebounds, four assists and two blocked shots. Rasheed
Wallace and Pippen, the Trail Blazers' leading scorers, were a
combined 7 for 16 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal took one more shot than the both of them on his way to a
very, very quiet 17 points. His postgame mumblings were louder.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers' game plan from the beginning has been to
contain the Lakers' stars, O'Neal and Bryant, and make the Lakers'
other players beat them. On this night nobody but Brian Shaw (12
points in 15 minutes) answered the call.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice didn't; he missed more shots than he made on his way
to 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper couldn't; he had zero assists to go along with seven
points.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry wouldn't; he tried just four shots and made zero
3-pointers en route to six points.
</P>
<P>
   So the series will go the distance. At the beginning, the
so-called experts were predicting as much.
</P>
<P>
   This series, remember, is the NBA's answer to CBS's
``Survivor,'' with the two teams with the best regular-season
records thrown together to see who will emerge as the last one
standing in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Survival is all that matters. Style points don't count. If on
Sunday the Lakers can avoid losing three games in a row for the
first time all season, nobody will care if it took them seven games
to dispose of the Trail Blazers or five.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are 48 minutes from glory. That's what they need to
focus on, not the 96 minutes they've squandered this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
