<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGDOD-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT-HITTING ANGELS HAVE THEIR WAY WITH DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Interleague play hasn't been kind to the
Anaheim Angels, so they brought in a couple of ringers from the
National League Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Kent Bottenfield and second baseman Adam Kennedy's N.L.
experience might not be the answer to reversing the Angels' woes
against the National League. But the 29th worst interleague team
will take any advantage available.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield's pitching wasn't spectacular and Kennedy probably
isn't ready to declare his slump over but their contributions were
enough to lift the Angels past the Los Angeles Dodgers 12-5 before
a sellout crowd of 43,619 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Since interleague play was created three years ago, the Angels
were just 20-30 overall and 5-9 against their Southern California
neighbors. Only the Tampa Bay Devil Rays (9-25) have suffered more
interleague grief than the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield and Kennedy were acquired from the St. Louis
Cardinals in the Jim Edmonds trade on March 23. But Bottenfield has
yet to match his 1999 breakout year in St. Louis and Kennedy has
cooled considerably following a quick start.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, who went 18-7 in an All-Star year with the
Cardinals, took a 3-5 record and a 5.00 ERA into his 12th start for
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old right-hander labored at times over five innings.
He threw just 61 of 107 pitches for strikes, walked three and
allowed seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (4-5) made key pitches when needed, outside of
allowing a solo homer to Eric Karros and a three-run shot by Paul
LoDuca.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a Cal State Northridge product, was one of many heroes
in a lethal Angels offensive barrage. He helped end Darren
Dreifort's night with a three-run homer in the fourth and added an
RBI single in the sixth and a third base hit in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The homer broke an 0-for-10 tailspin for Kennedy, who had a
brief call-up to the big-league level with St. Louis last year.
Kennedy went 3 for 27 on the Angels' recent nine-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's average had sagged to .257, and after sitting down the
final two games of the trip, he was demoted to eighth in the
batting order.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just trying to get that feeling back and have
confidence at the plate,'' Kennedy said before Friday's game.
``Once that comes, I think I'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy wasn't the only Angel to escape the doldrums. Shortstop
Benji Gil doubled twice from the ninth spot, after he suffered an 0
for 24 spell that was snapped with a two-hit game on Wednesday at
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Every Angels starter but Mo Vaughn collected at least one hit
Friday, led by Garret Anderson (single, double, solo homer).
Anaheim scored in five of the first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (3-3) had his third shaky start in four outings since
his brilliant two-hit shutout of the Cardinals on May 12. The
Angels almost knocked him out in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The first six Anaheim hitters reached base safely. The only out
Dreifort could record in that span was thanks to his catcher,
LoDuca, who threw out Darin Erstad stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon's run-scoring single and a two-run single by Troy
Glaus gave Bottenfield an early 3-0 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had chances against Bottenfield, but one sloppy
base-running blunder killed a threat in the third when the deficit
was still manageable.
</P>
<P>
   After Alex Cora led off the third with a double, Todd
Hollandsworth reached on an infield single that was smothered by
Gil behind second base.
</P>
<P>
   Cora never hesitated coming despite what appeared to be a stop
sign from third-base coach Glenn Hoffman. Cora was easily thrown
out by Gil and the Dodgers didn't score in the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
