<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE DID ALL HE COULD DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ With Shaquille O'Neal off target, Phil Jackson
stumped for answers and the Los Angeles Lakers' cool melting away,
they laid Friday night's playoff game at the feet of Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   He responded as you'd expect from a young man with one good foot
and one bad.
</P>
<P>
   The good: Bryant took up the challenge like a hero in the
making, playing all 48 minutes, raining a game-high 24 shots and
scoring a game-high 33 points.
</P>
<P>
   The bad: It wasn't nearly enough for the Lakers, who got too
little from their healthy players, lost to the Portland Trail
Blazers 103-93 and now face an all-or-nothing Game 7 in the NBA
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   In their latest test, Bryant passed and the Lakers failed.
</P>
<P>
   It figured to be his night _ one way or the other _ from the
start. From before the start.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had sprained his right foot in the Lakers' loss at the
Staples Center on Tuesday. He'd sat out the Lakers' two practices
since then. He skipped Friday morning's shoot-around at the Rose
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers listed him as a ``probable'' starter but that didn't
diminish the drama. A gametime decision was promised.
</P>
<P>
   Would he play? Would he !ital!ever emerge from his long
treatment session in the trainer's room?
</P>
<P>
   He started. Deep down, everybody knew he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a blessing in disguise,'' Lakers forward Robert
Horry said. ``He won't be able to run around so much.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Horry supposed the irrepressible 21-year-old
might not feel he had to take the offense on his shoulders, as he
often does to the detriment of Jackson's team concept.
</P>
<P>
   So, sure enough, Kobe came out . . . firing.
</P>
<P>
   He knocked down a step-back 20-footer, was fouled by Scottie
Pippen and completed the three-point play the first time the Lakers
had the ball. He took the shots on the Lakers' first three
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of nervous about it at first. I had to test it,''
he said. ``This kind of game, you've got to push through it. If I
hurt it worse, I hurt it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I started playing, I didn't think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the foot seemed to rob Bryant of his drive to the basket. Or
maybe it was the Blazers. The Lakers were down by 11 before Ron
Harper drove to their first layup.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed by 10 at halftime. The difference was the scoring
by the backcourts. Portland guards Steve Smith, Damon Stoudamire
and Bonzi Wells had 30; Pippen, unbelievably, had shot only once.
L.A. guards Bryant, Ron Harper, Brian Shaw and Derek Fisher had
combined for 18; Kobe had 14 of those.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Neal had been held to 8. The Lakers can operate as
a two-man team but not one.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever was going on beneath that black sock and shoe on his
right foot, it seemed to hurt his defense more than his offense.
</P>
<P>
   You can choose your push-off foot when you have the ball. You
have to go both directions when you're guarding Stoudamire or
Smith. Sometimes you feel as if you have to go both ways at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Kobe played OK, but I wasn't pleased with his
defense,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers kept working their way inside. The Lakers couldn't
spell defense for long stretches, giving up eight scoring
possessions in a row to fall behind 26-15, never to recover.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was getting battered under the basket, had lost the range
from the free-throw line, and finished with 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice was held to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Before Brian Shaw threw in four straight 3-pointers as the
Lakers tried but failed to come back in the fourth quarter, the
guards' contribution was . . . Kobe's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of carrying your team _ but not far enough _
showed on Kobe's face. He was reduced to a pouting kid when Arvydas
Sabonis hammered him to the red-painted floor after he split a
double-teaming defense, and Bryant didn't get the foul call.
</P>
<P>
   The 33 points, including 6 of 9 3-pointers, were Bryant's
highest in 13 games, since he tried but failed to carry them in
their game 3 defeat in the Sacramento Kings series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we expect from him,'' Fisher said of the attempted
heroism, not the defeat. ``We knew if Kobe got there, he was going
to perform well. We just have to figure out a way to put together a
consistent performance.''
</P>
<P>
   One man, on one foot, wasn't enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
