<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-REDSOX-PHILLIES-BOS     06-03 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX LOSE IN EXTRA INNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-PHILLIES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ On their most recent tour through the National
League, the Red Sox must have found themselves asking, ``Haven't we
taken this vacation before?''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been hotter than they imagined (87 degrees at the
first pitch), quirkier than they remembered (a 19-minute light
delay), and longer than they wanted (3 hours 35 minutes). But when
all information was gathered at the end, the result was the same:
The Sox lost to an NL team.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies won it in 11 innings Friday night at Veterans
Stadium, 2-1. The game ended when John Wasdin couldn't get a
fastball by pinch hitter Alex Arias. Before pitching to Arias _ who
knocked a long single over a defense that was playing for a short
single _ Wasdin walked Brian Hunter and hit Desi Relaford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I was having some problems with my control,'' Wasdin
said. ``I thought my velocity was good and, with the heat, it was
easy to get loose.'' But as much as Wasdin struggled on this night,
the Sox have struggled with interleague play since it began in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   They were 6-12 against NL competition last season. They are
21-29 all time. They are 0-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams might say, the kids certainly competed. But their
competition didn't lead to anything significant off righthander
Robert Person in the first six innings, although it appeared from
the start that Person would have a long night. Literally and
figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed for 19 minutes in the top of the first
because all the stadium's lights were not turned on. So, before
they could be flicked on, all of them had to be turned off first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange things happen in baseball, huh?'' Sox starter Brian
Rose said of the delay. ``If it was going to affect anybody, it
would have affected Person. He had already pitched to a guy (Donnie
Sadler) when the game was stopped. It didn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply turning the lights on here takes seven minutes. When
Person finally began to work again, he wasn't sharp. He issued four
walks in the first three innings, including a surprising one to
Rose in the second. But it was the Phillies, not the Sox, who
scored the second-inning run. Brian Hunter, who came into the game
batting .171, doubled home Kevin Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   If any team would have trouble scoring, you would think it would
be this bunch, owners of the NL's worst record. The Phillies also
are missing Rico Brogna and Scott Rolen. But the Sox were able to
give no support to Rose, who left after pitching six innings of
four-hit, three-walk (two intentional) ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not too much to say,'' said a raspy-voiced Rose, who
has been sick (clubhouse virus) the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   The look and sound of the game changed in the eighth. Philly
fans, known for their famous intensity, were almost serene with
their team leading, 1-0. That was before Carl Everett connected
with a Wayne Gomes outside breaking ball and slammed it into the
visitors' bullpen in left field. It was Everett's 18th (he had 25
all of last year), and he has homered in four consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   After the shot, fans became increasingly restless with each
single. They taunted Gomes with chants of ``Gopher.'' The reliever
allowed three consecutive singles to Troy O'Leary, Jason Varitek,
and Wilton Veras. On the Veras single, which came with two outs,
third base coach Wendell Kim tried to get O'Leary home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they score that run, that could have been the ballgame,''
Gant said. ``It was one of those do-or-die plays. You can't think
about the ball being thrown too high or too low. That's one of
those plays where you just come up firing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gant did that, making a perfect throw to Mike Lieberthal, who
blocked the plate and tagged O'Leary out. If the Sox were awarded
runs for defensive brilliance, they would have had at least two in
the first. Doug Glanville led off with a drive to center. Everett
dived for the ball, retrieved it on a hop, and then quickly jumped
off the turf as if he had been scorched, and threw a strike to
Nomar Garciaparra at second. Glanville's foot slid off the bag, and
the Sox had a spectacular 8-6 put out. But on this night, they
weren't so fortunate at the plate. The Phillies weren't much
better, but they were one run better. Which is to say, one game
better. Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
