<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND PULLS EVEN IN SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Ever the patient ones, ever the
procrastinators, ever the NBA's drama queens, ever the shameless
teases, the Los Angeles Lakers sat perched and waiting to spring on
their first NBA Finals berth in nine years Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   And perched, they sat.
</P>
<P>
   And sat. And sat.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time they tried to spring, tried to replicate the
kind of late charges that put them in control of this series in the
first place, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 was lost, the Lakers' advance stalled once more, as they
fell 103-93 to the supercharged Portland Trail Blazers before a
raucous 20,340 at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, once up 3-1, have procrastinated themselves right
into a deciding Game 7 in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of disappointing, but we also realized it would be
hard toget three games up here,'' said Shaquille O'Neal. ``So we
just have to be ready on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal struggled through a sea of Blazer defenders and was held
to 17 points on 7-of-17 shooting _ a statistic he attributed to
uncalled Portland fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why I missed,'' he said. ``You all saw the
(bleeping) game.''
</P>
<P>
   That left Kobe Bryant to try to deliver the series
singlehandedly _ and with a single foot, no less _ and he came
through with a game-high 33 points, but the Lakers were otherwise
impotent. Especially on defense,as they allowed the Blazers to
shoot 50 percent, with five players in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, shaking off a the effects of a sore right foot, played
all 48 minutes and made 12 of 24 shots, including a torrent of four
3-pointers in a desperate fourth-quarter charge. But the game had
long been decided, the Lakers trailing from the first quarter on.
</P>
<P>
   So the Indiana Pacers have to wait two more days to discover the
identity of their Finals dance partner, and the Lakers and Blazers
will duel once more, Sunday at 4:30 p.m. at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we wanted,'' said Glen Rice, the Lakers' third
highest scorer with 12 points. ``But we know we have to win this
thing. That game is going to be a war. It's going to be a real
emotional game, a very rough game.''
</P>
<P>
   A brief charge at the start of the third quarter got the Lakers
within4 points, but they quickly faded again under a 9-2 Blazers
run. O'Neal made just 2 of 8 field-goal attempts in the quarter,
and the Lakers trailed by 8 points, 71-63, heading into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The series stayed true to form as the Blazers took control early
and took a 49-39 lead into halftime, riding a three-pronged attack
of Rasheed Wallace (11 points), Steve Smith and Damon Stoudamire
(12 each).
</P>
<P>
   But Stoudamire's inclusion in that group was one of many
oddities in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring was a zero-point effort from Pippen _ the
Blazers' most prolific scorer in their victories _ despite the fact
he was guarded by slow-footed Glen Rice, instead of Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Lakers emphasized the need to hammer Portland
inside with O'Neal, he scored just 8 points in the half, on 4-of-8
shooting. He also missed all six of his free throws _- in contrast
to his last trip here, when he went 9 for 9 in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Oddest of all was a 14-point half from Bryant to lead the
Lakers. Despite his sore foot, Bryant scored the Lakers' first two
points, later threw down a one-handed dunk and made 5 of 11 shots.
</P>
<P>
   He also had three steals in the half but otherwise seemed
limited on defense. Bryant was assigned to Stoudamire, and later
Smith, and both took advantage of his hobbled foot with drives to
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire, a bit player for most of the series, led the charge
for Portland. The Lakers led 9-6 in the first quarter before the
Stoudamire caught fire, scoring 8 points, with three layups, in a
14-2 run. The Lakers trailed 26-15 by the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Portland extended the lead to as much as 15 points in the second
quarter and shot 56.1 percent in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' shaky opening included eight turnovers in the first
half _ with two apiece by O'Neal and Bryant _ which Portland cashed
in for 12 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0021 </DOCNO>
