<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACERS-KNICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS CLOSE OUT KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A little more than three years ago, he told Pacers
president Donnie Walsh he could get his non-playoff team to the
Finals, and that is exactly what Larry Bird has done.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Reggie Miller had something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about me,'' said Bird. ``It's never been about me.
I'm just so happy for the older players. They're gonna play for the
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no ageism connected with the new Eastern Conference
champion Indiana Pacers, 93-80 conquerors of the New York Knicks in
Friday night's Game 6 at Madison Square Garden. You've got Sam
Perkins, who will be 39 in 11 days; Mark Jackson, 35; Miller, 34;
Derrick McKey and Rik Smits, 33; Dale Davis, 31; and even
36-year-old Chris Mullin, who did not play but who may yet have his
moment to shine before the season is over. They've been a-knockin'
on the door of the Finals since 1994, and now they have kicked the
door down with a clutch road effort many people doubted they would
see from the supposedly soft Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we could win one road game,'' said Bird. ``I wasn't
sayin' we could win two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of guys had a hand in this, but the Man of the Match was
the Human Matchstick himself. For, absent his sweet shooting, the
Pacers would be suiting up for Game 7 in Conseco Fieldhouse Sunday
afternoon. But, in this game, Miller was, well, Bird-esque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' said Bird in reference to Miller's 34-point effort
that included five 3-pointers, three of them in the first six
minutes of the final period, when the Pacers were putting enough
space between themselves and the increasingly frustrated Knicks to
ensure they could spend the final three minutes at the foul line
(28 for 31).
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just that Miller was making shots. It was what he was
making. He was making shots only the truly great make _ deep,
clutch, hump-busting jumpers normal people can only dream of.
``Last year, we were beaten in this series by Allan Houston and
Latrell Sprewell, who could literally create a shot any time they
wanted,'' said assistant coach Rick Carlisle. ``Over the summer,
Reggie studied his game and their game. He worked very hard to
create a new dimension for himself. Now he isn't restricted to just
beating you off screens. He can also beat you one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   For five games, people were wondering when Miller would explode.
Friday night, they found out. His major run started with a huge
hoop, a 3-pointer with 25.2 seconds left in the third quarter that
tied the game at 62 and enabled the Pacers, having just blown a
50-41 lead with 5-for-23 third-period shooting, to enter the fourth
period on the up-tick.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, a noble loser in this one (32 points), nailed a three
to start the fourth. But, following two Austin Croshere free
throws, Miller answered with a right-wing three to regain the lead
at 67-65. It was Miller again with a three at the clock that made
it 72-65 (``Probably the biggest shot of the game,'' said Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy), and it was Miller once more with a step-back
three out of his coach's playbook that made it 75-68. The man who
long ago proclaimed how much he loved being the enemy was now being
deliciously villainous.
</P>
<P>
   New York never mounted a response, and now it was Travis Best's
turn to torment the hosts. First the Springfield, Mass., lefthander
drilled a face-up jumper. Then he got real nasty, sinking a running
hook high off the glass. That made it 81-71 with 2:25 to go. You
should have seen the natives scurrying for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana had been the aggressor from the start, grabbing a 30-25
one-period lead with some exemplary ball movement. New York got
back into it in the third, when an opening 11-2 blast turned the
game around. But the most New York could squeeze ahead by was 3,
and each of the last two times they did so, Miller had something to
say about it.
</P>
<P>
   Long, long ago, in a far more innocent world, the Pacers won
three ABA titles. Outside that little fraternity, people yawned.
Wednesday, they will begin play for the real championship. ``They
have no idea what to expect,'' said Bird.
</P>
<P>
   But Bird does. That's why Donnie Walsh hired him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZERS-B     06-03 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-TRAIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS FORCE GAME 7
</HEADLINE>
 BLAZERS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ They came to the Rose Garden Friday night
bearing signs, balloons, hearty voices, boundless energy, and,
above all, an abiding faith in their Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   They were not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The little people and the big hitters _ how do Bill Gates, Tiger
Woods, and Steven Spielberg sound for starters? _ bore witness to
the continuing Kafkaesque story that has become the Western
Conference Finals. Down, 3-1, six days ago and on the precipice,
the resurgent Blazers took a 103-93 decision over the suddenly
submissive Lakers to even the series at 3.
</P>
<P>
   The conference champion will be determined Sunday night at the
Staples Center, where Portland already has won two games in this
series. As the victorious Blazers left the floor Friday night,
several waved their index fingers to the sky, signaling the job was
still not finished. That in itself is a remarkable gesture given
that Portland was all but cooked after losing twice at home last
weekend to fall into the aforementioned 3-1 hole.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're even again. The Blazers got 26 points from Steve
Smith, a ``Where did that come from?'' 20 from Bonzi Wells, and a
big, long game (season-high 45 minutes) from big, long Arvydas
Sabonis. Five Blazers were in double figures, none named Scottie
Pippen. He all but avoided offense and instead focused on
disrupting the Lakers in a 47-minute stint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed him to direct the team, distribute the ball and play
defense,'' Mike Dunleavy said of Pippen. ``He does a lot for us
when he's on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers got 33 points from a gimpy Kobe Bryant, who had not
practiced for two days due to a sore right foot. He still went
wire-to-wire and had six treys. Shaquille O'Neal also played all 48
minutes, but he managed only 17 points, a playoff low against
Portland. It was all Greek to the Big Aristotle Friday night; he
was 7 of 17 from the field and 3 of 10 from the line. No one else
stepped into the breach and the margin was somewhat misleading due
to a late flurry of 3-pointers by the Lakers. Los Angeles was 12 of
19 from international waters.
</P>
<P>
   Former Celtic Rick Fox was also in it at the end, but only in a
provacative sense. He jawed with Dunleavy _ ``I was asking him for
good restaurants in LA,'' the Blazers' coach joked _ and also
baited Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   LA coach Phil Jackson said he liked Fox's energy and
aggressiveness. ``That's why he's out there,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the posturing already has begun, it would not be
necessary at this stage had not Portland staged a fairly dramatic
about-face. The Blazers became the 14th team to tie a series after
being down 3-1. Six teams have won series after being in a 3-1
hole, the last being the 1997 Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a dogfight,'' Dunleavy said. ``We wanted this
opportunity and now we have it. There's no fear factor on our
part.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers? ``They're not happy, that's for sure,'' Jackson
said. ``But they understand they only lost a battle. The war is not
over.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not. Portland made sure of that. The Blazers took an
11-point lead after one, getting a great jump-start from Damon
Stoudamire, who, in a twist, found himself guarded by Bryant. That
was due to concerns about Bryant's lateral quickness. He had been
guarding Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Portland was in Constitutional Mode:
preserve, protect, and defend. It didn't hurt that the Lakers were
brutal from the line, missing 14 of 27. Or that their bench was
invisible until the fourth quarter. Or that the usually hack-prone
Sabonis stayed out of foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made a few, anticipated bursts, but, each time, the
Blazers had the right response. LA got to within 4 early in the
third (51-47) after a Glen Rice 3-pointer. The Lakers missed a
chance to get closer and then Smith stole the ball from Rice and
went in for a layup. That kicked off a 9-2 Portland run that pushed
the lead back to 11. It was 10 at the break and 8 after three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Seven straight Laker points, capped by a pair of O'Neal free
throws, made it an 83-75 game with 5:31 left. But Pippen (9 points,
six rebounds) was fouled and made two and, after two LA misses,
Smith knocked down Portland's only trey of the night to make it
88-75.
</P>
<P>
   LA, despite knocking down eight treys in the fourth (tying a
playoff record), never got closer than 9 as Wells romped for 14 in
the fourth, bringing the Rose Garden faithful to their feet. They
can only hope it won't be for the last time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
