A3522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MAMBO-KING-NYT &LR;      06-03 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MAMBO-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A MAMBO KING BOWS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday June 3:
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra leader Tito Puente, who died Wednesday at the age
of 77, fronted a hot Latin jazz orchestra for more than half a
century and was broadly influential as a percussionist, composer
and arranger. Known in the Latino community as El Rey _ The King _
Puente is primarily viewed as a pillar of Latin music. But he was
also an American original _ and a crossover figure in the 1950s,
before the term was invented.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York at the height of the Jazz Age, he made it his
life's mission to form a revolutionary fusion of the Afro-Cuban
rhythms of Latin music with arrangements derived from traditional
jazz. As a friend said recently, ``he came out of nowhere,''
creating a music that was both danceable and intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   Puente, the son of Puerto Rican immigrants, was born in East
Harlem in 1923. After playing briefly with the noted singer and
percussionist Machito, he dropped out of school to start his own
group and remained a band leader until his death. He made more than
100 records and won five Grammys. He helped to begin the mambo
craze in the 1950s. The period featured other wildly popular Latin
bands and became the subject of ``The Mambo Kings Play Songs Of
Love,'' a celebrated novel by the Cuban-American writer Oscar
Hijuelos.
</P>
<P>
   Puente's music was clearly shaped by orchestras like those
commanded by Duke Ellington, Count Basie and Fletcher Henderson,
bands that used dance rhythms and jazz improvisations to enormous
effect. Jazz grew cerebral as the decades moved on, culminating in
the laid-back music of Miles Davis, which began in the ``Birth of
the Cool'' sessions at the start of the 1950's.
</P>
<P>
   But Puente continued to swing, with percussion-driven music that
was covered by younger musicians, including Carlos Santana. At an
age when many people have retired, El Rey was playing more than 200
gigs a year and was scheduled to perform in Manhattan on Wednesday,
when he entered the hospital for heart surgery. Tito Puente liked
to say of his beginnings in East Harlem that he was ``born in
rhythm.'' In half a century as percussionist in his bands, he spent
his life in rhythm as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
