<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLINTON-MOSCOW-N     06-03 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-MOSCOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLINTON'S SUMMIT WITH PUTIN IMPORTANT OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 3:
</P>
<P>
   Meetings between American presidents and their Russian
counterparts pack less drama than they used to. But they still
matter. Bill Clinton's meetings with Vladimir Putin, the first
since Putin became Russia's president, provide a timely opportunity
to discuss issues ranging from nuclear arms control to market
reforms and human rights. Clinton should use his public
appearances, including a radio call-in show and an address to the
Russian parliament, to hail Putin's steps toward reform and
criticize troubling signs of authoritarianism.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's leadership personality is still unfolding. The theme of
his presidency so far has been the reorganization of the central
government. That is a reasonable response to the catastrophic
breakdown of services over the past decade. But there are concerns
that Putin, who was a KGB officer in the Soviet era, means to
reassert Kremlin powers at the expense of Russia's nascent civil
liberties. Last month's raid on Media-MOST, a leading private media
company, was troubling in this regard. So is Moscow's continuing
military brutality in Chechnya and Putin's legislative drive to
override the power of elected regional governors.
</P>
<P>
   More encouraging are the economic goals reflected in his cabinet
appointments and proposals to reform the income tax code. Higher
oil prices and the consequences of earlier ruble devaluations have
spurred a modest economic revival in Russia. But this windfall must
now be sustained by a coherent set of government policies including
further simplifications of the tax code and improvements in
property and bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   No breakthroughs on nuclear arms cuts or missile defense are
expected this weekend. But in an interview with NBC News Putin
acknowledged that he, too, recognizes a potential threat from
small, unpredictable nuclear powers. He said he intended to propose
a joint defensive system to counter it. The details of Putin's
ideas have yet to be filled in, but they are likely to be quite
different from the national missile defense system currently being
tested by the Pentagon. Clinton should listen carefully to any new
Russian proposal. It could ease the path to an eventual agreement.
As for offensive warheads, both sides have strong reason to move
ahead with deep new cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's presidency is just beginning, while Clinton's is drawing
to a close. But the remaining seven and a half months during which
their terms overlap should not be wasted. Clinton has full
authority to negotiate on nuclear issues through next January. As
leader of the world's foremost democracy he also has the moral
authority, and obligation, to speak out in defense of human rights
and Russia's newly won freedoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
