<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS WIN BY TEARING DOWN SHAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Not long ago in this space, it was suggested
that, by virtue of two consecutive impressive wins here that gave
them a 3-1 lead in the Western Conference finals, the Los Angeles
Lakers were on the verge of winning the NBA championship,
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Lakers could still win the title.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``verge'' idea ... guess it depends on the definition
of verge.
</P>
<P>
   If verge also means ``plunging into the abyss with two straight
losses and looking so inept that national sports humiliation is
imminent,'' well, the word works.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't ... oops.
</P>
<P>
   But who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy and a small knot of his
black-clad warriors, nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Because nobody had ever heard of the Blazers' new defense
unveiled Friday night in Game 6 in the Rose Garden:
</P>
<P>
   Hijack-a-Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Blazers found a car with a trunk big enough to
stuff in Shaquille O'Neal. This morning he might well be bound,
gagged and secured in a barn on some filbert farm down the
Willamette Valley.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers don't cut him loose by Sunday's seventh game, it's
Indiana vs. Portland for the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Not a pretty thought, certainly, for a league seeking retrieval
of its luster, but at least the New York-vs.-Los Angeles conspiracy
theorists would have to retreat to another grassy knoll for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   In the Blazers' 103-93 triumph that was nearly wire-to-wire, the
Lakers behemoth scored just 17 points, missing 10 of 17 field goals
and seven of 10 free throws. On most occasions, O'Neal barely
touched the ball before a cavalcade of Blazers munchkins peeled him
down to a dermatology experiment.
</P>
<P>
   And since no other Laker stepped up until a too-late flurry in
the fourth quarter, they were left with the disturbing prospect of
having to win a final game at home Sunday against a team that has
no respect whatsoever for the alleged Staples Center homecourt
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won two there already,'' said Dunleavy. ``There is no
fear factor. We know we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The week's remarkable turnaround established that these Blazers
have shed the reputation built on six consecutive first-round
playoff exits, followed by last year's sweep out of the West finals
by San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 games this season against the team with the NBA's best
regular-season record, they are 5-5. Even a loss Sunday can't
change the fact they they have stared the monster in the eye and
didn't flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they knew, even up 3-1,'' said Scottie Pippen, ``that
this series was far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Lakers didn't know was O'Neal, a versatile fellow of
some thespian experience, could play the Invisible Man well before
the new film debuts. His total was the lowest in 14 career
playoffgames against the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of packing it in against Shaquille,'' said
Lakers coach Phil Jackson, who for one of the few times in his
recent career found himself thoroughly outcoached. ``We never could
really establish ourselves. They played extremely well inside.
O'Neal struggled all night. We struggled with offensive spacing,
but we had some good shots we just didn't make.''
</P>
<P>
   The big gentleman was a trifle irked with the mauling. Normally
his bullrushes to the hoop put center Arvydas Sabonis, the only
Blazer with serious gravity, in foul trouble before the national
anthem has faded from the building. But Sabonis didn't draw his
first personal until the third quarter, drawing a rousing hand from
the faithful when his belated first infraction was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Sabonis stayed out of foul trouble,'' O'Neal said,
mumbling over the duct tape during his captivity, ``is because they
weren't calling anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A rather pitiful whine from someone 330 pounds, particularly in
view of the fact that even when fouls were whistled, O'Neal
reverted to form and failed to capitalize, as did his teammates.
The Lakers missed 14 of 27 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the Lakers' domination of Game 4 here, this was not
the same team of big contributions from multiple players.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was forced to go with O'Neal and Kobe Bryant the entire
48 minutes, and results were negligible. Bryant, operating on a
sore foot sustained in Game 5 that earlier threatened to keep him
on the bench, scored 33 points, but the bulk came in a late binge
of treys that gained the Lakers little ground.
</P>
<P>
   As the triumph grew obvious near the end, the Lakers turned
cranky, slugging it out with hard fouls and harder words. The
sudden appearance of aggression foretold more hostile manners
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've noticed as the games went on that they start to turn
away from playing the game and start doing other types of
activities,'' Pippen said. ``Taking cheap shots and trying to start
altercations. I'm telling my guys to stay focused and to continue
to play hard and just try to walk away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   After having their best player hijacked, the Lakers' ill-temper
is understandable. For a night anyway, they lost not only the game
but the sport's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   While it's an embarrassing gaffe for one evening, failure to
fetch his gargantuan self by Sunday will become its own episode of
``Unsolved Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
