<HEADER>
A3529 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NULAKE-LADN-(SLAN     06-03 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NULAKE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND EVENS SERIES ON PROCRASTINATORS
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Ever the patient ones, ever the
procrastinators, ever the NBA's drama queens, ever the shameless
teases, the Los Angeles Lakers sat perched and waiting to spring on
their first NBA Finals berth in nine years Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   And perched. And sat.
</P>
<P>
   And sat. And sat.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time they tried to spring, tried to replicate the
kind of late charges that put them in control of this series in the
first place, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 was lost, the Lakers' advance stalled once more, as they
fell 103-93 to the supercharged Portland Trail Blazers before
20,340 at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, once up 3-1, have procrastinated themselves right
into a deciding Game 7 in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we wanted,'' said Glen Rice. ``But we know we
have to win this thing. That game is going to be a war. It's going
to be a real emotional game, a very rough game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not what anyone outside of the Rose City wanted. But having
no choice now, the Lakers are adjusting quickly to the idea of the
all-or-nothing finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone fantasizes and dreams about being in a Game 7
situation, to either win a championship or advance to the Finals,''
said Derek Fisher, ``and I think if we harp too much on the fact
that we should be there, we're going to lose on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, when the series started, people anticipated seven
games, so the way that it got there is totally amazing. But the
fact that there is a Game 7 on Sunday, the winner advances. To look
above that or beyond that or anything around that, we won't be
doing ourselves any favors.''
</P>
<P>
   They could hardly do themselves any worse than the hole they dug
the last few days, blowing chances to clinch the series both at
home and in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' victory marked the first time since Game 1 that
either team defended its home court successfully. The Lakers swept
two here last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of disappointing, but we also realized it would be
hard to get three games up here,'' said Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal struggled through a sea of Blazer defenders and was held
to a series-low 17 points on 7-of-17 shooting _ numbers he
attributed to uncalled Portland fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why I missed,'' he said. ``You all saw the
(bleeping) game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said coach Phil Jackson, ``I thought they played extremely well
on Shaquille.''
</P>
<P>
   That left Kobe Bryant to try to deliver the series
singlehandedly _ and with a single foot, no less _ and he came
through with a game-high 33 points. After shaking off a the effects
of a sore right foot, Bryant played all 48 minutes and made 12 of
24 shots, including a torrent of four 3-pointers in a desperate
fourth-quarter charge.
</P>
<P>
   But the game had long been decided, the Lakers trailing from the
first quarter on.
</P>
<P>
   They were shorthanded on offense and impotent on defense.
Portland shot 50 percent, had five players in double figures and
led continuously after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Game 7,'' coach Phil Jackson said, in summation. Was he
shocked? ``No. Are you? This is what we anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Indiana Pacers have to wait two more days to discover the
identity of their Finals dance partner, and the Lakers and Blazers
will duel once more, Sunday at 4:30 p.m. at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   A brief charge at the start of the third quarter got the Lakers
within four points, but they quickly faded again under a 9-2
Blazers run. O'Neal made just 2 of 8 field-goal attempts in the
quarter, and the Lakers trailed by eight points 71-63 heading into
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The series stayed true to form as the Blazers took control early
and took a 49-39 lead into halftime, riding a three-pronged attack
of Rasheed Wallace (11 points), Steve Smith and Damon Stoudamire
(12 each).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they dropped a little bit out of focus during the
course of the first half,'' Jackson said. ``But outside of some
mental mistakes _ Smith got a couple steals, questionable steals,
that brought them back in the ballgame and got the runouts that
were unavoidable _ but we obviously exposed ourselves offensively.
That created the defensive mismatch and a layup.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lakers emphasized the need to hammer Portland inside
with O'Neal, he scored just eight points in the half, on 4-of-8
shooting. He also missed all six of his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   It was the closing minutes of the game that gave Portland
something to think about, however. The Blazers objected to some
hard fouls, notably a flagrant by O'Neal on Pippen, and a few hits
by Rick Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started taking fouls and they put a little extra mustard
on those fouls,'' Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``I don't
think it was appreciated at our end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
