<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3530 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-03 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 MOYER GIVES M'S A NICE RETURN; MARTINEZ STAYS HOT
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jamie Moyer gave the Mariners a little taste of what
they'd missed.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez gave the M's a little more of what they've
reaped.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the veterans opened interleague play in impressive
style Friday night at Safeco Field, helping the Mariners to a 7-4
victory over the San Diego Padres, a win that enabled Seattle to
reclaim sole possession of first place in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, just off the disabled list, pitched five innings and got
the win. Martinez, apparently convinced May has at least 33 days in
it, had two more hits, including a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't put any expectations on myself,'' Moyer said. ``If
you put expectations on the evening, you're setting yourself up for
a letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no letdown. Moyer, pitching for the first time since
April 14, allowed two runs in five innings. The strained muscle in
his left shoulder that caused him to miss six weeks of competition
didn't seem to be a hindrance as he used his changeup and breaking
pitches to keep the Padres reasonably off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sharper than I thought he'd be,'' catcher Dan Wilson
said. ``He had good stuff and looked sharp, especially for having
all that time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer didn't come out and try to light up the night. He doesn't
have the fastball for it, so he stuck with his basic recipe _
breaking pitches and changeups _ and made it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really liked,'' pitching coach Bryan Price said, ``was
that for a guy who has been chomping at the bit to get going, he
pitched a real professional game. He didn't get over-zealous the
way pitchers can get when they're anxious to get out there. He just
stuck with his game plan and made good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had been hoping for six innings from Moyer. They
only got five, but after the left-hander served up a two-run homer
in the first inning, Moyer was close to the top of his game for his
remaining time on the mound. A hanging changeup to Phil Nevin
resulted in Nevin's 14th homer, but other than that, Moyer was in
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt decent,'' Moyer said. ``This gave me the basis of
something to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer allowed only two more hits and one walk in his remaining
four innings, and when he needed a nice defensive play to give him
a boost, he got it.
</P>
<P>
   A two-out double by Damien Jackson and a subsequent walk to Eric
Owens put the potential tying runs on base in the fifth. The next
Padres batter, Al Martin, came up with a hot smash toward first
base that was trouble. But first baseman John Olerud judged the
short hop correctly, plucked the ball out of the air on the first
hop and made the play at first, extinguishing the Padres for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer threw just 74 pitches, less than the 80-90 that manager
Lou Piniella would have considered perfect. But as usual, Moyer
gave his teammates a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, meanwhile, followed up on his American League-best
.441 average of May with two more hits, keeping his AL-best average
at .376. Martinez singled and scored a run in the third, then added
a two-run homer in the seventh, his team-best 16th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gar's homer was the big hit of the game,'' Wilson said. ``That
was what gave us the cushion we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer was the centerpiece of a three-run seventh inning that
gave Seattle a 7-2 lead before the Padres staged a late rally
against M's reliever Arthur Rhodes in the eighth. Kazuhiro Sasaki,
asked to bring home a win with a three-run lead in the ninth,
closed out the Padres on one hit for his eighth save.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Martinez homer was the big blow, the Mariners were
able to put together some of the ``little ball'' Piniella has said
the club needed all along.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have had more than their share of bunts backfire
this year. But in the second inning, the M's got more than they
could reasonably expect from a bunt. David Bell tried to advance
Olerud and Jay Buhner with a sacrifice try down the first-base
line. But when first baseman Ed Sprague threw the ball away,
Seattle got two quick runs to tie the game in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had a couple of nice contributions of his own to the
offense. He had a sacrifice fly in the third, good for run No. 4
and a 4-2 lead, then singled to load the bases in the seventh,
setting up Mark McLemore's bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to drive in a run in the second, too, and I'm
disappointed I didn't get it done,'' Wilson said. ``But we finally
got some runs. Gar's homer put us where we needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
