<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 10:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3571 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-ETHIOPIA-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-03 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM AN OLD-FASHIONED WAR, A VERY MODERN CALAMITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The war between Ethiopia and Eritrea is often
described as the most deadly in the world, fought on terrain of
little consequence while millions of people in two very poor
countries face starvation. This is all true.
</P>
<P>
   But the war _ which may finally be winding down after two years
_ is also something else, something that has become quite rare: A
war fought between the regular armies of two nations, in which both
sides generally follow the rules of war.
</P>
<P>
   It is an irony that while civilian deaths from the side effects
of war are so high, direct civilian casualties from combat are
quite low. And neither side is accused of gross violations of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in short, a very old-fashioned kind of war, the only
clearly defined conflict in the world right now between two nations
(though India and Pakistan exchange artillery fire and the armies
of Rwanda and Uganda have skirmished recently in a third country,
Congo).
</P>
<P>
   Even the fighting itself has a tinge of sepia to it: Armies
lined up in trenches battle in close quarters, in contrast to the
remote-control technological wars that rich nations favor these
days.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest in any way that this is a quaint or
``good'' war. But as Chris Bowers, a spokesman for the
International Committee of the Red Cross, put it: ``It certainly
has a different character, and that is important to note.''
</P>
<P>
   In Africa since the Cold War ended, there has been a great deal
of conflict but hardly any between nations. This pattern dates to
the 1960s, when Africans gained their independence from Europe and
the newly-formed Organization of African Unity forbade African
nations from fighting each other directly. With few exceptions,
they haven't, out of concern for self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the wars in Africa have tended to be internal explosions
of ethnic violence, as in Rwanda or Burundi, or of flat-out greed
masquerading as a liberation struggle, as in Angola or Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Civilians are often the targets in these wars: ethnic rivals are
slaughtered in Rwanda; children's limbs are hacked off in Sierra
Leone. Almost any hospital at any time in eastern Congo will have
patients _ sliced in the head with machetes, pocked with bullet
holes _ who have been caught in the fighting from one of the
uncountable factions there.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia and Eritrea went to war in May 1998. Unlike many
conflicts in Africa, which are the result of states falling apart,
this was in many ways about people defining themselves as nations.
Once an Italian colony, then a British protectorate, Eritrea was
formally annexed in 1962 by the Ethiopian emperor, Haile Selassie,
to become Ethiopia's northernmost province. In 1991, guerrillas
from both Eritrea and Ethiopia defeated Mengistu Haile Mariam, who
had ousted the emperor in 1974, and in 1993 Eritrea peacefully
became a new nation.
</P>
<P>
   But its borders were not defined and good relations with
Ethiopia never developed. So a series of border skirmishes exploded
into all-out war that the leaders of neither side had the strength
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ethiopia and Eritrea were until recently united, it
could be argued that this war is just barely one between states.
But they have fought as if it was. There were two trained armies
lined up across trenches, with tanks, planes and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   A military analyst in the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa,
believes this is why Eritrea has done so badly against an Ethiopian
offensive launched on May 12: The Eritreans, he said, were
excellent guerrilla fighters during their 30-year struggle against
the emperor and then the Mengistu regime. But once they had to
fight a conventional war, the analyst said: ``They didn't have
clue. Maybe the fact that they are sovereign nation and think of
themselves as a sovereign nation induced them to fight a battle
they didn't know how to fight.'' (The Eritreans say they were not
defeated militarily at all, but simply withdrew to save lives and
fight on their own terms.)
</P>
<P>
   Early in the war, Ethiopia bombed what it said were military
sites in the Eritrean capital, Asmara, and Eritrea bombed a school
in the northern Ethiopian town of Mekele. Amnesty International has
said ``dozens'' of civilians were killed in the first round of
fighting. But since then, civilians have for the most part been
moved away from the fronts, minimizing the danger.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the last two weeks _ as Ethiopia drove north away from
the trenches and into Eritrean territory _ there have been few
reports of civilians killed, no more than a handful on either side.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, all of that may make little difference in
the impact the war is having on these desperately poor societies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The humanitarian disaster has been drought and famine
affecting both countries,'' said Martin Hill, the Amnesty
International researcher in London who follows the wars on the Horn
of Africa. ``Fortunately there hasn't been another humanitarian
disaster of killings of civilians or killing fleeing refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hill suggests, this war may have been played more by the
rules than others in Africa, but there is no taming war itself.
Ultimately, it has been extraordinarily costly.
</P>
<P>
   Even before this latest round of fighting, it was estimated that
this very conventional war had ended the lives of at least 20,000
soldiers. Last year, President Clinton put the number of dead at
70,000.
</P>
<P>
   And that is far from the only cost. There is also the question
of resources: The war diverted perhaps $1 billion that could have
gone toward development. Both nations are among the poorest in the
world and have fought at a time when 8 million Ethiopians and some
770,000 Eritreans faced severe food shortages begun by drought and
worsened by war.
</P>
<P>
   It is also estimated that some 550,000 Eritreans have been
pushed from their homes by the latest round of fighting _ most of
them in the most fertile agricultural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations now have representatives in Algeria to talk
about peace, but there has been no cease-fire and nobody is going
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a very severe effect on civilians,'' Bowers
said. ``The food situation was not great beforehand. And this is
not going to make it any better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
