<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-03 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO WIN THE PEACE YOU DANCE WITH THE DEVIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Northern Ireland is locked in a grim struggle to trade
in tested old tribal instincts for risky new communal ones, and the
qualms and tensions in that swap were on display last week in
Belfast in the actions of a central figure in the peace
negotiations, David Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend Trimble, leader of the province's largest
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, revived what has been a
repeatedly jeopardized peace accord by persuading his quarrelsome,
doubting rank and file to trust in the disarmament promises of its
Catholic sworn enemies in Sinn Fein, which represents the Irish
Republican Army. Supporters of the 1998 accord, which aims to end
three decades of violence with the creation of power-sharing
political institutions, promptly praised him for his courage and
vision _ virtues infrequent in Ulster politics.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after achieving his narrow victory, Trimble stepped out
into the luminous gallery of glass-sheathed Waterfront Hall, which
is itself a symbol of a brighter future for the conflicted
province, and promptly reverted to an all-too-familiar
name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as democracy is concerned,'' he said of the Sinn Fein
politicians whose word he was championing moments before, ``these
folk ain't house-trained yet.'' They would have to be ``brought to
heel,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the opposition dogs and worse is standard-issue oratory
in Northern Ireland, where insult is the common currency of public
dialogue. One of those consigned by Trimble to the kennel, Sinn
Fein Assemblyman Alex Maskey, robustly protested the crude allusion
but quickly added that it was probably something the Ulster
Unionist leader felt impelled to say to keep party hard-liners on
board.
</P>
<P>
   Out of this kind of grudging acceptance of each other's
atavistic imperatives has emerged a sense of sameness between two
rival communities that have spent generations fighting to maintain
their differences. It may not be the ultimate equality that
reformers are seeking, but it is a kind of companion conduct that
suggests consensual politics may stand a chance in Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the home rule government up and running last week
than Sinn Fein dominated debate with an argument over whether its
ministers would allow the British flag to fly over public buildings
they now occupied. It was telling behavior for a party that has
regularly mocked Protestants for devoting so little time to real
issues and so much to symbolic ones like defending their right to
wave banners and parade around the province in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble finally got his delegates' support for going into
government with Sinn Fein by warning that if they voted no, they
would be banishing themselves to the margins and leaving the main
arena to their opponents. His point _ one that has taken time to
dawn on his tradition-bound audience and produced the support of
only a slight majority _ was that the only way to keep power was to
share it. Continue trying to hold onto all of it, he was saying,
and there's the unenviable possibility of ending up with none of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Summoning his party to the center was a daring bid because it is
the fringes that often are more alluring to Ulster politicians.
George Mitchell, the former U.S. senator who brokered the original
peace agreement, once commented that while the normal movement of
politics in Western societies was toward the middle space of
reconciliation, in Northern Ireland it was toward the poles of
defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has been in both places.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1944 in Bangor, a seaside resort in County Down, and
formerly a law professor, Trimble had his first political
involvement on the clamorous right wing of the unionists, whose
unionism sprang from a wish that Northern Ireland remain part of
the United Kingdom. He joined the Ulster Vanguard, which was formed
in 1972 to confront the more mainstream Ulster Unionists, and took
an active part in the hard-line protests that helped end the
Sunningdale Agreement in 1974, which was the last attempt at
power-sharing in the province.
</P>
<P>
   A result of that agitation was to bring down the home rule
government of Brian Faulkner, a Protestant moderate who occupied
the same position then, premier of Northern Ireland, that Trimble
does today as first minister.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper Bann district that he has represented in the British
Parliament since 1990 includes the town of Portadown, known as the
citadel of the militant Orange Order. It has been the scene of
violent standoffs every summer when the black-suited ``brethren''
in their bowler hats and orange sashes have tried to take their
parade commemorating centuries-old Protestant triumphs from
Drumcree Church along a road that wends through Catholic
neighborhoods. In 1995 Trimble attracted attention by leading the
marchers into a police formation blocking their path, hurling
himself against a patrolman and giving the officers a red-faced,
finger-wagging lecture. When the Orangemen penetrated the police
lines and reached their destination at the Portadown Orange Lodge,
he danced a victory jig arm in arm with the Rev. Ian Paisley, the
preacher-politician who is the best-known opponent of any
accommodation with Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble won a Nobel Peace Prize in 1998, but just years earlier,
he was making his mark by acting rude, truculent and spiteful, his
occasional smiles tight, joyless and disdainful. Hardly a matinee
idol today, he has mellowed into a more relaxed and broadly
persuasive orator, indulging in the occasional hot-tempered
flashback as a reminder that his more primitive past still lurks.
</P>
<P>
   These days he is denounced by Paisley as a Judas, and Trimble's
picture hangs in a hut on Drumcree Hill, altered to show satanic
horns protruding from his forehead. His party has traditionally
been most comfortable saying no, and only 53 percent of the 862
ruling council members chose to say yes to accepting the IRA
pledges on disarmament and participating in government with Sinn
Fein.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments, the two sponsors of the peace
effort, both believe that Trimble is the only person on the
Protestant side capable of maintaining progress in putting into
place the power-sharing arrangements that have continually
faltered. Sinn Fein also appreciates his fundamental value, and the
biggest threat to him now comes from his own co-religionists. There
will be lots of tactical maneuvering among them to try to undo what
he has done, and his leadership is sure to be challenged again.
</P>
<P>
   To the task of dealing with this crafty enemy within, Trimble
brings an important qualification. He was until recently one of
them himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
