<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-VIRUSES-REVI     06-03 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-VIRUSES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A WORM NEEDS LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month a hyperactive computer program bearing the message
``I Love You'' ricocheted around the world's e-mail systems in less
than 24 hours and infected tens of millions of computers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``I Love You'' bug, allegedly launched by a computer student
in the Philippines with too much time on his hands, touched off a
cyber-flu season. More than 29 variants have emerged so far,
including diabolical derivatives with names like ``NewLove'' and
``Resume _ Janet Simons.'' Most of the mutants arrived without
tidings of love, but instead carried a software payload designed to
erase victims' disks once the message's attachment was opened.
</P>
<P>
   While ``I Love You'' was startlingly swift and effective, most
of its imitators went almost nowhere. According to some computer
security experts, the copycat cyberplagues should have spread just
as rapidly as the worm (in computer entomology, worms propel
themselves while viruses hitchhike on other documents) they were
mimicking.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, what's love got to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   Quite a lot, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts looking at the different contagion rates are
divided about whether Internet users learned a hard lesson in
computer hygiene or whether the world is actually a lonelier place
than anyone realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that men were much more likely to open the `I
Love You' worm than women,'' said George Cybenko, a computer
scientist at Dartmouth University and a founder of the Institute of
Security Technology Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the ``I Love You'' message was so simple and beguiling
that in some cases it hoodwinked even the most sophisticated
computer programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Capps, a senior Microsoft software designer, padded
downstairs at 5 a.m. on the morning of the ``I Love You''
infection, poured himself a cup of coffee and sat down at his
computer to read his e-mail. It happened to be his birthday, so as
he scanned his mailbox he thought he saw a love note from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   After opening the program Capps quickly realized his error and
managed to delete the bug before it spread widely. ``What I
remember thinking was, ``How did Marie manage to sneak downstairs
late at night to send me a birthday note?'' he said sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   Capps was not alone. Hewlett-Packard &AMP; Co. acknowledged last
week that its computers suffered more than 700,000 infections from
the ``I Love You'' worm _ more than 500,000 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The total damage _ primarily time spent restoring files and
cleaning out clogged e-mail systems _ may reach $950 million,
according to ICSA.net, a computer security company that tracks the
cost of computer infections.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the far more lethal ``NewLove'' bug began
infecting the address books of users of the popular Microsoft
Outlook e-mail program, sending itself to every person on the list.
But instead of delivering the endearingly named document
LOVE-LETTER-FOR-YOU.TXT.VBS, NewLove cloaked itself by snatching a
recent document name from its victim's hard disk and using that
name in the subject line of all subsequent messages sent from the
address list, destroying data on the hard drives of affected
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the ``Resume'' bug urged e-mail recipients to look at
a job seeker's fabulous curriculum vitae, helpfully included as an
attachment _ which, of course served as an electronic Trojan Horse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their cleverness, however, both ``NewLove'' and
``Resume'' were stopped in their tracks. ``If `NewLove' had come
before `I Love You' it would have spread more slowly but we would
have had a bigger disaster,'' said Peter Tippett, chief technology
officer of ICSA.
</P>
<P>
   Tippett, who was trained as an epidemiologist before starting an
antivirus software company in the 1980s, has long argued that
computer viruses and infections closely mimic the biological world.
</P>
<P>
   That might be another reason why the lethal ``NewLove'' was less
effective than ``I Love You.'' In the real world as well as in
cyberspace, diseases that kill their hosts quickly tend to have
limited success in spreading through large populations. ``Viruses
that kill their hosts never make it,'' Tippett said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the Darwinian imperative or the irresistible power
of love at work, experts believe the current cyber-flu season will
not be the last, especially as the millions of PCs of the 1990s are
transformed into billions of cell phones, personal digital
assistants and even toaster-connected Internet appliances by the
end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   For each new device connected to the Internet there are dozens
of new ways to spread infection. Even now, computer security
experts are warning that the growing popularity of music and
file-sharing programs like Napster, Gnutella, iMesh and Scour
Exchange will virtually insure new vectors for diseases.
</P>
<P>
   That will mean that disease in the cyberworld will become as
routine as cold season is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what concerns me,'' said Kevin Kelly, author of ``Out
of Control: The New Biology of Machines, Social Systems and the
Economic World'' (Addison Wesley, 1994). ``These new systems leave
us completely open to these infections and we may just have to
learn to live with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-VIRUSES-REVI     06-03 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-VIRUSES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A WORM NEEDS LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
