<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3580 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-PERU-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-03 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU'S FUJIMORI: AUTOCRAT? DEMOCRAT? WELL, BOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ The year was 1991. Alberto Fujimori was Peru's
newly elected president, and diplomats were rejoicing that every
government in Latin America except Cuba's was now democratically
elected. So Fujimori joined the leaders of Peru's four Andean
neighbors in proposing a radical plan: the Organization of American
States would require all 34 member states to sever diplomatic
relations with any government that took power unconstitutionally.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, Fujimori must be happy his plan was never
adopted. This week, the Organization of American States is to
consider how to punish Fujimori for claiming a third five-year term
after an election last Sunday that was tainted by dirty tricks and
re-interpretation of the constitution, which limits Peru's
presidents to two terms. His opponent, Alejandro Toledo, wound up
boycotting the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Peru is probably safe from any drastic measures, in large
part because the United States has backed away from supporting
strong OAS condemnation, and because Peru is not alone among its
peers in slipping back into old authoritarian patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The current president of Ecuador, a civilian, came to power in
January by military coup. The elected president of Venezuela is a
former military coup leader who has made all-out war on the
Congress and the courts. Paraguay's civilian government is
teetering.
</P>
<P>
   Does this turn of events mean that the man on horseback is
coming back in Latin America? Or is it that Latin America never
completely unsaddled him?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, authoritarianism and democracy have long coexisted in
Latin America, and a swing toward elections has never meant
autocracy is dead. A pattern of generals replacing civilian
presidents only to be replaced again by generals has been the rule
from Panama to Argentina for the better part of a century. A
variant on the theme, in places like Peru and Mexico, is a civilian
leader who is elected and then rules by fiat, fraud or manipulation
of the courts and congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The box on the outside is labeled a democracy,'' said Piero
Gleijeses, a professor of Latin American studies at Johns Hopkins
University, ``but inside you have an authoritarian system.''
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Paz, the Mexican essayist, once wrote that the problem
with democracy in Latin America is that it was ``imported but not
adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   So Fujimori is not so much a model of a new kind of
authoritarianism as an exemplar of something older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our military regimes were never that tough and our elected
governments were never that democratic,'' said Carlos Tapia, a
former Peruvian Congressman and social critic. ``Our coups were
never initiated by the military alone. There was always a group of
civilians ready to manipulate the military to jump in.''
</P>
<P>
   The model for the civilian strongman in Peru goes back at least
to the 1919 election of Augusto Leguia, a businessman with a taste
for top hats and thoroughbred horses, who served until a coup
upended his rule in 1930. Like Fujimori, Leguia was a
master-builder of roads and ports who eagerly sought foreign
investment. He also displayed little compunction about breaking
democratic rules. He ordered the army to shut down the congress, he
closed down newspapers that opposed him, and his race horses had
remarkable success at the track during his years in office.
</P>
<P>
   As for governing Peru, neither the military nor the civilian
strongmen have a stellar record. Most recently, the military
regimes that ruled from 1968 to 1980 pushed through a radical land
reform. But it ultimately failed, leading to a slump in agriculture
and a chaotic peasant migration to the cities that created
shantytowns that are still spreading. It did little for public
confidence in military efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   When civilians returned to power in 1980 the people were
overjoyed. But the next 10 years were marked by hyperinflation,
massive corruption and the eruption of terrorist violence. This
ultimately discredited the two traditional political parties,
leaving the public in despair about their hopes for order.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the people turned to Fujimori, the ultimate outsider, a
son of Japanese immigrants who belonged to no party and promised a
clean break with the past. His popularity soared when he disbanded
the Supreme Court and Congress in 1992, claiming that their corrupt
ways were blocking his policies. In 1995 he won re-election in a
landslide; it amounted to a democratic affirmation of
authoritarianism and left advocates of democracy worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full democracy means more than elections,'' noted Carlos
Ivan Degregori, an anthropologist at the Institute of Peruvian
Studies. ``It requires sturdy institutions: strong political
parties, an independent judiciary and a Congress willing to vote
against the executive branch.'' Most often, he said, ``the boundary
between democracy and authoritarianism is not so clear.''
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true in the region's poorest countries,
such as neighboring Bolivia, where the democratically elected
president is a former military dictator. But it is also true in
Latin America's more economically and politically developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Chile is still governed under a constitution that was written
when Augusto Pinochet was dictator; it gives the army independent
powers over selecting its commanders and even senators. The new
governor of Buenos Aires province in Argentina, when faced with a
rising crime problem, selected as his police chief a former army
colonel who had led a 1987 uprising to block trials against former
junta leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whichever way the pendulum swings,'' said Felipe Noguera, an
Argentine political consultant, ``it's not like the people
overnight become perfect democrats and the next day become
supporters of coups. People in this region are aware of both the
weaknesses of democracy and the perils of authoritarian rule.''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why in the days leading up to last Sunday's
election, opinion polls showed that even though a majority of
Peruvians said they thought the election process was tainted, they
would vote for Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
