<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHERNOBYL-REVISITED (CHERNOBYL, Ukraine) _ They are gardening
again at Chernobyl. Rounding the last corner on the road to the
destroyed reactor of Unit No. 4 at the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant, the most striking discovery at the site of the worst
radiation accident in history is the two young women in white masks
picking gingerly at the earth with hoes and rakes. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON (Moscow) _ In his final visit to Moscow as
president, Bill Clinton arrived here Saturday to find Russia and
its new leader, Vladimir Putin, absorbed with domestic politics, a
wrenching set of economic reforms just getting under way and an
unresolved war in Chechnya. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   THIRDWAY-LEADERS (Berlin) _ When they met in Italy one year ago,
they were leaders of a ``Third Way'' and their founding members
were President Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
Saturday, as Clinton joined 12 other left-of-center presidents and
prime ministers here in Berlin, the ``Third Way'' was banished in
favor of ``Progressive Governance.'' And Blair, pleading the need
to help his wife care for their new-born baby, decided to stay
home. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-EUROPE (Warsaw, Poland) _ Having finally achieved full
NATO membership only a year ago, Poland finds itself caught
awkwardly between its European aspirations and its loyalty to the
United States. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GAY-PARENTS (Jerusalem) _ Four-year-old Matan
Berner-Kadish has always had two mothers. But it was not until
Monday that the state of Israel accepted that basic fact of his
existence, with a watershed court ruling that drew howls of outrage
from the religious right. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.S. (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ As Sierra Leone
slid back into war last month, the British were conspicuous as the
one Western power willing to shore up the faltering U.N.
peacekeeping force. Their presence merely emphasized the absence of
the United States, which last year was a major backer of the peace
agreement that granted amnesty to a brutal warlord, Foday Sankoh,
and even brought him into government. By Norimitsu Onishi with Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   RED-CROSS-LEADER (Geneva) _ While most international officials
of his rank are out on this city's thriving cocktail party circuit,
Jakob Kellenberger, a courtly but determined former Swiss diplomat,
heads home from the International Committee of the Red Cross,
getting an early night for his customary 7 a.m. start next day.
Kellenberger, 56, has taken the helm of the 137-year-old
International Red Cross when global humanitarian agencies are
facing more challenges than ever before. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-TORTURE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ When a harsh report
asserting that torture is widespread in Turkey was released, the
surprise was not just the amount of damning evidence it contained,
but also the source. Rather than being prepared by a private
advocacy group, the report was the work of the parliamentary
committee on human rights. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CHURCH (Decatur, Ga.) _ Nearly 50 years after the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. scolded Christians for making 11 a.m Sunday
the most segregated hour of the week, the Assembly of God
Tabernacle here is the rarest of religious institutions: a truly
integrated church in the heart of the South. And yet, the
Tabernacle is deeply conservative, socially and theologically. What
draws its members is the intensity of their Pentacostal faith,
which teaches that the Holy Spirit can move in the lives of all
believers, regardless of background. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   (First in a series of articles, ``How Race Is Lived in
America.'')
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-TEACHERS-TAXES (Los Angeles) _ Gov. Gray Davis' proposal
to show support for California's public school teachers by
exempting them from state income taxes has run into unexpected
opposition. Legislative leaders of both parties in both houses in
Sacramento oppose it as bad policy and the start of a slippery
slope toward similar demands from other public employees. Even the
teachers' unions oppose the plan. They fear it would leave them
open to attacks from fellow government workers, and prefer salary
increases instead. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   APPALACIA-MARIJUANA (Hindman, Ky.) _ Countless hidden marijuana
patches dot the springtime ``hollers'' of Appalachia the way
moonshine stills used to. ``Moonshine went out in the late '70s,
just when marijuana started big around here,'' said Sheriff Wheeler
Jacobs. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-PROTESTS (Detroit) _ For the next three days, anyone
wearing a mask in this city or carrying gasoline in a portable
container will go to jail. And those in possession of ammonia,
urine, feces or squirt bottles can expect intense police scrutiny.
This is Mayor Dennis Archer's response to human rights campaigners
who plan, starting on Sunday, to unleash the same kind of protests
that left Seattle with $2.5 million in damage last December after a
meeting of the World Trade Organization. The protests planned here
are directed at a three-day summit being held across the Detroit
River in downtown Windsor, Ontario. Delegates from the Organization
of American States, a coalition of 34 nations, are gathering to
discuss ways to bolster trade in North and South America. By
Nichole M. Christian.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-QUANDARY (Chicago) _ The nation's biggest food companies
face a marketing quandary in the debate over genetically altered
crops, which environmentalists contend are potentially dangerous
but which the Food and Drug Administration has deemed entirely
safe. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IMAGE (Austin, Texas) _ Are George W. Bush and his allies
overplaying his disdain for intellectualism, to the point where
they are sometimes making him out to be a self-satisfied boob? By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   TRIAL-LAWYERS-POLITICS (Undated) _ The powerful Association of
Trial Lawyers of America has vowed to do everything to defeat Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, who has long made changes in liability
laws a centerpiece of his campaign. But while the trial lawyers
have given Al Gore a great fund-raising advantage, they have also
given the Republicans a ready target in their campaign to link Gore
to the image of greedy trial lawyers. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Term-limit reneger gets party help;
Lighter Nader grows heavier in polls; Bowing out in Ohio with eye
on future; Nevada GOP pulls shock on abortion; Polls say Bush leads
in electoral votes. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Where money works but people don't.
By Paul Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Double-faulting to the bank. By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
