</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT101-106
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CHERNOBYL-REVISITED (Chernobyl, Ukraine) _ They are gardening
again at Chernobyl. Rounding the last corner on the road to the
destroyed reactor of Unit No. 4 at the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant, the most striking discovery at the site of the worst
radiation accident in history is the two young women in white masks
picking gingerly at the earth with hoes and rakes. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT1,2,3
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE-COURT (New York) _ The prosecutor is a soft-spoken
young man of 16 with a crown of cornrows. The defense lawyer is 16,
too, only recently out of jail on a charge of attempted murder. And
when the accused, a gawky 15-year-old charged with graffiti writing
and weapons possession, rattles off the names of gangs he has a
``beef'' with at school, the courtroom congregation nods and
murmurs knowingly. No, this is not a high school moot court, where
students pretend to be players in a court of law. This is a small,
quiet experiment in which Bronx teen-agers arrested on misdemeanor
charges and even minor felonies are judged, quite literally, by a
jury of their peers. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
