<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.S.-ART     06-03 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.S.-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW U.S. LEFT SIERRA LEONE TANGLED IN CURIOUS WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI with JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ As Sierra Leone slid back into war last
month, the British were conspicuous as the one Western power
willing to shore up the faltering U.N. peacekeeping force. To many,
their presence merely emphasized the absence of the United States,
which last year was a major backer of the peace agreement that
granted amnesty to a brutal warlord, Foday Sankoh, and even brought
him into government.
</P>
<P>
   To critics, including senior officials in the U.S. State
Department, that agreement amounted to a Band-Aid response by the
Clinton administration to criticism of its African policy after
President Clinton went to Africa in 1998, talked of an African
renaissance and promised greater involvement in the continent.
</P>
<P>
   To backers of the Lome agreement _ named for the capital of
Togo, where it was signed last July _ the inclusion of Sankoh and
amnesty for his gunmen's atrocities was the only effective way to
stop a war that outsiders would not help end militarily. A Clinton
administration official said the choices were Lome or ``chaos,''
adding that the accord was intended to ``end the killing, restore
order, point a way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone's violence has pointed up the quandary facing
Western governments in the post-Cold War world of geopolitically
insignificant but spectacularly brutal conflicts. In the Balkans,
and last year in East Timor, outside powers have intervened to halt
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, many critics say, the Clinton administration has been
unwilling to risk the lives of U.S. troops since the death of 18
soldiers in Somalia in 1993. The administration faces congressional
constraints in paying for international peacekeeping efforts and,
the critics say, pays only intermittent attention.
</P>
<P>
   Whether justified or not, a result of this criticism is that
Washington's offers to help calm Sierra Leone's most recent
violence have largely been spurned. Kofi Annan, secretary-general
of the United Nations, rejected an offer to fly fresh U.N. troops
to Sierra Leone, because the price of U.S. military planes was too
high.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Clinton's special envoy for
democracy in Africa, came to West Africa to help defuse the crisis,
he was forced to cancel a stop in Sierra Leone because he was not
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was given the role of special envoy to Africa after
helping to keep the black vote solidly behind Clinton in 1996. He
is a vocal proponent of intervening in Africa's conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   In May last year, Jackson criticized the administration for
protecting Kosovo Albanians but leaving Africans to defend
themselves so that Sierra Leone's war was ``fought in the dark''
for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks helped to train U.S. attention on Sierra Leone,
where Sankoh's rebels had killed, raped and hacked the limbs off
thousands of inhabitants in an assault on Freetown in January 1999.
Last summer, peace talks that had limped along in Lome suddenly
yielded an agreement to share power and hold elections in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   This embrace of Sankoh was distasteful to many. ``It seemed to
be yet another indication of the U.S. being unwilling to invest the
political capital to ensure that a sustainable peace could be
arrived at by incorporating the broader issues of human rights,''
said Janet Fleischman of Human Rights Watch. ``When you do that,
you may have a short-term solution, but it will not buy you peace
in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, an administration official said, three
high-ranking officials _ Harold Koh, the assistant secretary of
state for human rights; David Scheffer, the ambassador at large for
war crimes; and Julia Taft, the assistant secretary of state for
refugees _ recorded their opposition to giving Sankoh a role in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hoped they could eventually wrest control of Sierra
Leone's diamond mines from Sankoh, who became chairman of the
commission that manages vital resources. His men have long
controlled the mines, using diamonds to buy arms.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, even supporters see the flaws. ``Bring Sankoh
into the government? Make him the head diamond counter? What were
we thinking?'' said another U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to reach the Lome accord began to build after
Sankoh's assault on Freetown. Nigeria, which was leading a West
African intervention force known as Ecomog, managed to recapture
the town from the warlord's Revolutionary United Front. But
Nigeria's involvement in Sierra Leone was costly _ in cash and
human lives _ and increasingly unpopular back home. After taking
office in May last year, Nigeria's president, Olusegun Obasanjo,
pledged to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials and several congressmen,
searching for a way to fill the vacuum that Nigeria would leave,
began looking to Jackson and his long friendship with Charles
Taylor, the warlord-turned-president of Liberia, Sierra Leone's
eastern neighbor, who in turn was a friend and ally of Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official said U.S. decision makers on Sierra
Leone decided to overlook the conflict of interest between Jackson
and Taylor for the sake of ``political expediency and the pressure
from Nigerians to get out.'' Jackson leaned on Taylor to lean on
Sankoh to go to Lome, the official said, and the accord was signed.
</P>
<P>
   As a corollary, a U.N. force with no U.S. soldiers was envisaged
to keep peace and to win the U.S. financing that Congress had
refused for the West African force.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the accord was that the government Sankoh
joined and its president, Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, were _ and remain _
powerless and unpopular, dependent on outsiders for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah, a former U.N. Development Program official, rarely seems
to leave his hilltop presidential palace; his presence is
manifested mostly as a voice in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leonean and U.S. officials with knowledge of the peace
talks say negotiators believed that Sankoh was central to any
lasting peace. A deal signed in 1996 unraveled precisely because it
had no role for him. What is more, after Sankoh was arrested on an
arms-trafficking charge in Nigeria and later sentenced to death for
treason in Sierra Leone in late 1998, his men went on their ghastly
spree of maiming and killing.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty was granted, not only to Sankoh and his men, but also to
other militias.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the government point of view, the benefits outweighed the
costs of having that provision in the accord,'' said Septimus
Kaikai, Kabbah's spokesman. ``If you look at the war from '91 to
'99, the amount of people who have lost their lives, or were maimed
or raped or had their properties destroyed _ granting amnesty was
to bring peace and create the environment for the government to get
things back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the potential embarrassment of giving amnesty to
Sankoh, the United Nations signed the Lome accord with a notation
declaring that the amnesty did not apply internationally _ a ruse
that allowed the accord's backers to argue that Sankoh could
eventually be tried outside Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's participation was capped last
October by a visit from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
Freetown. Albright toured a camp for mutilated victims, cuddled a
3-year-old girl who had no hands, and _ in a building carefully
placed off limits to photographers and journalists by her aides _
met Sankoh, who was several hours late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sankoh is delivering the right message,'' she said, ``and I
hope very much he will continue to intensify his efforts to ensure
full adherence to the Lome accord.''
</P>
<P>
   After Albright's visit, Washington's interest in Sierra Leone
waned. The United Nations dispatched soldiers from India, Pakistan
and other African nations to serve as peacekeepers. But when, in
late April and early May, that force tried to go to the area of the
diamond mines, and simultaneously the last of the Nigerian troops
left Sierra Leone, Sankoh's men took 500 peacekeepers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration announced that Jackson would come to
West Africa to help negotiate the hostages' release. But even
before he left the United States, Jackson angered people in
Freetown by saying that Sankoh ``should be coaxed back into the
political equation'' and by drawing a parallel between Sankoh's
Revolutionary United Front and Nelson Mandela's African National
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After intense pressure from the State Department, Jackson later
adopted a harder stance against Sankoh. But it was too late.
Jackson's friendship with Taylor is viewed askance in Freetown, and
his safety could not be guaranteed here.
</P>
<P>
   Salih Booker, a senior fellow at the Africa Policy Information
Center in Washington, said the reliance on Jackson is a symptom of
a muddled policy and lack of commitment toward Africa in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just flies out with his own God-given talents and allows
the administration to wish him well and distance itself in some
ways,'' Booker said. ``If he fails, it's his failure. If he
succeeds, it's the Clinton administration's success.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics, like Annan, said that new, complex peacekeeping
efforts such as those in Sierra Leone were severely limited by the
United States' lack of willingness to provide direct military
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   On May 26, Clinton announced $20 million in aid to the United
Nations and several individual nations, including Nigeria, for
their operations in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sierra Leone's people have suffered far too much, for far too
long,'' Clinton said, ``and they need immediate assistance to
prevent a return to full-scale civil war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
