<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHERNOBYL-REVISITED-A     06-03 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERNOBYL-REVISITED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING IN THE SHADOW OF CHERNOBYL'S REACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT 1, 2 and 3 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERNOBYL, Ukraine _ They are gardening again at Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding the last corner on the road to the destroyed reactor of
Unit No. 4 at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant, the most striking
discovery at the site of the worst radiation accident in history is
the two young women in white masks picking gingerly at the earth
with hoes and rakes.
</P>
<P>
   They were preparing a flower bed in the shadow of the
``sarcophagus,'' the mammoth concrete and steel structure, riddled
with leaks and cracks, that now encases the shattered reactor hall
where nearly 200 tons of radioactive fuel lie melted and fused with
sand, concrete and other debris from the explosion and fire that
erupted on April 26, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily, we would have had flowers growing long ago,'' said
Katya Premak, 33, explaining why nothing was coming out of the
ground so late in the spring. ``But we are going very slow,'' she
added, leaning on her hoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, they found a hot spot over there,'' she said,
pointing to where a scoop of earth had set off a radiation monitor
during a routine sweep. ``We wear these masks because we are
stirring up the dust and it can be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   To any visitor, it seems more than unusual that thousands of
people still come to work here every day, 14 years after a disaster
that killed 28 people outright with high radiation doses and
touched off a still accelerating epidemic of thyroid cancers among
children who lived downwind of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, something is to change.
</P>
<P>
   President Leonid Kuchma has declared that Ukraine will close the
last operating reactor at Chernobyl, Unit No. 3, sometime this
year. He said he would announce a specific closing date during
President Clinton's two-day visit to Kiev, which begins Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ourselves want to shut down the last remaining unit,''
Kuchma said in an interview in Kiev, Ukraine's capital, 80 miles to
the south. ``So this is not a political game. We will shut it
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But the shutdown is only the beginning of a new chapter in the
life of the ill-fated power station, whose radioactive wastes and
debris must be guarded for decades, if not centuries, to prevent
them from further poisoning the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do tens of thousands of Ukrainians depend on the plant
for jobs and power, but Ukraine faces an acute energy crisis, even
now, before Chernobyl is closed. Despite intensive medical
investigations into the health effects of the huge amount of
radiation released from the explosion and fire that ripped through
reactor No. 4 in 1986 after an experiment went disastrously wrong,
the overall health of the plant workers remains good, though more
questions than answers remain about Chernobyl's long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question is who will pay for what needs to be done
here. Since 1986, Chernobyl's endgame has been marked by unceasing
recriminations among Ukraine, the United States and the world's six
other wealthiest industrial nations over financing for major
decommissioning projects and the replacement of Chernobyl's
electrical output.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine would like to complete two nuclear power plants that
were under construction in western Ukraine before the Soviet Union
collapsed, but the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, responsible for Western financing, has failed to offer
lending terms Ukraine can afford, in the view of Kuchma and his
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electricity deficit has been catastrophic in our
industries, so if we just shut down a unit that has been producing
1 million watts,'' Kuchma said, referring to Chernobyl, ``it will
be a complete disaster for the Ukrainian economy because nuclear
power is the cheapest.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, controllers from Kiev enforce rotating blackouts for
as long as eight hours a day in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Chernobyl closes, the costs of monitoring what happens
inside the sarcophagus, and keeping radiation firmly encased, will
run on. A permanent corps of safety engineers is needed. Moreover,
a new sarcophagus costing as much as $750 million will probably
have to be built, since the current one rests on potentially
unstable foundations and suffers from intrusions of rainwater that
create clouds of humidity in the radioactive darkness, corroding
the maze of pipes and steel girders and increasing the risk of
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   A plant for processing radioactive waste will be needed, and a
$100 million heating plant and new electricity supplies to run all
the support facilities. Leaders of the seven wealthiest nations
have pledged about $400 million of the money needed for the
sarcophagus, but Kuchma said Western aid had been slow to
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like closing a big door and putting a big lock in
place and then forgetting about it,'' he said. ``We have to
continue servicing this plant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Kuchma indicated that Ukraine would seek
Russian help, if necessary, to replace Chernobyl's electrical
output, a step that would undermine the Western goal of reinforcing
Ukrainian independence at a time when President Vladimir Putin of
Russia is emphasizing the ``common roots'' between his country and
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will probably look for a compromise with Russia because 90
percent of the equipment in these plants was made in Russia, and so
economically and politically it's highly profitable and interesting
to the Russians,'' Kuchma said.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks may have been intended to put pressure on the West
in advance of the July meeting of the Group of Seven leaders with
Russia in Okinawa, but he nevertheless is under considerable
pressure at home, where the energy sector is notoriously corrupt
even as major industries go begging for electricity supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of what to do about Slavutich, the
city of 28,000 built in the 1980s to house Chernobyl's corps of
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Units No. 1 and 2 of Chernobyl operated until the early 1990s.
Unit No. 2 was shut down in 1991 after a fire swept through its
turbine hall, causing extensive damage, though not to the reactor.
And Kuchma agreed to shut down Unit No. 1 in 1994 after the Group
of Seven pledged to help finance an overall plan to decommission
the Chernobyl complex _ assistance that has been halting at times.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From Slavutich, Chernobyl's denizens ride an electric train 40
minutes to ``the zone,'' the depopulated area of abandoned farms
and villages where 135,000 people once lived within an 18-mile
radius of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there was farmland, weeds and brambles have taken
over, enveloping houses and hiding earthen mounds where radioactive
trucks and bulldozers are buried and equipment yards where
irradiated helicopters that dumped tons of sand and boron on the
burning reactor still are quarantined. Some pilots died from the
radiation they received.
</P>
<P>
   In man-made canals that once carried cooling water to and from
the reactor, hefty carp and catfish have taken over. And in the
nearby forests the swelling deer population has attracted poachers
who ply the trails of the zone at night.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of 1986, Chernobyl became a symbol of nuclear
devastation that incited a numbing fear in Ukraine and Belarus, a
fear that researchers suggest has so far been more destructive to
public health than the huge release of radiation. The accident also
laid bare industrial incompetence and a contempt for the
environment that helped to fracture the Soviet edifice.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 6,000 Chernobyl workers and their dependents today
in independent Ukraine, the power station represents more than
anything a paycheck and a guaranteed apartment when so many in the
former Soviet Union are without both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a student in electrical engineering in Moscow and came
here two years after the accident,'' said Irina A. Kolbich, who
works for the plant administration. ``Frankly I came for financial
reasons because living here on 1,300 rubles a month with your own
apartment was better than living in Moscow on 130 rubles a month
with no apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir A. Komarov calls himself ``a patriot of Chernobyl''
because he has worked here for 20 years. ``If you talk to our
experts, all agree that this plant could be operated until 2006 or
maybe longer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The culture of safety still is not exactly pervasive. Neither
Premak nor her co-worker, Natasha Poplegina, were wearing their
dosimeters, which measures radiation, while gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are supposed to wear them all the time, but I keep mine in
my locker,'' Premak said.
</P>
<P>
   In the flower bed, the radiation, though low, was about four
times higher than the naturally occurring levels in the
environment. ``Since you don't see it, who knows what to expect
anyway?'' Poplegina said.
</P>
<P>
   On the deck that overlooks the sarcophagus, where Vice President
Al Gore stood briefly during his visit to Chernobyl in 1997, the
radiation goes from four times to 10 times the naturally occurring
level, still not necessarily dangerous but not recommended for
extended exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Control Room No. 3 operates Chernobyl's last functioning nuclear
dynamo. On a recent afternoon, Alexander N. Yelchishev, 46, a shift
supervisor, monitored the reactor closely.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of Unit No. 4, Yelchishev lost a classmate and a
neighbor to radiation poisoning in 1986. Still, he remains a
believer in nuclear power, and laments that the closing of Unit No.
3 will constitute a waste of about $300 million in safety
improvements financed by the United States and other Western
donors.
</P>
<P>
   The fixes are intended to prevent the reactor from surging out
of control, as Unit No. 4 did during a low power test in 1986,
setting off steam and hydrogen explosions that ripped apart the
graphite reactor core, blew off the roof and spewed radioactive
material into the atmosphere for days.
</P>
<P>
   Yelchishev does not blame the West for the pressure to close
Chernobyl as much as he blames Ukraine's leaders for allowing
corruption and inept reforms to retard economic development.
</P>
<P>
   In the accident, about 50 tons of radioactive dust and debris
was carried by winds and rain to virtually every country in the
Northern Hemisphere, but the worst contamination was in the areas
near the zone, especially southern Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Thyroid cancer rates have increased tenfold in Ukraine and as
much as 84 times in parts of Belarus. In 1996, about 800 thyroid
cancers had appeared in Ukraine and Belarus, but the numbers have
since risen sharply and continue to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of today, we have operated on about 1,500 children in
Ukraine alone,'' said Dr. Valery P. Tereshchenko of the Institute
for Endocrinology and Metabolism in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   The health effects from other long-life radioactive elements,
like cesium and strontium, have been difficult to measure. There
have been no clusters of leukemia or other cancers in the fallout
zones where the thyroid cancers have appeared, but the latency
period for other health effects may be longer, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. conference on Chernobyl concluded in 1996 that the only
clear change evident in health to date was a ``highly significant''
increase in thyroid cancer rates among people who were children in
1986 in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' said Dr. Mykola D. Tronko, director
of Ukraine's thyroid cancer institute, ``even 14 years after the
accident, we have more questions than answers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3607 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-JUVENILE-COURT-760(2T     06-03 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-COURT-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH COURT OF TRUE PEERS JUDGES WITH FIRM HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball caps and do-rags are dutifully removed while court is
in session. The prosecutor is a deliberative, soft-spoken young man
of 16 with a crown of cornrows. The defense lawyer is 16, too, only
recently out of jail on a charge of attempted murder. On the
six-member jury sits a girl with searing eyes and the memory of
juvenile jail still fresh in her mind. And when the accused, a
gawky 15-year-old charged with graffiti writing and weapons
possession, rattles off the names of gangs he has a ``beef'' with
at school, the courtroom congregation nods and murmurs knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not a high school moot court, where students pretend
to be players in a court of law. This is a court of law, a small,
quiet experiment in which Bronx teen-agers arrested on misdemeanor
charges and even minor felonies _ anything from graffiti writing to
small-time robberies and drug sales _ are judged, quite literally,
by a jury of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   They are all first-time defendants. They are referred here by a
probation officer or a judge, as an alternative to prosecution in
the city's overtaxed Family Court, where children under 16 are
tried.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers who run the Bronx Youth Court, begun two years
ago by youngsters organizing inside the city's juvenile jail, see
their mission as nothing short of what the Constitution guarantees:
a speedy trial before a jury of one's peers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them have been through the juvenile justice maze, what
they universally call ``the system.'' They know well the inside of
a juvenile jail (19 months in the case of Francisca Martinez, 16,
the defense lawyer, known in Youth Court as youth advocate). They
know how ponderously the Family Court can move (three and a half
months in detention for one juror, Latoya Orr, accused of stabbing
another girl, until a judge ruled in her case). Indeed, the court
seems to derive its very credibility from the youngsters' firsthand
knowledge of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got to talk to my lawyer the way I wanted to,'' said
Martinez, who was convicted of the stabbing. ``I wanted to be there
for somebody, being that nobody was there for me,'' she said in
explaining her mission.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of such youth courts is largely unproven, but
they have emerged across the country in the last decade, spurred by
a general sense of frustration with the juvenile justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 650 youth courts exist nationwide, compared with 50
in 1991, according to the Justice Department's Office of Juvenile
Justice and Delinquency Prevention. They handle mostly nonviolent
first-time defendants: children accused of shoplifting, vandalism,
starting schoolyard brawls and committing other crimes unlikely to
be prosecuted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feel-good quality to them,'' said Jeffrey Butts, a
senior research associate with the Urban Institute, a
Washington-based research organization, who is conducting a
national evaluation of youth courts for the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   That same quality gives experts like Butts a sense of deja vu.
``A hundred years ago, we invented juvenile court to get kids out
of the bureaucratic criminal court system,'' he said. ``Now we're
inventing youth courts to get them out of juvenile court, or to
create alternatives to that system.''
</P>
<P>
   There are four such courts in New York City, all fairly new. Two
were established by the state court system, in Harlem and in Red
Hook, Brooklyn. A third, in Hollis, Queens, was begun by civic
leaders and the city corporation counsel's office, which prosecutes
children in Family Court. All but the Bronx court handle youngsters
arrested for the smallest of infractions. A fourth of all the cases
tried in the Brooklyn Youth Court, for example, involve truancy, an
infraction that is not prosecuted in Family Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Youth Court is unusual because it judges more serious
offenses _ drug possession with intent to sell, robbery, weapons
charges. The idea is not to punish, but to help steer the accused
away from crime and provide some restitution to the community.
Among the judges, jurors and lawyers are those whose own sentences
include serving in youth court.
</P>
<P>
   Not many get off. Of the roughly 70 youngsters who have appeared
in the Bronx Youth Court in the last two years, only two have been,
in effect, acquitted, according to statistics maintained by Youth
Force, the youth-run community group that established the court.
</P>
<P>
   The City Probation Department does not keep exact figures,
though officials there say anecdotal evidence suggests that the
program is effective.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other day, as the late afternoon sun streamed in through the
barred windows at Youth Force's headquarters in Mott Haven, the
court was weighing the case of a freshman at Columbus High School.
Police believed that he had been a lookout for a graffiti crew. The
defendant, who agreed to allow a reporter to attend his trial on
the condition that his name not be used, said he had merely been
standing on the sidewalk trying to hail a cab while his friends
were ``bombing'' a wall with graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Peppering the defendant with questions, the jurors homed in on
certain details: The police had found a knife in the defendant's
pocket, and, it turned out, he had missed nearly three months of
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who carries a knife in their pocket, if they get
busted, there should be some sort of consequence,'' argued Dante
Motes, the prosecutor, known in the court as a community impact
assessor.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, removing his baseball cap at Martinez's urging,
said he felt unsafe at school. His friends, fellow
Albanian-Americans, had angered several gangs, and some were shot a
couple weeks before. That was why he wasn't going to school, he
said, and also why he carried a knife. ``People are looking to jump
me, shoot me,'' he cried. ``How you expect me to feel safe?''
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors were skeptical. His friends were shot only two weeks
ago, but he hadn't been in school for several months. If he really
felt unsafe, why didn't he go to the principal to seek a transfer
to another school?
</P>
<P>
   What did he do in his spare time? Were there youth centers near
his home? Why had he been hanging out with these friends, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   So it went for nearly two hours, as the jury struggled to
decipher the penal code and asked questions to understand the
defendant's life better.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, they learned, was in Yugoslavia. He lived with his
sister and brother in the Bronx. He was not in a gang. He was
trying to transfer to another school. He liked to play football.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating for 20 minutes in a closed room upstairs, the
jurors found him guilty on all counts. They sentenced him to a
two-hour legal rights workshop (mandatory for all Bronx Youth Court
defendants), four hours on a Youth Court jury, and 16 hours working
on a Youth Force community project. Such projects have included
voter registration drives and undercover stings against stores that
sell alcohol to minors.
</P>
<P>
   What lasting effect, if any, this will have on the young man
remains to be seen. Recidivism rates of Youth Court defendants are
only anecdotal, but supporters of the Bronx Youth Court and others
point to the alarmingly high recidivism rates in the juvenile
justice system. A recent study by the State Division of Criminal
Justice Services, for example, found that among boys incarcerated
in the state juvenile justice system, 81 percent were rearrested
within three years of their release.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Bronx Youth Court like to point out to their
peers how they fared in the juvenile justice system. ``From arrest
through court through incarceration, we went through feeling
confused, powerless and alone,'' reads a paragraph from a pamphlet
given to all defendants. ``Almost all of us came out of the system
disillusioned, better criminals, less educated and without the
resources needed to succeed.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
