<SLUG> BC-SUPERLOTTO-CHANGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LOTTERY REFORMULATED FOR BIGGER JACKPOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE CARNEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Come Wednesday, winning at least some money in
California's lottery becomes much easier with the first drawing of
the new SuperLotto Plus.
</P>
<P>
   But don't buy that Jaguar and mansion just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The jackpots will be bigger, but the odds of winning them are
much worse. On the flip side, the chance of winning at least
something will get much better.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, California lottery officials expect to reverse
declining ticket sales with this game, emulating the multistate
Powerball and Big Game lotteries - the ones that have grabbed
national headlines and players' dollars with their massive jackpots
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of winning at least something are increasing from one
in 60 to one in 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of that, the players stay interested in the game much
longer than in a conventional lottery game,'' said Edward Stanek,
director of the Iowa lottery and inventor of Powerball. ``The
customer is looking for the chance at that really big prize, but
they're only going to continue playing if they keep winning
something on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The new SuperLotto Plus play slips will begin appearing today.
</P>
<P>
   To win, players must pick five numbers from one through 47, and
a sixth ``mega-number'' from one through 27. The mega-number is the
equivalent of the Powerball in the game of that name.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the jackpot still requires matching all six numbers, but
that becomes far harder because the mega-number is chosen from a
different bin from the first five. That allows for a repeated
number in the sequence, and vastly decreases the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having only four chances to win, by matching three,
four, five or six out of six numbers, players will now have nine
opportunities to win.
</P>
<P>
   A player can win a dollar by simply matching the mega-number or
can win even more by matching the mega-number and any other
combination of numbers. Two matches plus the mega-number will net
about $10, for example, Hasegawa said. Or a player can win by
matching three, four or five of the regular balls.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of winning the top prize in the SuperLotto Plus will
drop to about one in 41 million from the current one in 18 million.
With longer odds, the jackpots will swell by rolling over more
often.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, two Big Game ticket holders split a $363
million jackpot - the largest in the nation's history. The previous
record was a $296 million Powerball jackpot that 13 Ohio machinists
split in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For California, the previous high for the California Lotto was a
``mere'' $118 million in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   With the new SuperLotto Plus, players will get a head start on
larger jackpots, as the state is raising the minimum to $7 million
instead of the current $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   And SuperLotto Plus will feature more chances to win lesser
amounts. The Powerball-type game features a larger second prize -
about $20,000 for a near-miss instead of the current $1,500 - and
increased chances to win lesser amounts.
</P>
<P>
   After sales of SuperLotto tickets began to dip in the past year,
California Lottery officials in April decided to change the game
slightly to revive interest. This year, for the first time, sales
of scratch-off tickets outpaced SuperLotto tickets, $1.15 billion
to $975 million, said Jim Hasegawa, game development manager with
the California Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa said the state decided to go it alone with SuperLotto,
instead of joining the 20 states and District of Columbia playing
Powerball, or the seven states playing Big Game. Officials felt
California was large enough to support its own game, and wanted to
keep the income and the winnings in-state, Hasegawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the $2.85 billion expected from California lottery sales
in the coming year will go toward prizes, while 34 percent of the
proceeds fund public education needs.
</P>
<P>
   If the theory works, the game will immediately produce more
winners. And lottery officials say that fact, and the higher
jackpots, will attract more players.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that isn't such a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lottery is to gambling what marijuana is to drug use. It's
an entry-level activity,'' said Tom Tucker, executive director of
the California Council on Problem Gambling. ``They're going to get
more people, there's no question about it. Gamblers are really
hooked on the high, the thrill of the chase.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the possible payoff is sky-high, ``the existing problem
gamblers are going to reach deeper into their pockets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the California Lottery has reached an agreement for the
council to start answering its gambling problem assistance line,
(888) 277-3115. And Tucker said they're trying to persuade the
state to increase its gambling-problem education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the California Council has its own counseling hot
line, (800) GAMBLER, and a Web site at www.calproblemgambling.org.
</P>
<P>
   Stanek said the Powerball-style game can be more beneficial for
low-income players, as it offers larger middle-level prizes and
greater chances to win them. For someone not making a lot of money,
winning $20,000 for picking five of six can have a huge impact, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the potentially huge jackpots will attract even well-to-do
players, who might not be swayed by a $15 million SuperLotto kitty,
but could be intrigued by a $100 million SuperLotto Plus jackpot.
That might get them to drop a few dollars on Quick Picks, just for
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of games means they have to be entertaining. You
can only play a game so long, unless you have something very
interesting to keep it alive,'' Stanek said. ``I think California
is going to be very happy with this.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
