<SLUG> BC-LIBRARIES-PAPERCUTS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL MAY END FREE PRINTED GOVERNMENT DOCUMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's librarians have raised a storm of
protest over a House budget-cutting plan that could deny the public
access to thousands of free government books, brochures and
documents.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee voted on May 9 to cut funding
for the Federal Depository Library program, which distributes
printed materials for free to more than 1,350 city, county and
college libraries, including 47 sites in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents, led by cost-conscious Republicans, argue the move
would save the Government Printing Office $18.3 million annually.
They also say the public can now gain access to many government
documents via the Internet. An estimated 50 percent of all
government documents are now available on line at
www.access.gpo.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, led by the Chicago-based American Library
Association, say that most libraries and their patrons are
ill-equipped to go online and that the public has a right to access
all printed documents that are compiled and produced at taxpayer
expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at this move as reducing access,'' said Mancy Mahr,
spokeswoman for the Los Angeles County Public Library. ``In many
cases, library patrons are precisely the people who don't have
computers or training and who depend on us and printed material for
their information.''
</P>
<P>
   Foes of the measure are hoping to get funding restored when the
House reconvenes this week. The measure must still be voted on by
the full House and the Senate, which has opposed the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Government Printing Office, which has been using local
libraries as depositories since 1858, last year distributed 16.1
million copies of 40,000 titles nationwide at a cost of
approximately $30 million. Most items are in print form, but a
number of documents are also produced on CD-ROMs and microfilm.
</P>
<P>
   Titles popular with the public include brochures on student aid,
small business loans and other programs, occupational outlook
guides, detailed census data, reports by federal agencies, the U.S.
Code (a listing of all federal laws) and the Congressional Record.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-branch Los Angeles County library system includes eight
Federal Depository Libraries that keep large numbers of government
documents on hand as reference materials. Smaller numbers of
documents are available at all branches.
</P>
<P>
   Mahr, the library's spokeswoman, noted that Internet access is
still in its infancy in the county system, which only last fall
finished installing needed wiring and placing computer terminals in
each of its 84 branches.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the branches have only one terminal and customers must
reserve them in advance. Public use is free, but customers are
often limited to 30 minutes online.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Curzon, dean of the library at California State University,
Northridge, said her facility serves a predominantly computer-savvy
student clientele, but she still is concerned about access.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone ought to be concerned about the potential
loss of a rich treasure trove of information,'' said Curzon, who
noted that CSUN's government document collection, staffed by
full-time librarians, is used extensively by students, faculty and
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government's intent is to go digital, why not have a
strategic plan and work with us on new ways to disseminate
information?'' she added. ``This proposal will only widen the
digital divide and disenfranchise those who can't afford or can't
access technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanore Schmidt, Long Beach's director of library services,
echoed those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Long Beach, Schmidt
called the depository program at the city's main library ``one of
the great bargains of government. The Government Printing Office
supplies the publications, but libraries provide the space to house
them, the staff to help the public and the computers, photocopiers
and other equipment needed to use the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt also said that, if printed materials were eliminated,
Long Beach ``would be unable to provide enough computers to meet
the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
</TEXT>
