r a BC-LIBRARIES-PAPERCUTS-2     06-03 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBRARIES-PAPERCUTS-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
  
WASHINGTON: to meet the demand.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lynne Bradley, director of government relations for the American
Library Association, said the federal government's Internet
operation is still woefully inadequate compared to its publications
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of reports and data that are still
available only in print,'' said Bradley. ``And even if everything
were online, there are still issues with the speed of connections
and librarians using their limited time to teach specialized
computer programs to patrons.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Taylor, R-North Carolina, sponsor of the library
budget cut and chairman of the House Legislative Appropriations
Subcommittee, said in a May 9 congressional report that ``the
committee recognizes that the public availability of government
information is a basic right that must be maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   But he went on to say that the program ``could be performed with
more cost effectiveness by making greater use of electronic
information technology.''
</P>
<P>
   House staffers said a few days ago that many GOP members are
having second thoughts about scrapping the depository program. The
cuts are already opposed by most Democratic members, including Rep.
Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Los Angeles, a member of the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been motivated to revisit the issue in part by
the Senate Appropiations Committee, which voted May 18 to fully
fund the library program.
</P>
<P>
   House GOP leaders will be meeting this week to decide whether to
rescind the cuts, which are embedded in the proposed 2000-01
operating budget for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One of those GOP leaders is Rep. David Dreier, R-Covina,
chairman of the House Rules Committee. Dreier said Thursday that he
is sympathetic to the needs of librarians and patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must strive to improve access and efficiency in government
without creating new hurdles for people and the local institutions
that serve them,'' Dreier said. ``While I support new technology to
expand Americans' access to government, I share the concerns of
those who worry that such a major change in distributing federal
documents may go too far, too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of Southern California libraries that are
classified as Federal Depository Libraries, which could face the
loss of government publications.
</P>
<P>
   City libraries:
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, Arcadia, Downey, Inglewood, Long Beach (Main), Los
Angeles (Central), Monterey Park, Ontario, Palm Springs, Pasadena,
Riverside, Santa Ana, Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   County libraries:
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Library branches in Carson, Culver City,
Lakewood, Lancaster, Montebello, Norwalk, Valencia, West Covina.
San Bernardino County Library (San Bernardino). Orange County
Library (Garden Grove).
</P>
<P>
   College libraries:
</P>
<P>
   Caltech, Claremont University Center, Cal State San Bernardino,
Cal State Dominguez Hills, Cal State Fullerton, Cal State Long
Beach, Cal State Los Angeles, Cal State Northridge, Loyola Law
School, Pepperdine University, Southwestern University School of
Law, University of La Verne Law Library, UC Irvine, UC Santa
Barbara, UCLA (Young and Law libraries), UC Riverside, University
of Southern California (Doheny and Law libraries), University of
Redlands, Whittier College.
</P>
<P>
   Other:
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Law Library, Orange County Law Library, San
Bernardino County Law Library.
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Government Printing Office
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
