u s BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      06-03 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TWO REELING LOSSES IN NEW YORK, MILLER TOOK CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers never trailed in the Eastern Conference
finals. And yet, after losing two lackluster games to the Knicks in
Madison Square Garden last week, they seemed like a train derailed,
the players ready to scatter their separate ways to free agency, if
not their summer tee times.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose said the offense was staid and predictable. Travis
Best hinted that speed would be a better starting option at point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   And Reggie Miller was out of character altogether, having scored
no more than 19 points a game in a series he supposedly could not
wait to dominate, against a team he hated with a well-documented
passion.
</P>
<P>
   Only when Miller turned into the best version of himself,
demanding the ball and letting his shots silence the Garden crowd
in Game 6 on Friday night, was Indiana's transformation complete.
They started rebounding. They started playing defense. They adopted
the intensity their third-year coach, Larry Bird, had as a
Hall-of-Fame player. And they became the team that brought
Indianapolis its first appearance in the NBA finals in franchise
history.
</P>
<P>
   Miller scored a game-high 34 points, 17 in the decisive
fourth-quarter, and finished with five rebounds and four steals in
the Pacers' 93-80 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 7 would have been, to tell you the truth, too much
pressure for us,'' Miller said. ``We wanted to end it here. Tonight
was our Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller sank a trio of 3-pointers and all eight free throws in
the fourth quarter, bringing the Pacers their first Eastern
Conference championship, breaking a string of two devastating
near-misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time and time again, he made the big plays,'' Dale Davis said.
``Every time they made a run, he stuck a basket at the most crucial
times.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks were making a final run, Miller said he told Bird,
``Just run the offense every single play through me. Either I will
get a good look or someone else will get a good look, but I had to
have my hands on the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of urgency _ missing in Miller in last year's Game 6
loss to the Knicks at the Garden _ emerged before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would flip the switch and ask the guys, `If it
came down to one game, one game to move on to the big show, where
would you want to play?''' Miller said. ``Personally, I would want
to play it here and want to play against New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, almost 35, is one of six Pacers who will become free
agents after the season. His message was not lost on the Pacers.
``Reggie's the guy who takes it personal when we don't play well
against New York,'' Rose said. ``Everybody knows he doesn't like
them and they don't like him for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added, ``He wasn't going to be denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor were the rest of the Pacers. For the fourth time in six
games, Davis had 16 rebounds. For the second straight game,
Indiana's point guards Mark Jackson and Travis Best outplayed and
outscored Charlie Ward and Chris Childs, combining for 19 points
and eight assists to 12 points and 11 assists for Ward and Childs.
Rose scored 11 points, second-highest on the team.
</P>
<P>
   And in the fourth quarter, the Pacers outrebounded the Knicks,
12-4, and limited the Knicks to six field goals and three free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two games ago players were questioning what I was doing, and
all I told them,'' Bird said, `You got to believe and you got to
get up and play harder and if you lay it on the line, it will work.
If you are soft, they will take advantage of you.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``You hear Jalen say you need some new plays and
that's not good, but then they believe in the system and they end
up winning two good games.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for the first time in 10 trips to the playoffs, four to the
conference finals, the Pacers advanced to the NBA finals. In 1987,
the year the Pacers drafted Miller out of UCLA, the Knicks drafted
Mark Jackson out of St. John's and Brooklyn. Thirteen seasons
later, Jackson had 9 points and four assists for Indiana, and he
was on the podium next to his close friend, Miller, wiping tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reg and I have been talking about this for years and years and
years and time and time again, keeping each other up all night
long, calling in the middle of the night and wondering how are you
feeling,'' Jackson said. ``We have gotten there time and time
again, but to finally finish it off was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Brooklyn native Sam Perkins was the only Pacer to have
previously reached the finals, with Seattle in 1996. After scoring
6 points and getting three of his four rebounds in the final 10
minutes Friday night, Perkins could not stop grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' he said of winning at New York. ``We kept digging
down,'' Perkins said. ``All those things going into the season
about how old we are'' _ Perkins is the oldest Pacer, just 10 days
from his 39th birthday; Rose is the youngest at 27 _ ``we didn't
need to be reminded of that. It was just worthwhile for this day,
right now, it's satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment will be all too fleeting, though. ``We're not really
content _ we've got four games left,'' Perkins said, just as
Portland was sending the Western Conference finals to a seventh
game against favored Los Angeles. ``No matter who we play we'll
probably be the underdog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
