<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yankees, Red Sox: A Race With Only Winners?
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Boston Red Sox appear to be in a race that
will very likely not turn out to be a race at all. How can there be
a race when no one loses?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly much can happen in the remaining two-thirds of the
season, but from the vantage point of the first weekend of June and
the first interleague series of the season, the Yankees and the Red
Sox have the look of playoff teams. The only question would be
which will go as the division champion and which as the wild card.
Therein, some people believe, lies the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty old school,'' John Valentin, the Red Sox third
baseman, said before sustaining a season-ending knee injury last
Tuesday. ``I'd rather fight them in a pennant race and be the
winner and have no wild card. Then these games would mean a lot
more. They really would. Right now these could be pennant-type
ballgames. They're exciting now, but they're not going all out. The
atmosphere is different.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the collection of 10 games the Yankees and
the Red Sox have in a four-week span (why they are playing all of
those games this early in the season is another issue). The games
are less meaningful, Valentin suggested, because no matter who
prevails in them, no matter who winds up in first place at the end
of the season, the other team expects to be right there, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Stanley, his teammate, disagreed about the value of the
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't a fan of the wild card until the first year, '95,
when we won it,'' Stanley said, referring to the Yankees, the team
he played for then. ``I came back with the Yankees in '97 and we
were the wild-card team. In '98 and '99, I was with this team and
we were the wild-card team. So every year except '96 I've been on
the wild-card team, so I'm a big fan of it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your ultimate goal is to get into the playoffs,'' the
wild-card king added. ``You're just looking for a spot to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig acknowledged that the existence of the
wild card could dilute the excitement of a division championship
race but only if the loser of that race is guaranteed the wild-card
spot. And, he noted, baseball offers no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that the one that doesn't win is guaranteed the
wild card,'' he said, referring to the Yankees and the Red Sox.
``You have an interesting Chicago-Cleveland scenario, and Toronto
isn't far behind the Yankees and Red Sox. There could be quite a
race for the wild card as well as for the division championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Orza, the No. 2 man at the players association, said
wild-card races were more likely to produce excitement than
division races. ``The wild card has the potential that division
races do not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of teams in a division race, Orza added, is limited
by the number of teams in the division. A wild-card race can
include any number of teams from all of the divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The National League wild-card team has been decided the past two
seasons by playoff games. The Chicago Cubs defeated the San
Francisco Giants in 1998, and the Mets knocked off the Cincinnati
Reds last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has its pluses and minuses,'' Selig said, ``but I
think the pluses with the wild card outweigh the minuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the schedule is that if the Yankees and the Red Sox
were playing at least half of their games in the second half of the
season, as they have been accustomed to doing, the dilution of
their race for first place could be even greater because they would
be in a better position to know their chances of reaching the
playoffs as the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   No one has a specific explanation for why the teams play 10 of
their 13 games before the end of June and why the Red Sox play in
New York twice in three weeks, the second time before the teams
play in Boston for the first time. Perhaps more interestingly,
according to a person with knowledge of the schedule-making,
neither team raised the chronology as undesirable.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since the American League went to a
balanced schedule with expansion in 1977 that the Yankees and the
Red Sox were scheduled to play the majority of their games in such
a short period. In 1978, they had seven games in 16 days in June
and early July, but they played eight other games that season,
including six in a memorable September.
</P>
<P>
   Katy Feeney, a major league schedule expert, was not involved in
planning the AL's 2000 schedule, but she said interleague play had
affected schedules generally. Special team requests and travel
patterns also influence the schedule, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' Home Run Pace
</P>
<P>
   In a spring training conversation about the increase in the
number of players who have hit 50 home runs in recent seasons,
Barry Bonds of San Francisco was asked if he thought he could hit
50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never hit 50 so I'll never say I can hit 50,'' said Bonds,
whose career high is 46. ``If I had done it before, I'd say yes,
but I've never hit 50. I'm not going to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds, entering the weekend, had slugged 20 home runs in the
Giants' 50 games, placing him only 1 behind Mark McGwire, the major
league leader. His home run ratio would project to 65 for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   When Marquis Grissom of Milwaukee hit a home run last Monday, he
relinquished his lead in the race among players who do not know the
baseballs are supposed to be livelier this season. Grissom produced
his first home run of the season on his 197th time at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, the new leader was Miguel Cairo of Tampa
Bay. He had hit no home runs in 173 at-bats. He was followed by
Homer Bush of Toronto at 150 and Mickey Morandini of Philadelphia
at 142.
</P>
<P>
   Darrin Fletcher of Toronto hit three grand slams in his first
944 major league games, a career that spanned nine years of major
league service. But in his first 41 games this season he matched
that total, slugging grand slams against Kent Mercker of Anaheim on
April 20, Jason Johnson of Baltimore on May 8 and Doug Brocail of
Detroit on May 26. Fletcher leads the majors this season with three
grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson Unbeatable
</P>
<P>
   Kent Bottenfield struggled through five seasons with five
different teams and compiled an 18-27 record. Then last season he
won 18 games and lost seven for St. Louis. The Cardinals traded him
to Anaheim for Jim Edmonds in March because they felt Garrett
Stephenson was ready to start for them. Stephenson had pitched in
four seasons with four different teams, emerging with a 14-12
record. Stephenson went into his start against Cleveland Saturday
night with an 8-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Trachsel, who was Tampa Bay's scheduled starter against
the Mets Saturday night, has pitched one complete-game shutout and
seven innings in each of two other shutouts for his only victories
of the season. In his other nine starts, he had allowed 41 earned
runs in 43 and two-thirds innings for an 8.45 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of five days, the Chicago White Sox lost the first
of James Baldwin's eight starts, the Arizona Diamondbacks lost the
first of Brian Anderson's eight starts and the Mets lost the first
of Al Leiter's nine starts.
</P>
<P>
   Alignment Plans
</P>
<P>
   Officials plod on trying to devise an alignment and a schedule
format for next season. The prevailing plan is the one that would
have 16 teams in the National League and 14 in the American, withArizona and Tampa Bay switching leagues. The players association,
however, has submitted an idea for two leagues of 15 teams each,
with Houston moving to the AL.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of the 15-15 alignment would be that the leagues
and their avenues to the playoffs would be symmetrical _ three
divisions of five teams each with three division champions and a
wild card for the playoffs. Under the 16-14 setup, the NL would
have four division winners and no wild card and the AL would have
two four-team divisions and one six-team division.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials don't like 15-15 because it would require
seasonlong interleague play. The officials prefer their interleague
games in two clusters, as they are scheduled now. But the union has
devised a format for an unbalanced schedule, which is the No. 1
goal of Commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   The union format provides for 72 games against division
opponents (18 each), 72 games against the other 10 teams (seven or
eight each) and 18 interleague games (three each against five
same-division teams and three against a geographical rival or
otherwise selected opponent).
</P>
<P>
   Other than having seasonlong interleague games, the alignment
has two problems:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Texas Rangers have wanted out of the AL West to play more
games in their own time zone for television purposes, but a
lucrative new 10-year television contract has apparently rendered
that problem moot. Furthermore, the Astros would join the Rangers
in the AL West, creating a Texas-sized rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Astros' owner, Drayton McLane, has said he does not want
to change leagues, and he can veto a move. He would have to be
convinced it would be in the best interests of baseball for the
Astros to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response from the players has been overwhelming,'' Gene
Orza, the union's associate general counsel, said. ``They're very
enthusiastic about it. They like the absolute balance. They like
the idea of everybody playing the same kind of schedule, having the
same number of teams and having the same ways of getting to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The players have to approve any change in the leagues'
alignment.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
