<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      06-03 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roster For the Olympics Remains Unsettled
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardaway is probable, Grant Hill and Tim Duncan are
questionable, and Allen Iverson is extremely doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   As injuries pile up for the U.S. Olympic men's basketball team,
the alternate list keeps growing. While Hardaway's injured foot is
expected to heal in time for the Sydney Games, which begin Sept.
15, Hill and Duncan are question marks after recent surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all indicated that they want to play,'' Craig Miller,
the director of USA Basketball, said. ``It's all about their
recovery time now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who was passed over for the previous teams, does not
want to miss an opportunity to compete in the Olympics. But if Hill
is out, Kobe Bryant is the favorite to be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who is recovering from knee surgery, is also a question
mark. Antonio McDyess, Eddie Jones or Shareef Abdur-Rahim would
most likely take the spot. But the committee has not ruled out
approaching Shaquille O'Neal, who originally turned down the
request to play.
</P>
<P>
   Two USA Basketball officials, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said Iverson was a long shot to make the team because of
the team's depth at guard.
</P>
<P>
   Alternate decisions will not be made until mid-June, Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the team will not be hurting for talent although its
presence will not rival the pageantry surrounding the original
Dream Team in 1992. The 2000 team will open preliminary play on
Sept. 17 against China, then play Italy on Sept. 19, Lithuania on
Sept. 21, New Zealand on Sept. 23 and France on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the injured players, Ray Allen, Vin Baker, Vince Carter,
Kevin Garnett, Allan Houston, Jason Kidd, Alonzo Mourning, Gary
Payton and Steve Smith will represent the United States.
</P>
<P>
   McGrady Appears to Be Moving
</P>
<P>
   All Arn Tellem, the agent for Tracy McGrady, will say is,
``We're keeping all our options open.'' But it is looking more and
more as though McGrady, the skywalking Toronto Raptors forward,
will not be helping Vince Carter much longer.
</P>
<P>
   McGrady, the pick of the free-agent litter with Tim Duncan,
Grant Hill and Eddie Jones, is leaning toward signing with Orlando
or Chicago _ the teams with the most salary-cap money stockpiled.
According to a person familiar with McGrady's plans, McGrady's
decision may come down to what other prominent free agents the
Magic or the Bulls sign before McGrady commits.
</P>
<P>
   If Glen Grunwald, Toronto's general manager, feels he is going
to lose McGrady to another team for nothing, the possibility of a
sign-and-trade deal grows exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the long-held notion that McGrady would not leave
the Raptors because of his close relationship with Carter is fading
fast _ almost as fast as the notion that McGrady enjoys playing for
Coach Butch Carter enough to remain in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   His tale is tied to a larger one to be played out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   If McGrady, Hill, Duncan and Jones command the maximum-allowable
salary for a player of their experience levels, the money left for
those second-tier free agents whose current teams decide not to
re-sign them will be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Deemed one of the major setbacks to players in the new
collective-bargaining agreement, free agents like Glen Rice, Toni
Kukoc, Ron Mercer, Jalen Rose and Rashard Lewis can only hope their
teams want to retain their services and pay fair-market value. If
they do not, they may end up playing for $2 million exceptions for
teams that do not have the money to compensate them.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. Avery Johnson. Antonio Daniels. Kurt Thomas.
Kendall Gill. Tim Thomas. Tim Hardaway. Players like those and
Maurice Taylor, Cuttino Mobley and Tariq Abdul-Wahad may have to
scramble to find a salary commensurate with their skill levels
after all the big money is paid out.
</P>
<P>
   Great system, no? The elite players are about to get richer as a
plethora of former and potential all-stars may have to work for Joe
Kleine-type wages. It will be the price extracted for cutting down
on widespread player movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Falk Influence
</P>
<P>
   Rod Thorn's joining the Nets as president and chief of
basketball operations not only gives the organization a bona fide
presence in the front office, but it also squelched the notion that
the agent David Falk was somehow running the team through the
connection with his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Falk, who represents Stephon Marbury, Keith Van Horn and Kerry
Kittles also has a close friendship and business relationship with
John Thompson, whom the Nets interviewed for the position. Falk has
often been accused of leveraging the contract extensions of Van
Horn and Kittles against delivering Marbury to the Meadowlands from
Minnesota. Falk was deeply involved in the blockbuster trade, but
had no say in other personnel matters.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost a break for Thompson that he did not get the job.
His personal association with one of the game's most powerful
agents would have unfairly distorted the perception his own job
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Nets Top Pick Up For Auction?
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are already talking about moving their No. 1 pick in
the draft, according to a Western Conference general manager who
spoke on the condition of anonymity. The Nets are not enthralled
with any of the most likely top four picks _ Chris Mihm, Kenyon
Martin, Stromile Swift and Marcus Fizer _ and have considered swaps
with both Orlando, which has the fifth, 10th and 13th selections,
and Chicago, which has the fourth, seventh and 24th picks.
Vancouver has also been talking with Orlando about shipping its No.
2 pick to the Magic for a compilation of Orlando's picks, according
to an Eastern Conference team official.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
