<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      06-03 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oakland Raiders' organization and much of the National
Football League remain saddened _ and puzzled _ over the death of
Raiders safety Eric Turner last Sunday from complications of
abdominal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the league, especially his teammates and coaches,
wondered how the cancer could have so quickly struck down a top,
young athlete with seemingly little warning. In a matter of months,
Turner, 31, went from a Pro Bowl player who last season was a
contributing member of the Raiders, to recently losing 70 pounds
from his 215-pound frame.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who two weeks ago denied reports that he was seriously
ill, died at Los Robles Hospital in Thousand Oaks, Calif. Because
of privacy concerns, the Raiders and family members have released
little information about his illness.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's death has caused some players, especially his
teammates, to make themselves more aware about cancer. One agent
said he had asked his clients, with the Raiders and others
throughout the league, to see their team doctors for a checkup. One
Raider said that because he eats ``a lot of greasy bad food'' he
planned to get a screening for abdominal cancer soon.
</P>
<P>
   Abdominal cancer, according to Dr. Martin Oster, an oncologist
at Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center, is an insidious disease
that is hard to detect, and once it spreads, it kills quickly. Even
the detailed physical exams administered to NFL players would not
have most likely detected the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of cancer might begin without any specific
symptoms,'' Oster said. ``The patient may have vague symptoms, like
stomach pain or weight loss. In a healthy young person, those
symptoms do not alarm. So the cancer advances.''
</P>
<P>
   Such symptoms would not have most likely alerted Turner, or
almost any other player. Football players are used to enduring
physical discomfort. They routinely play with broken fingers, sore
knees, battered ribs and other injuries. So Turner would have
barely noticed a stomach ache, and any weight loss might have been
attributed to workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know all of the details of his case of course, but
there is a stage in this type of cancer, like many types of cancer,
where it is early, and the cancer is curable,'' Oster said. ``But
this cancer is an iceberg cancer. The symptoms can be few while the
cancer grows. Then by the time it is diagnosed, it can be beyond a
surgical cure.''
</P>
<P>
   While the exact details of when the stomach cancer was diagnosed
are unknown, what is known is that last season he was playing. So
the diagnosis had to have come in the past year _ it is hard to
imagine a doctor diagnosing stomach cancer in Turner during the
season and then Turner continuing to play _ which means the disease
was most likely diagnosed after the season and in the last six
months.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for this type of cancer to spread rapidly and
do massive amounts of internal damage. ``About 10 to 20 percent of
the people who get this cancer may live five years or longer after
the diagnosis,'' Oster said. ``But for the vast majority, about 80
to 90 percent, it is not uncommon to see death within a year.''
</P>
<P>
   As Turner's illness worsened, he withdrew from some teammates
and friends. Terry Donahue, who coached Turner at UCLA, said he had
sent him a note several weeks ago after word of his illness leaked
out, but he never heard back from him. Several teammates tried to
contact Turner by phone, but could not reach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, he was exceedingly private in cloaking this
illness in the most private of terms,'' said Art Modell, the
Baltimore Ravens owner, whose Cleveland Browns drafted Turner
second over all in 1991. ``It's very sad that a young man that age
has to be taken that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players questioned how a young person in outstanding
physical shape could lose his life so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in good shape and taking care of yourself never hurts,
no question,'' Oster said. ``But overall, I'm afraid, it means very
little. It doesn't help you fight the cancer. Why you get the
cancer is a function of genetics and what you eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Raiders are remembering Turner as a gregarious,
friendly person, as well as an unselfish player. Oakland Coach Jon
Gruden said Turner was ``a great guy who will be sorely missed by a
lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon Kaufman, the Oakland running back, said: ``He was
compassionate and a class act. It was truly a pleasure to have
known Eric and I will miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders May Join Redskins
</P>
<P>
   A Dallas Cowboys' team official said he hated the idea that
cornerback Deion Sanders might end up playing for the rival
Washington Redskins, but conceded it would probably happen.
Sanders, who was released Friday by the Cowboys, could sign with
the Redskins soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys believe Sanders is still a good player, but they
simply could not afford to keep him on their roster. If Dallas did
not cut Sanders before Friday, his contract for the next two years
_ a $10 million roster bonus and $500,000 in base salary for the
coming season and a $13 million salary for next season _ would have
been guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has been working with a speed coach, and the Pro Bowl
player believes he is in great shape. The Redskins and other teams
agree. Tampa Bay and Denver are also interested in Sanders and the
Dallas owner Jerry Jones will not rule out an attempt to re-sign
Sanders at a cheaper price. But look for Sanders to end up in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles Budgeting Well
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles are in the best position of any team to
take advantage of the remaining free-agency period, since last week
the team was an astounding $7 million under the $62 million salary
cap. Even though the Eagles will use $4 million to sign draft
picks, the remaining cash will allow them to sign one or two
quality free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have had a tremendous off season so far, acquiring
linebacker Carlos Emmons, fullback Stanley Pritchett and offensive
lineman Jon Runyan through free agency. In the April college draft,
they selected defensive tackle Corey Simon of Florida State, a
possible future Warren Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia is definitely a team to watch next season in a
division, the NFC East, that is certain to be one of the toughest
in football.
</P>
<P>
   Young Torn Between Options
</P>
<P>
   According to someone close to the quarterback, Steve Young
simply cannot make up his mind about his future. One day, Young
will talk to friends about how he would like to finish his career
in Denver playing for Coach Mike Shanahan, one of the most
innovative minds in the game. Then the next day, Young says he will
retire, and the next, Young expresses the desire to finish his
playing career with the 49ers. Young has also expressed the desire
to become a football television analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Young's indecision was the reason he asked San Francisco for
extra time _ until June 10 _ to make a decision regarding his
future. Privately, the 49ers said they would like Young to retire
because they feared for his health. Young has sustained a number of
concussions, and San Francisco's line next year is expected to be
porous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
