<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS FIRED UP AND READY FOR GAME 7 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Intensity turned into raw emotion and spilled
toward the Portland Trail Blazers' bench with 36.6 seconds left in
Game 6 on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, perhaps in a flashback to his playing days, Coach Mike
Dunleavy decided to add emphasis to his team's 103-93 victory over
the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   As officials cleared away an altercation on the court, Dunleavy
rushed to the defense of his players and jumped in the face of the
instigator, Rick Fox. Dunleavy offered a few heated words that
might make a lip reader blush. Both the Portland coach and the
Lakers reserve forward were whistled for technical fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asking him for a good restaurant in Los Angeles,''
Dunleavy said, ``because I knew I was going to be down there this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers forced the four-of-seven-game Western
Conference finals to Game 7, which will be played in Los Angeles at
7:30 p.m. Eastern time on Sunday, and again avoided elimination
with stubbornness as much as skill. After losing twice at the Rose
Garden, they protected their home court like pit bulls and left the
Lakers asking how a 3-1 series lead evaporated into the showdown at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: equal parts Lakers' denial and Blazers' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not shocked,'' said Lakers Coach Phil Jackson, dismissing
any thoughts that his team might be reaching the panic stage. ``We
anticipated this would be a seven-game series.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant said: ``We're fine. On defense, we need to buckle
down. We just need to bring it all to the table on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' focus was apparent from the start in Game 6. Once
again, they flung themselves at the Lakers from all angles and set
a fast, physical pace. Portland's balanced scoring was led by Steve
Smith, with 26 points, and Bonzi Wells delivered the clinching
performance by scoring 14 of his 20 points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, a backup guard, hit five of seven shots, made all four of
his free throws, grabbed two rebounds and had two assists to help
fend off any rallies by the Lakers. Often posting low on the
smaller Brian Shaw and Ron Harper, Wells suddenly became the focal
point of the Blazers' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like street ball for a few minutes there,'' Wells
said. ``You get your basket, I'll get my basket. Mine just kept
going in.''
</P>
<P>
   On playing against Shaw and Harper, Wells added: ``I definitely
like to explore those matchups, and my teammates know it. I played
some forward before in college, so I'm not a stranger to playing
with my back to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against them, it's just a matter of making my shots. They
don't really respect me a lot, because I haven't done anything in
the league yet. I'm the youngest guy on our team, and to have the
guys go to me like that really means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Also for Portland, Rasheed Wallace continued his fine series
with 18 points and Damon Stoudamire scored 14. Defensively, the
Blazers did their best job on Shaquille O'Neal, holding the Lakers
center to 17 points on seven-of-17 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Neal, Bryant played the entire game. Playing with a
sprained foot from Game 5, Bryant scored 33 points. Beyond the
Lakers' two stars, though, nobody was able to close out Portland.
Glen Rice and Brian Shaw added 12 points each.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to stop us,'' Wells said. ``They've got to key on
five guys, not two, which is all we have to really concentrate on.
We've got a lot of different matchups that are causing them
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, despite two victories each at the other's arena, the
series will end with the Lakers having the home-court advantage.
Still, the Blazers have the momentum and are now in position to
become only the seventh team in National Basketball Association
history to win a four-of-seven-game series after falling behind by
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no momentum; there's no home-court advantage,''
Dunleavy said. ``It's one game now. You've got to come, and you've
got to bring it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
