<HEADER>
A3647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POLAND-EUROPE-760(2TA     06-03 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-EUROPE-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAND IS CAUGHT BETWEEN TWO LOYALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ Having finally achieved full NATO membership
only a year ago, Poland finds itself caught awkwardly between its
European aspirations and its loyalty to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   European officials, led by France, have pressured Poland to be
more accommodating toward a new European defense initiative, asking
the Poles to decide whether they really want to be members of the
European Union, senior Polish officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been told, `You have to make a choice _ be with the
U.S. or with us if you want to be Europeans,''' said a senior
Polish official. ``This poses a serious challenge for our foreign
policy, and it could be another pretext or justification for
delaying Polish accession to the European Union.''
</P>
<P>
   While defense issues will not decide the fate of Poland's
application to join the European Union, Foreign Minister Bronislaw
Geremek has said privately that he feels torn between his
Francophilia and his concept of Poland's national interests, which
call for a strong U.S. military presence in Europe and an
undiminished NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   What is at issue is the European Strategic Defense Plan, an
effort pressed by France _ and formally supported by the United
States _ to create a solely European armed force of 60,000 troops
capable of being deployed quickly to a place like Kosovo, for
example, and then staying for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Authorized in December, the force would be the military arm of
the European Union, with its own command staff, and would give the
nascent federal Europe the force to back up what is supposed to
become a single foreign and defense policy. The main civilian
charged with making this notion a reality by 2003 is the former
NATO secretary-general, Javier Solana, a Spaniard respected in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Poland, as a NATO member that wants to be in the European
Union, feels it has been frozen out of the planning for this
European military arm that it will have to join later. And many
Polish officials believe the reason for this exclusion is that
France believes Poland will act as a ``Trojan horse'' for U.S.
preferences inside the new grouping.
</P>
<P>
   Given Poland's history of conflict with Russia, Poland is deeply
skeptical about a European defense that does not keep the United
States intricately involved with its superior force, technology,
intelligence and nuclear might.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply don't believe that Europe without the United States
is safe,'' a senior Polish official said. ``If this century has
taught us anything, it's that Europe and North America are one
strategic space.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland is also being dragged unhappily into the trans-Atlantic
debate over U.S. plans for a missile-defense system, which
Europeans worry will separate their security from the United
States', at least in American minds.
</P>
<P>
   On these issues, the Poles are close to the British, full
members of both the European Union and NATO, which continental
Europeans often regard as too close to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although they strongly back the European defense initiative, the
British have worked closely with the Poles, arguing for
consultation by the 15 full members of the European Union with the
six non-European-Union members who are full members of NATO _
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Turkey, Iceland and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   British officials argue that Poland, a large country with a
strong military tradition, will be crucial to any new continental
force and should be involved in the planning.
</P>
<P>
   But French officials have made it clear that the planning will
be done by current European Union members only. With British
prodding, however, the European Union has just had its first
``consultations'' with the six other nations, including Turkey,
which has been even more vocal than Poland in raising alarms about
the possible dilution of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a senior Polish official and others said, Poland has
been facing French pressure and lobbying on issues ranging from the
percentage of European content in domestic broadcasting to vodka
trademarks to military procurement decisions. And they say the
French have hinted that membership negotiations on difficult topics
like agriculture and the environment will be easier if Poland
follows the federalist European line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not impressed with this policy of pressure and
gestures,'' said another senior Polish official. ``This is a
typical European dance around serious issues. And we will not be
forced to choose between NATO and the European Union _ both are
essential to Poland's future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He grimaced. ``It seems ridiculous to us that the 15 are not
taking our experiences and interests into account. The French
sometimes push too far and lose touch with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials here dismiss the accusation of pressure, with
one senior diplomat saying, in jest: ``Push them around? We haven't
even tried yet!''
</P>
<P>
   The French official said the Poles were too quick to run to the
Americans to complain about the European defense initiative. ``We
told the Poles that this appeal to Washington, making roughly the
same case as Turkey, was tactically wrong, and damaged the claim
that stems from their history.''
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France met with Geremek this spring
and reportedly asked him whether Poland wanted to be part of Europe
or to be ``the 51st state.'' They met again, later, when Chirac
insisted ``This idea of pressure is not true,'' the French official
said. France simply wants to build the new defense corps with
current European Union members, he said, ``and when we've decided
among ourselves, we will consult, so please be patient and accept
being outside for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Polish official involved in foreign and defense policy
answered: ``If we're not involved in the planning, and if our
application for the European Union is not acted upon until 2004 or
2005, then we can hardly prepare our forces to take part in the
ESDI. That strikes me as counterproductive for the whole
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Geremek, with a pained look, said slowly: ``Because of our
traumatic history, we want to belong to both NATO and the European
Union. Poland is attached to its sovereignty, and if we can give up
some part of it to Europe, it is only to defend our national
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the European initiative has produced the usual
schizophrenia: complaints about European unwillingness to ``share
the burden,'' and then nervousness whenever the Europeans,
traditionally prompted by the French, begin to act independently.
</P>
<P>
   These tensions are not conducive to further NATO expansion,
another senior Polish official said, especially since the likely
new candidates will include more strong advocates of Washington's
continued, pre-eminent role in NATO. Russian objections to
expanding NATO aside, the official said, ``The French fear that if
they enlarge NATO they'll get more American Trojan horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way through ``the triangle of the United States, the
European Union and Russia will be a very subtle task for Polish
foreign policy,'' the official said _ ``more difficult than joining
NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo proves the logic of a European foreign and security
policy capable of action, the official said. ``But we have to
preserve the coherence of the NATO alliance and the American
umbrella.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kulakowski, Poland's negotiator with the European Union,
said: ``We're asked, `Are you for America or Europe?' It's like
choosing your mother or your father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be a Trojan horse for the U.S. in Europe. We are a
European country, and we will show our solidarity, which doesn't
mean we have to challenge the United States. But on some issues,
we'll participate in some decisions of the EU that the U.S. won't
appreciate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
