<HEADLINE>
SAILING DOWNWIND AND INTO A DIFFERENT AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. _ ``I won't do cheesy to win; I won't
protest when it's not necessary,'' said Amanda Clark, allowing the
qualifying conjunction to begin tacking around her port side. ``But
I will not let the girls think that they can beat me. I will try to
keep the image of advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   If that means a jabbing remark or two flung into the wind as
boats come close in open sea, well, Clark is 18 years old now and
there are regattas in which she is the old lady fiercely determined
to qualify for the big race. She has set her mind on competing in
Sydney, Australia, this year, but she will have to wait until
December, long after the Olympics are over.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is a year older, 15 pounds heavier with weight-room muscle
and slightly colder-eyed than when we last met her. She was then
about to embark on a downwind summer that would fill her sails and
her potential to become a teen-aged member of the Olympic team. But
she didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympic trials for the Europe Class in San Francisco in
April, she got the jitters and started poorly. She made a
spectacular run from 18th place among 23 racers to finish third.
Only the winner would go to the Games, and that was Courtenay Dey,
who had coached Clark in a more innocent time.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, sitting as she was last week in the sunny, airy
living room of her parents' spacious house on this summer resort
island off the East End of Long Island, Clark remembered a
revelatory day with Dey when ``everything clicked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The boat just felt so good,'' Clark said. ``I wasn't fighting
the helm. The shape of the sail was right, nothing twisted, no big
wrinkles, and I felt the power of the boat and I felt in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going downwind,'' Clark recalled. ``I knew my limits and
I sailed the line, just how far I could push the boat without
flipping over. I had it. I knew it was time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   She moved from Optimists to the more competitive Europe
dinghies. There was another coach. The 2000 Olympics seemed
possible. The Shelter Island Yacht Club was at the heart of a
campaign that would eventually raise more than $50,000. There was a
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Courtenay Dey figured in a revelation, the older
woman was leaning out of her own boat at the Olympic trials and
saying, in a way that Clark found cutting and intimidating and
appropriate, ``Oh, you got a little close to the mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Dey, who is 35, had won a bronze medal in 1996 in the Europe
class. Her rivals were relieved when she entered the Olympic trials
in the 470 class earlier this year. But after she finished second,
she climbed back into a Europe dinghy. When Dey showed up at San
Francisco in April with a new mast and sail, Clark was nervous.
Many of the younger women told each other that the experienced Dey
would have the added advantage of old friends among the officials
who would cut her slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably true, but it's life,'' Clark said. ``A lot of
racing is psychological, and if people think you have some kind of
advantage, it's better to let them keep thinking that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Clark has been operating mostly on determination and
genes. Her grandfather, Albertus ``Toots'' Clark, was a
professional captain. Her father, Dennis, a painting contractor
here and one of the few local members of the yacht club, put
Amanda, her sister, Rebecca, and her brother, Greg, on his sailboat
just as soon as they were big enough to be rail meat. Her mother,
Ellen, who runs a recruitment agency for pharmaceutical scientists,
remembers that Amanda was never afraid as she became a tireless,
driven sailor.
</P>
<P>
   The family supported her passion, which has been expensive and
time-consuming; six-hour round trips to regional training centers
and regattas have become months in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The dream goes on. Clark is a child in the sport, although she
will begin traveling alone soon. Later this month, she will be
graduated with honors from Shelter Island High School. Before she
enters Connecticut College in the fall (there is a sailing team,
but no athletic scholarships), she will compete in the European
Championship in Spain and the Leiter Cup, in Newport, R.I., which
is the qualifying event for the Youth World Championships in Sydney
in December. Last year, Clark won a bronze at the Youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I'm going to be the Courtenay, the old lady,''
Clark said. ``It'll be my last chance to compete in the Youth, and
I want to win the gold. My plan for the summer is to get the fun
back in sailing and to play around with what I learned at the
trials. I'm preparing for 2004, too, the Athens Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   She says, just a little too perkily, that she was not
disappointed at missing the Olympic cut; when your biggest rival is
old enough to be your mother, there is time. Besides, she still has
kids to scare in her final 18-and-under regattas. She's been very
aware of a 15-year-old, still raw, but with a lot of ``spunk.''
Clark was reminded of herself, and those are just the ones you need
to intimidate and sail away from fast. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
