u a BC-JUVENILE-COURT-1STLD-     06-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-COURT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH COURT OF TRUE PEERS JUDGES WITH FIRM HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Adds NY dateline.) 
By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baseball caps and do-rags are dutifully removed while
court is in session. The prosecutor is a deliberative, soft-spoken
young man of 16 with a crown of cornrows. The defense lawyer is 16,
too, only recently out of jail on a charge of attempted murder. On
the six-member jury sits a girl with searing eyes and the memory of
juvenile jail still fresh in her mind. And when the accused, a
gawky 15-year-old charged with graffiti writing and weapons
possession, rattles off the names of gangs he has a ``beef'' with
at school, the courtroom congregation nods and murmurs knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not a high school moot court, where students pretend
to be players in a court of law. This is a court of law, a small,
quiet experiment in which Bronx teen-agers arrested on misdemeanor
charges and even minor felonies _ anything from graffiti writing to
small-time robberies and drug sales _ are judged, quite literally,
by a jury of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   They are all first-time defendants. They are referred here by a
probation officer or a judge, as an alternative to prosecution in
the city's overtaxed Family Court, where children under 16 are
tried.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers who run the Bronx Youth Court, begun two years
ago by youngsters organizing inside the city's juvenile jail, see
their mission as nothing short of what the Constitution guarantees:
a speedy trial before a jury of one's peers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them have been through the juvenile justice maze, what
they universally call ``the system.'' They know well the inside of
a juvenile jail (19 months in the case of Francisca Martinez, 16,
the defense lawyer, known in Youth Court as youth advocate). They
know how ponderously the Family Court can move (three and a half
months in detention for one juror, Latoya Orr, accused of stabbing
another girl, until a judge ruled in her case). Indeed, the court
seems to derive its very credibility from the youngsters' firsthand
knowledge of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got to talk to my lawyer the way I wanted to,'' said
Martinez, who was convicted of the stabbing. ``I wanted to be there
for somebody, being that nobody was there for me,'' she said in
explaining her mission.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of such youth courts is largely unproven, but
they have emerged across the country in the last decade, spurred by
a general sense of frustration with the juvenile justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 650 youth courts exist nationwide, compared with 50
in 1991, according to the Justice Department's Office of Juvenile
Justice and Delinquency Prevention. They handle mostly nonviolent
first-time defendants: children accused of shoplifting, vandalism,
starting schoolyard brawls and committing other crimes unlikely to
be prosecuted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feel-good quality to them,'' said Jeffrey Butts, a
senior research associate with the Urban Institute, a
Washington-based research organization, who is conducting a
national evaluation of youth courts for the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   That same quality gives experts like Butts a sense of deja vu.
``A hundred years ago, we invented juvenile court to get kids out
of the bureaucratic criminal court system,'' he said. ``Now we're
inventing youth courts to get them out of juvenile court, or to
create alternatives to that system.''
</P>
<P>
   There are four such courts in New York City, all fairly new. Two
were established by the state court system, in Harlem and in Red
Hook, Brooklyn. A third, in Hollis, Queens, was begun by civic
leaders and the city corporation counsel's office, which prosecutes
children in Family Court. All but the Bronx court handle youngsters
arrested for the smallest of infractions. A fourth of all the cases
tried in the Brooklyn Youth Court, for example, involve truancy, an
infraction that is not prosecuted in Family Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Youth Court is unusual because it judges more serious
offenses _ drug possession with intent to sell, robbery, weapons
charges. The idea is not to punish, but to help steer the accused
away from crime and provide some restitution to the community.
Among the judges, jurors and lawyers are those whose own sentences
include serving in youth court.
</P>
<P>
   Not many get off. Of the roughly 70 youngsters who have appeared
in the Bronx Youth Court in the last two years, only two have been,
in effect, acquitted, according to statistics maintained by Youth
Force, the youth-run community group that established the court.
</P>
<P>
   The City Probation Department does not keep exact figures,
though officials there say anecdotal evidence suggests that the
program is effective.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other day, as the late afternoon sun streamed in through the
barred windows at Youth Force's headquarters in Mott Haven, the
court was weighing the case of a freshman at Columbus High School.
Police believed that he had been a lookout for a graffiti crew. The
defendant, who agreed to allow a reporter to attend his trial on
the condition that his name not be used, said he had merely been
standing on the sidewalk trying to hail a cab while his friends
were ``bombing'' a wall with graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Peppering the defendant with questions, the jurors homed in on
certain details: The police had found a knife in the defendant's
pocket, and, it turned out, he had missed nearly three months of
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who carries a knife in their pocket, if they get
busted, there should be some sort of consequence,'' argued Dante
Motes, the prosecutor, known in the court as a community impact
assessor.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, removing his baseball cap at Martinez's urging,
said he felt unsafe at school. His friends, fellow
Albanian-Americans, had angered several gangs, and some were shot a
couple weeks before. That was why he wasn't going to school, he
said, and also why he carried a knife. ``People are looking to jump
me, shoot me,'' he cried. ``How you expect me to feel safe?''
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors were skeptical. His friends were shot only two weeks
ago, but he hadn't been in school for several months. If he really
felt unsafe, why didn't he go to the principal to seek a transfer
to another school?
</P>
<P>
   What did he do in his spare time? Were there youth centers near
his home? Why had he been hanging out with these friends, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   So it went for nearly two hours, as the jury struggled to
decipher the penal code and asked questions to understand the
defendant's life better.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, they learned, was in Yugoslavia. He lived with his
sister and brother in the Bronx. He was not in a gang. He was
trying to transfer to another school. He liked to play football.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating for 20 minutes in a closed room upstairs, the
jurors found him guilty on all counts. They sentenced him to a
two-hour legal rights workshop (mandatory for all Bronx Youth Court
defendants), four hours on a Youth Court jury, and 16 hours working
on a Youth Force community project. Such projects have included
voter registration drives and undercover stings against stores that
sell alcohol to minors.
</P>
<P>
   What lasting effect, if any, this will have on the young man
remains to be seen. Recidivism rates of Youth Court defendants are
only anecdotal, but supporters of the Bronx Youth Court and others
point to the alarmingly high recidivism rates in the juvenile
justice system. A recent study by the State Division of Criminal
Justice Services, for example, found that among boys incarcerated
in the state juvenile justice system, 81 percent were rearrested
within three years of their release.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Bronx Youth Court like to point out to their
peers how they fared in the juvenile justice system. ``From arrest
through court through incarceration, we went through feeling
confused, powerless and alone,'' reads a paragraph from a pamphlet
given to all defendants. ``Almost all of us came out of the system
disillusioned, better criminals, less educated and without the
resources needed to succeed.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
