<P>
   CANES-BEACHES _ When hurricanes roar ashore, they destroy miles
of beachfront, sweeping the sand back to the sea. To repair the
damage, communities from Gulf Shores, Ala., to Florida to North
Carolina's Outer Banks are relying on beach renourishment_a costly
plan of pumping sand back on the shore. Critics say it's a waste of
money and a sign that coastline development should be curbed.
Developers claim it's a logical step in protecting fancy homes and
high-rises. As the Atlantic hurricane season opens June 1, a look
at how well beach-front development can be protected.
(Manuel/Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   CANES-EVAC _ Last year when Hurricane Floyd threatened the
Southeast shoreline from Florida to Virginia, millions of people
swarmed inland during the largest peacetime evacuation in U.S.
history. Motorists clogged interstates in nightmarish proportions.
As hurricane season begins this week, a regional planning group is
looking at what was learned in Florida and the Carolinas to get
people out of danger without stalling them on the highway.
(Burritt/Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
