<P>
   WHOLESOME _ WASHINGTON _ On June 6, 1906, the House Committee on
Agriculture was embroiled in a debate on what should be covered by
a bill on food safety. Everyone agreed that meat ``unfit'' for
human consumption should be banned. But what about something that
might not hurt a person but might be ``offensive to his ideas as to
what he will consume?'' The bill said food should be ``wholesome,''
a term meat industry executives wanted cut. Despite nearly a
century of legislation, regulations, investigations and exposes,
the debate that began on that day 94 years ago is still very much
alive. (Jaspin, Cox News Service).
</P>
