<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE-RUSSIA _ In 1993, President Clinton delegated to his vice
president a sensitive and vital priority of U.S. foreign policy:
managing the United States relationship with the former Soviet
Union. Until 1998, Gore held ten high level talks with Russian
officials on everything from arms control to farm exports. The
bi-lateral commission, now teetering on the brink of extinction
because of political turmoil in Russia, achieved mixed results
during its five year existence, experts say. Analysts credit Gore
with a number of largely unpublicized successes in arms control,
but say he missed opportunities and remained oblivious to the
scandals that ultimately brought down Boris Yeltsin and his
long-serving prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin. (Foskett, Cox
News Service). 27''
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (p) Politics and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Just in time for Fathers' Day, the gun crowd is
shanghaiing no less than the Founding Fathers themselves into its
service, bandying about quotes from Jefferson, Franklin and others
to the effect that an armed citizenry is the surest, and an
essential, hedge against tyrannical government. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Oh, how the world is turning. It is almost
acceptable on the European side of the Atlantic that mistresses are
a tolerable part of daily life. Yes, there is some grouching but
reality is reality to Europeans. Now, on the U.S. side, mistresses
and other things naughty, while still raising some apoplectic
reaction, are becoming more common. (We give Europe Starbucks
Coffee and McDonald's and they give us mistress tolerance.)
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   DOLLIE-COLE - After the 1977 plane crash death of her husband,
former General Motors president Edward Cole, Fort Worth native
Dollie Cole returned to Texas and opened the Briarpatch Ranch nine
miles outside of Lockhart. Always involved in charitable pursuits,
the 70-year-old Dollie's main project now is the Pegasus School, a
residential treatment center for abused boys between the ages of
7-17. Besides donating 300 acres to the four campuses near
Lockhart, Dollie scours auctions, garage sales, estate sales etc.
and buys every bit of furniture for the school, as well as clothing
for the boys, who see her as their fairy godmother. She also has
got her high society friends involved - for instance, all soap,
shampoo and toiletry items comes from the Hilton hotel chain, a
gift from Baron Hilton. Don't call this woman who once designed a
Cadillac for the King of Saudia Arabia a socialite: instead she's
an intriguing, well-traveled woman with a refreshing philosophy of
giving. (Corcoran, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI-RIVERROAD _ On the famous River Road between Baton
Rouge and the Big Easy, the once-grand houses of the old sugar cane
plantations flank the Mississippi. Some are pristine and
refurbished; others are sagging and fading, forgotten beauty
queens. All sit in the shadow of the petrochemical empire. ``The
striking juxtaposition is what the modern age has supplied, a
reflection of ourselves and what we find important,'' photographer
Richard Sexton says. Sexton, an Atlanta native, grew up in
Georgia's Miller County. His latest book, ``Vestiges of Grandeur,''
is artistic documentation of one of the strangest, haunting
corridors in America, the so-called River Road. The geography is
specific, the debate universal. The River Road is many roads . . .
(Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ART _ HAVANA _ It's Sunday afternoon in a sweaty Havana
barrio called ``Callejon de Hamel,'' and curious tourists mingle
with dark-skinned Cubans as drummers pound out an Afro-Caribbean
beat and dancers sway to the hypnotic rhythm. Strolling through the
crowd, looking cool despite the sweltering heat, bearded, dark-eyed
Salvador Gonzalez greets friends, visitors and devotees to his
secluded, chic corner of Havana. Gonzalez has earned a world-wide
reputation as one of Cuba's most important mural painters. His
subject is Santeria, the mystical Afro-Cuban religion filled with
superstitions, animal sacrifices and frightening spirits that
correspond with Catholic saints. We profile Gonzalez and his work.
(MWilliams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., May 31, in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TONYS _ NEW YORK _ Symbolism fans must have relished the
1999-2000 Broadway season. With the century's close, it was indeed
the end of an era for commercial theater, marked by finales for two
blockbuster musicals and the deaths of two prominent impresarios
from an earlier, healthier theatrical time. Cats and Miss Saigon,
two British blockbuster musicals that dominated Broadway for the
past 18 and 10 years respectively, have posted their closing
notices. No more prancing kitties or roaring helicopters for
awhile. But the new productions of this season, which ends tonight
with the 54th annual Tony Awards telecast, prove that Broadway is
having trouble finding durable musicals for a new millennium.
(Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 70
</P>
