u a BC-CALIF-TEACHERS-TAXES-     06-03 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-TEACHERS-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN BENEFICIARIES OPPOSE PLAN TO REWARD TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was supposed to be a slam-dunk, a bold
aggressive play from a politician usually thought of as anything
but. Instead, Gov. Gray Davis' proposal to show support for
California's public school teachers by exempting them from state
income taxes has not been anywhere near the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders of both parties in both houses in Sacramento
oppose it as bad policy and the start of a slippery slope toward
similar demands from other public employees. Even the teachers'
unions, initially flattered, oppose the plan, which would reduce
the average experienced teacher's state tax by about $1,350 a year.
They say that it may leave them open to attacks from fellow
government workers and that they prefer salary increases instead.
</P>
<P>
   So far, about the only ringing endorsement has come from the
California Association of Highway Patrolmen, whose president, Mark
Muscardini, wrote Davis last week: ``Yes, we admit that our first
reaction was, `us too.' However, we would simply like to put our
own selfish interest aside long enough to express appreciation to
the teachers of California.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to the proposal shows the pitfalls when policy
innovation meets interest-group politics, along with the enduring
difficulty of reaching consensus on how best to address the
problems of California's troubled schools, which once led the
nation by many measures but have drifted toward the bottom over the
last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, has repeatedly vowed to make education his
top priority, but he has come under increasing fire from fellow
Democrats and the state's biggest teachers' union for not moving
quickly enough to return California's per-pupil spending on
elementary and secondary education to something like the national
average. The teacher tax exemption was part of some $3 billion in
new spending for education that he proposed in his nearly $100
billion budget for the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis aides described the exemption as the first such peacetime
tax break for any occupation in American history and hatched it in
greatest secrecy, planning to make a national splash with an
announcement in Sunday newspapers last month. It won big national
headlines, but a Bronx cheer from the audience of politicians whose
support was required to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not a good idea to exempt people from paying taxes
based on their profession, because one's favorite is not somebody
else's favorite,'' said John Burton, the Democratic president pro
tem of the State Senate and an old-line liberal from San Francisco.
``Start with teachers and go to cops and firefighters, go to social
workers, go to emergency room docs and news reporters. It's a very
slippery slope.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the governor counter that the state tax code is already
full of some $14 billion in special expenditures and preferential
treatment, for homeowners, the elderly and other groups. Davis
vowed to ``fight for this puppy,'' and his advisers expressed
puzzlement that the idea of exempting teachers had fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, teachers are the only constituency group in
California that still wants to pay taxes,'' one state official said
dryly.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' communications director, Philip Trounstine, said:
``What's appealing about it as an idea is that it makes a bold
statement, and the governor still believes this, both throughout
the state and across the country: that teaching is an extraordinary
profession and deserves extraordinary recognition and that in the
context of a shortage of perhaps 300,000 teachers over the next
decade and national competition to attract teachers to California,
this was a terrific way to let everyone know that teachers' work
was valued here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Johnson, president of the 500,000-member California
Teachers Association, the state's largest teachers' union, replied,
in essence, thanks but no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're somewhat uncomfortable in saying, `We understand you're
really trying to help us, but we just don't care much for the
idea,''' Johnson said. He said a poll of the union's membership
found that the measure was opposed by 60 percent and that when
other elements of the proposal were explained (including the fact
that teachers' federal taxes would rise because they could no
longer deduct state income taxes), opposition rose to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers that I'm talking to are saying that if this
proposal is going to cost roughly $500 million a year,'' Johnson
said, ``then take the $500 million and put it into the education
budget up front and let us bargain for it. They seemed to be far
more in favor of that kind of approach. I've heard things like,
`Well this singles us out, it makes us a sacred cow, alienates fire
and police and other public employees.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, since teachers consistently argue for higher taxes to
support public education and finance bonds for school construction,
he said, they do not want to be in the position of winning special
tax breaks that others could criticize. And because the tax
exemption would not constitute a direct expenditure on education,
it would not be counted as part of the percentage of state spending
that, by law, must be devoted to education.
</P>
<P>
   Davis can be stubborn, and as the first Democrat to lead the
state in 16 years, with partisan majorities in both legislative
houses, he has been used to getting his way since taking office
last year. Efforts are under way in Sacramento to find some form of
compromise that would let the governor claim moral victory while
quietly burying his big idea.
</P>
<P>
   These include proposals like raising starting salaries for
teachers, providing tax credits to teachers who buy supplies for
school and making new bonuses tax-free for teachers in schools that
improve their academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to value teachers, as we all do, there's a way to
do it: give them more money,'' said Burton, the Senate Democratic
leader. ``Increase starting pay, or reimburse them for certain
expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the governor's thinking suggested that he
might find some sort of general tax credit for teachers acceptable,
perhaps one phased in with rewards based on experience.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jack O'Connell, a Democrat and former social studies
teacher from San Luis Obispo, on the central coast, sponsored a
bill that passed the Senate this week, aimed at increasing starting
teacher salaries to about $38,000 a year, from the present range of
$26,000 to $32,000. It would reimburse districts that raise
starting salaries and would cost about $325 million.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he thought that the governor was willing to
entertain various ways of achieving his goal of attracting and
retaining teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor is totally wedded to the idea of making
teaching more attractive,'' he said. ``I just don't believe he is
wedded to any one particular concept. He's a bottom-line guy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DOLLIE-COLE0604-COX     06-03 2798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLIE-COLE0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By the Grace of God and Dollie Cole
 &HT;    By Michael Corcoran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Miss Dollie Cole! Miss Dollie Cole! `` a
buzz-headed boy of about 15 says when the well-dressed,
well-coiffed woman in oversized black-and-gold-framed glasses steps
out of her Suburban. ``I love my watch, Miss Dollie Cole.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiles and heads toward the horse stable to check the
condition of a horribly bony horse, which had just been snatched
from a life of mistreatment in Arizona. Two more kids in crew cuts
look up from their job of feeding and watering down the pony.
``Miss Dollie Cole!'' they say. ``Miss Dollie Cole!''
</P>
<P>
   It is a name that Robert Ellis remembers hearing over and over
when, after five years as a counselor at Darden Hill in Dripping
Springs, he launched his own residential treatment center for boys
near Lockhart. It was early 1990 and Ellis found an early supporter
in Brian McCoy, whose McCoy Building Supply Centers donated
materials to erect Pegasus School on land about five miles out of
town. When he asked the community for more help, people kept
telling Ellis that he needed to talk to Dollie Cole, the
charity-minded Lockhart rancher and widow of former General Motors
President Edward Cole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just called her up cold and told her about my plans,'' says
Ellis. She heartily agreed with his belief that the best way to
break the cycle of abuse is to give troubled kids positive role
models, and said she'd be getting in touch with him. A few weeks
went by, however, and Ellis still hadn't heard back from Cole, so
he was wondering whether she'd given him the brushoff.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day Miss Dollie Cole just drove up to the Pegasus
School towing a trailer full of desks, chairs, appliances and other
things the school would need before it opened in November1990. ``I
checked you out and heard good things, so I'll be helping you from
now on,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ellis and Cole have developed a mother-son
relationship. The 40-year-old Ellis even has to hide his cigarettes
from her. ``Dollie caught me smoking once in front of the boys and
she said, `Robert, you spend all your time and energy trying to
save these boys' lives; why do you want to show them how to kill
themselves?' '' By cashing in their pasts for the good of the
future, this unlikely pair has found a shared purpose and watched
enrollment at Pegasus soar from 15 to 97 boys.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the secondhand circuit with vigor, Cole completely
furnished Camp Pegasus, which opened in 1993 on land donated by
Austin's Robert Meyer. She bought three Capital Metro mini-buses to
transport the boys and pick up food and supplies and also gave
money as needed. Cole, who turned 70 May 13, also started getting
some of her oldest friends involved, including Redken founder Paula
Meehan, New Orleans Saints owner Tom Benson and hotel heir Barron
Hilton. Meehan paid for a road to be built, Benson gave money for a
basketball court, and Hilton made sure the school and camp were
stocked with toiletries from the Hilton chain. The kids, most of
whom had never stayed in a hotel before, had never seen such small
bottles of shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the kids, she's the fairy godmother,'' says Ellis. ``It's
never `Miss Cole,' never `Miss Dollie.' Always `Miss Dollie Cole.'
'' The name has a rhythm that suggests buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   She good-naturedly credits ``a touch of insanity'' with
inspiring her move back to Texas in 1983. How else could a woman,
then 53, leap from the lap of luxury into the rugged life of a
rancher? She named her spread Briarpatch Ranch after the prickly
bush that Brer Rabbit kept finding himself being thrown into.
</P>
<P>
   Before she met Robert Ellis, the unsinkable Dollie Cole had a
dream of her own in Lockhart. She wanted to open a historical Texas
village that would educate and entertain schoolkids and history
buffs. She bought and hauled the old Luling train depot, the house
of the first doctor in Caldwell County, and even the
still-operational Fentress skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Dollie overestimated the demand of the public
to revisit the Texas of old, and the Embassy closed in 1993. In May
1996, Pegasus offices moved into the village, and Dollie donated
300 acres south of Lockhart so Ellis and the boys could open Camp
Comanche and Cole Ranch, expanding the number of residents to 97.
The only problem was that the new locations, which included
administration offices, were seven miles from the Pegasus School.
So the plan is to close the original two campuses and move the
entire Pegasus operation to a central location on Cole Ranch. Ellis
expects the new Pegasus School to be completed in time for the 10th
anniversary celebration in November.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis credits his closeness with Cole to ``an absolute mutual
respect for what each other has accomplished on their own.''
They've found common ground in Lockhart, but the duo arrived there
through completely different paths. Ellis grew up poor in Lockhart,
suffering nightly beatings and sexual abuse from an alcoholic
stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   Once, while trying to escape the drunkard's wrath through a
narrow fence opening, Robert got stuck and his stepfather jumped on
the 12-year-old's leg and broke it in two places. Authorities sent
Ellis to a home for boys, but eight months later he was returned
home.
</P>
<P>
   When he reached 13, Ellis had had enough. ``My stepfather just
started whaling on me in the car one night, punching me in the face
while he drove, and I just opened the door and rolled out with the
car going.'' Ellis, whose name was originally Hill, ended up at the
doorstep of his best friends, Carl and Earl Ellis. Eventually the
Ellis family adopted Robert, who took his rage out on opposing
quarterbacks as a defensive end for the Lockhart High School team.
</P>
<P>
   But where some battered boys turn to crime, Ellis was able to
right himself because of what he calls ``an all-encompassing belief
in God. Even at a young age, in the midst of all that abuse, I felt
that someone was watching over me.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven years working for a demolition company right out of
high school, Ellis attended the University of Texas with the
intention of becoming an English teacher. Instead, destiny took him
to a job as camp counselor at the now-defunct Darden Hill
residential treatment center for emotionally disturbed boys. ``I
knew that this was what I wanted to do, but I wanted to do it a
little bit differently than they way they did it at Darden Hill,''
Ellis said. ``I wanted to start a place that was more about
positive reinforcement and less about discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the year Ellis was brought into the world by a single
mother, a Fort Worth rancher's daughter named Dollie Cole became
queen of Detroit, marrying General Motors President Edward N. Cole.
``As a rule, auto executives' wives tend to be relatively
anonymous,'' says Charlotte Craig, who covered the auto business
for the Detroit Free Press for 21 years. ``But that wasn't Dollie.
She was more flamboyant and outspoken than the rest, and she was
admired by some and resented by others because she stood out.''
</P>
<P>
   While married, Dollie wrote articles for the Saturday Evening
Post and eventually became a senior editor at the Post's parent
company, Curtis Publications. But even as she strived for her own
identity, Dollie says that ``my top priority was to be Mrs. Edward
Cole.'' When he died on May 2, 1977, after the British Beagle
aircraft he piloted ran into bad weather and crashed, Dollie was
devastated. ``I had to stay strong for (my son) Nick, though,'' she
says. ``He was only 10 years old when it happened, so helping him
through the tragedy became my focus.'' Dollie's three children from
her previous marriage to a Naval officer were adopted by Cole, but
they had already moved on to their careers by the time of the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   After years racing Corvettes, the car his father developed, Nick
Cole currently manages Dollie's expansive ranch, where the Coles
raise more than 40 racehorses, as well as the abandoned pets that
are often tossed over the ranch fence.
</P>
<P>
   She owns the desk Gen. McArthur used in the Philippines, but by
far the piece of furniture Dollie Cole values most is her husband's
old desk from when he was General Motors president from 1967 to
1975. She bought it after he retired and surprised him with it when
she redecorated his home office. Unable to part with the castle of
her own Camelot, Dollie kept the Michigan mansion, built and
designed by her husband, for 20 years after his death, though she
rarely stayed there. Finally, it got too expensive, with a tax bill
of $40,000 a year and rising upkeep costs, so Dollie sold her house
of memories two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the smartest man I ever met,'' Dollie says of the
automobile innovator who landed on the cover of Time magazine in
1959 after he designed the Corvair, America's first economy car.
She went to Stanford (majoring in special education), but Dollie
says, ``The best education I got was being married to Ed Cole. He
included me in everything. He taught me the auto business.''
</P>
<P>
   She's had quite a life, and nothing tells the story of her past
better than the walls of her eccentrically decorated house. Photos
of Dollie's young adult life as a glamour gal, modeling in ads for
Dr Pepper and winning the 1950 Miss West pageant, share wall space
with pictures of her with such world leaders as Margaret Thatcher,
Ronald Reagan, Barry Goldwater, George Bush and John Glenn. Her
best friends from the world of entertainment are also represented,
including Jim Nabors (``like a brother''), Phyllis Diller and
Florence Henderson. Her pal A.J. Foyt (``the greatest race car
driver who ever lived'') smiles back from several snapshots, and
from the business sector, there are pictures of Dollie with
manufacturing kingpin Rick Bowen (whose 70th birthday gift to
Dollie was a check for $10,000 to Pegasus).
</P>
<P>
   But don't call her a socialite. ``I hate that word,'' Dollie
says. ``To me a socialite is someone who wears expensive clothes
and jewelry and shows up at charity events to be seen. They might
not even know what the cause is. But I've never been someone who
just shows up and writes a check. I need to be in the trenches,
where the real work is.'' Busy'' describes Cole's schedule about as
meagerly as ``forceful'' does a Shaquille O'Neal dunk. She sits on
several boards, including Project HOPE, is chair of the National
Corvette Museum in Bowling Green, Ky., and is vice chair of the
Smithsonian's Air &AMP; Space Museum. She travels so often that Nanci
Falley, her personal assistant for the past 14 years (and a fellow
ranch owner), is the president of the board of Pegasus School, so
she can sign off on items when Dollie's out of town.
</P>
<P>
   There always seems to be enough time, however, to go out
trolling for something useful or unusual to buy. ``When I first met
Dollie, she said, `I don't drink and I don't smoke,' '' Ellis
recalls. `` `The only vice I have is auctions.' Boy, is that the
truth. Just last week Dollie bought four big gymnasium scoreboards
at an auction, then she spent all this time on the phone trying to
find someone who needed one.''
</P>
<P>
   A firm believer in creating beauty from the discarded, Cole
built her house piecemeal, using lumber she salvaged from the
Lockhart Cotton Compress. The finishing touch (at least for now),
is a Wendy's restaurant that Dollie bought at auction and had
hauled from Ben White to her ranch. After it sat in a field for two
years, Cole finally attached it to her house and uses the room to
entertain.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Sheehan of the Gaston &AMP; Sheehan auction house in
Pflugerville said the regulars get a big kick out of the elegant
Dollie, ``until she starts bidding on something they want,'' he
said. ``She's a super person, but she can be real shrewd and hard
as nails.'' The local bidding brigade knows that when Dollie sees
something that the school could use _ from bulldozers to
blackboards _ she'll go all out to get it. Another cause
well-served by Cole's auction addiction are the volunteer fire
departments in towns surrounding Lockhart. Dollie has provided
several firetrucks to towns, which repay the cost with no interest.
</P>
<P>
   It's Pegasus, however, that is foremost in Dollie's charitable
mind, and when she hears that a graduating senior had to scramble
for a cap and gown, she wishes she had been in town to help. Under
a sign that says ``Thou Shalt Not Whine,'' John B. thanks all his
teachers and staff of Pegasus and Miss Dollie Cole. ``I'm sorry for
some of the things I've done in the past, but I wouldn't trade my
experiences here for all the money in the world,'' he says, as his
grandmother weeps and hugs his sister. ``You were with me when I
was down and with me during the good times,'' he says to his
classmates. In the back of the room stands a group of Pegasus
``Colts,'' who at ages 9 to 13 look too young to be returning to
barrack-style dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the extreme example of latchhkey kids,'' Ellis says of
the Colts. ``In most cases their parents are too busy getting drunk
or taking drugs to care for their kids, so they're out running in
the streets at age 6,7,8.''
</P>
<P>
   John's the only one who graduated from the Pegasus School campus
this year, because most residents stay only about 18 months, or
when the money from their home counties runs out. Ellis says the
cost per kid is between $2,500 and $3,000 a month, most of which
goes to pay the staff of 85.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the drawbacks of the system is that we can fix a kid,
but then he'll often go back to the same broken environment,'' says
Ellis, who knows from experience. ``I look at what some of these
kids have gone through, and it seems like my life was Disneyland in
comparison. Some of them have never owned a toothbrush. They've
never been taught hygiene.''
</P>
<P>
   To give these forgotten children a better sense of self-worth, a
big part of their therapy is helping to revive distressed animals.
``It's great to feel needed,'' says Pegasus chief administrator
Mark Lowman, who followed Ellis from Darden Hill, along with
several other key personnel. ``The animals give these kids an
incredible amount of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis shows a photo of a teen (though his face is not shown per
the school's confidentiality policy) feeding a crippled piglet with
a baby bottle. ``This kid came to us in shackles, being led by two
officers,'' he says. ``He had so much anger and rage inside him
that the cops were afraid he'd attack them. But once he started
working with animals, we started seeing a new kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the residents in the Pegasus system are from the inner
city. They've never communed with nature before, but they learn to
camp, rock-climb and canoe. Several 16- and 17-year-olds even built
an Indian sweat lodge, where they are led in chants by counselor
John Sergent, who has performed tribal ceremonies with the Lakota
Indians for five years. And every year a group of Pegasus kids
earns a camping trip to Colorado through their good behavior and
grades. They're such a polite, hard-working bunch that you'd never
guess that, according to Ellis' estimates, 90 percent of the boys
had been sexually abused and all of them had been in trouble with
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Judging the recidivism rate by how many kids don't end up in
jail or prison, on probation or in other restrictive settings five
years after their stay at Pegasus, Ellis estimates that the program
is successful in about 80 percent of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis says that wayward kids truly do want some structure, some
guidance in their lives. Every morning the boys rise at 7 a.m. and
tackle one of 20 daily chores.
</P>
<P>
   Amen, says Dollie Cole, who's always preferred sweat to
champagne. ``God never meant this world to be easy,'' she says.
``If you don't spend your life trying to make it better for others,
then you're really missing out on a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to derail the cycle of abuse, Robert Ellis told her
in that out-of-the-blue phone call 10 years ago, is to expose
troubled kids to role models worth following.
</P>
<P>
   For Edward Cole's funeral, which was held at Detroit's St.
Francis School for Boys, one of the couple's favorite charities,
Dollie wrote a letter ``To My Children'' and signed it Edward Cole.
An actor friend read it at the service, and although Dollie has a
copy of the letter framed on her wall, she can't bear to read it.
It's just too sad to remember that time in her life. Instead, she
lives the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give, don't take, for happiness is giving,'' was one passage.
It's the philosophy that guides Dollie Cole in all the good that
she does. Don't call her a socialite. Robert Ellis certainly
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
