<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MISSISSIPPI-RIVERROAD     06-03 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSISSIPPI-RIVERROAD0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Historic route along Mississippi a story of extremes
 &HT;    By Rheta Grimsley Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALONG THE RIVER ROAD, La. _ Save your breath. This well-tramped
path defies description.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing subtle about the River Road _ nothing subtle or
common or middle-class or in-between. It is paved with extremes.
</P>
<P>
   The River Road _ not really one road at all but several _ is the
historic route between Baton Rouge and New Orleans along both sides
of the Mississippi River. At any given point through your car
window, the scenery is either dramatically rich or pitifully poor,
breathtakingly beautiful or terribly tacky. It is excess and want,
neglect and care, industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The River Road rolls through half a dozen parishes and a
multitude of towns with musical names: Gramercy and Vacherie,
Carville and Reserve, Plaquemine, Donaldsonville, White Castle and
Convent. It subdivides some of the richest land known to man, rich
both agriculturally and rich with oil. Then, of course, there's the
logistical cherry on top: It is situated next to one of the
nation's mightiest thoroughfares, the wet way to market, the
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Once this was the heart of Louisiana's sugar cane and cotton
plantation country. Now the petrochemical industry rules.
</P>
<P>
   But experts warn that oil reserves are playing out. Who knows
what we'll find a decade from now on Louisiana's River Road?
</P>
<P>
   Today there's no question what you'll find in the slow drive
down from Baton Rouge to the Big Easy. You'll find color. Riotous
color. A vine-wrapped little church posts the commandment ``Thou
Shalt Not Kill'' right beside its front door. A satellite dish
blooms in front of a century-old shotgun house.
</P>
<P>
   There are antebellum mansions in every stage of upkeep and
neglect, with tours 10 to 5, or No Trespassing signs. In fact signs
of all kinds are everywhere: Bill's Bail Bonds. Po Boys Served
Daily. Get Us Out of the United Nations. Repent!
</P>
<P>
   Cemeteries full of Catholic aristocrats and ornate shrines are
chockablock to ugly refineries, and industrial conveyors crisscross
the road like a hungry octopus' tentacles. Majestic live oaks shade
hubcap emporiums, and fine French lace hangs in the wavy windows of
gentrified cottages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The River Road is a study in juxtaposition that the modern age
has supplied,'' author Richard Sexton says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a reflection of ourselves, and what we feel is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   With his gorgeous book _ ``Vestiges of Grandeur: The Plantations
of Louisiana's River Road'' (Chronicle Books, $40) _ Sexton does
what no photographer really has done since Clarence John Laughlin
shot the derelict plantation homes half a century ago. ``Ghosts
Along the Mississippi'' is a classic and its creator, Laughlin,
``the predecessor I had to lurk in the shadow of,'' Sexton says.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton, 46, is an Atlanta native who grew up in small-town
Colquitt in Miller County. His family lived in a house just off the
courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   Young Richard graduated from Emory University in political
science, but while in college he also bought his first camera, a
Nikon F. That purchase changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Sexton moved to San Francisco, where he went to the Art
Institute for a spell. He began a notable career as a photographer
of architecture, interiors and gardens, or, as he puts it, ``the
human condition framed by architecture.'' In 1991, he moved back
home, to the South, to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't his first visit to that thrumming town. En route to
South America as a teenager, he had driven his Datsun to New
Orleans, his first stop after Colquitt. The city had impressed him
then, but he missed a few dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relocating to New Orleans was a move to a new and exotic city
and a return to the familiar climate and terrain of the Gulf
South,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The return seems predestined. Though he has numerous books to
his credit, Sexton's Louisiana photography is exceptionally
organic. He writes about the ``swampy infinity'' of the River Road
as if he grew up here, and nobody packs such a wallop with a shot
of cracked ceiling plaster.
</P>
<P>
   He knew about the River Road plantations _ that some had been
``prettied up too much and some had gone to seed'' _ but hesitated
to tackle the well-traveled theme. But after he finished the photo
essay book ``New Orleans: Elegance and Decadence,'' Sexton decided
to put his stamp on the River Road subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   He'll tell you he has tandem desires. To shoot compelling,
artistic images, but only the ones that document a particular place
and a particular time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell stories with photos,'' he says. We are seated in his
New Orleans studio on Dauphine Street near the French Quarter. His
old Creole cottage is the color of mustard. In the courtyard behind
us pink impatiens overflow a pot. The streets are steamy, and the
whole world seems one big photo essay.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Colquitt when I was growing up, we didn't have art museums
and galleries. But in our home we did get all the big picture
magazines _ Life and Look. That was really my inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton was met with ``some reticence'' when he asked permission
to photograph the plantations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the owners are not proud of the condition of the
houses,'' he says. (Petroleum companies own many of them.)
</P>
<P>
   But Sexton stressed he was searching for ``the inherent beauty
still within.'' He began shooting any surviving vestiges of the
historic River Road, from the perfectly restored houses to rubble.
He steadfastly refused to be judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book represents as flattering a view of the landscape as
one can take,'' he insists. And that claim seems true, even when
blue sky shows through a collapsed ceiling of a neglected parlor
filled with ruined antiques, or a fine old home is dwarfed by
smokestacks.
</P>
<P>
   There were many examples of both ``corporate responsibility and
lack thereof,'' he says. But the petrochemical companies that now
wield the power on the River Road are not the entire picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic vitality is a national story, along with the
evolution of land use. One of the most dramatic evolutions that's
ever occurred was here. And it's not over. The oil reserves will be
depleted and the landscape will morph into something else, maybe go
back to nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton hopes agriculture will survive in some form along the
River Road. Growing up in South Georgia gave him an appreciation
for the family farm, and he rues the fact that each year fewer
Americans claim agribusiness as a livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   But any wide open spaces along the River Road are long gone,
vanished. Any time a petrochemical company chooses a new site, it's
got to be at the expense of something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``A historic building will be torn down, a Native American
burial site disturbed . . .''
</P>
<P>
   At book signings along the River Road, Sexton sometimes heard in
person from the owners of his architectural subjects. Most comments
were approving. Owners of the once-grand homes still felt ``some
sort of pride, no matter how tainted by the condition,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still see in this something positive, that vestige of
grandeur.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
