<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-YOEL-LEVIQ&AMP;A0604-COX     06-03 2085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOEL-LEVIQ&AMP;A0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yoel Levi: The exit interview
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some things never change in the Yoel Levi clan. The
family still scavenges for pets in the woods near its Sandy Springs
home and gives them names like Egmont (from the Beethoven overture)
and Berlioz. Oldest son Eyal, 21, is still into long hair and heavy
metal. And the maestro, in his final days as conductor of the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, remains as enigmatic as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Like another lame duck baby boomer, President Clinton, Levi
seems to have no idea what he's going to do next. He recently lost
his cell phone. He's never bothered to get on the Internet. He is
being managed by a Dutch talent agency. But this much is certain:
As he kicks off the monumental cycle of Beethoven concerts marking
the end of his 12-year tenure with the ASO, he is holding true to
his essential self: kind-mannered, yet emotionally cloistered,
bittersweet but determined not to show it _ a picture of
undiminished pride, egotism and musical vigor.
</P>
<P>
   How history will deal with Levi is an open question. Only 49, he
could end up a globe-trotting orchestra builder, the Jimmy Carter
of classical music. Or he might be remembered as a political
bungler _ paranoid, misunderstood, yet ultimately hallowed, like
Richard Nixon. On this day, Levi sits stiffly through a lunch at
his restaurant of choice, then sticks on his best Bill Clinton
smile for a photo shoot at a nearby Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a stylish, European-cut gray suit, a black mock
turtleneck and an up-to-the-minute Nike joggers' watch, he is at
first resistant to talk about much of anything _ his personal life,
his future, even his beloved Beethoven. ``People are always asking
me, `What are you going to do? What is your next job?' They don't
understand: You don't need to have a job as a permanent conductor.
You can just do guest conducting.''
</P>
<P>
   Determined to put a positive spin on his exit, he refuses to
dwell much on the controversy surrounding his dismissal. Yet he is
quick to point up the need for a new Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he surrenders to the childlike flights of fancy that
have characterized him in the past, going off on a riff about the
``special breed of musical flies'' that appear when he's onstage at
Symphony Hall. And he proudly shows off a program from his middle
son Amir's recent Atlanta International School production, where
the graduating senior staged a music and dance revue that included
his older brother and family friend Amber Boardman, whom the Levis
have taken under their wing.
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened backstage after your Mahler concerts a couple
of weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``First of all, there were a lot of people, a lot, every
night. It was very tense, very emotional. People were crying and
couldn't hold back. Thank God, I hold my ground, because I really
don't like to lose my composure. But people are very sincere, very
emotional, very thankful. There was an old lady in my room who I'd
never met. She asked me if I would forgive them (the ASO board that
fired him). I said: `It's OK. Everything is fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you feel like you have made your peace with the
organization?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I think so, and there is no question that I will always be
grateful for the role of (recently departed board chairman) A.D.
Frazier for making things happen and trying to heal this community.
I will always consider him a personal, dear friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And have you achieved what you set out to do here?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Yes, anyone who listens to our records, 30 records, will
hear that this is incredibly, truly a great-sounding orchestra, and
I hope that's what is going to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: As you say goodbye, what do you want to say to the community?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Thank you. (He pauses as if that's all he has to say.)
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's more than thank you. It's a community I can't thank
enough for their support. The support they have shown me is
something I will never forget. It is something that has never
happened in the history of U.S. orchestras. I don't know if it will
ever happen again. But it's something that means a lot to me, the
support, the letters, the way they react every time I step on the
podium _ it's something I will always take with me in my heart, and
I will always be very grateful for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And to the musicians?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I will thank them for everything they have done for me _
all the wonderful concerts, recordings, tours, for working hard and
rising to the occasion every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And to the board?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I would thank them for everything they have done for this
organization, because at the end of the day, you cannot do it alone
and you need help. I just thank them for the opportunity they gave
me. I only gave my best. Now the responsibility belongs to someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What advice do you have for new music director Robert Spano?
</P>
<P>
   A: (He laughs) ``Ah? Advice? I don't know. Just to make great
music. He's getting a very precious instrument in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: He has said so publicly.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``And I really appreciate that. If people think it's the same
orchestra I got when I came here, they have a very short memory or
a lack of understanding or are practically ignorant. Or deaf.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: ASO President Allison Vulgamore said recently that she
regretted the decision not to renew the tenure of the six musicians
(which ultimately led to the musicians strike of 1996). Do you have
any regrets?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Maybe. You can always look back at things and say, `Well,
maybe I would have done it differently here or differently there.
There is no point in going back, because you cannot change what
happened in the past. You have to go forward. But you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you offer a better explanation of why your relationship
with the ASO did not work out?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I think every relationship has a life. I only know what I
did. I did my best to bring this orchestra to where I promised I
would bring it from Day One... This is what I did. I cannot comment
for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you glad you stayed these last two years?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Absolutely, absolutely. Except even now, they still have a
gap of one year that there's almost no one there. Who knows what
would have happened? But in any case, I am very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's lacking in Atlanta's cultural life?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The commitment, the vision. I mean, we have been talking
about a new concert hall for how many years? Since Day One that I
arrived here. And yes, there is a moment again, so I believe in
this coming decade probably something will happen, but why does it
have to take so long? The resources are here. It's one of the
richest cities in America. . . . Obviously, it's not on the
priority list. It's sad. Atlanta is really behind almost any other
city in having a first-class facility, whether you look at Dallas
or Baltimore or St. Louis or Pittsburgh. Wherever you look! They
have a better facility than here in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will it take to change that?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I don't know. If people don't have enough reasons up to
this moment, then they will never have enough reasons. It's about
how much they really care, truly care about how Atlanta is
portrayed in the world. That's the bottom line. They can tell you,
`Oh, we are really proud. We really care.' But do they really care?
If they really cared about the cultural ambition of this city, we
would have had here a great concert hall five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you be willing to help raise money for a new hall?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I can always try to help. I cannot guarantee what people
will do. I let them always use my name for anything they need, and
I do not see why they cannot use it in the future. As long as our
relationship continues, I will be very happy to help. I rarely say
no to anything. But there's only so much I can do after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did you pick Beethoven for your last concerts?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``To do a marathon of this nature, very few people have ever
done it. Ever. Period. Very few people have the talent or the
capability or the understanding to do it. For me, to do all the
Beethoven symphonies and concertos in two weeks, it's one of the
highest musical achievements that anyone can really dream of.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the orchestra, Beethoven is one of the most difficult
things. You are exposed. You cannot hide. You have to produce true
quality. This is a marathon for everyone, not only for me, but for
each musician. . . . Who knows if they will ever have this
challenge again?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have anything new to say with it intellectually?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``There's always new things about Beethoven. You always find
a different way to do it, a different experience, a different
meaning. And you accomplish it in the rehearsals and hopefully it
comes alive in the concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are you not doing the Missa Solemnis?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We just don't have time. I did the Missa Solemnis a few
years ago, and this was something very special. That was the only
time I worked with Robert Shaw. He prepared the chorus and it was a
very special time with him, talking about the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: He loved to talk about it!
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Yeah, and he told me the last time he had prepared the
Missa Solemnis was for Toscanini, and I told him how much I really
appreciated it. I will never forget what he has done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you must be taking a long vacation after these concerts?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``No, I have to go to Florence. I will be doing Puccini's
`The Girl of the Golden West.' I will be a month there.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What else is on your plate this season?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I want to take some time off. I really need it. This will
be the first time in over 20 years that I can have a little bit of
time off to do things, to read, relax, travel, do what I want, look
at the world a little bit differently. That's what I am going to do
next year. I will still conduct from time to time, but I will not
be pushing myself to run from one place to the next. I want to
spend time with my young one (Daniel, 10), the only one that is
going to be home now.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: It sounds as if you are going to be working more in Europe
than America.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Maybe in the short term I am going to dedicate myself more
to projects in Europe. But in the long term my future will be here
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the long term, do you want to be music director of another
major U.S. orchestra?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Sure. Eventually. Maybe not now, but eventually. I have
proven to myself that I can take an orchestra at a certain level
and change them and create a great orchestra, so I believe I can do
it anyplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: But if it's a second-tier orchestra, you will not go there?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``No, I will not go there. But I can always take any level of
orchestra and make them absolutely one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you want to be known as The Orchestra Doctor?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, not really. That's the role of any conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's one of the funniest things that's ever happened to you
onstage?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I don't know that anyone knows that we are developing a
very special breed of musical flies at the concert hall. This is a
very funny phenomenon. Sometimes they interfere with the
conducting. As a matter of fact, I must tell you that at one of my
last concerts, the Mahler, it sat on my right hand in the middle of
the piece. During the rehearsal, when we see the fly, I say, `Oh,
he's back! He likes Mahler!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when the musicians see a quick movement from me that
was not meant to be, then they realize it was a fly. At one point
it even sat on my baton in the middle of a concert. I could not
believe it: On the end of the baton was a fly! Sometimes I tell the
musicians: `Whoever destroys the fly gets a bonus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that the end is here, you seem OK with it.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Change is something good for you. There is no question that
I am a much stronger person than I have ever been in my life,
wiser, more experienced, and I am very happy what the future will
bring to me. There's a saying in the Jewish tradition: When God
closes one door, he opens another door. Look, a man should be happy
with what he's blessed with. As long as you have your health, your
talent, your family _ not necessarily in that order _ as long as
you have these ingredients, there is no reason to look back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
