<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HENSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERIPATETIC SPORTING LIFE OF A YANKEE PROSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWICH, Conn. _ Like many of his classmates at the University
of Michigan, Drew Henson spent the week of spring break in Florida.
But for Henson it was no week on the beach, but a week of baseball
with Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill and other Yankees at the team's
spring training complex in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, Henson was back on the Michigan campus in
Ann Arbor throwing passes to his receivers during the start of
spring football practice. Then, a week after the 15 football
practices ended, on April 15, Henson took his last final exam. The
next day, he flew back to join the Tampa Yankees, the parent club's
Class A affiliate in the Florida State League. Two weeks later,
after hitting .333 in five games for Tampa, Henson headed north to
join the Yankees' Class AA affiliate, the Norwich Navigators of the
Eastern League.
</P>
<P>
   Such has been the peripatetic academic and sporting life of Drew
Henson, who will be Michigan's starting quarterback this fall _ and
presumably also in 2001 _ and who, in a few years, is expected to
take over at third base for the Yankees. In fact, Mark Newman, the
Yankees' vice president for baseball operations, says he will not
be surprised if Henson, who is 20, is in a Yankee uniform by next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about an extraordinary baseball talent here,''
Newman said. ``Drew is not just your everyday good baseball
prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   So good that the Yankees gave the 6-foot-5-inch, 225-pound
Henson a $2 million signing bonus after he graduated from Brighton
(Mich.) High School in 1998 while knowing that he had accepted a
football scholarship to Michigan and that he planned to play four
years of college football. Under his arrangement with the Yankees,
this season and next, Henson will play his last baseball game on
July 31 so that he can be in Ann Arbor the next day for the start
of preseason football practice.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Henson is not about to complain about the
difficulty of playing two sports whose seasons interlock.
``Physically, it's no problem,'' Henson said before Tuesday's game
at Dodd Stadium in Norwich. ``But at times I could use a mental
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   A smooth fielder with a rifle arm and good range who hits both
for average and power, Henson is regarded as the Yankees' next best
prospect after first baseman Nick Johnson, whom Henson is expected
to join on the Class AAA Columbus Clippers next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Before he threw his first pass for Michigan in the 1998 season,
Henson had already spent one season with the Tampa Yankees of the
rookie Gulf Coast League, where he batted .318. Last year Henson
hit .280 with 13 home runs in 69 games for the Class A Tampa
Yankees of the Florida State League.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday night's game in Binghamton, N.Y., Henson was
hitting a team-high .302, with 25 hits, three home runs, 16 runs
batted in and a .477 slugging percentage in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for Drew is not to expect too much too soon,'' said
Dan Radison, a career minor leaguer who is in his first year as
manager at Norwich. ``He's in a learning process here, and he's got
to remember that. He's not going to tear up the league at the
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Radison has seen enough to be impressed. ``Drew is
something special,'' Radison said. ``He has a relaxed manner, nice
soft hands in the field and an easy swing that can send the ball a
long way. He's the real deal _ the whole package _ and he can't
miss.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been the whole package since high school, where he was a
straight-A student, the co-valedictorian of his graduating class
and a member of the National Honor Society, scoring 1,360 on the
College Boards. As a senior, he was not only rated the top football
prospect in the Midwest and one of the top three in the nation, but
he was also named high school player of the year in baseball by
Baseball America after setting a national high school record of 70
home runs over four seasons. In addition, he set a school scoring
record in basketball while averaging more than 20 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Henson comes by his athletic genes naturally: his father, Dan,
was a college football coach and his mother, Carol, taught and
coached basketball. Henson's sister, Brittany, is a star basketball
and volleyball player at Brighton High. The family moved to
Michigan from Utah during Henson's freshman year in high school
when his father became the offensive coordinator at Eastern
Michigan. The elder Henson is now the head football agent at the
International Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   Henson is a dean's list student at Michigan, where he will be
starting his junior year in September. As the backup quarterback to
Tom Brady the last two seasons, Henson appeared in 18 games,
completing 68 of 137 passes for 800 yards and six touchdowns. As
the starter this season, he is expected to be one of the top
quarterbacks in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to appreciate what Drew has done playing football
and baseball,'' said Lloyd Carr, the Michigan football coach.
``He's so talented as a football player that if he stays in the
game he'll be one of the first three or four quarterbacks picked in
the NFL draft in 2002. If he wasn't playing baseball, he'd be even
further advanced, but he's trying to climb both Mount Everest and
Mount Annapurna.''
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, Henson will decide to climb as high as he can in
the Yankees' system and perhaps play alongside a fellow
Michigander, Jeter, on the left side of the infield. Mainly because
of Jeter, Henson is represented by Jeter's agent, Casey Close, who
is with the International Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what I'll do, but I won't play both
professionally,'' Henson said. ``I'll base my decision on what
sport I think I can play the longest without serious injury.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Henson is looking ahead to returning to Michigan and
plans to start throwing a football soon to some of his Navigator
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find a high school field, and I'll throw some,'' he
said. ``I also plan to fly in two of my receivers at Michigan _
Dave Terrell and Marquise Walker _ in July and throw to them,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   A $2 million ``bonus baby'' can afford to do such things. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
