<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-760(     06-03 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERM LIMIT BATTLE ROUND 2; THE NADER CHALLENGE; THE KASICH
NONCANDIDACY; NEVADA GOP'S ABORTION VOTE; A BUSH LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., Nev., Ohio)   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reinforcements are coming to the aid of Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, since Nethercutt broke his pledge to serve
only six years in the House, he has been the target of a relentless
advertising assault by U.S. Term Limits. The advocacy group's
no-punches-pulled message: George Nethercutt is a liar.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt has fought back with his own advertising campaign,
calling officials of U.S. Term Limits felons. But the Washington
State Republican Committee, seeing the need for even stronger
measures, has just opened a $100,000 advertising blitz that it
hopes will ensure the Spokane-area seat does not fall into
Democratic hands. The committee's message, delivered in a
commercial drawn up by the National Republican Campaign Committee:
U.S. Term Limits is engaged in ``mudslinging paid for by secret
donors.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the betting is that Nethercutt will probably be
able to hang on. Still, few House races in the country are more
bitterly contested than this one. But, then, few have the
love-gone-sour aspect this one has.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, U.S. Term Limits made Nethercutt its poster boy
when his pledge to serve only three terms on Capitol Hill helped
him unseat Speaker Tom Foley, a 15-term Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Hell hath no fury ...
</P>
<P>
   NADER GROWS HEAVIER IN POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Now and again Ralph Nader may come forth with a play on words,
as in the title of his book on the auto industry, ``Unsafe At Any
Speed.'' But with him, the issue is the thing, and so he is mostly
seriously serious.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment he is seriously serious about running for
president _ so serious that he is pulling close to 5 percent of the
vote in many national polls, much of it at the expense of Vice
President Al Gore. There is serious talk that he could cost the
Democrats the White House.
</P>
<P>
   To get to that 5 percent level, Nader has been working the
college circuit hard, using his anti-establishment pitch to appeal
to the just-old-enough-to-vote crowd. And that crowd, all baggy
pants and tattoos and go-Ralph laughter, seems to be having a
relaxing effect on the buttoned-down 66-year-old consumer crusader.
</P>
<P>
   Nader tells them heavy things, like, for example, ``What this
campaign is really about is breaking the grip of the two-party
duopoly on American politics.'' Then he might segue into a light
riff about how he was asked to go on a Superman television special
to warn about ``the dangers of kryptonite.'' After that, he lets
drop that, well, he may look square but he's hip, with a list of
supporters and fund-raisers that includes the likes of Jackson
Browne, Phil Donahue, the Indigo Girls, Pearl Jam, Willie Nelson,
Paul Newman, Bonnie Raitt, Linda Ronstadt and Susan Sarandon.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the teen-ager, leather-clad, body-pierced, hair
dyed Day-Glo pink, who crowded close to him at a recent rally on
the Boston Common.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope,'' Nader said, ``the dye was at least organic.''
</P>
<P>
   OHIO: KASICH WITH AN EYE ON THE FUTURE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, was one of the first candidates to
drop out of this year's race for the presidential nomination. And
though he is chairman of the House Budget Committee, a major power
post, he is not seeking re-election to a 10th term in Ohio's 12th
Congressional District, which stretches north from Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   So is Kasich abandoning politics for good, having spent almost
half his 48 years in elective office?
</P>
<P>
   No way, he insists.
</P>
<P>
   While he has started looking for a nonpolitical job to settle
into once he leaves Congress, perhaps something in the business
world, he says he will stay involved in politics and may even run
for office again, possibly president. To that end, he disclosed
last week, he has formed a political action committee, the New
Century Project, with the goal of raising $500,000 over the next
year for distribution to candidates around the country who strike
his political fancy _ limited-government conservatives like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my way of continuing to be in public service without
holding public office,'' Kasich told The Columbus Dispatch. ``And
to do that, frankly, you have to have some resources, some staff,
an organization. It will allow me to build a network of people
around the country who I will have a relationship with and who are
potential supporters for me in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A footnote: His presidential campaign committee, Kasich 2000, is
still in operation and will finance his political travels this
year. It has almost $1 million in the till, according to the latest
Federal Election Commission report.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA: GOP SAYS NO TO ANTI-ABORTION RESOLUTION
</P>
<P>
   Nevada is a state in which voters are always given an extra
choice on the ballot: ``None of These Candidates.'' And ``None''
has been known to finish first in some minor races.
</P>
<P>
   It follows, then, that Nevada politics can sometimes be
unpredictable and filled with surprises. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   In last weekend's Republican State Convention in Carson City,
the delegates passed resolutions opposing legalized marijuana,
same-sex marriages and openly gay people serving in the military.
</P>
<P>
   No surprises there. Then the delegates passed a resolution
opposing U.S. membership in the United Nations and calling for the
United Nations and its staff to be moved off American soil.
</P>
<P>
   That raised an eyebrow or two.
</P>
<P>
   But the real eye-opener came when the delegates, after noisy
debate, voted 166 to 149 to kill a resolution declaring that the
party opposed all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   With many leading Nevada Republicans opposed to abortion, the
expectation going into the convention was that the anti-abortion
resolution, having already made it through committee, would be
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the resolution carried the day by contending that
the party would do better in the fall elections if it took no
position on abortion and allowed individual candidates to express
their individual views. Many of those delegates wore buttons
warning: ``GOP Pothole Ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   POLLS SAY BUSH LEADS IN ELECTORAL VOTES
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline, the popular Internet political tip sheet, keeps a
running tab of presidential preference polls in various states as
they become available. Here is how things stood overall at the end
of last week:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush led in 26 states, worth 282 electoral votes.
Vice President Al Gore led in 13 states, worth 178 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Needed to win: 270 electoral votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
