u i BC-THIRDWAY-LEADERS-NYT &LR;      06-03 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIRDWAY-LEADERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING CLUB OF LEADERS STRAINS TO FIND A CLEAR FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ When they met in Italy one year ago, they were leaders
of a ``Third Way'' and their founding members were President
Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as Clinton joined 12 other left-of-center
presidents and prime ministers here, the Third Way was banished in
favor of ``Progressive Governance.'' And Blair, pleading the need
to help his wife care for their new baby, decided to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was that although the meetings were unshakably
friendly _ the main agenda was ``dialogue,'' interspersed with a
few good meals _ leaders found themselves struggling for words.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody agreed that they stood for a new brand of
social-democratic leaders who support free trade and globalization
yet are determined to soften their harsher effects through strong
government support for social justice, education and public health.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps inevitably, most of the conclusions beyond that were
murky.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Saturday, the Third Way had brought German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder a measure of political heartburn. In a
move he later admitted was a mistake, Schroeder infuriated
left-wing traditionalists in his Social Democratic Party last year
when he signed a ``Third Way'' declaration with Blair praising
economic deregulation and greater support for business.
</P>
<P>
   The new mantra of Progressive Governance appears to have several
virtues. It implies modernization and a focus on the future, both
key themes for Europe's new generation of pragmatic
social-democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the word ``progressive'' carries echoes of
more traditional Socialist goals like income redistribution and
strong government.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Perger, an editor of the influential German news weekly
Die Zeit and a German delegate to Saturday's meeting, said that
those echoes were enough to set themselves apart rhetorically from
center-right leaders like French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac, who is neither Third Way nor Progressive, was not
invited. But Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of France, one of
Europe's most traditional Socialist leaders, is a charter member of
the group.
</P>
<P>
   Although some members, like Blair, have strongly pro-business
views, the leaders here rarely if ever mentioned the word
``reform.'' Perger said that may have reflected a recognition that,
in Europe at least, ``reform'' has become largely synonymous with
deregulation and reduced government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who helped coin the phrase Third Way and wanted to make
the new club of like-minded leaders a part of his legacy, admitted
he was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Third Way because it is sort of easy to remember,''
he said wistfully Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien of Canada had his own proposal for
a new label: ``I am the radical center,'' he remarked.
</P>
<P>
   In their concluding communique, the leaders praised the
so-called New Economy and said they accepted economic globalization
but were duty-bound to temper the harsher effects of reliance on
unfettered market competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are leaders who are aware of the opportunities of
globalization, without denying the dangers,'' the communique said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization must lead to higher living standards for all and
not a destructive race to the bottom at the expense of
environmental and worker protections.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference Saturday was the first time that the former Third
Way club has invited leaders from Latin America and South Africa.
The newest members were President Ricardo Lagos of Chile, President
Fernando de la Rua of Argentina, President Henrique Cardoso of
Brazil and President Thabo Mbeki of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion made identifying the criteria for membership more
difficult. The group, for example, does not include the
social-democratic president of Finland, one of the Europe Union's
fastest-growing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the group include Jose Maria Aznar, the center-right
prime minister of Spain who is arguably closer in mind-set to the
Progressives than he is to Spain's own Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   There was enormous speculation about whether Blair was now
trying to distance himself from the group because it had tilted too
much toward the likes of Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder of Germany made a special point of denying such
rumors, saying Blair stayed in London purely because he wanted to
help his wife, Cherie, with their baby.
</P>
<P>
   There were political reasons to believe those claims: Blair had
come under a fair amount of political razzing in Britain because he
refused his wife's request to take time off from work for paternal
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, with a grin, jumped in with assurances on the question.
``The Third Way and Progressive Governing are pro-family,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
