u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-DALLENBACH     06-03 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DALLENBACH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLENBACH TRYING TO FIND THE RIGHT PIECES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach finished 28th in last Sunday's Coca-Cola 600,
but for the veteran driver, it's not about where he finishes now.
It's about where he finishes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach is the driver of Darwin Oordt's Galaxy Motorsports
Ford. Although Dallenbach has been in NASCAR 10 years, his team has
been together less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Oordt recently hired Newt Moore to take over as crew chief. Like
Dallenbach, Moore has moved around trying to find the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to this team, things were as bad as I've ever seen
them,'' Dallenbach said candidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get the right people. At the start of the year,
everybody's set. Everybody's optimistic and talking about winning
the championship,'' he said. ``Then things happen and you start
having changes. When people become available, you've got to pick
them up,'' Dallenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   So Galaxy Motorsports has been doing that, hoping, in the
process, to strengthen the team. Dallenbach thinks they are on the
right track, which is why he is not overly concerned with where he
finishes now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only important to have good people, you need to have
people you like to be around because you probably spend more time
with them than you do your family,'' Dallenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach has a wealth of experience to draw from. He's been
with two powerhouse organizations, driving for both Jack Roush and
Rick Hendrick. He's also been with owners who have had to scramble,
like Bud Moore and Junie Donlavey. And he's been with Richard Petty
and Felix Sabates, who can never seem to get it right no matter how
much money he spends.
</P>
<P>
   Running with a top team like Roush or Hendrick and not cutting
it can leave a driver with a stigma, but Dallenbach is comfortable
with the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to worry about it, but I haven't the last two or three
years,'' he said. ``I think I've shown that if you put me in a good
car, I can make it run. I don't think any of the teams I was with
can say I didn't contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, he never had much of a shot with either Roush or
Hendrick.
</P>
<P>
   When Dallenbach joined Roush in 1992, his first full season in
Winston Cup, he was a team car to Mark Martin. The emphasis was on
making Martin a winner. Dallenbach's program was pretty much an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he drove the third Hendrick car, but Hendrick's
primary focus was Ray Evernham and Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   He said that at Hendrick ``they said we all had access to the
same things, but there really wasn't a lot of information going
back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At Roush, Jack gave me my start and I'll always be grateful to
him for that, but if I went out and qualified really well, that
motor would be out of my car and in Mark's for the race,''
Dallenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach is not bitter about the past. He's trying to make it
work for him. He has definite ideas about how a race team should be
set up and how it should function, and much of that was picked up
at Roush and Hendrick, two of the winningest organizations in
NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach thinks Galaxy Motorsports is in the process of
putting the pieces together, and says he's going to do everything
in his power to see they're put together right.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
