u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      06-03 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR TAKES BABY STEPS TOWARD CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other day, something extraordinary happened at City Hall:
The city's two top elected officials had a conversation with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   To be specific, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had a private, cordial
meeting with his longtime tormentor, Mark Green, the public
advocate. At a bill-signing ceremony the same day, the mayor even
patted Green on the shoulder and whispered in his ear, ``Good job,
good job.'' Green, who has been a frequent target of the mayor's
ire, said afterward that his new relationship with the mayor felt
good but ``strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also initiated a meeting last week with Alan Hevesi,
the city comptroller, with whom he has been at war, and told him,
Hevesi said, that he ``wanted to take some steps to repair the
relationship.'' Around the same time, Giuliani called Virginia
Fields, the Manhattan borough president, and asked to meet with her
as part of what he promises will be a new relationship with the
city's minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after he dropped out of the race for U.S. Senate,
saying that he wanted to be a better person and a better mayor,
Giuliani has started to make tentative overtures to former enemies.
But as he continues to research his treatment for prostate cancer
and sort out his messy personal life, it is clear that any mayoral
transformation is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new Rudy,'' if such a creature exists, is still in his
cocoon. City Hall remains in limbo, waiting for the mayor to decide
on his cancer treatment as well as the initiatives that he promised
would redefine his mayoralty in its last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Giuliani does not appear to have talked with many of the
city's black leaders, even though he said in his withdrawal speech
that he wanted to bring down the ``barrier'' that he had erected
between himself and some communities he had alienated. Nor has he
contacted the family of Patrick M. Dorismond, the unarmed black man
shot dead by the police in March, although he said he wanted to
find a way to belatedly express his sympathy to them. He has not
reached out to Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem, a Democrat and the
dean of New York's congressional delegation, or to former allies
like the Rev. Calvin Butts and the Rev. Michel Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sent him a couple of messages,'' said Faulkner, the
pastor of the Central Baptist Church, who went on a fast and prayer
vigil to protest the mayor's repeated attacks on Dorismond. ``I
haven't heard back from him.'' He added: ``I know that his personal
situation takes pre-eminence over what's going on, but I hope he
would understand the seriousness of the condition of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, Giuliani remains an engaged and energetic
mayor, with a schedule full of the substance and ceremony of his
job. His main business the last two weeks has been directing
negotiations with the City Council over a pending $37 billion city
budget package, plus monitoring intense talks between his top
deputies and officials in Albany over legislation that would affect
the city's pension costs and ability to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
   He has also, in the 15 days since withdrawing from the race,
given six speeches, held at least six news conferences, attended
three funerals, marched in three parades, appeared on two radio
programs, presided over two receptions, had one town hall meeting,
sworn in two judges and cut one ribbon. His four deputy mayors,
meanwhile, are said to be working on initiatives intended to revise
his legacy, but short of race relations there is no indication of
what form they might take.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Giuliani does not appear to miss the
Senate race or his brief campaign trips upstate. Asked the other
day whether he had followed the Republican Party's nomination of
Rep. Rick Lazio, who replaced him in the race against Hillary
Rodham Clinton, Giuliani replied, ``somewhat _ not in great
detail.'' Then he added offhandedly, ``I was doing other things
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's personal life remains complicated. He has had quiet
dinners in midtown restaurants with his ``very good'' friend,
Judith Nathan, a district sales manager for Bristol-Myers Squibb
who is divorced and has a teen-age daughter. Friends say he is in
love with her.
</P>
<P>
   But he also celebrated his 56th birthday last Sunday at Gracie
Mansion with his two children and his estranged wife, Donna
Hanover, who recently hired a divorce lawyer to work out the
couple's separation agreement as they live in the same house. ``She
got him a gift, and they shared an ice cream cake with the
children,'' said Joannie Danielides, Hanover's press secretary.
Later that day, he was honored at a party with some 50 staff
members and friends at an Italian restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ``new Rudy,'' Giuliani sometimes seems as skeptical
as his critics. ``No, there isn't a new Rudy,'' he told Rich Lamb
on the WCBS radio show ``Ask the Mayor'' on Thursday night. ``You
grow from things. Things that happen to you make changes in you.''
He added that his illness ``has changed me in certain respects''
and is ``probably going to change me even more, but not into a
totally different person.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropping out of the race ``was the right decision, oh yeah,
sure,'' he said. ``I haven't looked back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
