<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3719 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TONYS0604-COX     06-03 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONYS0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Symbolism fans must have relished the 1999-2000
Broadway season. With the century's close, it was indeed the end of
an era for commercial theater, marked by finales for two
blockbuster musicals and the deaths of two prominent impresarios
from an earlier, healthier theatrical time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats `` and ``Miss Saigon,'' two British blockbuster musicals
that dominated Broadway for the past 18 and 10 years respectively,
have posted their closing notices. No more prancing kitties or
roaring helicopters for awhile. But the new productions of this
season, which ends tonight with the 54th annual Tony Awards
telecast, prove that Broadway is having trouble finding durable
musicals for a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for finding producers with sufficient artistic
vision, financial resources and gambler's instincts. That was
underlined by the passing this spring of the irascible David
Merrick, who assembled shows such as ``Gypsy'' and ``Hello, Dolly!
`` while importing prestige items such as ``Marat''/''Sade;'' and
his rival Alexander Cohen, whose credits ran from ``Angel Street''
to this season's ``Waiting in the Wings.'' In their place are
faceless committees _ it took 11 producers to bring the
three-character ``Copenhagen'' from London _ and monolithic
corporations like Disney, which spent untold millions on a pop rock
version of the opera ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a season without anticipated new shows from Broadway's
usual suspects. Stephen Sondheim's Palm Beach-themed musical about
the Mizner Brothers, ``Wise Guys,'' had a workshop presentation
off-Broadway, but no full production. The long gestating,
much-revised Martin Guerre , by the ``Les Miz''/''Miss Saigon
``team of Alain Boublil and Claude-Michel Schonberg, began a tuneup
tour that derailed before arriving on Broadway. And Neil Simon
churned out another comedy, ``The Dinner Party,'' premiering it in
his adopted hometown of Los Angeles, then deciding it needed more
work before bringing it to New York.
</P>
<P>
   If the old guard did not deliver, the first season of the new
century was marked by emerging young talents who may or may not
stay around to put their stamp on the commercial theater. The
busiest tunesmith this season was certainly Michael John LaChiusa,
the composer-lyricist-playwright of both ``Marie Christine,'' a
modern, Americanized retelling of the Medea legend, and ``The Wild
Party,'' a fictional slice of Jazz Age social history based on a
1928 narrative poem by Joseph Moncure March.
</P>
<P>
   Such double exposure earned LaChiusa four Tony nominations, but
has yet to produce much audience interest for his hard-edged,
melody-stingy style. ``Marie Christine `` ran briefly this winter,
but was most notable for its leading lady, that classically trained
force of nature, Audra McDonald. The lurid ``Wild Party'' was on
the verge of closing when it pulled in seven Tony nominations _ as
many as any new musical this season _ and it probably needs an
upset win tonight to stay open. LaChiusa is among a new generation
of theater composers who seem more suited for not-for-profit arenas
than the commercial, often middlebrow, taste of Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a dominant creative whirlwind today, it is
director-choreographer Susan Stroman, who also copped four Tony
nominations for her sugary revival of ``The Music Man'' and her
inventive dance-musical, ``Contact.'' This latter show is the
front-runner for the season's best new musical Tony (it already won
the Drama Desk and Outer Critics Circle awards), now that the
nominating committee has decided, begrudgingly, that ``Contact ``
actually is a musical.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this series of three dance-driven stories has no
singing, no new music written for the stage and no live music.
Still, it is an enormously audience-friendly evening and an assured
Broadway directing debut for Stroman, who is expected to return
next season with a musical based on Mel Brooks' audacious show
business farce, ``The Producers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with an armload of Tonys, ``Contact'' will never be the
popular success that Disney's ``Aida'' has become. Roundly panned
by critics, it is nevertheless the third hit in a row (after
``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``The Lion King'') for the theater
divisions of the Mouse Factory. Following a false start at
Atlanta's Alliance Theatre two years ago, the show was overhauled
at an estimated cost of $20 million, certainly a Broadway record.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the critical carping, audiences have clamored for
tickets _ a tidy $752,890 in sales last week, which is 99 percent
of capacity, better than any other new show. ``Aida'' and her
Nubians will be circling the globe soon, making the initial
investment seem like chump change. Much is uncertain about the
future of Broadway, but the Disney presence seems assured, with a
stage version of ``Hunchback of Notre Dame'' on deck and a live
``Little Mermaid `` on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   While Disney proves that Broadway can be good business _ if you
have a family-oriented, spectacle-heavy musical _ it continues to
be treacherous territory for dramas. To fill the new play category
this year, the Tony committee had to take the dubious position that
any work not presented before on Broadway is new.
</P>
<P>
   That means Sam Shepard's ``True West,'' written 20 years ago and
prominently presented off-Broadway, competes for the award
alongside Arthur Miller's ``The Ride Down Mt. Morgan,'' a slight
effort that London theatergoers saw a decade ago and off-Broadway
audiences last season. If it had been deemed worthy, the late Noel
Coward's 1960 ``Waiting in the Wings'' could have competed as a new
work. Presumably, Broadway's head-in-the-sand producers find this
preferable to admitting that most serious plays _ at least those
without box office stars in them like Patrick Stewart (''Mt.
Morgan''), Kelsey Grammer (''Macbeth'') or Lauren Bacall
(''Waiting/Wings'') _ now go off-Broadway, where the last three
Pulitzer Prize winners could be found.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, one can see the 2000 Pulitzer winner ``Dinner With
Friends,'' the delightful ``Fully Committed,'' August Wilson's
acclaimed ``Jitney,'' John Guare's early utopian drama Lydie Breeze
and a docudrama about the Matthew Shepard case, ``The Laramie
Project,'' but they are all off-Broadway. The American theater is
alive and healthy, just not on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are two worthy new plays on Broadway, the
serious-minded ``Copenhagen'' and the more playful, heartfelt
``Dirty Blonde,'' but for how long? Plays there have the half-life
of the nuclear isotopes that ``Copenhagen `` is concerned with.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers, this has been a record year for Broadway, with a
new all-time sales mark of $603 million and a second-highest-ever
11.4 million attendance level. Next year, no matter how good a
season it becomes, those totals will probably be down without the
considerable business from ``Cats'' and ``Miss Saigon.'' At
tonight's Tony ceremony, there will be the usual bombast about
Broadway, but the really good performances will come from those who
can flash wide smiles without showing the nervousness behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
