<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TONY-AWARDS0604-COX     06-03 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And the award should go to . . .
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Tony Awards are Broadway's biggest party of the
year. For theater-loving kids like me, who grew up in the Midwest,
the annual event was the most magical night of the year. It beat
Oscar. And the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   PBS telecasts the first hour of tonight's awards, during which
the Tonys for direction (play and musical), choreography, original
score, book of a musical, costume design, scenic design,
orchestration, lighting design and regional theater (the Utah
Shakespearean Festival) will be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Do not skip this hour and wait until 9 p.m. The PBS telecast
always provides a seductive backstage look at how Broadway shows
are made. In many ways, it is far superior to the CBS portion.
</P>
<P>
   And now, here's an educated, if admittedly biased, handicapping
of tonight's top races:
</P>
<P>
   BEST PLAY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Copenhagen'' by Michael Frayn; ``Dirty Blonde''
by Claudia Shear; ``The Ride Down Mt. Morgan'' by Arthur Miller;
and ``True West'' by Sam Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: Frayn's play of ideas focuses on two friends who did early
work on nuclear fission but find themselves on opposite sides of
World War II. It's considered one of the strongest plays in years,
perhaps since the ``Angels in America'' twofer, and has a
first-rate cast _ Philip Bosco, Michael Cumpsty and Blair Brown.
Darkhorse: Shear's ``Dirty Blonde,'' a funny, poignant, human look
at Mae West.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MUSICAL
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Contact,'' ``James Joyce's The Dead,''
``Swing!'' and ``The Wild Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: ``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: Director/choreographer Susan Stroman's dance play stretches
the boundaries of what a Broadway musical can be. It is beautifully
performed, with each of its three dances holding a surprise twist
for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   BEST REVIVAL OF A MUSICAL
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Kiss, Me Kate;'' ``The Music Man''; ``Jesus
Christ Superstar''; and ``Tango Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``Tango'' what? And answer this: Why would anyone want to
resurrect the painfully dated ``Superstar?'' This clearly is a race
between ``Kate'' and ``The Music Man,'' a beautifully staged visit
to Meredith Willson's Iowa of days gone by. ``Kate,'' Cole Porter's
play-within-a play sendup of Shakespeare's ``Taming of the Shrew,''
is, as The New York Times' Ben Brantley put it, ``One ear-to-ear
grin.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST REVIVAL OF A PLAY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Amadeus,'' ``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' ``The
Real Thing'' and ``The Price.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: ``The Real Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``The Real Thing'' or ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten.'' Both are worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``The Real Thing,'' Tom Stoppard's play about love and
betrayal, features Tony nominees Stephen Dillane and Jennifer Ehle.
Eugene O'Neill's ``Misbegotten'' features Tony nominees Cherry
Jones, Roy Dotrice and Gabriel Byrne. Both are serious,
audience-pleasing works with seriously strong performances. Go with
the Brits. It's a hunch.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING ACTOR IN A PLAY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Gabriel Byrne, ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'';
Stephen Dillane, ``The Real Thing''; Philip Seymour, ``True West'';
John C. Reilly, ``True West''; and David Suchet, ``Amadeus.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Dillane.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Dillane, Seymour or Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Why: Dillane's work has earned nothing but praise, as has the
work of Seymour and Reilly. But the fact that they alternate in
``True West's'' main roles may hurt them. Who do you vote for? For
which role, which night? Byrne doesn't catch fire until midway
through Act 2. Suchet is the forgotten man. Go with Dillane.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING ACTRESS IN A PLAY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Jayne Atkinson, ``The Rainmaker''; Jennifer Ehle,
``The Real Thing''; Rosemary Harris, ``Waiting in the Wings'';
Cherry Jones, ``A Moon for the Misbegotten''; and Claudia Shear,
``Dirty Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Ehle or Shear.
</P>
<P>
   Why: This, one of the toughest categories of the evening, pits
mother (Harris) against daughter (Ehle). Wouldn't a tie be nice?
Expect to see Harris on the podium, though, for what amounts to a
lifetime achievement award and for giving the only palatable
performance in Noel Coward's creaky ``Waiting in the Wings.'' Some
consider Jones (a Tony winner for 1995's ``The Heiress'') miscast.
But Shear can't be counted out.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING ACTOR IN A MUSICAL
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Craig Bierko, ``The Music Man''; Brian Stokes
Mitchell, ``Kiss Me, Kate''; George Hearn, ``Putting It Together'';
Mandy Patinkin, ``The Wild Party''; and Christopher Walken, ``James
Joyce's The Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Why: Call it justice for the Tony he didn't get two years ago
for ``Ragtime.'' And he's very good as the arrogant, swaggering
showman Frederic Graham/Petruchio in Kate. The other nominees _
even Bierko making a charming Broadway debut _ aren't in his
league.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING ACTRESS IN A MUSICAL
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Toni Collette, ``The Wild Party''; Heather
Headley, ``Aida''; Rebecca Luker, ``The Music Man''; Audra
McDonald, ``Marie Christine''; and Marin Mazzie, ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Headley.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Mazzie.
</P>
<P>
   Why: Perhaps the toughest category to call. Tony voters seem to
love Hollywood (Collette), but Headley gives a starmaking
performance in the weak ``Aida.'' Honoring her could be a way to
toss Disney a bone, even though her performance has grown less
theatrical and more diva-like with time. Luker is as exciting as
white bread. McDonald, already a three-time Tony winner at age 29,
is deserving, but voters may say enough is enough. Mazzie stops her
show eight times a week with ``I Hate Men.'' As the chilly Lilli
Vanessi/Kate, she sings songs that challenge the best of voices.
And delivers. If Tony has a brain (and it often doesn't), this is
her year.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/PLAY:
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Michael Blakemore, ``Copenhagen''; James Lapine,
``Dirty Blonde''; David Leveaux, ``The Real Thing''; and Matthew
Warchus, ``True West.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Blakemore.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Blakemore.
</P>
<P>
   Why: He'll win for ``Copenhagen'' _ and for directing a show
that couldn't be further from it _ ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' Yes, he's
nominated for best director of a musical, but that will go to Susan
Stroman (more on her later), so this is a way to honor him for
both.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/MUSICAL:
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Michael Blakemore, ``Kiss Me, Kate''; Lynne Taylor
Corbett, ``Swing!''; Susan Stroman, ``Contact'' and ``The Music
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Stroman.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Stroman.
</P>
<P>
   Why: Put aside her popularity and the fact that she lost her
husband, director Mike Ockrent, to cancer in December, the
medallion is hers. Stroman achieved something rarely done in
American musical theater, putting two critically praised and
popular shows on their feet in the same season. Not only did she
direct and choreograph ``Contact,'' she co-conceived it. Couple
that with her exhilarating _ if not perfect _ work with ``The Music
Man,'' and you might as well rename her prize ``The Susan.'' She'll
win for ``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
