</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-GRADS-JOBS-ART-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG JOB MARKET CREATES A HIRING FRENZY FOR RECENT GRADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif., Mich., Texas, Pa., N.H.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1.2 million college graduates in the nation's class of 2000
are entering an unusually strong job market that is a result of a
flourishing economy and, especially, the boom in high technology.
</P>
<P>
   From Northeastern University in Boston to the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena, from the University of
Michigan to the University of Texas, colleges, universities and
professional schools are reporting a record number of recruiters
competing to hire students in a time of low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Engineering students from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and other universities in the East have been flown to
Silicon Valley and Seattle for audiences with billionaire
executives, while investment banks have flown Stanford University
students to New York for high-priced dinners accompanied by job
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Some graduates have landed jobs paying more than $60,000 a year.
With unemployment near its lowest level in three decades, despite
the increase in unemployment announced on Friday, salaries overall
for this year's graduating class are up 6 percent over last year's,
job placement experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gangbusters,'' said Carol S. Lyons, dean of the
department of career services at Northeastern University. ``There
are even more jobs now than last year. Obviously the hot market is
high-tech, but if you're any kind of a business major, you're in
fine shape. And even if you're a liberal arts major there are
plenty of opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   But those in computer sciences are doing best of all. Many
technology companies are offering signing bonuses of $5,000, with
stock options often added on top. One graduate of Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute in Troy, N.Y., has taken an $82,000-a-year
job in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   This year's computer science graduates have landed jobs
averaging $48,500, while graduates in accounting average $37,200
and liberal arts graduates, $29,100, according to the National
Association of Colleges and Employers, which represents employers
and college job placement officers.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Lowe, a senior at Stanford who majored in product design
engineering with a minor in computer science, said she would earn
about $60,000 next year with a software company in San Diego, and
that is before the $5,000 signing bonus and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had five job offers, including one from a company in Arizona
that agreed to fly me to San Diego every weekend to visit my
fiance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But some university officials see troubles behind this bright
picture. A smaller percentage of students from this year's
graduating class is planning to go to graduate school. At Columbia,
administrators say, about 20 percent of this year's graduating
seniors said they would attend graduate school next year, down from
a high of 70 percent in decades past, usually during recessions.
This trend makes many college officials fear that a smaller, and
possibly less capable, group will choose to become professors.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, university officials say, is that at a time
when educators and government officials see an acute need for more
_ and more talented _ teachers, the lavish starting salaries
offered by the private sector are drawing away potential teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem isn't so much the high-tech salaries, but the
level of teacher salaries,'' said Stanley O. Ikenberry, president
of the American Council on Education, an association of 3,500
colleges and universities. ``Can you imagine a high school teacher
of physics or mathematics receiving a paycheck that might be
$25,000 a year, as opposed to the $50,000 or $75,000 in a
comparable role in business? It's a tough choice for a young person
to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Some college officials say a bidding war between technology
companies, investment banks and consulting firms has pushed salary
offers to record levels, with average salaries jumping nearly 20
percent from three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In one unusual episode, several Columbia students who had
accepted $45,000-a-year jobs from a New York bank were delighted
this spring when the bank, fearing it would lose them to
competitors, announced that it was raising their starting salaries
to $55,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if the starting salaries for this year's college
graduates are the same as that MBAs were receiving seven years
ago,'' said Margaret O'Hara, a senior consultant with the Hanigan
Consulting Group, which advises scores of companies on hiring
college graduates. ``What's happened in the past few years is we've
gone from being employer-centric to being employee-centric.''
</P>
<P>
   At Northeastern University this year, there were 440 job
recruiters, up from 400 the year before. At the University of
Michigan, 170 employers made presentations selling themselves to
students, up from 120 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just too many employers chasing too few students,''
said Patricia Rose, director of career services at the University
of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Frustrated that there are not enough qualified college
graduates, many high-technology companies have pressed President
Clinton to nearly double, to 200,000, the number of annual visas
for skilled foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   University officials say the high demand for skilled workers has
created improper dealings. Some companies, eager to catch their
prey, have made what are called ``exploding offers'' _ students are
told they have 24 hours to accept a job offer or the offer
disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Pressured by such offers, students accept and, after continuing
to look or after stumbling upon something more attractive, a few
renege on those offers and take other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some downsides to this wonderful market,'' said
Robert Thirsk, director of career development services at Stanford.
``Exploding offers put students in a very precarious position. We
tell these companies, `You put the student in a difficult situation
of having to make a decision like that. What do you think they're
going to do?' When students renege on offers, it's usually because
they haven't been given enough time to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has told employers that, beginning this fall, companies
that recruit on campus must give students at least three weeks to
respond to job offers.
</P>
<P>
   The giddy job situation at colleges is giddier yet at business
schools. There, $25,000 signing bonuses are common, and some
companies fly not just prospective employees, but their spouses,
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Cochrane, director of career services at the Tuck School of
Business at Dartmouth, said the average base salary for this year's
MBA graduates was $90,000, up from $80,000 last year. She said
overall median first-year compensation was actually $135,000, after
adding in signing bonuses, a guaranteed first-year bonus and
employers' paying a student's second-year business school tuition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FORGOTTEN-DISEASES     06-03 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FORGOTTEN-DISEASES-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC DISEASES LOOM LARGE, TAKING ATTENTION AWAY FROM COMMON
HEALTH THREATS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Calif., Md.)  By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It seems summer is finally here, and with it the fear
of flying insects. It puzzles public health officials, this
obsession with mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Although few of them carry the West Nile virus that killed seven
people and sickened 62 others in the metropolitan region last year,
New Yorkers can be singularly obsessed with the insects. The Health
Department gets frantic calls when they fly into homes. Some New
Yorkers have been known to call their local emergency room when
stung. Suburbanites have vowed to spend the entire summer under
netting.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, if you will, the tick. Ticks carry Lyme disease; more
residents of New York state get Lyme disease than those of any
other state. Ticks also carry Rocky Mountain spotted fever, a
disease not associated with the five boroughs that nonetheless
sickens a handful of city dwellers each year. Yet that media buzz
in your ears is from the mosquito, not the tick.
</P>
<P>
   And don't even get health care workers started on the lack of
interest in the vaccine that staves off a wholly preventable
seasonal illness that kills roughly 3,000 New Yorkers a year: the
flu.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the West Nile virus, which can cause encephalitis and was
unknown in the Western Hemisphere before last year, exemplifies the
increasing challenges to public health departments in large cities
like New York.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, health care workers have to be ever alert for
diseases new to the region and have to find ways to deal with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, we are seeing more exotic diseases,'' said Dr.
Marcelle C. Layton, the assistant commissioner for communicable
diseases of the New York City Health Department. ``West Nile is an
awakening that although these things are uncommon, they do happen
and we need to keep our eyes on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, those same workers must turn the public's
attention to the seemingly eradicated or more mundane diseases that
emerge each year. New York's population, which grows more diverse
each year, has its share of both.
</P>
<P>
   And so an interesting paradox has emerged: while the technology
used to identify and treat diseases has become increasingly
sophisticated, public health has needed to extend down to the grass
roots, penetrating even the most insular communities, one disease
at a time. ``We could create the best and most advanced
surveillance system in the world,'' said Dr. Stephen M. Ostroff, an
epidemiologist at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
in Atlanta. ``And despite that, I see no scenario where we can
replace the front-line public health people.''
</P>
<P>
   Take malaria. It has grown at a rapid clip in the last decade.
In 1997, there were 308 cases in New York City, up 227 percent from
1988. It is not easy to transmit. Unlike West Nile, it is carried
by a mosquito that is uncommon in this region. And it needs weeks
of hot, dry air to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in malaria can be almost single-handedly attributed
to people who go back to their home countries and find out the hard
way that they are no longer immune, Layton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get the message out to people who came from areas
where the diseases are endemic but who have been here awhile that
their immunity to the illness is lost after a certain number of
years,'' she said, citing African and Indian immigrants as the most
common carriers. ``Children are particularly susceptible, because
they were never immune.'' Earlier this year, the CDC reported three
cases in New York City of meningococcal disease among Muslims
returning from the hajj, the pilgrimage to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of features that are contributing to the
emergence of these pathogens,'' said W. Ian Lipkin, a scientist at
the University of California at Irvine who identified the West Nile
virus in New York last year. Those include a change in the
distribution of disease-carrying insects and animals, global
warming, the movement of certain populations into new areas and an
increase in global trade and travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate that we will see more of these diseases,'' Lipkin
said. ``And we need to have ways that we can rapidly recognize and
treat them. HIV came out of jungles and rapidly spread. Hepatitis C
had a similar pattern.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To find people who may be cut off from the increasingly
fragmented health care system, health care workers have begun to
work more closely with community groups, religious leaders and tiny
advocacy organizations that speak the same language and understand
the cultural issues, like distrust of doctors, that prevent people
from getting care. This effort, known as Turning Point, was started
in 1998 in large part to find groups on the margins of the health
care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really trying to build alliances with organizations who
perform a very important function in a very multicultural
community,'' said Sandra Mullin, a City Health Department
spokeswoman. ``It is in some ways going back to very basic public
health.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, groups are extremely hard to identify. For
example, a rise in tuberculosis cases in the 1980s led health care
workers to focus intensely on the disease, and the number of cases
in New York City fell 33 percent between 1988 and 1998. But this
spring, the disease control centers said it had identified an
outbreak in New York City and Baltimore among young, gay, black,
transgender men who attend balls thrown for their various social
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Finding men who acknowledge being among that group is hard
enough, health care workers said. ``As we move toward TB
elimination, the last cases will be the most difficult,'' said Dr.
Peter McElroy, an epidemiologist at the CDC
</P>
<P>
   In the case of these young men, it was hard for health care
workers to insinuate themselves into that world, said Rosalyne
Blumenstein, the director of the gender identity project at the
Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center in Manhattan. It was not
enough for workers to seek out gay men in bars, which worked for a
hepatitis outbreak in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, the public is often much more agitated
about diseases it can do little about, like West Nile, than about
preventing those it can. The flu, for instance, which can be fatal
to the elderly, can usually be avoided with a shot. But each year
flu cases flood the city's emergency rooms, and doctors lament the
number of people who forgo the shot. New York state lags behind the
rest of the nation in pneumococcal immunizations; in New York City,
only 30 percent of the city's residents over 65 get it, according
to data from Ipro, a nonprofit group that studies the quality of
health care.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to immunize children results in avoidable outbreaks of
other illnesses in the region. Last year, in the upstate county of
Chautauqua, a whooping cough epidemic involved more than 250 cases.
Back to why health officials say the tick should get more attention
than the mosquito. ``There may be a public perception that you are
more at risk for a mosquito than a tick,'' said Kristine Smith, a
spokeswoman for the New York State Health Department. But the Culex
pipiens, the type of mosquito that government agencies are devoted
to wiping out, is far less of a menace than ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Ticks carry Lyme disease, which sickened 4,265 New Yorkers last
year, and that does not include the city. They also carry
ehrlichiosis, a bacterial disease that is fairly new to the United
States. The disease sickened over 70 people in the state last year
and can be far more dangerous to elderly patients than West Nile.
``No one really talked about that,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
