<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A slow area of low pressure passing through very moist air
across western Arkansas will promote abundant rainfall. Some
locations will receive over 2 inches of rain, with flash flooding
likely, especially in poor drainage locations. Farther to the east,
showers and thunderstorms will bring temporary relief to dry
conditions in the Southeast. Showers and storms will also develop
in the Carolinas along a stationary front, with heavy rain in some
places.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure in the north central Plains will direct showers
into the Great Lakes states. To the east, a front will cross
northern New England, accompanied by clouds and a stray shower,
especially in the mountains. The northeast coast will stay dry as
high pressure pushes offshore. Meanwhile, the Southwestern deserts
will remain hot, with readings over 110 degrees in spots.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: ENORMOUS HAIL
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening the town of Oakdale, Wis., was bombarded by
softball-sized hail. Much of the hail measured 4.5 inches in
diameter and most buildings in the town reported roof and window
damage because of the extraordinary fall of hail. Such large hail
requires thunderstorm updrafts of nearly 90 mph to keep the stones
airborne. These fierce upward motions alone would tear the wings
off most planes, to say nothing of what the hail could do to the
body of an aircraft. While aircraft can steer clear of storms,
Oakdale had no place to hide.
</P>
</TEXT>
