<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED-CROSS-LEADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 MONTHS ON JOB, RED CROSS LEADER STEPS UP TO EVOLVING CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ While most international officials of his rank are out
on this city's thriving cocktail party circuit, Jakob Kellenberger,
a courtly but determined former Swiss diplomat, heads home from the
International Committee of the Red Cross early most evenings, since
he customarily starts his days at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Kellenberger, 56, has taken the helm of the 137-year-old
International Red Cross at a time when global humanitarian agencies
are facing more challenges than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for ever-dwindling funds is tough; the post-Cold
War world has spawned numerous and increasingly nasty wars; and,
alarmingly, combatants are more suspicious, even contemptuous, of
efforts to ease the hardships of civilians caught in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In just five months on the job, Kellenberger has faced the
challenge of getting his organization back into war-torn Chechnya,
and defusing a potentially devastating dispute over whether an
Israeli contingent can join the International Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Returning Red Cross teams to Chechnya was complicated not just
by Russian politics and the chaos inherent in a war zone,
Kellenberger said, but also by the lingering trauma that resulted
from the death by shooting of six Red Cross workers there in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on skills honed from a lifetime in diplomacy, including
six years negotiating Swiss accords with the European Union,
Kellenberger sought guarantees that the Red Cross could return to
Chechnya, where lawlessness had forced it and other relief agencies
to operate mainly in neighboring Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside the offers of meetings with low-level Russian
officials who could not guarantee the Red Cross unfettered access,
Kellenberger said he insisted on meeting Russian President Vladimir
Putin. Finally, Kellenberger said, he hammered out an agreement
allowing Red Cross workers access to prisoners in all detention
centers, where human rights groups say many abuses of detainees
occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one source of satisfaction,'' said the soft-spoken
Kellenberger, interviewed in his office days after visits to the
detainees began.
</P>
<P>
   Kellenberger, chosen for the four-year Red Cross appointment by
a committee of 20 Swiss citizens, prepared for his job with his
customary determination: he said he spent three months visiting
some of the most troubled areas where the Red Cross' 11,000 workers
are posted, including Afghanistan, Colombia, Rwanda and Uganda.
Those travels drove home for him the perils Red Cross workers face
daily in the field, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armed conflicts are increasing again and becoming more
complex,'' Kellenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that the degree of cruelty to the civilian
population is increasing. And it's worrying that international
humanitarian organizations have become conscious targets for
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   For an organization that is often the first into conflict zones
and the last out, frayed lines of authority can be dangerous.
Nevertheless, Kellenberger rejects using armed escorts because
their presence means ``we risk not being perceived as really
independent and neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   And maintaining the Red Cross' strict neutrality, and ensuring
others perceive the organization's neutrality, said Kellenberger,
``is essential, at the heart of our mandate.''.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, refraining from publicly taking sides, said
Kellenberger, ``does not mean that we are not talking plain
language to the Russians or the Chechen groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 shootings of the six Red Cross workers in Chechnya
illustrated the challenge the organization continues to face, and
helped provide urgency to the idea for a new emblem, Kellenberger
said, because the Red Cross symbol was challenged by Muslims there
who believed it had religious overtones. The Red Cross emblem is
the Swiss flag with the colors reversed, in use since the 1983
founding of the Red Cross by Switzerland's Henri Dunant.)
</P>
<P>
   Discussion about a new emblem, an idea bandied about for years,
brought Kellenberger to his second thorny problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the new president of the American Red Cross, Dr.
Bernardine Healy, precipitated further urgency to the issue when
she publicly demanded immediate admission of Magen David Adom,
Israel's relief group, which uses a red Star of David as its
emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Although not stated publicly, implications that the Israeli
society's exclusion was rooted in anti-Semitism hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   The International Red Cross, a three-time Nobel Prize winner
known globally for its probity, had already been buffeted by
charges, which surfaced in the 1990s, that it kept quiet about the
Holocaust even though its field workers had documented mass
deportations and executions of Jews in Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans began to withhold contributions from the
International Red Cross and its sister International Federation of
Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, which work on disaster
relief, the public debate broke open and threatened to splinter the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, a new process was agreed upon that will probably lead
to approval of a new emblem, most likely a red diamond, by the end
of the year, although Israel has rejected the proposal for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   A new emblem would give Israel and Kazakhstan, which uses
another barred symbol, an alternative emblem and allow them to
join.
</P>
<P>
   Kellenberger said it was ``high time'' that the Israeli society
and others be recognized, and noted that the Israeli group should
also be admitted to the federation, where 60 percent of the 176
member nations must approve any new participant.
</P>
<P>
   While Kellenberger said he does not expect many national
societies to adopt a new emblem, he added, ``In certain contexts,
the International red Cross could be in a situation to use the
diamond.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the future, Kellenberger, the father of two
daughters, said he would like to see the International Red Cross
work more to protect and assist women and girls, adjusting budget
priorities and perhaps recruiting more women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something close to my heart,'' Kellenberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
