<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-LEVI-ASSESS0604-COX     06-03 1779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVI-ASSESS0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An accomplished, if rigid, maestro, lofty legacy of
accomplishments
 &HT;    By Susan Elliott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been quite a ride. The highs, onstage, could be
exhilarating; the lows, mostly backstage, were demoralizing. And in
between, plenty of controversy. Classical music boring and staid?
Not in Atlanta. Not lately anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 12 seasons, Yoel Levi is stepping down as music
director of the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra. His final musical
statement as the boss begins Friday when he launches a two-week
Beethoven extravaganza that covers all the symphonies and
concertos.
</P>
<P>
   Levi will return in years hence, starting in 2001-02, Robert
Spano's first official season as his successor. Spano, music
director of the Brooklyn Philharmonic and a protege of the Boston
Symphony's Seiji Ozawa, comes to the orchestra with the same kind
of rising-star image that Levi did in 1988. In his tenure, Levi's
biggest gift to the orchestra has been to make it a tighter and
more flexible band than predecessor Robert Shaw's was, hiring some
of the top instrumental talent in the country. But his time also
has been characterized by a certain rigidity, both in his
performances and in his dealings with the musicians. Following in
the footsteps of such a magnanimous humanitarian as Shaw has not
been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, the excitement of playing well together
technically just wasn't enough,'' says principal cellist
Christopher Rex, who's been with the orchestra for 21 years. ``A
conductor needs to inspire artistry in the musicians, not merely
control them. Mr. Levi doesn't always seem to be comfortable
dealing with human beings. Unfortunately, the orchestra is made up
of human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the orchestra has been on a decided upswing since late
last year, largely by signing an unprecedented four-year musicians'
contract and by giving Levi the going-away present of a lofty title
_ music director emeritus _ and a very generous salary to go with
it (reportedly $1 million over a five-year period). Both helped end
the turmoil that has surrounded Levi's reign since the mid-1990s.
Spano's appointment also adds to the buoyant spirits at Symphony
Hall. His partnership with the ASO shows every sign of being a
winner, even in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Spano arrives at the ASO at the same age _ 38 _ and the same
caliber of pedigree as his predecessor. Levi had all the right
credentials when he got here, especially his six years of training
with the esteemed Cleveland Orchestra, the last four of which had
been as resident conductor under music director Lorin Maazel. Among
the most highly regarded maestros in the business, Maazel just
celebrated 40 years of collaboration with the self-governed Vienna
Philharmonic, a notoriously picky ensemble when it comes to
conductors. He is a brilliant technician, a consummate orchestra
builder. Levi learned well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a feeling that Atlanta had gotten itself a really
hot conductor,'' recalls associate concertmaster Jun-Ching Lin, who
was hired by Levi during his first season. ``When I first got here,
the orchestra sound was very lush and warm and a little over the
top. Yoel was able to tighten that up immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Woods, president of Telarc, the ASO's main record label,
remembers that the consensus on the search committee that chose
Levi was that he would help build the orchestra _ school it in
discipline that would probably be beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   The ASO was relatively young when Levi arrived (founded in 1945,
compared with 1911 for the San Francisco Symphony and 1842 for the
New York Philharmonic). To a large degree, it was still on the
steep learning curve that Shaw began in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw established the ASO's reputation by using the 200-voice ASO
Chorus as its calling card; Levi is largely responsible for
maintaining its profile, mostly by honing the orchestra's ensemble
sound minus the chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Shaw's orchestra we were sort of the choral
accompaniment,'' says Dan Dowdakin, who retires this season after
45 years with the ASO. ``We felt that all of the love he was
pouring out was going over our heads to that wonderful chorus
behind us. That made us feel very `accompanimentary.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Levi turned the orchestra around in two ways: by demanding a
more consistent and cleaner sound from his players and by hiring
top-flight talent. Of its 95 players, Levi hired 33. Eighteen of
those are titled positions, such as principal flute or associate
principal clarinet. Says concertmaster Cecilia Arzewski, who left
her job as associate concertmaster in Cleveland to join Levi,
``When I came here in 1990, I felt that this was the most exciting
place for a musician to be.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TOAST OF EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Levi's skills as an orchestra builder were proven during the
ASO's 1991 European tour. Playing in some of the continent's most
sublime venues _ Vienna's Musikverein, Paris' Salle Pleyel _ the
orchestra largely wowed European audiences and critics. The
Dusseldorf Post equated the ASO with the Big 5 U.S. orchestras
(Chicago, New York, Boston, Philadelphia and Cleveland), while
London's Guardian remarked upon its ``brilliance, bite and
precision of ensemble.''
</P>
<P>
   Today many musicians cite that tour as the high point of Levi's
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, things continued to go well for the Levi-ASO
partnership back home. Some of the CDs were getting good reviews
(Levi's ASO has made 30 recordings for Telarc) and selling
relatively well, especially the 1995 recording of the Mahler Fifth
Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Levi has been willing to try just about any repertoire, other
than the Baroque and the contemporary, and insists on using what is
presumably a photographic memory, memorizing everything he conducts
_ a tiresome gimmick to some, an impressive bit of showmanship to
others. He is at his best when he gets out of the way and lets the
composer speak for himself, as he did with Shostakovich's
gut-wrenching ``Babi Yar'' in March.
</P>
<P>
   And while it would be unfair to compare him to his predecessor,
Levi's primary failing has been a lack of soul or inspiration in
his interpretations. Many miss a certain humanity, passion or sense
of personal submission to the power of the art form at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always hoped that his musical interpretations would grow
and deepen to the level of his technical abilities,'' says Lin.
``But it never seemed to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This rigidity began to sour Levi's relationship with his
players. As the 1996 Olympics approached, some felt increasingly
that his demand for precision had become a demand for total control
_ perhaps another reason why his performances missed a sense of
elasticity, of the players ``breathing'' together as a natural
unit. Levi's competency level has never faltered, but too many
performances became unexciting to audiences and predictable for the
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   A TIME OF CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   The mid-'90s were also about the time that Levi's
guest-conducting stints began to drop off, particularly in the
United States. He had by that time conducted at most of the major
orchestras, but was rarely invited to return.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the orchestra's debt mounted. In February 1996, the
ASO board announced that six nontenured players would not be
rehired. And while their salaries were subsequently rescued by an
anonymous angel, the damage to morale had been done. An ugly
10-week strike began in the fall of '96, ending just in time for an
East Coast tour in February 1997. The reviews paled compared with
those of the European tour six years earlier. ``Mr. Levi seemed
content to skate over the top,'' The New York Times said in a
largely negative review of the Mahler Sixth.
</P>
<P>
   In the months that followed, Levi announced that he would not
renew his contract beyond the 1999-2000 season. The time was ripe;
the musicians were eager for a change in artistic leadership. Even
if that hadn't been the case, 12 years is a long time for a music
director to stay with an orchestra, at least in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's followers responded loudly. Amid cries of anti-Semitism
and other such accusations, a small but vociferous ``support Levi''
group mobilized to protest his departure, using pickets outside
Symphony Hall and large billboards to canonize him. Within the next
year, Levi suggested he might unresign, causing the board and
musicians to pass separate resolutions to continue the search for a
new conductor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Levi support group did Mr. Levi any
favors,'' Rex says in retrospect, ``and I don't think it did the
orchestra any favors. By protesting his leaving, it only begged the
question of whether something was missing. They stirred up a
controversy as though there were some sinister motive, and there
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   That is behind the orchestra now. And though it cast a shadow
over Levi's years, and potentially his future, it by no means
diminishes his contribution. He built an orchestra of which
Atlantans can and should be proud, one that can adapt to virtually
any style from epic Mahler in Symphony Hall to singing strings at
Chastain Park Amphitheatre. He leaves behind an ensemble of winning
players just waiting to become a winning team. Robert Spano is a
lucky man, and Levi is largely responsible for that good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   A LEVI TIMELINE
</P>
<P>
   1988: Yoel Levi appointed music director of the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra. His first concert is broadcast live on Atlanta
television.
</P>
<P>
   1989-90: Makes the first of more than 30 recordings with the
ASO; makes Carnegie Hall debut with ASO; inaugurates ASO
Summerfest.
</P>
<P>
   1991: Conducts ASO and ASO Chorus in Mahler's Symphony No. 2
(``Resurrection'') at Lincoln Center; leads European tour of 16
cities.
</P>
<P>
   1993-94: Allison Vulgamore named executive director (title
changed to president in following season); Levi leads birthday
tribute to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. with Jessye Norman and
Morehouse and Spelman college glee clubs, which evolves into the
orchestra's annual King celebration.
</P>
<P>
   1995-96: ASO celebrates its 50th season; Levi conducts the ASO
and ASO Chorus in national broadcast; ASO and ASO Chorus perform in
Opening Ceremonies of 1996 Olympics; Levi conducts ASO in four
Olympic Arts Festival concerts in Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   1997: Leads ASO on brief Northeast tour; announces he will not
renew contract beyond 1999-2000 season; serves as music adviser to
the Israel Festival; begins three-year appointment as distinguished
visiting professor at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   1999: Named ASO music director emeritus for 2000-2005.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
