<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      06-03 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING HAS BECOME A CONVENIENT ALIBI FOR THE KNICKS' TROUBLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: D.C., Fla.)  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing was alone, as usual. While his
teammates shook hands with a group of Indiana Pacers players
fluttering around the floor like paper dolls, Ewing disappeared
into the tunnel by himself Friday night. While the rest of the New
York Knicks gathered their things and left Madison Square Garden
after their elimination, he leaned back in his locker as if
retreating into an isolation booth.
</P>
<P>
   He just stared ahead, lost in thought. Then a timer went off. He
snapped to attention, peeled the ice bags off his joints and tossed
one after another into a pile until it resembled a sandbag wall
built to stop a flood. Just another barrier in the locker room,
another visual to his solitary existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Patrick, he doesn't say much to us,'' Marcus Camby
has said on a number of occasions this season. ``He doesn't talk to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But plenty was said about him this past week, some of it by the
very players who, like so many outside the team, have little
sympathy for an aging and aloof superstar on the decline. In the
aftermath of the Knicks' Game 6 loss that gave the Pacers the
Eastern Conference title, 4-2, the players offered up only
transparent appreciation for Ewing. All the buzz phrases flowed:
He's a warrior, he's gutsy, he's not to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair for people to criticize him, but that's life,''
Allan Houston ventured. ``Not everyone is going to praise you.
You'll have some critics. You do the best you can, and that's what
Patrick does.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the last week, through innuendo and whispers, several
players said the team was slowed down, held back and stylistically
cramped with Ewing on the floor against the Pacers. Even Latrell
Sprewell let the repetition of the popular stat _ the Knicks were
5-1 over two playoff runs against the Pacers without Ewing _ seep
into his logic. ``Numbers don't lie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if the numbers are misleading or if their
theories are flawed. While it is the players' fault if they stand
around in Ewing's presence _ sticking him with bail-out jumpers on
the shot-clock, loitering in the background while he rebounds,
failing to drive the lane when he is on the floor _ the perception
has become reality.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has become a mental albatross. If the team believes he
weighs it down, then he does. If he has become the convenient alibi
for the team's failure, maybe the excuse has to be removed. The
team has grown weary of the reclusive Ewing. And at times, Ewing
has been fed up with the organization's thin show of gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the general manager, Scott Layden, had a brief
conversation with the Washington Wizards about trading Ewing back
to a city that would embrace him for the Georgetown hero he was and
the Hall of Fame player he is sure to be. Now, with one year left
on Ewing's $68 million deal, one Eastern Conference official said
the team will explore that option again. Ewing has a right of
refusal in his contract. But there are likely two teams he would
agree to play for: Miami and Washington. The Wizards make the most
sense.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards will be searching for salary cap space for the
summer of 2001, and Ewing's $16 million salary next season would
fall off their payroll. Until the team has money to spend on free
agents, Michael Jordan's cache means nothing. In return, the Knicks
would have to take Juwan Howard or Rod Strickland, plus some dead
weight from the Wizards. There are luxury tax issues that would
come with Howard, but the Knicks might find a creative way to lower
their burden. If not this deal, then some move will be made by the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long summer,'' said Chris Childs, who is
eternally on the trading block. ``Management will do what they do
and make decisions. Whatever decisions they make, they'll make. We
had an opportunity this year, and we didn't cash in on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon his arrival late last summer, Layden kept a low profile,
remained a barely audible and hardly visible executive, and did
nothing to improve the Knicks before the trade deadline. With a
season that did not live up to expectations _ as extreme as they
were _ decisions have to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Do they trade the fragile Camby or trust him as their starting
center if Ewing is hurt or in another team's jersey? Do they
re-sign the temperamental Kurt Thomas or let him go? Do they make a
bid for John Starks or look for another 3-point threat in reserve
clothing? Do they address the structural flaw they have with
Sprewell at small forward or leave him as a compliment to Houston?
Do they believe in Charlie Ward the playoff hero or fear he will
revert to his regular-season inconsistency?
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the Knicks have to find more value from their
roster. Coach Jeff Van Gundy's seven-man rotation in the playoffs
eventually created conditions that were ripe for injuries.
Throughout the playoffs, the Knicks' roster looked like a storage
area for outdated parts. On the end of the bench, there were
uplifting chemistry guys, but how much could David Wingate and
Andrew Lang help in the end? Once the young but unused John Wallace
did dust himself off to play in Game 4 against Indiana, he was not
able to function on command.
</P>
<P>
   In an ill-fated, Van Gundy-supported signing that did not work,
Wallace was the only notable move the Knicks made last summer. This
summer, it is up to Layden to upgrade the team. He is reputed to be
a draft guru able to pluck talent ready for action instead of a
project player like the Knicks' lost Frenchman, Frederick Weis. As
last year's 15th pick overall, Weis may never see Madison Square
Garden without a tour guide.
</P>
<P>
   As Utah's architect, Layden did not have to take many
free-agency risks with Karl Malone and John Stockton working their
illusive bob-and-weave, pick-and-roll to the delight of Jazz fans.
Layden could bide his time without pressure. In New York, patience
snuffs out careers. Coach Pat Riley could unearth his Holy Grail by
nabbing a great shooting guard, Philadelphia might only get better,
Toronto may discover peace amid its dysfunction and Orlando coach
Doc Rivers could lure Tim Duncan from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks cannot afford to stay put with a roster dotted with
deteriorating veterans, like Ewing, Larry Johnson and Chris Childs,
and filled with likable but inconsistent stars, like Camby, Houston
and Sprewell. After last year's run to the finals, the Knicks
trusted the expiration date on the magic potion they thrived on
last season would last through the third week of June this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the potion curdled Friday night, just before 10 p.m. At that
moment, Ewing slipped away from the Pacers-infused commotion on his
home court. As a punctuation to his inglorious departure, he was
heckled upon his exit. Who will they berate if he is gone? Who will
his teammates have to blame?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
