<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENVIRON-POLITICS-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OF RIVER GROUPS' LEADERS IGNITES A FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT WORTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Pataki administration ordered the chairmen of the
state's two Hudson River Greenway organizations last week to fire
their executive directors and several board members, an action that
has angered environmentalists and prompted a backlash by state
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the two groups' boards said the administration's
effort to oust the two directors had introduced politics into a
program whose success had depended on its bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Saturday Night Massacre,'' said Harriet Cornell,
a Democratic member of the Rockland County Legislature who is one
of the board members being singled out for dismissal. ``Here is a
successful program that has managed to keep politics out, that has
managed to work with conservationists, hunters, all kinds of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly members Richard Brodsky and Susan John, both Democrats,
announced on Thursday that they intended to hold hearings on the
matter to determine who ordered the firings and on what grounds,
and whether further measures were necessary to ensure the
Greenway's freedom from political interference.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups, known jointly as the Hudson River Valley
Greenway, were created in 1991 to coordinate environmental
planning, foster tourism and assist communities through grants in
13 counties bordering the Hudson, from Waterford in Saratoga County
to Battery Park in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maurice Hinchey of Saugerties, who wrote the Greenway
legislation as a state assemblyman, said it was deliberately
written to avoid partisan politics. ``It's going to be very
detrimental to the Hudson Valley over the next several years if
this goes through as it's been laid out,'' he said. ``To very
precipitously and unceremoniously remove these people without
presenting any rationale undermines confidence in the program and
jeopardizes its fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   The two directors had consistently received positive reviews
from their boards and have not been given a reason for their
dismissal. Both have served in their positions since the Greenway's
inception. David Sampson, director of the Hudson River Valley
Greenway Communities Council, is a Democrat, and Maggie
Vinciguerra, director of the Greenway Conservancy for the Hudson
River Valley, is a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson cited what he considered one possible reason for their
removal. He and Vinciguerra attended a presentation on Hudson
Valley programs earlier this year by Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of
housing and urban development and a potential political rival to
Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The directorships each pay $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the chairmen of the two groups were directed by Pataki
administration officials either to fire their executive directors
or to have their boards do so at their next joint meeting, on June
7.
</P>
<P>
   A Pataki spokesman, Michael McKeon, said, ``We believe new
leadership will bring new energy and vitality to the greenway and
make it even better than it is today.'' He added that Pataki had
been a co-sponsor of the Greenway's founding legislation in 1991
and had consistently supported its mission.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said the administration had told the boards of the two
groups of its intentions some time ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew Bender IV, chairman of the Greenway Conservancy,
said he was astonished by the instructions when he was called in to
speak to the governor's appointments officials on May 24. He said
he told them that he saw no reason to fire his executive director,
Vinciguerra, and that he would have to speak to the conservancy
board about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bender was himself dismissed from his post by Pataki
administration officials, a move that provoked further anger from
legislators and local environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced by Kevin Plunkett, a lawyer and a member of
the Westchester County chapter of the League of Conservation
Voters, said McKeon. Plunkett is the brother of William Plunkett, a
partner at Pataki's former law firm, Plunkett &AMP; Jaffe, of White
Plains.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is a coup d'etat,'' said Andrew Mele, executive director
of Hudson River Sloop Clearwater, an environmental watchdog group.
``Greenway is being transformed from a legitimate regional
organization to just a political tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pataki's proposed successor to Sampson, Barbara
Murphy, has been criticized as inappropriate because of her links
to a development project. Murphy is one of three principal
investors in Riverbanks, a multimillion-dollar condominium project
in Cold Spring that has drawn opposition from local residents. The
Greenway Council has played a role in negotiating the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   If Murphy becomes the council's director, she will be in charge
of the group that is negotiating the dispute over her own project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flagrant conflict of interest,'' said Mele.
</P>
<P>
   No successor to Vinciguerra has been named.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan to replace the directors appears likely to
succeed, with a majority of votes on the boards of both Greenway
groups nearly certain, said Barnabas McHenry, the chairman of the
Greenway Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council and the conservancy have a combined operating budget
of about $1.1 million a year. They jointly manage the programs of
the Hudson River Valley National Heritage Area, designated by
Congress in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
