<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TURKEY-TORTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH STUDY FINDS TORTURE OF PRISONERS IS WIDESPREAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add note to editors; no other changes)   (This story, originally slugged TURKEY-RIGHTS, was sent and held
May 31. It is now restored.)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ When a harsh report asserting that torture is
widespread in Turkey was released last week, the surprise was not
just the amount of damning evidence it contained, but also the
source.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being prepared by a private advocacy group, the
report was the work of the parliamentary committee on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Turkish leaders have sought to play down accusations
that torture is widely practiced here. That will be harder after
what the parliamentary committee found.
</P>
<P>
   Its report contains transcripts of interviews with many
prisoners who said they had been abused. It also includes photos of
torture equipment and floor plans that show where torture cells are
supposedly located in various police stations. No report by a
government human rights body has ever been nearly this extensive or
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members and investigators interviewed more than 8,500
prisoners over two years. They also conducted unannounced visits to
50 prisons and two dozen police stations, said the vice chairman,
Sebgetullah Seydaoglu.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee has existed for seven years but it hasn't been
functioning properly,'' said Seydaoglu, who represents the
southeastern city of Diyarbakir, where the mostly Kurdish
population has long complained of bad treatment by police. ``In the
last year we've become very decisive about our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, members of the committee presented a copy of their
report to the minister of justice, Hikmet Sami Turk. Afterward he
said the report would ``hold up a light for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Torture is a crime against humanity,'' Turk said. ``Turkey
will resolve this issue. No country can justify torture on the
grounds that other countries practice it. Claims of torture will be
followed up with resolve. Torture has never been and never will be
state policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The report says that when inmates of Istanbul's main women's
prison were interviewed, ``all recounted details of the torture and
abuse they suffered.'' Most prisoners interviewed at jails in the
eastern cities of Sanliurfa, Erzurum and Erzincan told similar
stories.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders have repeatedly told their Turkish counterparts
that Turkey must improve its human rights record if it hopes to
join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department said in its latest human rights report
that during 1999 ``torture, beatings and other abuses by security
forces remained widespread, at times resulting in deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates are unhappy with the government's record.
The bluntness of the new parliamentary report suggests that
impatience for change is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report says what we have been saying for years, that
torture is extensive and systematic in Turkey,'' said Nazmi Gur,
chairman of the Human Rights Association, which has often been at
odds with the government. ``This could be the beginning of progress
toward meeting European legal standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials have expressed fear of what might happen if the
Turkish police are forced to abandon their traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are happy with the performance of the police,'' the
deputy interior minister, Sami Sonmez, asserted at a parliamentary
hearing last year. ``The police are capable of extracting
confessions from the culprits. What's the use of creating a lot of
fuss as long as public opinion endorses what the police do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-ENDORSE-465     06-03 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ENDORSE-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL PARTIES ISSUE ENDORSEMENTS, ALONG PARTY LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With as much relief as enthusiasm, New York's
Conservative and Liberal parties reverted to type Saturday,
endorsing Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton, respectively, for
the Senate, after both parties had endured a queasy several months
that left their nominations in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   At the Intercontinental Hotel in Manhattan, the Liberal Party
went some distance toward mending its frayed relationship with its
traditional ally, the Democratic Party, by throwing its support
behind Clinton for the Senate. And Conservative Party delegates met
here, where they were to nominate Lazio, the Republican candidate,
cementing their longtime alliance with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Liberal Party leader Raymond B. Harding repeatedly
noted that Lazio was more conservative than the man he replaced as
the Republican candidate, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Their
remarks continued the struggle by the two candidates to claim the
political middle ground, and to paint each other as extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways my views are closer to those of the mayor than
those of my opponent,'' Clinton said. ``He is out of step with the
mainstream,'' she said of Lazio. ``My views are centrist views,
positive views,'' she added at a brief press conference at which
she referred to herself as a centrist no fewer than four times.
</P>
<P>
   Harding cited a long list of popular Democrats his party has
supported, like Daniel Patrick Moynihan, Hugh Carey and Robert F.
Kennedy, and noted that when it has supported Republicans for
statewide office, they have been widely revered centrists like
Fiorello La Guardia and Jacob Javits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to put Lazio at the end of that litany and it jars the
ear,'' he said. ``Put Hillary there and it fits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party's backing could be both an aid and a
burden to Lazio. Unlike the Liberals, the Conservatives still hew
to an ideology in keeping with their name, taking strong stands
against abortion, gay rights, affirmative action and big
government. And the party's ready embrace of Lazio as a real
conservative stands in contrast to its rejection of Giuliani as too
moderate, and could undermine Lazio's claim to being the centrist
in this race.
</P>
<P>
   Both minor parties are small _ the Conservative Party has fewer
than 2 percent of the state's registered voters, and the Liberal
Party fewer than 1 percent _ but they wield an influence beyond
their size. The major parties must play to them, because each of
the smaller parties presents a choice between closing ranks and
facing a challenger who can provide an outlet for protest votes. In
recent statewide elections, Republican candidates have pulled as
many as 300,000 votes on the Conservative line, while Democrats
often get well over 100,000 on the Liberal line.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As long as Giuliani was the presumptive Republican nominee, the
race had both minor parties in turmoil. The Liberals, whose
longstanding support of the mayor had alienated many Democrats,
faced a pitched internal battle over which side to take. Though
some Conservative Party leaders favored Giuliani, the party
chairman, Michael Long, had vowed that it would not support the
mayor because he was not far enough to the right, especially on
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials acknowledged that nominating their own candidate
would undermine the mayor and damage their relationship with the
Republicans, and that they were having some trouble finding a
viable candidate of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But when Giuliani dropped out of the race last month, and the
Republicans nominated Lazio instead, the battle lines became clear
and the Liberals and Conservatives fell into their comfortable old
roles. Lazio supports legal abortion, but unlike Clinton _ and
Giuliani _ he opposes government funding for it, and he backs a ban
on what anti-abortion groups call partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   One important question about the November ballot remains
unanswered: Who will be the nominee of the Independence Party, now
the state's largest minor party, with a shade more registered
voters than the Conservatives?
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party, the New York arm of the Reform Party
founded by Ross Perot, has been roiled by a seesaw battle for
control between two factions. One is aligned with the party's
founder, B. Thomas Golisano, the two-time candidate for governor;
the other is aligned with this year's oddest political pairing, Pat
Buchanan, the conservative commentator and likely Reform candidate
for president, and Lenora Fulani, known for her far-left politics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said she will not share a ticket with Buchanan, and
Saturday, she chastised Lazio for saying he would attend the
Independence Party's nominating convention, to be held Monday just
outside Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Party officials have seemed to be leaning toward
Giuliani, but they are unsure what to think of Lazio. They have
said they may hold a primary between Clinton and Lazio, nominate
one of them outright, or choose their own challenger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1600EDT &QL; 
