<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-03 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 13 YEARS, BIRD IS BACK IN THE FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His face red, his adrenaline still going, Larry Bird overflowed
with nostalgia and satisfaction. ``An unbelievable feeling,'' he
said on Friday night after his Indiana Pacers made franchise
history and dispatched the Knicks in Game 6 of the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been so long, I forgot what it's like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bird, it was like old times. His team was going to the
finals, possibly to Los Angeles, to play against Magic Johnson's
old team. ``Don't matter what the odds are,'' he used to say during
his playing days. ``You get to the finals, it's one big roll of the
dice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, listenin' to Magic coach that team out there for a
while, we may have a shot at it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed for a few seconds before he caught himself, as if
realizing he was the only one who thought he was funny. Every one
around him broke up the room.
</P>
<P>
   Bird sat in the back of the training-room area, adjacent to the
visitor's locker room at Madison Square Garden on Friday night. He
had slung off his coat, unfastened his tie, unbuttoned the top
button of his cream-colored dress shirt and began to enjoy the
solitude of a beer and another trip to the finals _ his first since
1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching is completely different than playing,'' he said.
``Playing is the ultimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Havin' that ball in your hands, makin' plays, goin' on the
road for a big playoff game. Winnin'. That's the ultimate. I'm just
so happy for a lot of our older players, they finally get to play
for a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   His Midwestern drawl still makes world championship sound like
``wurld champeen-ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, no? Over the past 20 years, The Hick from French Lick
became Larry Legend, just as Larry Legend eventually morphed into
Coach Bird. A little of each persona still remains. The broken
English from a Southern Indiana farm. The competitive drive of a
Hall of Fame Celtic. And that helpless feeling that no matter how
much you want it, if your desire does not transfer to your players,
the season is lost.
</P>
<P>
   When he took the job in 1997, Bird said: ``There's somethin'
about this team I like. I can't quite put my finger on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, the Pacers were an extension of Bird. There was
Reggie Miller's swagger and 3-point dagger. Mark Jackson's sleight
of hand. Chris Mullin's craftiness, the way the veteran understood
angles and trajectories like only someone who had spent his life
shooting alone in a dead-quiet gymnasium could. Dale Davis'
tenacity. Jalen Rose's fearlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Slow of foot, blessed with skill, they were all pieces of Bird.
So much of him was in them.
</P>
<P>
   Everything except his will. Because in the crucible moments _ in
Game 6 against the Knicks last season and Game 7 against Chicago in
1998 _ they did not want to go to the finals as much as Larry Bird
did.
</P>
<P>
   He had watched the Pacers implode in the playoffs enough to
build up a mounting frustration, a feeling that they were never
going to summon the same resolve he had had as a player. After
their 0-2 Memorial Day weekend in New York, Bird spoke of his
players with almost a rueful detachment, saying things like,
``That's the one thing that really kills me about 'em, that lack of
a killer instinct'' or ``When I went into a playoff game, I never
thought I was goin' to lose. I just thought I'd win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that they were going down, internal strife circling, he
was challenging them like he once challenged his beleaguered Boston
teammates after a playoff loss. ``We need 12 heart transplants in
this locker room,'' Bird once said.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost as if the legend wanted to remain above the fray
in case the coach failed, that, damn it, Larry Bird was not going
to let this soft bunch of players toy with his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   And at the moment he watched them almost throw their season away
again _ watched the rejuvenated Knicks open a 37-19 bulge on the
Pacers before a fed-up, jeering crowd at Conseco Fieldhouse in Game
5 _ his perception about his team changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back from that 18-point deficit in Game 5, I seen
a different team,'' Bird said. ``I really did, the best I seen
since I been here. They fought, they scrapped. They finally
believed in what we was trying to do here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see. God, I been so happy for 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   They parlayed that Game 5 comeback into a clinching Game 6
victory at the Garden, a victory that left Miller in the arms of
Rose, pumping his bony but lethal wrist, a victory that left Bird
beaming. The Pacers now had his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thing is, in the first half we were moving the basketball so
well,'' he said. ``It was unbelievable. All you can ask for is good
looks at the basket. And we had `em.''
</P>
<P>
   He thought about that for a moment and smiled. ``This poor
franchise has been there five times or somethin' _ couldn't get
through,'' Bird said. ``I'm so happy for 'em. I'm so happy for
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   When yer from the country, change comes awfully slow. Sometimes
it takes a while for the corn to sprout and grow. But on Friday
night at the Garden, in big, ol' New York City, Larry Bird's team
won and again is goin' to play for a wurld champeen-ship. Who
knows, they might just end up in L.A., where he and Magic last spun
the world on their fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it,'' he said, shaking his head. ``They did it. It's
goin' to be great going back to the finals. It's been ... 13
years.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
