<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: D . A . 'S IMAGE SUFFERS AS HER SPOUSE GOES ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ ``Al!'' Jeanine Pirro scolded her naughty
husband. ``Al!''
</P>
<P>
   There he went again, stepping just a wee bit over the line.
Defying instructions not to talk about his tax fraud trial, he was
entertaining reporters with sarcastic analysis of federal charges
that he had neglected to report a wee bit over $1 million in
personal income. ``Al!'' she scolded, with a smile. ``Zip it.''
</P>
<P>
   But on went Al, with Jeanine scolding and smiling at his side.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirros are well practiced as Westchester County's leading
song-and-dance team. Even with the Clintons-come-lately in
Chappaqua, the Pirros own the stage here. Albert J. Pirro Jr., a
leading real estate lawyer and Republican lobbyist, has long been
the man to see in Westchester. And Jeanine F. Pirro, a judge and
now district attorney, has long been the woman to avoid. He could
make you. She could break you.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro openly promoted his wife's political career, but they
worked to maintain an appearance of parallel lines of power: He had
his business, she had hers. But those lines are converging in
Pirro's tax-fraud trial in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro is not on trial. Albert Pirro and his brother,
Anthony, an accountant, are accused of charging $1.2 million of
Albert Pirro's personal expenses to his various businesses and
illegally deducting them as business expenses. But in the
prosecutors' dramatization, Jeanine Pirro is the leading lady, and
hardly Caesar's wife at that.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro's companies allegedly paid some of Jeanine Pirro's
political consultants. A private aide testified that Jeanine Pirro
had her send some personal bills to Albert Pirro's office, which
paid (and allegedly deducted) them through his businesses.
</P>
<P>
   One of Albert Pirro's companies owned the Mercedes-Benz his wife
drove, and claimed deductions for it, despite a circuitous paper
trail that made it appear she had paid for it, prosecutors say. An
investigator in Jeanine Pirro's office, who moonlights as a
security consultant, was hired on the side by Albert Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution says Albert Pirro essentially deducted life as a
business expense. And what a life it was _ fancy cars, a vacation
home, big dinners, small planes, cigars, even a dalliance that
produced a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a crime to have expensive tastes,'' a prosecutor,
Cathy Seibel, assured the jury in opening arguments. But it makes
good testimony in a dry tax case. The government casts Jeanine
Pirro, Westchester's chief law-enforcement officer, as procurer in
chief of items her husband improperly deducted.
</P>
<P>
   Her name came up in testimony by a man who had made an $1,800
wrought-iron pen for the Pirros' Vietnamese pot-bellied pigs. A
gallery employee said Mrs. Pirro had commissioned a $4,450 portrait
of her children, wanted it in time for a dinner party and sent him
faxes with district attorney's office cover-sheets. A house painter
testified that Jeanine Pirro had deducted $50 from his bill because
he had gotten paint on a carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Barrington D. Parker Jr. told the jury to ignore the
spotted carpet testimony and reminded prosecutors out of the jury's
earshot, ``She's not a defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is a prosecutor and a politician being splattered while
sitting loyally in the front row of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro has been investigated before and never charged, and
he could beat these charges. His premier legal team portrays him as
a busy man whose finances were handled by other people, including
his brother, and who willingly paid $1 million in back taxes once
told of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro accuses prosecutors of a ``desperate attempt'' to
tie her to the case ``whenever they can.'' Albert Pirro calls the
charges ``character assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   He's facing prison if convicted, but his wife's public character
is at risk. Albert Pirro's protection of his wife's image as a
hard-working, straight-arrow, telegenic politician is a theme in
his case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Albert Pirro concocted the Mercedes-Benz
transactions so Jeanine Pirro could ``state, if asked, that she
purchased'' the car, if it became an issue in her race for district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the ``Zoe Baird problem.'' Like President
Clinton's first choice for attorney general, the Pirros apparently
had tax problems with their household help. A political consultant
(paid by one of Albert Pirro's companies) advised Jeanine Pirro to
come clean on her cable television program. The program's expenses
also were paid by a Pirro company.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant said Jeanine Pirro had dealt successfully with
her Zoe Baird problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Al Pirro problem is another matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
