<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: IN NEW JERSEY, WINNER MUST LOOK THE PART 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ The state's newspapers are falling in behind Jim
Florio. The party establishment is squarely backing Jon Corzine.
The airwaves are full of nasty commercials about each of the Senate
candidates. So what is a Democratic voter to do?
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey primary season, which culminates in Tuesday's
election, has been the most competitive in a generation. The
retirement of Frank Lautenberg left a Senate seat open for the
first time in decades. And though the Republican primary drew four
reasonably experienced but little-known contenders, the Democratic
contest between Florio, the former governor, and Corzine, who spent
tens of millions to gain name recognition, gave rise to a rarity in
state politics: a match between two genuine household names.
</P>
<P>
   Because the race has been so hard fought and so well publicized,
it has also confronted voters with an unusual number of important
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., arose
as the answer to a search by Democratic officials for an
anyone-but-Florio candidate. Even though Florio remains popular
with many rank-and-file Democrats, he was considered by party
leaders to be unelectable in November because of the memory of a
$2.8 billion tax increase he pushed through the Legislature as
governor in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's appeal to voters, not surprisingly, has been framed as
a choice between an unhappy memory, embodied by Florio, and his own
idealized vision for the future, with strict gun controls and
ambitious new universal programs for health care, education and
long-term care for the elderly and disabled. But to judge from the
attack commercials Corzine has been running for more than a month,
it remains, at its root, a not-Florio campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, too, has naturally cast the race in terms that suit him.
For months, he described the primary as a choice between his 30
years of experience in Congress and state government and Corzine's
naivete.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Florio has seized upon Corzine's campaign
spending, asking voters whether they cared to let Corzine buy the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Voters can seize on only a few issues on which the men hold
opposing views. Corzine opposes the death penalty, and Florio
favors it, for example. And Corzine supports a limited investment
of the Social Security trust fund in the stock market, to extend
the fund's solvency, a position Florio has vilified in the starkest
terms. But the sharp line between the men on this subject was
blurred when it was reported that Florio's and Corzine's positions
were identical as recently as a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are more subtle questions, too. A vote for Corzine's
platform, for example _ with its hard-line support for abortion
rights, gay rights, affirmative action, gun control and big
government programs _ would seem to represent an embrace of the
kind of liberalism that has been out of fashion for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, meanwhile, has in many ways made his own campaign a
referendum on the nation's economic boom, warning voters that the
fantastic wealth created by the new economy has momentarily
obscured looming problems on issues like Social Security and
pension financing. Florio has hammered away at Corzine on trade
policy, corporate mergers and government borrowing. In doing so, he
has employed the kind of class-based attacks Democrats frequently
aim at Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one watchword in the primary, however, it is
electability. On the Republican side, voters must pick a contender
for November from a field of four relatively unknown candidates:
William L. Gormley, a veteran state senator from the south; Robert
D. Franks, a four-term congressman from New Jersey's prosperous
midsection; James W. Treffinger, a county executive in
predominantly Democratic Essex County; and Murray Sabrin, a former
Libertarian candidate for governor. In this race, where turnout is
expected to be light, party endorsements are likely to play a heavy
role.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, every attack that Florio and Corzine
employ can be reduced to the idea that only one of them has a
reasonable chance to prevail in November. To Florio, his opponent
is too left-wing, too soft. In Corzine's eyes, Florio is too
combative to win over even the most moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic voters have to ask themselves whether they're
selecting a candidate, be it Florio or Corzine, who can win,'' said
Gerald M. Pomper, a political science professor at Rutgers.
``Primaries are about such practical calculations. After all,
you're selecting somebody to carry the party's banner, not just
somebody you like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
