<SLUG> BC-MOMA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT WITH NO END IN SIGHT: PICKETING AT MUSEUM OF MODERN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A strike by workers at the Museum of Modern Art has
entered its sixth week with no sign of a settlement in sight. The
two sides have not held face-to-face negotiations since before the
walkout began.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say the strikers are holding strong even though
the museum says 117 of the 250 workers in the bargaining unit have
returned to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are holding up well,'' said Maida Rosenstein,
president of Local 2110 of the United Automobile Workers, which
represents the museum's assistant curators, bookshop workers,
librarians and other administrative workers. ``I think people's
resolve has hardened.''
</P>
<P>
   Each day since the strike began, between 10 and 30 strikers have
stood outside the museum, holding signs and urging tourists not to
visit. But museum officials say the strike has had little effect on
attendance or internal operations.
</P>
<P>
   A mediator with the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service
checks in periodically with the two sides to see whether they are
prepared to show new flexibility that would make it worthwhile to
bring negotiators together.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are divided over numerous issues, including health
coverage, wages, job security and the union's demand that all new
museum employees be required to join the union or, should they
decide not to join, pay the equivalent of union dues.
</P>
<P>
   That would create what is known as an agency shop, as opposed to
the current open shop, in which workers do not have to join the
union or pay dues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rosenstein said the demand to require museum employees to join
the union or pay dues was needed to strengthen the union and give
it more leverage against management. But museum officials said they
were reluctant to grant that demand because it would give more
power to a union that they say has irresponsible leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not shown itself to be a union whose strength the
museum wants to increase,'' said Robert Batterman, the museum's
chief negotiator. ``This has shown itself to be a union that's
destructive and not to be trusted. The museum is not looking to
increase its strength and its sway over the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the union's leadership has been dishonest in presenting
management's bargaining offers to the rank and file _ a charge that
Rosenstein vigorously denies.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman predicted that if the union dropped its demand for an
agency shop, the two sides would soon be able to settle their other
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstein said the museum had rejected the union's demand for
an agency shop because the museum wanted to prolong the strike to
weaken the union. She argued that the museum was being inconsistent
in not granting that demand when the six other unions at the
museum, including those representing guards, janitors and
engineers, had contracts requiring workers to join the union or pay
dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of simple fairness,'' Rosenstein said. ``If
people are hired into union jobs, they ought to be part of the
union. They get all the benefits of the contract. We have to
negotiate for them and represent them.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that when those workers who did not belong to the
union filed a grievance, the union had to represent them, a
sometimes expensive process that could involve hiring lawyers to
handle arbitrations.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials said the high percentage of workers who had
returned to their jobs showed that the strike was not going well
for the union. But Rosenstein said it was to be expected that many
employees would return to work because they were not required to
join the union. In most strikes, unions can penalize members who
cross the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had agency shop in the beginning, we certainly wouldn't
have had to go on strike for this long,'' said Eden Schulz, a
worker in the museum's permissions department. ``They would have
known that 250 members of the bargaining unit would walk out.''
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said that since the bargaining unit, known as the
Professional and Administrative Staff Association, was formed 30
years ago, the workers had not been required to join the union. He
said there was no need to change that system, saying it had worked
well.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said that most employees did not join the union,
except in the months just before contract negotiations. ``Half the
staff doesn't want to be forced to join at any given time, and
that's not going to change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstein said the museum was being anti-union for rejecting
the agency shop demand.
</P>
<P>
   But Batterman said, ``The museum is the furthest thing from an
anti-union employer. This is a matter of history and tradition.
This staff insisted on an open shop when it unionized. It's become
part of tradition, and the museum is not going to require people to
support the union.''
</P>
<P>
   One assistant curator, who crossed the picket line and harshly
criticizes the union's leadership, said that management was being
shortsighted in rejecting the agency shop demand.
</P>
<P>
   This curator, who insisted on anonymity, said that if all
workers had to join the union, then many moderating voices at odds
with the union's leadership would then belong to the union, causing
the union to be more moderate in negotiations and reducing the
likelihood and length of a strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0146 </DOCNO>
