u a BC-NY-CIGARETTES-695&AMP;ADD     06-03 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CIGARETTES-695&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE BILL IS SOUGHT OVER FIRE-SAFE CIGARETTES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Legislative leaders and Gov. George Pataki are in
intensive talks on a bill to require less flammable cigarettes _ a
compromise to replace a bill that Pataki vetoed late last month _
while the Assembly seriously considers a vote to override that
veto.
</P>
<P>
   With just two weeks left until the Legislature is scheduled to
adjourn for the year, the Senate and the Assembly are trying to
accommodate concerns raised by Pataki, whose May 24 veto caught
both houses by surprise. The sticking point has been the governor's
insistence that along with the bill on fire safety, the Legislature
approve his separate measure to combat cigarette bootlegging and
Internet sales of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Assembly's Democratic majority _ and, less
vocally, some Republican legislators _ have accused the governor, a
Republican, of inventing reasons to veto the bill and protect
tobacco industry interests. They say that he ignored or opposed
previous bills that dealt with bootlegging and Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get something done, but the governor's hypocrisy on
this issue is making it hard,'' said Assemblyman Alexander Grannis,
D-Manhattan, the bill's chief sponsor in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Grannis is pushing for the Assembly to vote Monday on a motion
to override the veto, and aides to the Assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, say he is inclined to agree. The Assembly Democrats will
meet on Monday to decide how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   An override vote would be no more than a symbolic step _ a very
public, and relatively rare, slap at the governor _ because the
Republican-controlled Senate would not go along. And Republicans in
the Senate and in the governor's office warn that it could be
counterproductive, making a compromise less likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to getting a bill this session that the
governor can sign,'' said Michael McKeon, the governor's
communications director. ``Instead of posturing, let's move forward
with good, comprehensive legislation that ensures that we have
fire-safe cigarettes and cracks down on bootlegging.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Assembly and the Senate passed a bill that would
have made New York the first state to set fire-safety standards for
cigarettes. The bill would have required that by 2002, all
cigarettes sold in the state stop burning when they are not being
puffed on. Advocates said the measure would have saved dozens of
lives and prevented hundreds of fires each year, and would have put
pressure on Congress to adopt national fire-safety standards for
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Over a month later, in the last two days he had to act on the
bill, the governor raised several objections and linked the measure
to his bill on bootlegging and Internet sales. In the end, he and
legislative leaders could not resolve all their differences, and he
vetoed the fire-safety bill.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies opposed the bill, saying that state-by-state
standards would be a burden for them. Anti-tobacco groups say the
industry's real concern is that if cigarettes do not burn
continuously, smokers might use fewer of them, cutting down on
sales. The less flammable cigarettes do not cost more to make.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are working on a compromise bill, and officials in
all three camps say they are likely to reach agreement soon. At the
governor's request, the bill would give cigarette companies six
months, rather than 30 days, to comply with fire-safety standards
once they are published, and would provide for fines for retailers
who sell noncomplying cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In another bow to Pataki, the compromise bill would also require
the state to make a finding that the new cigarettes posed no more
of a health risk to smokers than the old kind. ``The information we
have indicates that that is not really an issue, but we'll address
it anyway,'' said Sen. Frank Padavan of Queens, the chief Senate
sponsor of the bill. ``We want to come up with a bill that he
cannot veto.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of the bill on bootlegging and Internet sales
remains murky. Senate leaders have signaled that they will pass the
governor's bill, while Assembly Democrats and aides to Silver say
they are not sure what the Assembly will do.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pataki's bill would prohibit mail-order sellers, like those on
the Internet, from shipping cigarettes directly to individuals.
Such sales methods evade payment of the state's $1.11-per-pack
cigarette tax, the nation's highest, and can be used by minors to
buy cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the governor would require that the seller ship the
cigarettes to a licensed retailer, like a corner liquor store.
There, the buyer, after showing proof of age and paying the tax,
could pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   Bootlegging, the shipping of cigarettes into New York without
payment of state taxes, has become a bigger problem since the state
doubled its tax in March. Pataki has contended that smokers may not
like fire-safe cigarettes, encouraging still more bootlegging.
Backers of the bill dispute that, pointing to tobacco industry
studies that show that smokers cannot tell the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But legislators in both parties say that the governor showed no
interest in a variety of anti-bootlegging bills proposed in recent
years, and that he quietly opposed some.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Assemblyman Jeff Klein of the Bronx introduced a bill
to ban Internet sales of cigarettes, for the same reasons the
governor gave for his bill this year. The administration sent him a
letter in opposition to his bill, calling it illegal, but giving no
indication that the governor shared any of the concerns about
Internet sales. The bill passed, 148-2, but died in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
