<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINATOWN-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE-AMERICANS WHO SERVED IN U.S. MILITARY HAILED
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Mass.) By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About 900 marchers came from as far as San Francisco
on Saturday to honor Chinese-Americans who served in the U.S.
military.
</P>
<P>
   The parade commemorated the 50th anniversary of the start of the
Korean War, with veterans of that war marching near the front. It
also commemorated the 55th anniversary of the founding of
Chinatown's American Legion Post.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers, following dancing dragons, started at Columbus
Park on Mulberry Street in Chinatown in the ``We Serve With Pride
Parade,'' which was organized by the Lt. B.R. Kimlau Chinese
Memorial Post 1291 of the American Legion.
</P>
<P>
   They marched up Mulberry Street to Canal Street, then past a
reviewing stand near the Chinese-American Veterans' War Memorial,
in Chatham Square, where a statue built by Post 1291 was to be
rededicated and new officers were to be installed. A banquet was to
follow, with a private screening of a movie called ``We Served With
Pride.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimlau Post, which claims to be the largest Chinese-American
post of the American Legion, was named after a World War II
bombardier who was killed near New Guinea. It has about 600 members
from the New York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   There were not large numbers of Chinese-Americans in the
nation's wars, said Fang Wong, Post 1291's leader, who served in
Vietnam. ``You'd see them scattered,'' he said. ``There was not one
field where they were more highly visible than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Yuu, 76, was marching with a group of Chinese-American
veterans from Boston. ``I'm very very happy to come,'' he said.
``We're in good health so we come.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Chu, a member of Post 1291 who lives in New Hyde Park
and who fought on Okinawa in World War II, said he marched to show
his patriotism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
