<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DIMAGGIO-ATTORNEY0604     06-03 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-ATTORNEY0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morris Engelberg: Still saying so for Joe
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Fla. _ A tall man, 6-foot-4, drives a white van with
the license plate, ``DIMAG 5.'' He parks in front of a sign that
says, ``Reserved for the Yankee Clipper, Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg gets out. He is a 60-year-old lawyer in a
jogging suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Joe's,'' he explains, gesturing toward the van. ``I
just had it out to get it serviced.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to him is a parking space reserved for Morris Engelberg. It
is empty.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg is the sole trustee of DiMaggio's will, but few
attorneys identify so closely with their clients. For that matter,
the average attorney does not name his office plaza ``Yankee
Clipper Center,'' spend $8,500 on a marble plaque memorializing his
most famous client outside the front door, or drop another $2,300
to create museum-like rooms inside, with scores of DiMaggio
photographs and other memorabilia. When DiMaggio died last year at
his Hollywood home at age 84, no one had more control over his life
than Engelberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obsessed,'' Engelberg said. ``I admit it. He was like a
father to me. My own father died three months before I was born. As
a child in New York, I used to tell people Joe DiMaggio was my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they never met until DiMaggio reached the final two
decades of his life, but the attorney came to assume a powerful
role in the slugger's final years. That role would put him at odds
with political leaders in San Francisco, members of the Hollywood
(Fla.) Chamber of Commerce and DiMaggio's own brother Dom, who has
a home in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those people wondered if the line that separates Morris
Engelberg from Joe DiMaggio, like the line between their parking
spaces, has been rubbed out in Engelberg's mind somewhere along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg hired attorneys to file a lawsuit last week in federal
court in Miami to stop San Francisco from using DiMaggio's name at
a playground where he and his brothers used to play as children,
calling the playground unfit to bear DiMaggio's legendary name.
It's the most serious escalation yet in a war of words that has
gone on for months.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Supervisor Gavin Newsom said the North Beach
playground is anything but a dump _ the city has committed $4
million in improvements around a park that includes a pool and
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really an outrage and an insult to the people of San
Francisco,'' Newsom said.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom sees a troubling contradiction in the way Engelberg has
moved to block the naming of the playground and other gestures to
honor DiMaggio _ on the grounds it would cheapen the Yankee great's
name _ yet has allowed the auctioning of DiMaggio's personal
effects, including his driver license and passport, and now says he
is seeking up to $2 million for a book about DiMaggio's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is doing a disservice to Joe's legacy,'' Newsom
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio, one of three brothers to play in the big leagues
at the same time, supports the naming of the San Francisco
playground. Dom has homes in Ocean Ridge and Marion, Mass. He was
hurt and angered by Engelberg's claims that Dom was out socializing
last year while his brother was dying in his attorney's arms 40
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely false and venomous statement,'' Dom
DiMaggio said. ``That's all I want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg said he did not tell Dom and other family members
about the true extent of Joe's illness because that was the way Joe
wanted it. Only a handful of people, including Engelberg and
DiMaggio's doctors, were allowed to know, he said.
</P>
<P>
   From his hospital bed, DiMaggio entrusted Engelberg with the
responsibility to look after his legacy, according to the attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grabbed my tie _ I remember it was a blue one _ and said,
'You better protect my name,' '' Engelberg said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his book, Engelberg said he thinks Joe would approve _
even though while still alive, DiMaggio once vetoed a book deal
Engelberg had arranged with Simon &AMP; Schuster. Reason: He didn't
want to go on talk shows and be asked about former wife Marilyn
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg hints his book will delve into Monroe, among other
topics, but adds 25 percent of the proceeds will go to the Joe
DiMaggio Children's Hospital in Hollywood. By the time agents' fees
and taxes are taken out, Engelberg figures he will get about 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney-author has hired International Management Group to
represent him. Asked if IMG really expects the book to grab a $1
million or $2 million advance, Mark Reiter, vice president in IMG's
literary division in New York, answered, ``I sure hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   IMG does not expect the book to appear on shelves for at least a
year. Engelberg said he has written a draft, though IMG expects a
ghostwriter to be brought in at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should all be so lucky to have somebody protect us so
fiercely,'' Reiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Loy Anderson, president of Palm Beach National Bank, counts
himself a friend of Engelberg's and says nobody fights harder to
protect a client _ particularly a client who happens to be a
personal hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I think Morris always put Joe first, even ahead of
his own family,'' Anderson said. ``If you're looking for a trustee,
that's all you could ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   At his office, pictures of Engelberg's wife and daughter are
blended with those of DiMaggio. Here is Joltin' Joe at the
daughter's wedding. There is one with the wife.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the DiMaggio case is not the first in which
Engelberg has clashed with a client's blood relations. When
world-famous dollmaker Madame Bee Alexander died in 1990, Engelberg
challenged a version of her will that left most of her $12 million
estate to her daughter, Mildred Birnbaum of Boca Raton. He
supported an earlier version that named him executor, with a
reported $240,000 fee. It cut out the daughter entirely, and left
the bulk to Alexander's friends, former employees and charities.
Engelberg's firm claimed Alexander, who was 95 when she died, was
incompetent and brainwashed by her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Birnbaum reportedly received most of the money in a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who was Alexander's banker, said the dollmaker did
experience a loss of her mental faculties late in life, so a
challenge to a rewritten will was not unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   One executive with no complaints against Engelberg is Frank
Sacco, chief executive officer of Memorial Healthcare System.
That's the company that runs Memorial Regional Hospital in
Hollywood, where Joe DiMaggio's Children's Hospital is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morris did nothing but to work with us in a very cooperative
fashion,'' Sacco said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital decided to approach DiMaggio eight years ago with
an idea to care for sick children regardless of their families'
ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned the way to approach him was through Morris
Engelberg,'' Sacco said. ``We met in Morris' office. Joe asked what
we wanted and I told him. He wanted to see the place.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio eventually agreed to lend his name to what would become
his best-known charitable project. Later, in his illness, DiMaggio
would spend many of his final days at Memorial Regional.
</P>
<P>
   There was little question in Sacco's mind that Engelberg became
the gatekeeper for DiMaggio's life because it was what Joe wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally met with Joe,'' Sacco said, referring to a
meeting he remembered from late 1998. ``At that meeting, DiMaggio
said he was giving power of attorney to Engelberg. Morris was the
custodian. He had power of attorney. Our legal people said
everything is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg donated pictures of Joe that still decorate the lobby
in the children's hospital.
</P>
<P>
   It was other memorabilia, though, that raised eyebrows at a
Christie's auction in April in New York. DiMaggio's 1986 Florida
driver license was sold for $11,750, and his passport was offered
as well. The items were described as being owned by Engelberg and
others who worked for or knew DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Many items did not sell, including a golf cart Engelberg gave
DiMaggio, and a 1951 jersey worn in DiMaggio's final game. The
jersey was offered for a minimum bid of $120,000 by a woman who
worked in DiMaggio's home. She said she found it in a shopping bag
under DiMaggio's bed after his death. DiMaggio had given it to a
New York detective and the officer's family returned it to DiMaggio
after the officer's death, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's will makes Engelberg the trustee. Engelberg got a
court order last year that seals as ``confidential'' records that
describe the contents of the estate. As a result, the man in
control of sorting out what belonged to DiMaggio and his heirs, as
opposed to what was given as gifts to friends including Engelberg,
is Engelberg himself.
</P>
<P>
   The memorabilia designated as part of DiMaggio's estate was sold
last year to collector Ralph Perullo for a price the buyer said was
``in the millions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dom was cut out of the will entirely and son Joe DiMaggio Jr.
received just $20,000. More generous amounts went to DiMaggio's two
granddaughters and to nephew Joe DiMaggio, who lives in Boynton
Beach and is the son of Joe's brother Mike. Engelberg, who said he
never gave DiMaggio a legal bill when he was alive, will receive a
fee whose amount is not disclosed in the will.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Jr. was the only son of DiMaggio and actress Dorothy Arnold,
who were married in 1939 and divorced five years later. He
struggled with substance abuse problems and homelessness and was
sometimes described as ``estranged'' from his father. In the
mid-1970s, he had a blood clot removed from his brain after an auto
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Engelberg said it was untrue he or his father shut the son
out. The attorney arranged a condo for Joe Jr. in Hollywood. The
son was a pallbearer at his father's funeral, only to die himself,
apparently from natural causes at age 57, in a California hospital
in August.
</P>
<P>
   At Mama Mia's restaurant, at the circle on Hollywood Boulevard
and U.S. 1, DiMaggio had his own table, in the lounge near the
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Autograph seekers, young and old, frequently closed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He preferred kids to adults,'' manager Cathy Iezza said. ``He
thought adults were trying to take advantage of him.''
</P>
<P>
   That blend of shyness and suspicion may say something about why
DiMaggio allowed Morris Engelberg to play the role he did.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood attorney David Singer puzzled over that role last
year. He was part of a Chamber of Commerce group that wanted to
rename that city's Presidential Circle for DiMaggio. He was
surprised to be rebuffed with letters from Engelberg's firm
threatening legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals were purely civic-minded,'' Singer said. ``It sounded
like a no-lose situation. It was met not even with 'no, thanks,'
but threats and insinuations. There was no need for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer said it was unsettling to watch the way DiMaggio left the
world, increasingly separated from family and longtime friends as
Engelberg's influence over him seemed to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ended up with almost no family attachments, no friends,
everything was controlled by this one guy,'' Singer said. ``That's
a strange ending for a man who's an important part of the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
