<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CANES-BEACHES0604-COX     06-03 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANES-BEACHES0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waves of discord wash over beach issue
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When a hurricane crashes ashore, it washes the beach
away.
</P>
<P>
   This season _ when hurricane watchers predict 11 named storms
will form, including three with wind speeds of at least 115 mph _
coastal cities from Miami Beach to Long Island will spend $50
million to $85 million in federal funds on beach protection and
restoration. Congress continues debate on the final amount, which
has been as high as $100 million in years past.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the U.S. population lives in coastal areas.
Florida reports more than 12 million coastal residents, Virginia 4
million, Louisiana 2 million and South Carolina nearly 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Every day more people move to the shore to experience sand
between their toes and sunrises over the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal growth continues despite the forecast of a 60 percent
chance that a hurricane will hit somewhere on the U.S. coast this
season. The average probability of U.S. landfall, according to
researchers at Colorado State University, is 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A point of consternation _ not in Congress but in the local
communities where this is an issue _ is whether people should be
living on barrier islands,'' said Howard Marlowe, president of the
pro-beach American Coastal Coalition lobby based in Washington,
D.C. ``The fact is folks are living there. . . . People are not
going to leave, so we have to do something responsible to protect
our coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Beach towns are more than quaint villages. They're money makers.
</P>
<P>
   Beach economies in coastal congressional districts from
Louisiana to Virginia account for more than $48.6 billion in
tourism expenditures _ more than a quarter of the $185 billion
generated by the nation's seaside cities, according to the coastal
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, tourists spend about $30 billion a year. Georgia
beach visitors spend more than $1 billion a year. On Tybee Island,
a seasonal population of 3,000 swells to 10 times that from now
through August.
</P>
<P>
   That's why communities make their beaches wider by dumping sand,
a process known as renourishment.
</P>
<P>
   While it adds a theoretical buffer against the daily grind of
waves that move the beach back to the sea, fresh sand also puts
more distance between homes and destructive hurricane waters.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane storm surge, the wall of wind-whipped water built on
top of the tide, wipes away hotdog stands, cottages, boardwalks _
and sand.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of shoreline protection programs, however, claim the
projects are futile attempts to keep Mother Nature from destroying
private beachfront developments and tax-supported amenities like
roads, parks and sewers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, U.S. Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) of Savannah, who serves
the Georgia coast, has helped secure federal money in the past for
Tybee Island beach nourishment. Officials want it to keep their
industry afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm alarmed that what we're doing is buying time from Mother
Nature,'' Kingston said. ``Beaches come and beaches go. But when a
tourist comes, he doesn't want to know, `Is there going to be sand
or not this year?' I'm admitting it is a prop up (of the local
economy). . . . But it's a worthwhile investment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Legislature has started allocating $30 million a
year for beach protection. Last summer, Panama City completed a $21
million restoration project that pumped 8.5 million cubic yards of
sand _ almost 800,000 dump-truck loads _ along 17 miles of beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying beach restoration is the panacea of all
erosion projects,'' said Payden Woodruff, environmental
administrator of the Florida office of Beaches and Coastal Systems.
``But if tourism and recreation are the basis of your economy,
you're going to protect it. Some people say, `Let the buildings
fall in.' Well, what's the political reality of that?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for instance, the hurricane tag team of Dennis and
Floyd severely eroded North Carolina's coast from Ocean Isle north
to the Outer Banks. The state's most dramatic damage occurred
inland when rivers overflowed and turned streets into canals.
</P>
<P>
   But the sea claimed its share of beach houses. On Oak Island,
Hurricane Floyd washed away 50 cottages over a 3-mile stretch,
causing more than $25 million in private property losses. Some
homes had been in families for three generations.
</P>
<P>
   Those homeowners, though, got what was coming to them by
building on the beach, said renowned shoreline development critic
Orrin Pilkey.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke University geologist complains the federal program is a
waste of money in an erosion battle nature is destined to win. On
the East Coast of the United States, beachfront lots receive annual
federal shore protections worth an average of $4,000 to $18,000 a
year, Pilkey says.
</P>
<P>
   Pilkey's studies show nourished beaches actually erode up to 12
times faster than non-nourished ones because the natural flow of
sand is altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The erosion exists because people build right next to the
beach,'' said Pilkey, who's raised the ire of coastal managers
throughout the Southeast. ``If people didn't build there, there
wouldn't be a problem. Why should I in Durham or someone in Omaha
pay for someone who's dumb enough to live next to the beach and
then be his savior?''
</P>
<P>
   Groups like the National Wildlife Federation suggest the federal
government should cut in half its funding of beach replenishment.
In a March report on what it called wasteful water projects, the
environmental group complained beach nourishment ``encourages risky
development on congested shorelines. Alternatives such as voluntary
property buyouts, relocations and land swaps for less risky areas
should be explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a beachfront is saturated with development, flexibility in
shoreline management disappears, Pilkey argues. Officials will
build sea walls to protect high rises, all of which will wipe out a
beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're increasing the value of their property and giving them
protection,'' Pilkey said. ``That makes beachfront owners the
luckiest people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   On the North Carolina coast, Oak Island Mayor Joan Altman wishes
she had had some of that luck last September when Hurricane Floyd
washed out homes, water lines, roads and cable. The storm washed
out about $12 million of the town's tax base at the beach, its
primary source of revenue. A town gymnasium has been put on hold
because of the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss from Floyd means we've had to tighten our belts in
some places,'' Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the houses lost in the storm can't be rebuilt on the
beach because the water's too close to the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real losers are the public and the town. We can't insure
our tax base,'' Altman said. ``It's a loss to the town forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The widest spots of the beach, where sand from nearby dredging
is regularly dumped, suffered no loss of private property. Beyond
that, Altman advocates more scientific renourishment that involves
years of study and construction by the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers. She helped form the North Carolina Shore and Beach
Preservation Association, a group that lobbies for federal
renourishment funds.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, North Carolina has ranked seventh in the
nation in the amount of sand-pumping funds received from Congress,
with $16 million in federal renourishment funds. Neighbors Virginia
and South Carolina each got more than $40 million during that
period. New Jersey topped the list at $115 million followed by New
York at $105 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe that perhaps $1 million of sand at Oak Island
would have saved $25 million in property damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic benefits outweigh the cost of nourishment,''
Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
