<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CANES-EVAC0604-COX     06-03 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANES-EVAC0604-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricanes: Can we escape?
</P>
<P>
   By Chris Burritt and Alan Judd
</P>
<P>
   HOBOKEN, Ga. _ Bumper to bumper, stretching for 25 miles, tens
of thousands of motorists fleeing Hurricane Floyd crept through
this southeast Georgia town.
</P>
<P>
   Directing traffic at Hoboken's lone blinking traffic light was
Hoboken's lone policeman, Darren Crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a free-for-all,'' Crews said, recalling last Sept. 14,
when weary, panicky drivers from as far away as Miami ignored his
signals to stop. Some nearly ran over the 300-pound lawman.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles hauling campers and boats overheated and conked out in
Hoboken, 40 miles west of Brunswick. The scorching pavement
blistered Crews' feet.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he'd liked to have ticketed violators, he was too
busy dodging them. Working with a Brantley County sheriff's deputy,
Crews answered questions from motorists hanging out windows, all
the time wondering, amid the exhaust and horn blowing, when the
stop-and-go caravan would end.
</P>
<P>
   It ended late that night, after 200,000 vehicles had passed
through. ``It was total chaos, mayhem,'' Crews said.
</P>
<P>
   With hurricane season officially beginning last week, Crews, 29,
is bracing for a replay of Floyd, despite months of planning and
pledges of better cooperation and communication among Southeastern
emergency planners.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by the nation's largest evacuation _ 3.5 million
people from Florida, Georgia and the Carolinas fled Floyd _ state
and federal officials say they're better prepared for the next
hurricane threat.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd claimed 51 lives in North Carolina, which is still
recovering from its worst natural disaster ever. Here in Hoboken,
by contrast, Floyd ``hardly blew down any limbs,'' Crews recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But two days of evacuations demonstrated how Georgia faltered in
moving and sheltering evacuees in advance of Floyd's eventual
landfall at Cape Fear, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuees consisted of 350,000 coastal Georgians and a large
portion of the 2.3 million people who fled from Florida and some of
the 750,000 who left South Carolina, according to Georgia's
evacuation and shelter task force.
</P>
<P>
   The average evacuation time was seven hours from the Savannah
area and 6.4 hours from the Brunswick area, according to a recent
survey by Florida State University geography professor Earl J.
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ran like they never ran before,'' said Bill Massey, the
Federal Emergency Management Agency's hurricane program manager in
Atlanta. ``They knew this thing had the potential to come in and
smack them.''
</P>
<P>
   FEMA is working with Southeastern state agencies to improve
computer monitoring of evacuations. It hopes eventually to develop
a Web-based program so people can log onto personal computers and
see for themselves which evacuation routes are least congested.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Massey said FEMA is encouraging states to work
together on more conventional evacuation strategies, with help from
federal emergency planners.
</P>
<P>
   One such effort is set for Tuesday. Emergency management
officials from southeast Georgia and northeast Florida will meet in
Kingsland to work on evacuation efforts via staggered traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to coordinate it so that Florida people can be
moved out before Georgia people start evacuating,'' said Ed Abel,
the emergency management director for Georgia's Glynn County.
</P>
<P>
   That in turn could relieve traffic tie-ups in crossroads towns
such as Hoboken (population 440), which found itself smack in the
middle of a traffic jam stretching along U.S. 82 from Nahunta to
Waycross.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Crews is skeptical. ``If we had to evacuate tomorrow, it
would be the same thing as during Floyd,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia officials plan to erect hundreds of signs
designating evacuation routes and signaling directions to emergency
shelters. Plans also call for increasing the number of shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to improve communications with the public, Georgia
agencies will use Peach State Public Radio to broadcast travel
advisories, evacuation routes and shelter locations statewide.
</P>
<P>
   To speed the departure of coastal dwellers during an evacuation,
Georgia officials decided to extend by about 40 miles the stretch
of I-16 that could be made one-way heading west from Savannah. Four
lanes of traffic would flow west until U.S. 441 at Vienna, where
the I-16 median is being paved to help motorists return to the
normal westbound lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not mean we will not have traffic problems and
congestion,'' said Chuck Gregg, hurricane specialist for the
Georgia Emergency Management Agency. ``But it does mean we can stay
one step ahead of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans in South Carolina, Florida and Louisiana also call for
traffic to flow inland one-way during evacuations. They include
I-26 between Charleston and Columbia and U.S. 501 from Myrtle Beach
in South Carolina, seven major roadways in Florida and I-10 from
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, where highway officials and state troopers
tested the lane-reversal plan last month, Gov. Jim Hodges took the
blame for delays in reversing eastbound traffic on I-26 before
Floyd. That stranded tens of thousands of motorists, including some
who took 18 hours or longer to travel what is typically a 90-minute
trip from Charleston to Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only hope that (Hodges) learned a very important lesson
from that one,'' said Jan Maguire, 46, who evacuated from
Charleston with her 11-year-old daughter, Rachel, Pumpkin the cat
and Tigger the lizard.
</P>
<P>
   After traveling for 21 hours, while ``moving 2 feet then
stopping for 15 to 20 minutes,'' they arrived in Lexington, a
Columbia suburb. Maguire said it would be a ``tough call'' deciding
whether to evacuate again.
</P>
<P>
   Although emergency planners worry that coastal dwellers might
balk at evacuation, the Florida State survey of 7,000 people found
that fewer than 20 percent would not evacuate again under similar
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of people who evacuated (from Floyd) will
evacuate in the future, too,'' said Baker, the professor who
conducted the survey for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Baker also found that evacuees unnecessarily worsened highway
congestion in advance of Floyd. In Florida, for instance, officials
ordered 1.3 million people to evacuate, but an estimated 2 million
left their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, those extra people left noncoastal counties adjacent
to counties under evacuation orders, Baker said. In such counties
in Georgia, about 30 percent of the residents evacuated, even
though there was no reason for them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many evacuees tended to go farther than they
needed to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the word to those people somehow,'' Baker
said. ``If the area you're driving through is not being told to
leave, you'd be safe, too, if you stopped there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hoboken, Officer Crews can only hope that evacuees go
elsewhere during the next hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever seen a city in shock,'' he said, ``it was us
when that traffic came through.''
</P>
<P>
   Searching for alternatives to clogged I-95, I-75 and I-16,
motorists from southeastern Georgia and Florida veered on to U.S.
82 and Ga. 121, which intersect at the blinking light in Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   During normal times, the intersection is so congested by logging
and wood chip trucks that Crews has requested, unsuccessfully, that
state highway officials install a stoplight.
</P>
<P>
   Crews now believes that, judging by Floyd's evacuation, the
officers directing traffic are imperiled. ``Drivers will pay more
attention to a light changing colors than you waving your arms,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hoboken intersection didn't make the Georgia Department
of Transportation's list of 37 intersections considered critical
during an evacuation. The two nearest to Hoboken are at U.S. 82 and
U.S. 301 in Nahunta and U.S. 82 and U.S. 1 in Waycross.
</P>
<P>
   State highway planners don't doubt that Hoboken had problems
during Floyd's evacuation, said assistant maintenance engineer
Bryant Poole, but so did dozens of other places _ and planners have
focused on improving the intersections best suited for evacuating
large numbers of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got millions of people evacuating,'' Poole said,
``you've got problems everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
