u a BC-CANES-NCTOWN0604-COX     06-03 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANES-NCTOWN0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Town ready to regain use of bridge
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cindy Deaton never figured she'd miss a chunk of
concrete as badly as she does the bridge over Quankey Creek in
Halifax, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The two-lane bridge has been out of commission for nearly nine
months, ever since Hurricane Floyd turned the swampy creek into a
raging torrent that dug a crater 200 feet wide, cutting off the
bridge where motorists once crossed.
</P>
<P>
   People living in the southern end of Halifax County face a
detour of 20 minutes or more whenever they go to the courthouse in
Halifax to pay taxes or go to court.
</P>
<P>
   A popular spot less than a mile from the U.S. 301 bridge, Elias'
Supermarket and Grill has lost about half of its business, owner
Artie Elias said.
</P>
<P>
   He figures he lost his Halifax customers to Piggly Wiggly and
other Roanoke Rapids groceries, which became more convenient,
although farther away. Many of Elias' customers are forced to
detour 12 miles to get to his store.
</P>
<P>
   Quankey Creek separates Deaton from her home in Roanoke Rapids
and her job as an office assistant at the state prison in Tillery.
The detour lengthens her trip by about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes seem to add up especially fast in the afternoons
when Deaton darts from work to pick up her 2 1/2-year-old daughter,
Samantha, from day care in Roanoke Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   So it's with a sense of personal urgency that she and others
await the opening of the new Quankey Creek bridge, one of three in
Halifax County and one of 17 across North Carolina damaged so
severely by Floyd that they have to be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Floyd's flooding damaged 283 North Carolina bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minute counts when you are on the way,'' Deaton said.
``We are ready for our bridge to get back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   A new, $1 million bridge over Quankey Creek is scheduled to be
opened June 27, said John Emerson, assistant state bridge engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
