<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD0604-COX     06-03 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At late hour, Holyfield trains toward goal
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Midnight approaches. Do you know where your three-time
undisputed heavyweight champion is?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not cruising and clubbing, the nocturnal pastime of
choice for too many fighters. But neither is Evander Holyfield
between the sheets on this late Sunday night in mid-May, dreaming
whatever a rich-as-creme-brulee, woman-magnet, body-by-Blanks
celebrity dreams about.
</P>
<P>
   No, he's in the gym, training for the next fight.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh, now he's done it. Took one too many blows in the ring,
just as we feared, and got his body clock all out of sorts. Doesn't
know morning from night anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't boxers supposed to rise with the rooster's wake-up call,
wind down their work day by happy hour and have the rest of the day
to track down trouble?
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, that was Holyfield's routine, although his
relatively tame evening hours typically were spent at the movies or
a ballgame. ``I was always taught the early bird gets the worm,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lennox Lewis II, though, he turned his routine
inside-out, which brings us to a nearly unmarked upstairs room at
the rear of a bail-bond business in downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Main Street Boxing Gym is not, nor has it recently been, on
Main Street but rather in an area where you can park for a buck a
day. Holyfield is jumping rope, stretching and sparring in the
presence of his rainbow-coalition support group of trainer, fitness
adviser, manager, personal assistant; gym regulars; and five
Latinos who work in the bail-bond office. Gospel music, some with a
hip-hoppish back beat, blares through speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot better than the early-morning workouts,'' he says.
``My body gets accustomed to being up late. Previously, when I
fought in the evening and trained in the daytime, I'd wonder why I
was so sleepy (on fight night). I'd feel good in the locker room,
then get sleepy around 11 o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Holyfield is wide-eyed after sparring three
rounds with Sedrick Fields. All across the city, clocks are
striking twelve.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say he's too old,'' Fields pants. ``Pshaw. He's got
that fast combination, and he's got heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all accomplished athletes in the twilight of their careers,
Holyfield makes adjustments to compensate for an inevitable erosion
of ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older you get, it becomes more of a mental game,'' he
says. ``You work more on strategy. When I was younger, I didn't
work on no strategy. I worked on the idea I was going to beat the
daylights out of (the opponent). Now, I work on outthinking the
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The next guy is John Ruiz. They had set a date in Las Vegas for
Saturday at Caesars Palace, but a pulled muscle below Holyfield's
rib cage pushed the bout back to August. Aside from aerobic
activity, Holyfield will ease off the accelerator for a month, then
resume training.
</P>
<P>
   The carrot for this fight is a World Boxing Association title.
Lennox Lewis beat Holyfield twice last year _ once officially, once
not _ but had to unbuckle his WBA belt and hand it over for
refusing to fight the designated challenger, Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   The double whammo from Lewis and the anonymity of Ruiz has
gotten Holyfield demoted from the pay-per-view ranks to cable
television, Showtime. His projected pay is an unspecified few
million dollars _ a lottery-like windfall to the rest of us but
change spilled in the clothes dryer to Holyfield, who once
collected $35 million against Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when things don't go your way,'' he says, ``you take
two steps backward and then come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Ruiz is some palooka, ready to fall over at
the first stiff wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Critics) might call this guy a tomato can, . . . but he can't
wait to run into somebody and make his name,'' Holyfield says.
``I've got to tell him he bit off more than he can chew.''
</P>
<P>
   Although those words might apply more to Tyson, who once munched
on Holyfield's ears, the greater point is that he wants to treat
the three major belts as collectibles. If he corrals them all,
Holyfield would stand alone as a four-time, across-the-board
champion, at which time he would embark on some overseas farewell
tour to thank the global village for its support.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the Lennox Maul, a decisive win for Lewis in their
sequel last November, Holyfield might be waving arrivederci in
Rome, au revoir in Paris or adios in Buenos Aires. Instead, even
the best-case scenario seemingly calls for three more bouts. The
line forming to fight Lewis, the WBC and IBF designee, already
includes Francois Botha and David Tua.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ask to be in this situation,'' Holyfield says. ``I
should be the undisputed champion of the world now, going on my
tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the prideful one, he is convinced that the judges rendered
a wrongful verdict in Holyfield-Lewis II.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I watch the tape, there's no doubt about it. I whipped
him'' in the rematch, Holyfield says. ``When you compare it to the
first fight, you see a big difference with me. The reason he's
better is, I put the pressure on and made him fight _ and I still
got the best of him. I made the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, remember, I still had two belts. I was very aggressive,
so how could anything close go the (challenger)?''
</P>
<P>
   With Holyfield stretching his interests outside the ring, the
legendary trait of keeping his eye on the prize will be tested. His
Atlanta restaurant, Holyfield's New South Grill, recently toasted
its one-year anniversary. He contributes his name, money and
philosophy to a family-oriented cable TV network, MBC, for those
who ``want to watch shows with your kids and don't want to put your
hands over their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a music label, Real Deal Records, with a dozen artists.
His moribund clothing line, Holyfield Warrior, will resurface soon.
The Holyfield Foundation dabbles in local charities. Among his
endorsment connections is Coca-Cola, whom he steadfastly supports
in the backlash of discrimination charges by black employees.
</P>
<P>
   One distraction he happily unloaded was the dragged-out divorce
case with Janice Holyfield. Their split became official March 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your wife and you are having discord, that can allow you to
be weaker,'' he says. ``It's better to be single than to be in
disarray. It's a liability. Going into this fight, I don't have
that on my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so glad when we settled, I said, `Thank the Lord.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They are forgiving enough that Janice has remained on his
sprawling estate while her house outside of Atlanta is being
readied. ``We talk, see each other,'' he says. ``You don't trash
everything you know about the person.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, before his weekly return flight to Houston, he
had escorted her to a gate at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are (wondering), `I thought y'all were divorced?''' he
says, laughing.' '' ``We get along. Matter of fact, I get along
with all the mothers of my kids.'' That's six and nine,
respectively, for those counting.
</P>
<P>
   An imaginary conversation with one of his children partly keeps
Holyfield flailing away at age 37 in a sport that punishes
hangers-on far more than any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if I lost and said I quit? What is my son going to say
when I push him to do better? He'll say, `Daddy, you quit. You
didn't go back (in the ring) because those guys were bigger than
you, younger than you.' I'm back to prove to him you've got to give
your all in life. To learn from your mistakes and correct them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: He loves this game. ``Nobody has to call me to say,
`Wake up, Evander, and come to the gym.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Given his late-show training schedule, let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHT FACTS
</P>
<P>
   What: Evander Holyfield of Atlanta vs. John Ruiz of Chelsea,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   When: Tentatively in August.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Caesars Palace, Las Vegas (subject to change).
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Vacant WBA heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Holyfield 36-4-1, 25 KOs; Ruiz 36-3, 27 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   TV: Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
