<HEADLINE>
ROBERT C. BASSETT, 89, LAWYER AND PUBLISHER  
 JOSEPH A. BAILEY, 95, LAWYER AND POLITICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Wis., Fla., Conn., La., Ohio, Va.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert C. Bassett, a former lawyer, labor negotiator and
publisher who represented small-business interests on the councils
of two presidential administrations, died on May 2 in Las Vegas,
where he lived. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett was born in Sturgeon Bay, Wis., on March 2, 1911. He
earned a law degree from Harvard and was a founding partner at
Minahan &AMP; Bassett in Green Bay, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Navy as a lieutenant commander in World War
II, he moved to Chicago, where he became labor counsel for Hearst
Corp. In 1954, he became publisher of The Milwaukee Sentinel. Nine
years later, he founded Bassett Publishing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett served on the wage stabilization board in the Truman
administration and represented small-business interests on the pay
board of the Nixon administration from 1971 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   His third wife, the former Mary Holmes, died two years ago after
51 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett is survived by three daughters, Jane Quinn of Orlando,
Fla., Pamela Welter of Las Vegas and Karen Freeman of Westport,
Conn.; seven grandchildren; and eight great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Bailey, 95, Lawyer and Politician
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph A. Bailey, a Harlem lawyer and former
assistant attorney general for New York state who challenged Adam
Clayton Powell Jr. for his congressional seat, died May 17 at North
General Hospital in Harlem. He was 95 and lived in the Washington
Heights section of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Republican, Bailey ran against Powell in 1956, 1960
and 1964, but was easily defeated in the heavily Democratic 15th
District in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Arthur Bailey was born March 20, 1905, in rural Vaverda,
La., and grew up in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, he graduated from Lincoln University in Pennsylvania,
with a bachelor's degree in political science. He also attended
night classes at Columbia University and the New School for Social
Research. After receiving his law degree from Brooklyn Law School
in the mid-1940s, Bailey set up his law practice in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   He was assistant attorney general under Attorney General Louis
Lefkowitz in the 1960s and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey is survived by his wife of 47 years, the former Helen
Gordon. He is also survived by a daughter, Josette Bailey, of
Manhattan; two sons, Jonathan A. Bailey of Cleveland, and Gordon C.
Bailey of Washington; two sisters, Gertie Coleman and Lorraine
Brown, both of Roanoke, Va.; and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
