<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3763 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-Clinton-Praised-0604-     06-03 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Clinton-Praised-0604-Cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: For use either Sunday or Monday
 &HT;    Europeans Toast Clinton Foreign Policy
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   AACHEN, Germany Twelve centuries ago Charlemagne fashioned order
out of a continent of rival kingdoms and ruled most of what is
today's Europe from this ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   And so it seemed historically fitting that President Clinton
came here Friday to bask in the sunny glow of his own foreign
policy achievements that includes the expansion of a united and
prosperous Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In a week-long journey that ends Monday in the Ukraine, Clinton
has reveled in his role as the senior statesman of his age, bowing
for repeated accolades, even adulation, from a host of European
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, with your immense personal commitment, you have
brought the hope of a stabler world closer to reality,'' city mayor
Jurgen Linden gushed in a ceremony presenting Clinton with the
prestigious Charlemagne Prize for international statesmanship.
``You are not only a distinguished American president, but also a
great cosmopolitan.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, Clinton's status is the natural result of outlasting
his rivals. After seven and a half years in office, Clinton has
simply been around longer than any other leaders of major
democratic countries. Indeed, he's been around longer than leaders
of any of the permanent eight members of the United Nations
Security Council, with the notable exception of China's President,
Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   More than just longevity, though, Clinton is regarded, at times
revered, by his colleagues among the Group of Eight, or G-8,
nations for his conduct of a foreign policy that reflects his
country's rise as the world's last remaining superpower.
</P>
<P>
   For an outgoing president hoping to numb the sting of domestic
scandal with the balm of big picture accomplishments in foreign
affairs, Clinton's visit to Aachen provided a singularly shining
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days before, in Lisbon, Clinton also won high praise
from the president of the European Union Commission, Romano Prodi,
who declared Clinton no less than an honorary European, owing to
his efforts to strengthen U.S.-European security and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the reason why our transatlantic ties are so good now
and so strong,'' Prodi said, looking at Clinton during a joint
press conference. ``You belong to our family, really.''
</P>
<P>
   That was never an objective presented in Clinton's 1992 campaign
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Arkansas governor promised to ``focus like a laser
beam,'' on the domestic economy, a formula he employed to defeat
President Bush, an incumbent who had won the Cold War and the Gulf
War and was, in his own time, the undisputed senior statesman of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Once in office, though, Clinton learned, at times the hard way,
that foreign policy not only presented him with challenges that
couldn't be ignored, but also with opportunities to leave the kind
of legacy-making markers that a Republican-led Congress
consistently denied him on the domestic front.
</P>
<P>
   Where Congress has thwarted Clinton's plans for overhauling the
nation's health care system, for example, strengthening federal gun
controls or imposing a national energy tax, his Republican foes
have largely stood by and watched as he's pursued what has been, by
any reckoning, an aggressive and far-reaching agenda overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton led his NATO allies in ending Europe's bloodiest
conflict since World War II, in Bosnia, and in combating
institutional repression against ethnic Albanians in neighboring
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He has brokered a framework for peace in Northern Ireland, even
as he has worked, with negotiations as recently as this week, to
mediate an end to half a century of war and enmity in the fractious
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   He put more than $40 billion of U.S. money at risk in bailout
programs for Mexico, South Korea, Thailand and Indonesia, and
economists generally agree that the money was a wise and needed
investment in the economic security of a world of nations
increasingly bound by cross border commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He's crafted a new relationship between the United States and
China, ushering the world's most populous nation into the
130-country club of global trading nations playing by a single set
of rules.
</P>
<P>
   He's tied down North Korea's nuclear weapons program even as
he's helped nurture a thaw in Pyongyang's relations with Seoul, as
evidenced by the historic summit the two countries have planned for
mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   And this weekend Clinton is in Moscow for a summit with Russian
President Vladimir Putin, pursuing talks that could shift the
course of a generation of arms controls between the world's two
largest possessors of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's clear that the world, regardless of how it's
changed since the end of the Cold War, still looks to the United
States for leadership,'' said White House spokesman David
Stockwell, ``and that President Clinton, although he has a strong
domestic focus, has clearly become the world's elder statesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's critics contend that not all of his foreign policy
initiatives have advanced American interests abroad.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though some of Clinton's senior aides have taken to
referring to him as ``planet ruler'' in private, American influence
has its limits, as, critics say, does Clinton's skill as a
statesman.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of 20,000 U.S. troops, for example, Clinton was
able to force out a coup leader in Haiti and restore democratic
rule, but he's been unable to quell continuing domestic strife and
abject poverty in a country that remains the most tragic basket
case in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Balkans policy has ended the fighting without
supplanting it with anything like a genuine peace.
</P>
<P>
   He's made little apparent headway in persuading China to end its
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   He was humiliated last fall when Senate Republicans refused to
ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty prohibiting tests of
nuclear weapons, an accord Clinton had placed near the center of
his arms control agenda.
</P>
<P>
   And he was unable to stop even his close partner, former Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, from prosecuting a war in Chechnya that
destroyed much of the region, left a quarter of a million people
homeless and was characterized by some of the worst atrocities on
Russian soil since the time of Joseph Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most frustrating of all, despite seven years of trying,
Clinton's been unable to bring Israelis and Palestinians together
for a Camp David style peace conference, though he still harbors
hopes for convening such a summit as early as July.
</P>
<P>
   History will be a long time in rendering a fully fleshed verdict
on Clinton's foreign policy. Skeptics will wonder for decades, no
doubt, whether at base Clinton maximized his country's
opportunities, or squandered them, at a time of breathtaking
American prosperity amid
</P>
<P>
   stunning global change.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, and for the fleeting months remaining
before he leaves the White House in January, Clinton is walking
tall across the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   After delivering his acceptance speech Friday in Aachen,
Clinton, the Charlemagne medal dangling from his neck on a bright
yellow ribbon, Clinton returned to his seat on the sun-washed dais
in front of a 9th Century cathedral, surrounded by Czech President
Vaclev Havel, former European Commission president Jacques Delors
and several other architects of modern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the Aachen Symphony Orchestra reprised classics from
West Side Story, Clinton smiled broadly, tapped his hand against
his knee and sang.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans' email address is BobDeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
