<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PUTIN-0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON AND PUTIN BEGIN TALKS
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW President Clinton and his Russian counterpart, Vladimir
Putin, laid out opposing positions on the thorny subjects of
missile defense and nuclear arms reductions during a Saturday night
dinner, setting the stage for intensive talks Sunday on the high
stakes issues.
</P>
<P>
   A full afternoon of discussions is planned, to be followed by a
joint press conference.
</P>
<P>
   In the two leaders' first meeting since Putin took office last
month, the men and a handful of aides and interpreters dined on
cabbage soup, goose and spiced wild boar, then repaired to listen
to a set of jazz in the ornate 18th Century residency within the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   There was little time spent on pleasantries, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said, before the men got down to the
security and economic issues at the core of U.S.-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither leader spoke with reporters, however, after meeting for
nearly three hours, and Lockhart suggested that the men went little
beyond stating their views during a cordial yet business like
exchange, speaking mostly through interpreters, with Putin dropping
in an occasional English phrase.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their introductory meeting, Putin gave Clinton a tour
of some of his private enclaves, including a well-stocked library,
a small chapel and the presidential gym where Putin, an avid Judo
practitioner, lifts weights and gets massaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight is a chance, I think, to get comfortable and discuss a
wide range of issues,'' Lockhart told reporters traveling with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues included a proposed U.S. national missile defense
system Putin opposes, as well as prospects for nuclear arms
reductions and Russia's brutal war against seccessionst rebels in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined in the talks by Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbot, the administration's long term point man on Russia.
Putin was accompanied by his top foreign affairs adviser, Sergey
Prihodkho.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official who participated in the talks told
reporters afterwards that the two leaders ``got very much down to
business,'' yet were both cordial and engaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very easygoing nature to the conversation,'' said
the official, who briefed reporters on the condition of anonymity.
``It was quite clear that they knew each other, that they knew a
lot about each other's positions, and they were very interested in
hearing directly from each other about each other's positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin and Clinton are not strangers. They met twice last fall
once in New Zealand and later in Norway when Putin was serving as
Russia's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Putin became acting president last December, upon Boris
Yeltsin's abrupt resignation, was elected in March and inaugurated
in May.
</P>
<P>
   After a day spent in Berlin conferring with other world leaders
on the subject of 21st Century governance, Clinton flew here aboard
Air Force One and proceeded directly to the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   There he was greeted by Putin, a former KGB official.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's talks promise to be dominated by discussions of a
proposed U.S. missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to decide this fall whether to deploy the
system, designed to defend the United States against limited
attacks from a rogue state such as North Korea or Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is opposed to the system, which he fears could upset the
strategic balance of power between the United States and Russia,
which together possess more than 80 percent of the world's nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin will also take up the issue of nuclear arms
reductions. The men are in the opening stages of talks aimed at
attaining a third Strategic Arms Reductions Treaty, building on
START I and START II.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans' e-mail address is: BobDeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
