<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CAMPAIGN-0604-     06-03 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CAMPAIGN-0604 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 -COX &HT;    MEXICO'S RULING PARTY ON THE DEFENSIVE TO BEAT BACK OPPONENT
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY With less than a month to go before the tightest
presidential election in modern Mexican history, the ruling party
here has unleashed a barrage of American-style attack ads to beat
back a leading challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign workers for ruling party candidate Francisco Labastida
Ochoa have created a series of caustic television ads that portray
their chief opponent, Vicente Fox Quesada, of the coalition
Alliance for Change as a bumbler and unpatriotic.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, the Fox campaign has prepared its own arsenal
of ads that ridicule Labastida and his party which has ruled Mexico
for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is war,'' said Francisco Ortiz, Fox's campaign publicity
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   A charismatic campaigner and a former opposition governor of
Guanajuato state, Fox is running neck-in-neck with Labastida in
polls. A second opposition challenger, left-of-center Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas is running a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   While the race is close, these polls also show Fox is doing well
in Mexico's urban areas, a critical battleground for ads as the
campaign enters its final stages. About 70 percent of Mexico's
voters live in cities where they have easier access to television.
</P>
<P>
   To counter Fox's advance in the campaign, Labastida's campaign
has consulted on occasion with James Carville, President Bill
Clinton's former campaign strategist. The fierce Carville style may
have influenced some of these American-style television spots.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, Fox is speaking in English during an interview with
an American television show in March. He is describing his idea for
expanding trade agreements so that more Mexican workers can obtain
visas to work legally in the United States rather than having to
cross as undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
   An expansion of work visas is an idea the PRI has considered as
well, but the ad exploits Fox's awkward phrasing in English and
portrays him as a sell-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge need for gardeners in the United States,'' Fox
says in accented English that is sub-titled. ``Today we're training
in Guanajuato for that kind of speciality . . .''
</P>
<P>
   A voice in the background accuses Fox of wanting to send workers
abroad. Fox's words are contrasted with claims that Labastida will
create jobs at home.
</P>
<P>
   The ad cites his work as former agriculture secretary to open
the U.S. market to Mexican avocados.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most effective ad of all,'' Labastida campaign
manager Esteban Moctezuma said. ``It wounds the pride of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ad asks viewers, ``Can you imagine this man as
president?''
</P>
<P>
   Clips of Fox campaigning follow. In one he jokingly bends a
finger of a giant foam hand - his victory sign -- into an obscene
gesture. Another clip shows Fox stubbornly repeating ``today,
today'' while arguing with Cardenas over when to hold a debate.
</P>
<P>
   During a popular evening soap opera, the ad was followed by a
spot where a presidential-looking Labastida sits at a desk and -
over a crescendo of trumpets - promises, ``I'm going to be a
president everyone can be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said he'd release a spot this week challenging the
``gardener ad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The response is thanks to the PRI and its failed policies, we
now have 18 million Mexicans living in the United States,'' Ortiz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz produced ads with two famous soap opera stars urging
Mexicans to vote for Fox. But their television network wouldn't air
the ads, arguing that they violated the stars' exclusive contracts.
The ads were turned into radio spots.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the campaign Ortiz fashioned an ad from a debate with
Fox, during which Labastida tried to embarrass Fox by repeating
insulting names Fox had reportedly called him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's called me shorty, he's called me a pansy,'' Labastida
said. Fox replies, ``I can stop being rude, but you (and your
party) will never stop being corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want a president who tells the truth?'' a voice asks.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida workers are also attacking a key opposition argument:
If Mexico is to have a real democracy, the ruling party must lose
it's 71-year grip on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that the opposition parties have been
fomenting and promoting in their trips abroad,'' said Sandra
Fuentes, director of international relations for Labastida,
candidate of Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with members of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors, Fuentes said opposition politicians are promoting the
democracy argument in American newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very dangerous argument,'' she said, because it could
jeopardize the credibility of the election. After a decade of
electoral reforms the balloting is supposed to be the fairest and
cleanest in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 percent of Mexicans now live in areas with municipal
governments that are non-PRI, Fuentes also noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico lives with democracy,'' she said. ``The Mexican voters
will decide on July 2 if they want an alternation in power (at the
presidential level). But it's not a requirement. It's an option.''
</P>
<P>
   However, leading opposition challenger Vicente Fox is urging
Mexicans of all political stripes to consider him their first
chance in seven decades to oust the PRI from this country's
powerful presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is urgent, it is unavoidable that Mexico have an
alternation in power,'' Fox told the same group of American
newspaper editors last week. ``Government has corrupted . . . The
government of the PRI does not have any more to offer Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited two examples of how recent changes in state governments
revealed corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, which is now governed by a leftist party, the
former PRI mayor is suspected of diverting tens of millions of
dollars in public funds to the PRI. In Nuevo Leon, which is now
governed by a conservative party, former PRI officials are
suspected of diverting another $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``An alternation in power is one big step towards cleaning
government,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is the candidate of a coalition that includes Mexico's
conservative National Action Party, or PAN, and the Green Party, an
environmentalist party that is more leftist.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, opposition politicians are complaining that the
ruling party is using pork-barrel tactics and that some government
workers have tried to pressure social-welfare recipients in remote
areas to vote for the ruling party. Measuring the seriousness of
these claims or resolving them will be difficult
</P>
<P>
   before the July 2 election.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
