u s BC-OBIT-RUDD-NYT &LR;      06-03 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RUDD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVING RUDD, 82, PRESS AGENT IN BASEBALL, RACING, BOXING
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irving Rudd, a Runyonesque character who used wit and gimmickry
to promote the Brooklyn Dodgers, Yonkers Raceway, Nathan's Famous
and boxers like Muhammad Ali and Sugar Ray Leonard, died on Friday.
He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, a short, fast-talking raconteur, wore a tie clasp that was
a 1953 Dodgers money clip, sported a 1955 Dodgers World Series ring
and placed a sign that said ``Ulcer Dept.'' atop his desk. He
introduced himself as I. Rudd, while others called him Unswerving
Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd made sure you called him a press agent, not a
public-relations man, whose ranks he called ``posturing phonies.''
</P>
<P>
   Press agentry was an honorable and sporting game to Rudd, who
was born in the Brownsville section of Brooklyn and graduated from
Thomas Jefferson High School. In later years he joked that he
hadn't graduated; he was ``acquitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd learned to deal with reporters in the days before
television in much the same way that he dealt with the worthiness
of a boxer, a Dodger or a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd's job was to generate the ink that created the buzz that
put fans in seats. He started drumming up attention for fights for
$18 a week at a Harlem boxing hall called the Rockland Palace and
later worked in small fight clubs like the Ridgewood Grove and
Eastern Parkway Arena.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Dodgers in 1949 and subsequently devised bat day,
camera day, batboy for a day and music unappreciation night.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd once demanded to know if Gen. Douglas MacArthur, having
been recalled by President Harry S. Truman from Korea in 1951,
``had an allergy to Brooklyn,'' because he attended baseball games
at Yankee Stadium and Giants games at the Polo Grounds, but no
Dodger games at Ebbets Field. Eventually, MacArthur attended one
game in Brooklyn, which yielded a promotional bonanza. He attended
12 more, all Dodger losses. That happened to be the season the
Dodgers blew a 13{-game lead to the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers relocated to Los Angeles in 1957, Rudd went to
work for Yonkers Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   He staged his most famous stunt when the raceway reopened in
1958 after being rebuilt. Rudd told painters to misspell it
``Racewya'' on a sign next to the track, which made phone callers
inquire, ``Don't you idiots know how to spell raceway?'' Naturally,
photographers and television cameramen came to record the faux pas,
which generated clippings around the world.
</P>
<P>
   On a sweltering July day in 1979, he recalled to a reporter from
The New York Times that during summer days at Yonkers, ``We used to
go around to the barns and get a picture of a horse nuzzling one of
those great big cakes of ice.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We got a lot of ink that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He went a step further one day, placing newspaper ads that said:
``Urgently wanted: Pool for champion Australian horse who needs to
swim.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd was quick-witted enough to correct a man claiming to be the
sportscaster Howard Cosell's worst enemy by saying, ``Not while I'm
alive.'' And he was flexible enough to work for the feuding boxing
promoters, Don King and, then, Bob Arum, Rudd's boss until his
retirement in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In later years Rudd was the rare press agent in a sea of P.R.
men. But he retained his touch. When Marvelous Marvin Hagler fought
Thomas Hearns on April 15, 1985, he persuaded the Internal Revenue
Service to underwrite a television ad that had the fighters
advising the audience to file their tax returns early.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Gertrude, of Bayside, Queens; two
daughters, Susan Rudd-Cohen, of Manhattan, and Nancy Marmer, of
Henderson, Nev.; four grandchildren; and one great-granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
