<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-ENDORSE-1ST     06-03 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ENDORSE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL PARTIES ISSUE ENDORSEMENTS, ALONG PARTY LINES
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Updates throughout with events.)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With as much relief as enthusiasm, New York's
Conservative and Liberal parties reverted to type Saturday,
endorsing Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton, respectively, for
the Senate, after both parties had endured a queasy several months
that left their nominations in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks into his campaign, Lazio, a congressman
little known beyond his Long Island district, has been working to
establish himself in voters' minds as a centrist, but Saturday his
campaign veered to the right. Addressing the Conservative Party's
nominating convention at a hotel a few blocks from the state
Capitol, he promised ``a crusade,'' offering up a list of favorite
conservative causes like tax cuts, the death penalty, longer prison
terms and greater military spending.
</P>
<P>
   He also spoke of the issue most identified with the
Conservatives in recent years, opposition to what opponents call
partial-birth abortion. ``There is no place in our society for the
gruesome procedure partial-birth abortion,'' he said, to
enthusiastic applause from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier at the Intercontinental Hotel in Manhattan,
where Clinton accepted the Liberal Party endorsement, she and the
party's leader, Raymond B. Harding, noted that Lazio was more
conservative than the man he replaced as the Republican candidate,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways my views are closer to those of the mayor than
those of my opponent,'' Clinton said. ``He is out of step with the
mainstream,'' she said of Lazio. ``My views are centrist views,
positive views,'' she added at a brief press conference at which
she referred to herself as a centrist no fewer than four times.
</P>
<P>
   The day's events highlighted to Lazio that the Conservative
Party's backing can be both an aid and a burden, as each candidate
tries to claim the political middle ground. Unlike the Liberals,
the Conservatives still hew to an ideology in keeping with their
name, taking strong stands against abortion, gay rights,
affirmative action and big government. And the party's ready
embrace of Lazio as a real conservative contrasts sharply with its
rejection of Giuliani as too moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said nothing to distance himself from the Conservative
Party, even as he obliquely acknowledged that the affiliation could
be used against him. ``The other side is going to try to demonize
me,'' he said. ``They're going to try to demonize you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He also peppered his speech with attacks on Clinton, who barely
mentioned him Saturday. ``You won't catch us trying to nationalize
one-seventh of our economy,'' Lazio said, a reference to her failed
plan to restructure the nation's health care system. He reminded
his audience several times that Clinton was new to New York,
saying, ``I was able to jump into this race without a listening
tour because I've been listening to new York all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Clinton, he said, ``She comes to New York with the support of
every left-wing special-interest group from Washington insiders to
the Hollywood elite.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As long as Giuliani was the presumptive Republican nominee, the
race had both the Liberal and Conservative parties in turmoil. The
Liberals, whose longstanding support of the mayor had alienated
many Democrats, faced a pitched internal battle over which side to
take.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party chairman Michael L. Long vowed that his party
would not support the mayor because he was not conservative enough,
especially on abortion. Party leaders said they would nominate
someone to Giuliani's right, even if undermining him meant helping
Clinton and damaging the Conservatives' relationship with the
Republican Party. But the Conservatives were having some trouble
finding a viable candidate of their own.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani dropped out of the race last month, and the
Republicans nominated Lazio instead, the battle lines became clear
and the Liberals and Conservatives fell into their comfortable old
roles as contentious allies of the major parties.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative delegates said Saturday that they were relieved to
be able to unite with the Republicans, and one after another, said
abortion was the key issue. ``Abortion is the big difference
between Lazio and Giuliani,'' said Viola Hunter of Syracuse, vice
chairwoman of the party. ``We're not a one-issue party, but it is a
very vital, important issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio supports legal abortion, but unlike Clinton _ and Giuliani
_ he opposes government funding for it, and supports a
partial-birth abortion ban.
</P>
<P>
   In nominating Clinton, the Liberal Party went some distance
toward mending its frayed relationship with its traditional ally,
the Democratic Party. The Liberals had alienated many Democrats by
backing the mayor, and by refusing to support the Democratic
nominee for governor in 1998, Peter F. Vallone, and instead
nominating Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Harding cited a long list of popular Democrats his
party has supported, like Daniel Patrick Moynihan, Hugh Carey and
Robert F. Kennedy, and noted that when it has supported Republicans
for statewide office, they have been widely revered centrists like
Fiorello La Guardia and Jacob Javits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to put Lazio at the end of that litany and it jars the
ear,'' he said. ``Put Hillary there and it fits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party has fewer than 2 percent of the state's
registered voters, and the Liberal Party fewer than 1 percent, but
they wield an influence beyond their size. The major parties must
play to them, because each of the smaller parties presents a choice
between closing ranks and facing a challenger who can provide an
outlet for protest votes. In recent statewide elections, Republican
candidates have pulled as many as 300,000 votes on the Conservative
line, while Democrats often get well over 100,000 on the Liberal
line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
