<HEADER>
A3773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-03 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SAYS CONGRESSIONAL RECORD PROVES `MAINSTREAM' 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his eight years in Congress, Rep. Rick Lazio has
regularly broken Republican Party ranks and supported President
Clinton on matters like gun control, affirmative action and changes
in campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   But on the big tax and spending questions that have followed
along party lines and have often been decided by the narrowest of
margins, he has been a reliable ally of the conservative Republican
leaders of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio voted to impeach Clinton on two of the four articles
recommended by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of abortion, which Hillary Rodham Clinton, his
Democratic opponent in the race for the New York Senate seat, wants
to make a central issue, Lazio has taken middle ground, siding
neither with those who want to outlaw abortion entirely, nor with
those who oppose all restrictions on access to abortion procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Among his legislative accomplishments has been sponsorship of a
bill, enacted in 1998, to overhaul the system of federal housing
assistance. This year, he was instrumental in brokering a
compromise to increase the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has not been particularly involved in foreign policy, but
he has been among the House Republicans most supportive of the
president on international issues. For example, he supported the
president's intervention in Kosovo last year.
</P>
<P>
   When Lazio announced his candidacy for the Senate last month, he
said: ``I have a record that I am proud of. It is a mainstream
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign responded with the charge that far from being
moderate, the congressman was a loyal soldier in House Speaker Newt
Gingrich's conservative revolution.
</P>
<P>
   A review of Lazio's record found ample support for both
arguments. In his first two years in Congress, when Democrats were
in control, Lazio voted in favor of the Clinton administration's
legislation more often than almost any other Republican. For
instance, a study by the Congressional Quarterly found that in
1994, Lazio supported the president on 72 percent of the votes on
which Clinton expressed a position, a higher percentage than all
but two other Republicans in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But after Republicans won control of the House in the 1994
elections, Lazio advocated most of the Republicans' Contract with
America. Since then, he has been much less supportive of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the issues on which Lazio has broken with the
leaders of his party and voted the way Clinton might have voted:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gun control: Lazio voted for the Brady law, which requires a
five-day waiting period for handgun purchases, and for a ban on the
sale of assault weapons. Last year, he supported a measure to
require criminal background checks of people who make purchases at
gun shows. After that was defeated, he supported a bill endorsed by
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   _ Affirmative action: Lazio voted against a bill that would have
prohibited colleges and universities from using racial preferences
in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family leave: He supported legislation that requires many
companies to give their workers unpaid leave to spend time with a
newborn child or a sick family member.
</P>
<P>
   _ Environment: He voted against Republican bills to relax clean
water regulations, strip the Environmental Protection Agency of
enforcement power and help developers get zoning changes over the
objection of environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arts: He was one of only 15 Republicans who bucked Republican
leadership and voted for full funding for the National Endowment
for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Food stamps: He voted to restore food stamps to legal
immigrants, a benefit that had been denied by the 1996 welfare
bill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Campaign finance: He has voted for legislation that would ban
donations of largely unregulated soft money to political parties
and restrict the ability of parties to run issue advertisements on
behalf of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Labor: He voted to prohibit employers from hiring permanent
replacements for striking workers.
</P>
<P>
   But when it has come to budget issues, the main focus of the
contention between Clinton and the Republican Congress during the
last six years, Lazio has supported the party line.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Budget Committee in 1995 that produced
the measure with almost $200 billion in tax cuts over five years,
the abolition of the Department of Education and sharp reductions
in anticipated government spending for Medicare and many other
programs. Ultimately, the fight with Clinton over this budget led
to the shutdown of the government in the winter of 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   When his committee adopted the Republican budget in May 1995,
Lazio issued a press release proclaiming that it would ``move us
from the path of increasing debt and inefficient, big, centralized
government toward a government that is smaller, more decentralized
and efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Lazio voted for a constitutional amendment to
require a balanced budget, billions more than Clinton sought in
military spending and sweeping tax cuts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's record on other issues seems conventionally Republican.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gay rights: Lazio voted to codify the ban on homosexuals in
the military.
</P>
<P>
   _ Term limits: He supported a constitutional amendment that
would have placed a 12-year limit on the terms of senators and
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Death penalty: He voted to limit the ability of death-row
inmates to challenge their sentence in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   _ Education: He supported vouchers to help parents pay their
children's private school tuition, and he voted to allow states to
deny public education to illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Litigation: He voted to limit punitive damages in product
liability cases.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health care: He opposed a bipartisan bill last year that would
place restrictions on health insurers and allow patients to sue
their managed-care plans, and instead supported Republican
proposals that would not allow such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assisted suicide: He voted to overturn Oregon's
assisted-suicide law.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, Lazio voted to impeach Clinton on two of the
four charges brought by the Judiciary Committee: for committing
perjury before a grand jury and for obstructing justice in the
civil suit brought by Paula Corbin Jones. He voted against
impeachment for perjury in the civil suit and for lying to Congress
in written answers to questions posed by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bear no animus for Bill Clinton; I have no grudge against
him,'' Lazio said in a speech to the House during the impeachment
debate, adding that he planned to vote for impeachment, he said,
``to hammer home as best I can that we must continue to insist that
no one is above the law and that the truth must be told. We simply
cannot tolerate dishonesty in the heart of our government.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans made Lazio a deputy whip and one of two
assistant majority leaders. One of his assignments is liaison
between the Republican leadership and the ``Lunch Bunch,'' a group
of moderate Republicans, mostly from the Northeast, who meet weekly
for lunch to discuss politics and legislation.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders appointed Lazio to the Commerce Committee, one of
the most influential committees in Congress, and, waiving a party
rule, allowed him to keep his chairmanship of the Banking
Committee's Subcommittee on Housing and Community Opportunity.
Normally, members of the Commerce Committee are required to
relinquish their seats on other committees.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Lazio has consistently opposed the efforts of many
of his fellow Republicans to make abortion illegal. He also broke
with his party to support federal criminal penalties for people who
use force to block access to abortion clinics, and to allow
organizations that use their own money to provide abortions in
developing countries to be eligible for international
family-planning funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio has also opposed using federal Medicaid money to pay
for abortions for low-income women, and he has consistently voted
to outlaw the late-term procedure that anti-abortion forces call
partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   When Lazio's campaign was asked this week about the
congressman's legislative accomplishments, staff members provided a
list of measures he had backed: cracking down on Medicare and
Medicaid fraud, a screening program for breast and cervical cancer
in low- and moderate-income women, a bill Lazio sponsored to order
a Justice Department investigation of mistreatment of
Italian-Americans during World War II .
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign staff did not include Lazio's sponsorship of
the the 1998 law that overhauls federal housing assistance program.
</P>
<P>
   Among many other aspects, the law is supposed to increase the
proportion of those receiving federal housing assistance who work
and require many of them to perform community service. It also
encourages public housing authorities to reduce the concentration
of very poor tenants in buildings, a situation Lazio believes
contributes to crime.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio worked closely on the legislation with Andrew M. Cuomo,
secretary of housing and urban development, and the bill eventually
passed the House by an almost unanimous vote.
</P>
<P>
   On the minimum wage, Lazio tried to find legislation both
parties could support. Democrats favor increasing the minimum wage
to $6.15 an hour from the current $5.15 over two years. Most
Republicans oppose raising the minimum wage but favor tax cuts for
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio offered a compromise to raise the figure to $6.15 over
three years and to join it with a $30 billion tax cut for
businesses over five years. In March, the House passed a bill
similar to Lazio's proposal that would raise the minimum to $6.15
over two years and cut taxes by $46 billion over five years. That
measure is now pending before the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
