<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SAILING-TRANSATLANTIC     06-03 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAILING-TRANSATLANTIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
71 PREPARE FOR TRANS-ATLANTIC SOLO SAILING 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Prada Challenge of Italy advanced to last spring's
America's Cup finals, the team's helmsman and leader, Francesco de
Angelis, found himself at the center of a news media on-slaught.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the Prada crew had become national heroes, but when
asked how he handled the burden of his new celebrity, de Angelis
shrugged and invoked the name of his country's most famous sailor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more popular in Italy now,'' he said. ``But I'm no
Giovanni Soldini.''
</P>
<P>
   De Angelis was correct. Soldini _ a single-handed offshore
virtuoso whose training regimen includes beer, cigarettes and pool
halls _ is definitely one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the bearded, diminutive, 34-year-old Soldini will be
one of the favorites when the 10th running of the quadrennial
single-handed trans-Atlantic race begins off Plymouth, England,
bound for Newport, R.I. This year's event, which fields 71 boats
and is sponsored by the Europe 1 radio group and New Man
sportswear, is notable for its fleet of 19 Open 60s, the largest
collection of those beamy, skittish downwind flyers ever assembled
for a single race.
</P>
<P>
   Soldini's Fila is expected to be at or near the front of the
pack. Is Soldini daunted by the prospect of facing French
superstars like Yves Parlier, Marc Thiercelin and Catherine
Chabaud, or the young English prodigy, Ellen MacArthur?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said in a telephone interview last week. ``I will do
like always. I will sail my race.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Soldini's long-distance adventures have run the
spectrum from joyous to tragic. In the last Around Alone race,
Soldini shook off a disastrous opening leg to claim a stirring,
come-from-behind victory. Along the way he captured the world's
attention by performing a stunning rescue of his fellow competitor,
Isabelle Autissier, who had capsized in the desolate reaches of the
Southern Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But in the prelude to that race, Soldini's best friend, the
yacht designer Andrea Romanelli, was swept from Fila's decks in a
North Atlantic storm, and lost at sea. After winning Around Alone,
Soldini's first thoughts were of Romanelli. ``I wish he were
here,'' he said. ``This boat was his life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldini won Around Alone by sailing fast and intelligently,
pushing hard when conditions were favorable, but easing back when
the weather turned inclement. That old adage about solo marathon
racing _ you must finish to win _ topped his list of priorities.
But Soldini was lucky, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the midway point of the Around Alone race, Soldini was not
the leader. That distinction belonged to the rugged English
yachtsman, Mike Golding, aboard Team Group 4. Golding is also
competing in this year's single-handed trans-Atlantic race. And had
it not been for a simple, awful mistake, the roles could have been
reversed. Had it not been for an easily avoided sandbar, Golding,
not Soldini, might be the reigning Around Alone champ.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the first leg of the race, Golding was just 200
miles from duplicating the feat on second leg when, on a crystal
clear summer afternoon, he made a grave navigational error and
furrowed into the shallows off New Zealand's Cape Reinga at the top
of North Island, nearly ripping off his boat's deep canting keel in
the process. Golding survived the grounding, but was devastated
when he realized he would be forced to withdraw. ``It's so sad,''
he had lamented. ``It's a shattered dream.''
</P>
<P>
   With the passage of time, however, the starch has returned to
Golding's upper lip. ``It was unfortunate and even slightly
unlucky,'' he said last week. ``Another day, if I'd been 100 yards
to the right, it wouldn't have happened. But someone up there
predetermined that I wasn't going to finish that race and so it
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every sailor hits bottom at some point, and for me it was
highly public,'' he said, finding the humor in his plight.
</P>
<P>
   Like Soldini and most of the other Open 60 sailors, Golding is
using this event as a tune-up and qualifier for this fall's
grueling Vendee Globe nonstop solo race around the world. And
Golding also knows the trans-Atlantic race will be no laughing
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential for an extremely close, extremely good
race,'' Golding said. ``I'm looking forward to getting stuck into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So too are Americans Bruce Burgess aboard Hawaiian Express, the
only United States Open 60 in the field, and Martin van Breems of
Norwalk, Conn., sailing a J/44 called Monhegan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get out there and go sailing,'' said van
Breems, one of five American entrants in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for the opening days of the 2,800-mile dash,
depending on the route chosen, calls for moderate southwesterlies.
The roster of competitors who Golding believes are dangerous holds
few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Giovanni,'' Golding said. ``He's very fast and very
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   But when told that Golding and most everyone else was gunning
for him, Soldini would not take the bait. ``There are many, many,
many tough boats that could do well,'' he said. ``They are all very
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldini would not name his rivals, but he would venture a guess
on his arrival in Newport. ``Maybe in 14 days,'' he said. ``And 18
for the others. That would be nice, no?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
