<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-0604-COX     06-03 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courthouse talk: Lewis case weak
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The issue started as courthouse whispers a week ago
and is now being openly discussed: The murder case against NFL star
Ray Lewis could be dismissed in a directed verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Monday or Tuesday, Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard
is expected to announce that the state has finished presenting its
murder case against Lewis and two co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, lawyers for the three defendants will rise
and tell Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner they have a motion.
The jury will be excused, and the defense lawyers will ask Bonner
for directed verdicts. That means they contend there is not enough
evidence for the case to go any further and the charges should be
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge accepts the motion, the case won't reach the
jurors. Instead, she will decide for them.
</P>
<P>
   Although directed verdict requests are routine, they are rarely
granted. But lawyers and legal experts following the Buckhead
stabbings murder trial say Bonner may have a tough decision on her
hands. They cite a lack of evidence, particularly against Lewis and
one of his co-defendants, Joseph Sweeting, and the irony that many
of the prosecution's witnesses have seemed to help the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very close call,'' said Atlanta defense lawyer
Alan Baverman, who is commenting on the trial for national media
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 25, and friends Sweeting, 34, of Miami, and Reginald
Oakley, 31, of Baltimore, are charged with the Jan. 31 stabbing
deaths of Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, both of
Decatur, Ga., in a Buckhead altercation following post-Super Bowl
partying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to this case,'' said one of Lewis' lawyers,
Don Samuel, who is expected to argue the directed verdict motion.
``There's hardly a single witness they have called that we would
not have called. . . . I think we've got a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, directed verdicts can be granted if a judge
decides that no reasonable jury can find a defendant guilty, even
if it weighs all the evidence in the light most favorable to the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   As court adjourned Friday, Howard hadn't finished making his
case. And just because it's been rough sledding so far, he could
still end with a flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Howard is seeking to recall witness Duane Fassett, who is
resisting a return appearance. Fassett, the driver of Lewis' rented
limousine on the night of the slayings, was the embodiment of
pathos during his testimony, failing to deliver key prosecution
contentions _ based on his statements to police _ that Lewis
punched one of the victims and that, as the limo sped from the
scene, Oakley and Sweeting admitted to the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   Howard wants to put Fassett on the stand again to ask him about
the prior statements. If Fassett denies making them, Howard can
bring them into evidence by calling as a witness one of the police
officers to whom Fassett made the statements. If Fassett returns,
the question of a directed verdict likely will be moot.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's attorney, Bruce Harvey, said Howard stretched out his
case last week to buy time while he tried to get Fassett to return.
</P>
<P>
   Howard is also considering whether to call limo passengers
Carlos Stafford, Gino Hutcherson and Claudus Thompson. The three
would likely will seek immunity from prosecution in exchange for
their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Among highlights of the evidence so far:
</P>
<P>
   Only one witness, convicted con-man Chester Anderson, has
testified he saw Lewis attack a victim, and a man who was with him
gave a statement to police contradicting Anderson's testimony.
Among other witnesses, Jeff Gwen, one of the victims' friends, said
he saw Lewis ``tussling'' with a victim. Fassett said he merely saw
Lewis cock his hand back while Sweeting struggled with an
unidentified man.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have introduced evidence that Lewis lied to police
and allegedly orchestrated a cover-up that included ordering limo
passengers to keep quiet about the fight and having evidence
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony, Sweeting bought the knives police say
were used in the killings. He dropped the empty knife packages on
the street as he left the limo, testified Fassett, who said he
picked them up. Fassett also testified that he saw Sweeting
throwing punches at a man who lay on the street near where the
bodies were found. But Fassett was unable to say whether Sweeting
was, in fact, striking either Baker or Lollar. And none of the
witnesses has testified that he saw a knife in Sweeting's hand
during the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The most solid evidence placing one of the defendants in a fight
with the victims is against Oakley. Two of the victims' friends
said Oakley started arguing with, and challenging, them. Moments
later, Baker smashed a bottle over Oakley's head. That's one of the
few facts uncontradicted in the case. Fassett said he saw Oakley
chase and slam Baker to the street, striking him while he was down.
Christopher Shinholster, one of the victims' friends, said he saw
Oakley standing over Baker.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding directed verdicts, a judge must determine if there
is any evidence at all to support the state's theory as to how the
crime occurred. Such motions are rarely granted because the judge
must assume that the state's witnesses are telling the truth.
Whether there is evidence or testimony that impeaches those
witnesses is a question for jurors to decide.
</P>
<P>
   A problem with the state's case against Lewis is how the
prosecution indicted him, said Baverman, the Atlanta defense
lawyer, who won a directed verdict in a 1994 armed robbery case.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is charged with murder, felony murder and aggravated
assault. The latter charge accuses him of knifing one of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution sort of limited itself,'' Baverman said. ``If
they had charged aggravated assault with his feet and hands, it'd
be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here they have charged him with aggravated assault and felony
murder with the knife,'' Baverman said. ``Is there a reasonable
inference that he held somebody down so somebody else could stab
him or hurt somebody to the extent that it allowed somebody else to
stab him? So far, I haven't seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Clayton County prosecutor Brandon Hornsby, who has been
watching the trial, said a directed verdict is ``definitely a
possibility on Lewis'' but probably not against the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bare circumstantial case against Lewis,'' he said.
``There is a circumstantial case against Sweeting. And there is
direct evidence against Oakley.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hornsby said, it's not over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to wait and see,'' he said. ``Paul Howard may
present compelling evidence that will eliminate the issue of a
directed verdict from the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
