   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-WORKERS _ COLLEGE PARK, Md. _ A computer sciences graduate
recently left his Ivy League school straight for a newly formed
software company. Starting salary and benefits package: $250,000.
New college graduates, 1.2 million of them, are entering the job
market in a soaring economy. But many are in no rush to begin the
chase for their first million. In opinion polls and interviews,
they rate job satisfaction, corporate values and family life over
personal wealth. (Holmes, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: YOUNG-DATA _ Chart material.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday. Also available via a WAN search: Location
Atlanta, category National, subcategory Education.
</P>
<P>
   CANES-FORECAST _ The forecast for this year's hurricane season.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CANES-BEACHES _ When hurricanes roar ashore, they destroy miles
of beachfront, sweeping the sand back to the sea. To repair the
damage, communities from Gulf Shores, Ala., to Florida to North
Carolina's Outer Banks are relying on beach renourishment_a costly
plan of pumping sand back on the shore. Critics say it's a waste of
money and a sign that coastline development should be curbed.
Developers claim it's a logical step in protecting fancy homes and
high-rises. As the Atlantic hurricane season opens June 1, a look
at how well beach-front development can be protected.
(Manuel/Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CANES-EVAC _ Last year when Hurricane Floyd threatened the
Southeast shoreline from Florida to Virginia, millions of people
swarmed inland during the largest peacetime evacuation in U.S.
history. Motorists clogged interstates in nightmarish proportions.
As hurricane season begins this week, a regional planning group is
looking at what was learned in Florida and the Carolinas to get
people out of danger without stalling them on the highway.
(Burritt/Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CANES-NCTOWN _ HALIFAX, N.C. _ A look at how this rural
community in northeastern North Carolina is struggling since Floyd
washed out the bridge that separates residents from the local
grocery store. It's a 12-mile detour to a store that otherwise
would be less than a mile away. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ Overview of the status of the murder
trial of Baltimore Ravens' All-Pro linebacker Ray Lewis. He is
charged in the death of two men in Atlanta after a night of
partying just hours after the end of the Super Bowl. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
