<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0603: WACO REVISTED _ A full-page graphic detailing
the siege, the fire and the aftermath of the April 1993 fatal siege
on the Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas. Graphic looks at
those who died, a history of the Branch Davidians, a look at the
civil trial and a timeline of key events. (Staff, Austin
American-Statesman, Waco Tribune-Herald) Art includes a 3-column
color photo of the compound as it is today, a 1-column color photo
of the compound on fire and 1-column color photo of Janet Reno, a
1-column color photo of David Koresh and a 6-pica color photo of
the video ``Waco: Rules of Engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WHOLESOME _ WASHINGTON _ On June 6, 1906, the House Committee on
Agriculture was embroiled in a debate on what should be covered by
a bill on food safety. Everyone agreed that meat ``unfit'' for
human consumption should be banned. But what about something that
might not hurt a person but might be ``offensive to his ideas as to
what he will consume?'' The bill said food should be ``wholesome,''
a term meat industry executives wanted cut. Despite nearly a
century of legislation, regulations, investigations and exposes,
the debate that began on that day 94 years ago is still very much
alive. (Jaspin, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday. Also available via a WAN search: Location
Atlanta, category National, subcategory U.S. Government.
</P>
<P>
   ENIGMA _ WASHINGTON _ British newspapers are indignant about the
American movie ``U-571,'' which depicts the British World War II
submarine crew that captured a critical German code machine known
as Enigma as American ``heroes.'' ``Film Steals Hero's Glory,''
said the Sunday Mercury in a typical comment Bemused and irked by
the trans-Atlantic tempest are members of the Polish-American
community, because Poles _ not Britons and not Americans _ actually
captured the super-secret machine. (Weglarczyk and Nesmith, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday in (w) Washington and (i) International
categories. Also available via a WAN search: Location Atlanta,
category International, subcategory Other.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CAMPAIGN _ MEXICO CITY _ American-style radio and
television ads are creeping onto the airwaves here, stirring up the
masses as never before ahead of a presidential election. In many
ways, media campaigns may have eclipsed old-fashioned in-person
stumping in Mexico. In a country where the media is largely seen as
tied to the ruling party, is coverage fair and are the ads
effective? (Ferriss, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-RUSSIA _ In 1993, President Clinton delegated to his vice
president a sensitive and vital priority of U.S. foreign policy:
managing the United States relationship with the former Soviet
Union. Until 1998, Gore held ten high level talks with Russian
officials on everything from arms control to farm exports. The
bi-lateral commission, now teetering on the brink of extinction
because of political turmoil in Russia, achieved mixed results
during its five year existence, experts say. Analysts credit Gore
with a number of largely unpublicized successes in arms control,
but say he missed opportunities and remained oblivious to the
scandals that ultimately brought down Boris Yeltsin and his
long-serving prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin. (Foskett, Cox
News Service). 27''
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (p) Politics and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PUTIN _ MOSCOW _ Coverage of President Clinton's arrival
here Saturday night and scheduled dinner meeting with Russian
President Vladimir Putin. President Clinton is here for two days of
high-level meetings with Russian President Vladimir Putin on a
variety of issues, including nuclear weapons reductions. But in the
weeks and days leading up to the summit, the Clinton administration
has greatly reduced its aspirations about what the meetings will
produce. Developing. Wraps in developments from Germany. (Deans,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6 p.m. EDT in (i) International and (w)
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EVICTIONS _ BEIJING _ Zhao Zhifeng and her extended family
have lived in their modest one-story house all their lives. In
fact, they've owned it going back 200 years, or seven generations.
But one morning in March, about 30 men showed up, she says,
accompanied by two bulldozers and police in plainclothes, and
turned most of their house to rubble. Across Beijing, city planners
have been demolishing traditional courtyard-style homes to make way
for high-rises and wider roads. In most cases, officials have
helped displaced residents find new homes at the edge of town and
given them a cash incentive to leave without protest. But in
extreme cases, like that of Zhao and her family, regulations are
flouted. Beijing is aggressively transforming itself into a
cosmopolitan metropolis, but can it afford the human cost? (Chao,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ART _ HAVANA _ It's Sunday afternoon in a sweaty Havana
barrio called ``Callejon de Hamel,'' and curious tourists mingle
with dark-skinned Cubans as drummers pound out an Afro-Caribbean
beat and dancers sway to the hypnotic rhythm. Strolling through the
crowd, looking cool despite the sweltering heat, bearded, dark-eyed
Salvador Gonzalez greets friends, visitors and devotees to his
secluded, chic corner of Havana. Gonzalez has earned a world-wide
reputation as one of Cuba's most important mural painters. His
subject is Santeria, the mystical Afro-Cuban religion filled with
superstitions, animal sacrifices and frightening spirits that
correspond with Catholic saints. We profile Gonzalez and his work.
(MWilliams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
