<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   DIMAGGIO-ATTORNEY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ 04 (56 inches,
developing): Morris Engelberg is the sole trustee of Joe DiMaggio's
will, but few attorneys identify so closely with their clients. For
that matter, the average attorney does not name his office plaza
``Yankee Clipper Center,'' spend $8,500 on a marble plaque
memorializing his most famous client outside the front door, or
drop another $2,300 to create museum-like rooms inside, with scores
of DiMaggio photographs and other memorabilia. When DiMaggio died
last year at his Hollywood, Fla., home at age 84, no one had more
control over his life than Engelberg. ``I'm obsessed,'' Engelberg
said. ``I admit it. He was like a father to me. My own father died
three months before I was born. As a child in New York, I used to
tell people Joe DiMaggio was my father.'' In fact, they never met
until DiMaggio reached the final two decades of his life, but the
attorney came to assume a powerful role in the slugger's final
years. That role would put him at odds with political leaders in
San Francisco, members of the Hollywood (Fla.) Chamber of Commerce
and DiMaggio's own brother Dom. (Elmore, Palm Beach Post). 56.
MOVED.
</P>
