<P>
   (NYT6) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- June 3, 2000 -- COLLEGE-GRADS-JOBS
-- The 1.2 million college graduates in the nation's class of 2000
are entering an unusually strong job market that is a result of a
flourishing economy and, especially, the boom in high technology.
Emily Lowe, a senior at Stanford University, in Palo Alto, Calif.,
who majored in product design engineering, says she will earn about
$60,000 next year with a software company in San Diego, and that is
before the $5,000 signing bonus and stock options. (Thor Swift/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JERUSALEM -- June 3, 2000 -- ISRAEL-GAY-PARENTS -- Matan
Berner-Kadish hugs the knee of his ``eema,'' the Hebrew word for
mommy, Ruti Berner-Kadish, 36, holding his little brother Naveh.
Matan's ``mommy,'' Nicole Berner-Kadish, 35, whose rights as his
mother were recently recognized, sits at left. ``We're what's known
as white-picket-fence lesbians, or whatever the Israeli equivalent
would be,'' says Nicole Berner-Kadish. ``We're like perfect poster
children for alternative families.'' (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 3, 2000 -- WWII-CHINESE-VETS -- Kenneth
Lew, waving flag, and some of his fellow WWII veterans from the Lt.
B.R. Kimlau Amercian Legion march in the Chinese-American veterans
parade in New York City's Chinatown, Saturday. (Andrea Mohin/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHERNOBYL, Ukraine -- June 3, 2000 --
CHERNOBYL-REVISITED-3 -- A radiation monitor checks a construction
vehicle coming out of the18 mile radius around the Chernobyl
nuclear power station. In the aftermath of 1986, Chernobyl became a
symbol of nuclear devastation that incited a numbing fear in
Ukraine and Belarus, a fear that researchers suggest has so far
been more destructive to public health than the huge release of
radiation. (Patrick E. Tyler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHERNOBYL, Ukraine -- June 3, 2000 --
CHERNOBYL-REVISITED-2 -- The control room of Chernobyl's only
operating reactor, Unit No. 3, which is scheduled to close sometime
this year. But Chernobyl's radioactive wastes and debris will have
to be guarded for decades, if not centuries, to prevent them from
further poisoning the environment. (Patrick E. Tyler/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHERNOBYL, Ukraine -- June 3, 2000 --
CHERNOBYL-REVISITED-1 -- Despite intensive medical investigations
into the health effects of the huge amount of radiation released
from the explosion and fire that ripped through reactor No. 4 in
Chernobyl, Ukraine in 1986, the overall health of the plant workers
remains good, though more questions than answers remain about
Chernobyl's long-term effects. A sarcophagus covers the reactor
from the world's worst radiation accident at Chernobyl, where a
gardener recently tried to make flowers grow. (Patrick E. Tyler/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
