<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-UNSER-JR.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL UNSER JR. TRYING TO GET INDY-CAR CAREER BACK ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ He is carrying more baggage to the racetrack
these days, most of it unrelated to the art of manhandling an
Indy-car.
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr. never has had a problem with that, because sliding
his backside into a single-seat, open-wheel rocketship always has
been viewed as his family's birthright.
</P>
<P>
   But everyday life slowly and surely has been beating up on
Little Al, the son of four-time Indianapolis 500 champion Al Unser
and nephew of three-time Indy winner Bobby Unser. At 38, Unser Jr.
is recently divorced, the father of a daughter with a rare spinal
disease and a driver whose skills are rumored to be in decline.
</P>
<P>
   Along with clean underwear, these are the items Unser Jr. will
unpack for the first time this week at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I am at peace with myself _ as much as I can be.
Definitely,'' said Unser Jr., the marquee attraction of the Indy
Racing League's Casino Magic 500 on Saturday night. ``How can I say
it? You never know about somebody until they're really down and out
_ where their character lies and where their morals are and what
makes them what they are and who they are. I guess that's what
happened with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser Jr. racked up 31 career victories in the Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Series between 1983 and 1994, the year in which
he won four poles, eight of 16 CART starts, his second series
championship and second Indy 500. At the height of their celebrity,
Little Al and Marlboro Team Penske ruled open-wheel, seemingly from
flag-to-flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Unser Jr. will race you whether it's an IRL car, CART car,
IROC car or a lawnmower,'' said Eddie Gossage, executive vice
president and general manager of Texas Motor Speedway. ``He's a
true racer. He's probably the only driver in the last 20 years
who's been able to jump from open-wheel to \RNASCAR\S stock cars
and be successful. I've heard Dale Earnhardt talk about how he
feels racing against Al Unser Jr., and it's the ultimate form of
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a purist's standpoint, you have to love him.''
 &LR; subheds:HITTING A WALL  &LR; body:Unser admitted that his success in
almost anything he raced came awfully fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe, for sure, I didn't know exactly what it was and
what it meant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time team owner Roger Penske opted not to renew Unser
Jr.'s CART contract last August, he was in the midst of a series
winless streak that would cover five seasons and 71 consecutive
races.
</P>
<P>
   On the track, Unser Jr. bottomed-out when he and Penske teammate
Emerson Fittipaldi failed to qualify for the 1995 Indy 500. Unser
Jr., as close to royalty as there ever has been at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway, became the first reigning champion not to make the
33-car starting field. He packed up and headed home to Albuquerque,
N.M., with a crushed ego.
</P>
<P>
   Off the track, Unser Jr. was flattened early in 1999, when he
and wife Shelley began divorce proceedings after 18 years of a
stormy marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hell,'' Unser Jr. said. ``... The big thing right
now is getting to see my children as much as I possibly can, and
going on from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Al and Shelley are the parents of son Alfred, 17; daughters
Cody, 13 and Shannon, 11, and son Joseph, 3. During the divorce
proceedings the Unsers learned that Cody, then 12, had contracted a
rare spinal disease known as transverse myelitis (TM), paralyzing
her from the chest down. Cody now gets around with the help of a
custom-made wheelchair. Her condition, Unser Jr. said, has
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know Al personally. So I'm still looking at him from
the outside,'' Gossage said. ``Divorce is something you can get
through. But I can't put myself in his place because of the illness
to his daughter. To be an individual who's used to making things
happen _ and he can't do a darn thing about Cody _ that changes
your whole outlook and makes you mature beyond your years. It has
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping the start of the 1999 CART season would offer some
respite, Unser instead suffered a broken ankle in a crash at
Homestead, Fla., forcing him to miss three events. As Penske
flip-flopped between the Penske and Lola chassis in '99, Little Al
racked up only four top-10 finishes, including a season-high fifth
at Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission humbled, Unser was ready for a do-over.
Intrigued by the promise of a return to the Indy 500, Unser
accepted an offer to drive from longtime friend and former team
owner Rick Galles in the all-oval IRL. Unser Jr. and Galles, with
whom Little Al had launched his full-time Indy-car career in 1983,
clicked in their third start in the renamed Indy Racing Northern
Light Series in late April. Running second to Scott Goodyear with
20 laps remaining at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, Unser Jr. inherited
the lead when the engine in Goodyear's car blew.
</P>
<P>
   ``That win in Las Vegas was critical,'' said Unser Jr., driver
of the No. 3 Galles ECR Tickets.com G Force/Aurora. ``I mean, it
closed a chapter in my life that was a very trying time with my
divorce ... with Cody getting ill ... me breaking my leg for a
second time ... battling a car that didn't have the right engine or
tires ... just so many things that were out of my control that were
being put in front of me as challenges that I had to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the win in Vegas closed that chapter, and at the same time,
it opened a new one. We're back and winning races again. There's
some people that probably aren't convinced right now, that still
see me in a `decline' in my career. And so, let it be. I don't feel
that way. I mean, I never doubted myself, that I was over the hill
or anything. I just had bad luck. And the wrong equipment. Now I'm
a winner at it, and I'm going to continue to keep doing what I'm
doing.''  &LR; subheds:NEW START  &LR; body:That is exactly the attitude
Galles was anticipating when he signed Unser to a five-year
contract _ unusually lengthy by motorsports standards _ in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a driver, I think Al's matured a lot,'' said Galles,
president and chief executive of Galles Motor Co. in Albuquerque.
``He's had some difficulties in his life which he's had to cope
with _ which we all do _ which matures people. But by and large, Al
and I, we're pretty much the same. We share the same philosophies
of racing and we're just a little more mature. And it's been a lot
of fun getting back with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Galles, whose family-owned business has posted annual sales of
$200 million and employs more than 400, launched his racing career
with Unser Jr. in 1981. They won the Super Vee championship, a
developmental open-wheel series, that season. In 1982, Galles and
Unser Jr. moved to and clinched the Can-Am Championship for exotic
sports cars. They graduated to CART in 1983. After moving to
another team from 1984-87, Unser rejoined Galles. They won the 1990
championship and the 1992 Indy 500 in their own Galmer chassis.
</P>
<P>
   Penske lured Unser over for the 1994 season, but he and Galles
never lost contact.
</P>
<P>
   Unser had especially hoped to make a splash in his ballyhooed
return to Indy last month. But after qualifying 18th on Pole Day,
he made more headlines with his mouth than with his car. In what
served as the last hot story of race week, Unser warned Indy 500
rookie Juan Montoya, the No. 2 qualifier and reigning CART
champion, that the Speedway's concrete walls were unforgiving and
tended to ``bite'' the overzealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carry people out of here on stretchers,'' said Unser Jr.,
drawing upon the experiences of his previous 12 Indy 500 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Unser's words were not well-received by the brash Montoya, who
had clashed with Unser during their year together in CART. But when
Montoya won the race in a rout, leading a rookie record 167 of 200
laps, Unser was quick to join in the choir of praise for the
24-year-old Colombian.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a brilliant job. Brilliant job,'' said Unser Jr., who
finished a career-worst 29th after debris from the first crash of
pole sitter Greg Ray of Plano punctured his car's radiator after 66
laps. Unser Jr. returned for 24 more laps, but decided to park a
car he felt was not competitive and therefore a possible danger to
the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Like his old CART buddy, Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan respected it \Rthe Speedway\S, and that's what I wanted
out of him. Exactly,'' Unser Jr. said. ``He respected the place and
he respected the other drivers out on the racetrack, too. He showed
great maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I mean he lapped me _ he came off the corner and that
car's wiggling _ and we're 60 laps, 70 laps into the race. He's
driving that car like it was the last lap, and he did it ``every''
lap. To see that kind of talent with no mistakes ... it was
great.''  &LR; subheds:FAMILY ROAD TRIP  &LR; body:Big Al, Unser's father,
also made headlines at the Speedway as tutor to another Indy
rookie, 19-year-old Sarah Fisher. Fisher, who made her IRL debut at
TMS in October, became only the third woman to start the race in
its 84-year history. She finished 31st after being swept up in a
crash started, ironically, by Lyn St. James, only the second woman
to make the race.
</P>
<P>
   Selfishly, Little Al is hoping no woman wins the Indy 500 _
until his youngest daughter, Shannon, is ready to take her best
shot at the Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah. I believe she's interested in it,'' Unser Jr. said.
``Shelley doesn't give me time yet with my children, and we're
fighting that right now. They haven't come up with a parenting plan
yet. So, as soon as I get my children with me, then I'm going to
offer it to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Because it's a great life. Racing teaches sportsmanship,
it teaches competitiveness ... it teaches that if you work hard
enough at things, that it'll reward you. And if you don't stay on
top of it, it'll get away from you. And it doesn't get into your
color or your sex or anything. It's a science and it can be taught.
So I'd love for my little redhead to be the first female Indy
winner in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would light the whole family up, even the male
chauvinists _ which is my dad and uncle Bobby. It'd be the greatest
thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:AL UNSER JR. FILE  &LR; agatea:
</P>
<P>
   Birthdate: April 19, 1962
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Height: 5-foot-10
</P>
<P>
   Weight: 150 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Marital status: Divorced
</P>
<P>
   Children: Alfred, Cody, Shannon, Joseph
</P>
<P>
   Team: Galles ECR Racing, LLC, Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Car: No. 3 Tickets.com G Force/Oldsmobile Aurora
</P>
<P>
   IRL driver's standing: 10th/78 points
</P>
<P>
   Career IRL starts/victories: 4/1
</P>
<P>
   Career CART starts/victories: 273/31
</P>
<P>
   Career victories with Galles Racing: 20 (19 CART/1 IRL)
</P>
<P>
   Most victories in one season: 8/1994 (Marlboro Team Penske)
</P>
<P>
   Most poles in one season: 4/1994 (Marlboro Team Penske)
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis 500 champion: 1992 (Galles Racing), 1994 (Marlboro
Team Penske)
</P>
<P>
   CART PPG Cup champion: 1990 (Galles Racing), 1994 (Marlboro Team
Penske)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
