<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKO-TEXAS-COACHES-TEX     06-03 2397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-TEXAS-COACHES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER AND PERSUASION ARE PERKS FOR SUCCESSFUL HIGH SCHOOL COACHES
IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Hughes was told he would have to share.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, you don't tell the winningest public school
basketball coach in the country that he has to share. So, in the
fall of 1997, when Hughes' Dunbar Wildcats discovered they were
expected to share the gymnasium with a physical education class
during their athletic period, Hughes wasn't about to sit still.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes announced his retirement. Sort of. Actually, he announced
that he would retire unless ``some things'' changed. They did. By
midseason, he had the gym to himself, and talk of retirement faded.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a high school coach is far more than just someone who
draws Xs and Os and delivers fiery pregame speeches. In towns big
and small, high school coaches serve as surrogate parents, school
administrators, community political leaders and fund-raisers. They
are often paid more than any teacher in the district and at times
are feared for the power they wield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is known nationally for its coaches having an inordinate
amount of influence,'' said Tim Flannery, director of the National
Federation of State High School Associations' coaching program and
a longtime prep athletic director in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   While the emphasis on sports might be greater in Texas,
Hurst-Euless-Bedford district superintendent Gene Buinger said it
isn't unique to this state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a superintendent for 20 years in four states, and in
every community, the coach is a very important position,'' Buinger
said. ``People think that this is only a Texas phenomenon, but I've
seen the same thing in Georgia, Oklahoma and Kansas. In Indiana it
may be a basketball coach. In some states, maybe a wrestling
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of a coach as icon might be on the verge of
extinction in the professional and college ranks, it's not about to
die out in Texas high schools. Fueled by the popularity of
scholastic sports and salaries that are usually much higher than
their teaching peers, coaches _ particularly football coaches _
routinely rise to the top of the local power structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we designed this system,'' Buinger said. ``We
didn't. This is a reflection of all that goes on around us. You can
look at it and say it shouldn't be that way, but all you have to do
is pick up the newspaper and see there's a whole section devoted to
sports. Not academics. Not music.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, which ranks No. 1 in the nation in high school sports
participation according to a 1999 survey conducted by the National
Federation of State High School Associations, prep sports is
big-time. For coaches, that means perks like money and prestige,
but also added pressure to win. At the highest-profile schools,
such as Duncanville and Odessa Permian, the facilities, money and
fan interest resembles a small-college program. And, while some
states might generate a similar atmosphere, Texas sports _
especially football _ can seem like another universe to those
looking in from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most states, schools keep athletics \Rmore\S in
perspective,'' Flannery said. ``In most states, athletics is a part
of the total program and has its place. It's not as important as it
is in Texas.''  &LR; subheds:COMMANDING TOP DOLLARS  &LR; body:Art Briles won
four Class 4A state football championships at Stephenville. School
administrators kept rewarding him financially for his success.
Despite a salary approaching $100,000, however, he left for a
position as an assistant coach with Texas Tech last winter.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been no nationwide study ranking high school
coaches' salaries, Flannery said he believes Texas high school
coaches are at or near the top nationally. In contrast, U.S.
Department of Education statistics show Texas is 38th nationally in
teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Prairie High drama teacher Susan Crocker, a board member
of the Texas Classroom Teachers Association, doesn't totally agree
with the importance sometimes given athletics, but said she
understands why coaches get paid so well in communities where there
is rabid fan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supply and demand and it's what people want,'' Crocker
said. ``People have placed a great deal of emphasis on winning in
sports \Rhere\S, and it's not surprising that school districts have
responded to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere along the line, the measure of a district became
more related to athletics than academics. What we perceive as a
good district is often as tied to success in athletics as it is to
test scores and graduation rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Football coaches, who often serve as district athletic directors
or campus athletic coordinators, are usually among the highest-paid
employees in a school district, not far behind superintendents in
many cases.
</P>
<P>
   Highland Park's Randy Allen makes $112,500. Duncanville's Bob
Alpert is at $92,400. Several other coaches, including Peach,
Odessa Permian's T.J. Mills, Grand Prairie's Jerry Bomar, Converse
Judson's D.W. Rutledge and Midland Lee's John Parchman, are paid
$80,000 or more. Trinity girls basketball coach Sue Cannon earns
$75,950.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are far higher than the salaries of classroom
teachers in the same school districts. Alpert, for example, makes
21/2 times the average Duncanville teacher salary of $37,014, and
almost twice the average salary for teachers with more than 20
years experience ($47,765). And Alpert, like most coaches who serve
as athletic directors or coordinators, does not teach classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in other states, athletics isn't that important,'' said
Ron Caloss, who resigned as H-E-B superintendent last year to go
into private business. ``In Texas, sports, especially football, is
very important. The community dictates that.''
</P>
<P>
   With a mandate to win and support in the form of booster clubs,
it can be difficult for school district administrators to say no
when coaches say something, whether it be facilities, equipment or
additional personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the teachers come to you and say they need five more
kindergarten teachers, for example, that's a different situation,''
Caloss said. ``Kindergarten students don't have a booster club.
Coaches have a built-in group of supporters behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of their power, coaches can often dictate everything
from the assistants and sub-varsity coaches who surround them to
the funding of their program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, I gave the superintendent a list of things I
needed to be successful,'' Duncanville's Alpert said. ``We had no
weights at the junior high, for instance. Now we have them. If we
need it, we get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alpert not only gets what he needs, he gets who he wants. Like
many high school coaches, he has complete control over personnel in
his feeder program, from seventh grade up through junior varsity.
As the Duncanville school system's athletic director, he also has
the power to hire and fire coaches.
</P>
<P>
   He fired girls basketball coach Margaret Thomas this spring
after two playoff seasons, touching off complaints from some
Duncanville teachers. Alpert acknowledged that firing Thomas
created fear among other coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them were concerned,'' Alpert said, ``but after I
talked to them they were very supportive. If a coach doesn't do his
job, we'll get rid of him.''  &LR; subheds:POWER TO INFLUENCE
 &LR; body:Hughes, 71, has long claimed Fort Worth school administrators
would love to get rid of him but he was nevertheless able to get
his gym back by threatening to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert is a big asset to Fort Worth and to basketball,'' Fort
Worth school district athletic director Paul Galvan said. ``I'm
sure if he left under circumstances like that, there would be some
people in the community who would react. I don't know that they
would necessarily speak for the whole community, but I'm sure it
would be disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' commanding presence and no-nonsense style extends to his
players, who understand they are not to play another sport if they
want get playing time in basketball. Galvan said he has never heard
Hughes forbid his players from participating in anything else _
they just never do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He eats, sleeps and dreams basketball,'' Galvan said, ``and he
makes his kids feel the same way. He doesn't tell the kids they
can't play football. But he's so demanding that if you're going to
play for him, you have to eat, sleep and dream basketball, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The players do it because many of them grow up dreaming of
playing for Hughes _ and because they know not to cross him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players have to adjust to me,'' Hughes said. ``A coach
once told me, `You don't know how intimidating you can be.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a coach doesn't have to be feared to be powerful.
Football coach Ronnie Gage is one of Lewisville's most popular
figures, known for gestures such as delivering a cake to the
volleyball team after it made the 1997 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be part of the team here,'' Gage explained, ``and
not the part that people are jealous of or afraid of. There's a lot
of give and take in this business, but if you do things the right
way, people are going to want to work with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gage is close to his players, as Ken Ozee is to his players.
Ozee, who resigned from his position at Sam Houston High last week,
is among the area's most respected football coaches, not because of
his won-loss record of 59-56-4 at Sam Houston, but because of his
record in helping his players get college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of the coach is to help the kids past the adolescent
years,'' Ozee said.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime coach and current Arlington district athletic director
I.C. Little said, ``Coaches have always felt a responsibility to
help the kids. Now that there are more one-parent families than
ever, it increases that responsibility. Sometimes coaches become
almost like a father. They're everything in the world to that
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches like Ozee attempt to fill a parental role at times by
helping a player with everything from giving them a spare dollar to
supplying a couch to bunk on if needed, as well as making contacts
for scholarship aid.
</P>
<P>
   With so much power to influence young people, there is also the
danger that coaches misuse their influence. In attempting to teach
discipline and get results, a coach can tear down an athlete's
self-esteem as easily as build it up.
</P>
<P>
   What might seem like excessive discipline to some is simply
standard coaching procedure for others. Martin baseball coach Terry
King is admittedly old school, one who teaches discipline without
sugarcoating how a player performs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids today always want positive reinforcement,'' King said,
``but you can learn from negative reinforcement. Kids grow up today
with everybody telling them how good they are. And when they mess
up, they're told it's not their fault, it's someone else's fault.
Kids need to be told when they screw up. We don't pamper them. Some
people can handle that, some people can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Far bigger concerns than style develop when coaches abuse a
community's trust.
</P>
<P>
   At Trinity, football coach Ed Hickman's alleged misdeeds,
ranging from multiple instances of sexual harrassment of female
coaches to rifling through the office of a fellow coach, resulted
in a negotiated settlement this year that cost the H-E-B school
district more than $100,000 and cost Hickman his job. In 1999,
Corpus Christi Carroll football assistant Jason Murphy pleaded
guilty to 28 counts of sexual assault of a 16-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   Such accusations would create outrage regardless of who was
involved, but when it's a coach a community can feel betrayed,
according to Euless mayor Mary Lib Saleh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any coach is looked up to by our children,'' said Saleh, who
would not comment on Hickman's case. ``As parents, we expect any
coach or teacher to have the good morals to help bring up our
children in the right way. What a disappointment it is when we find
out our children have spent so much time with someone who hasn't
lived up to that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Far more often, though, a community rallies around a coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Celina football coach G.A. Moore asked for help financing
and building an indoor practice facility, local businesses and fans
rushed to help with money, material and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can get things done in this town that other people
couldn't,'' Celina assistant superintendent Don O'Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   Celina Mayor Olen Long agreed, saying Moore, who has won six
state championships, is the most popular figure in town. And what
if he ran for mayor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd lose,'' Long said.
The ``Star-Telegram's'' list of the most powerful and influential
Texas high school coaches outside of Fort Worth-Dallas.
1. D.W. Rutledge
</P>
<P>
   Age: 48.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Athletic coordinator//head football coach, Converse
Judson (1984-present).
</P>
<P>
   Salary: $83,255.
</P>
<P>
   Overall record: 190-25-5 in 16 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   State titles: Four _ 1988, '92, '93, '95.
</P>
<P>
   The power: Athletic program draws from 4,100-student campus. 2.
T.J. Mills
</P>
<P>
   Age: 46.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Athletic coordinator//head football coach, Odessa
Permian (First season).
</P>
<P>
   Salary: $81,000 ($78,000 base salary, $3,000 travel expenses).
</P>
<P>
   Overall record: 168-50.
</P>
<P>
   State titles: Four at Sealy, Class 3A _ 1994, '95, '96, '97.
</P>
<P>
   The power: One of few outsiders to be courted as head coach by
Permian.
</P>
<P>
   3. John Parchman
</P>
<P>
   Age: 50.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Head football coach, Midland Lee (1995-present).
</P>
<P>
   Salary: $78,500 (plus $5,604 in travel allowance).
</P>
<P>
   Overall record: 124-55-1.
</P>
<P>
   State titles: Two, 1998 5A Division II and 1999 5A Division I.
</P>
<P>
   The power: Unseated Odessa Permian as marquee program in West
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   4. Rhonda Farney
</P>
<P>
   Age: 45.
</P>
<P>
   Position Head girls basketball coach//girls athletic
coordinator, Georgetown High School.
</P>
<P>
   Salary: $56,317.25.
</P>
<P>
   Overall record: 610-176 in 25 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   State titles: None.
</P>
<P>
   The power: Leadership roles on state and national groups, wife
of UIL director Bill Farney.
</P>
<P>
   5. Phil Danaher
</P>
<P>
   Age: 51.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Head football coach//athletic director, Corpus Christi
Calallen.
</P>
<P>
   Salary: $77,719 per year
</P>
<P>
   Overall record: 241-70-4.
</P>
<P>
   State titles: None.
</P>
<P>
   The power: His Wildcats were the first Texas team with 12
consecutive 10-victory seasons.
