<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEFLON, NOT SHINING ARMOR, SUITS KNIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there were any question that Bobby Knight hasn't changed one
iota, it was resolved last week by his appearance on ESPN with Roy
Firestone and Digger Phelps.
</P>
<P>
   Knight came across as just what he is: a cold, manipulative,
truth-bending dictator who will continue in the future to do the
same things he has done for the past 29 years at Indiana. Some
good, some bad.
</P>
<P>
   That's my opinion. But I don't know Knight personally. When Greg
Elkin, who knows him well, watched Knight's hourlong TV interview,
he saw something else entirely, proving that truth is often in the
eye of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   Elkin, the Mavericks' director of media relations, spent eight
years working closely with Knight in the sports information
director's office at Indiana. He knows the animal in question
better than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that really bothers me is that people came out with
things that happened 10 and 12 years ago,'' Elkin said of the
Knight controversy. ``If these things were such traumatic
experiences for these people, why didn't they say something then?''
</P>
<P>
   No, Knight never threw a vase at Elkin, but Greg did have
dealings with the same athletic department secretary who had the
audacity to ask Knight ``What's it regarding?'' when the coach
phoned to speak to the athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Knight blew a fuse.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone, who has a reputation as a great interviewer, lost all
credibility when he admitted that he hadn't seen the videotape of
Knight choking former player Neil Reed. What, Firestone couldn't do
a little research before conducting such an important interview?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really interesting to me to see one group of
reporters say, `What great questions,' and another group say, `What
a joke,''' Elkin said of the ESPN interviews. ``I thought
\RKnight\S handled himself very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, my opinion's biased, but what other sports figure in
the country would ESPN have blown off their top-rated show to give
a complete hour to? That's the aura of Bobby Knight and underlines
what a compelling figure he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Compelling, yes. We can agree on that. But sympathetic? Not even
close. SCOOPED BY COWBOYS.COM There was a reason why the Cowboys'
PR department was scooped by the team's own Web site on the release
of Deion Sanders the other night _ publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' Web site _ dallascowboys.com _ posted the news that
Sanders had been released by the team just after midnight Thursday
night, about 11 hours before the PR department made it official
with the team's beat reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Why? In the hope that radio and TV stations and other news
outlets would make the announcement and credit the team's Web site
with the ``breaking'' news.
</P>
<P>
   Just another way to get 15 seconds of fame. THE DEION FILE Was
that wistfulness I heard in Deion's voice the other day when he
said the only baseball team he really wanted to play for was the
Rangers? Sounds like it broke his heart when the Rangers didn't try
to acquire him from the Reds, even after Rusty Greer and Gabe
Kapler were hurt. ...
</P>
<P>
   Why would Jerry Jones even consider bringing Sanders back under
a restructured deal? Because Deion is a sickness Jerry doesn't
really want to shake and, cutting to the chase, the Cowboys remain
very, very concerned about their cornerback situation, even after
drafting 42 of them in April. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has been working with New Orleans speed coach Tom Shaw
all right, but in Dallas, not the Big Easy. Since speed has never
been Deion's problem, it's obvious this is another way of trying to
convince potential bidders that he's serious about getting
physically ready for next season. TAX COLLECTOR One reason why the
Rangers don't like the current interleague setup is there are too
many trips to California. California has a state income tax and if
a visiting player or coach's own state doesn't have a reciprocal
state income tax, then he has to ante up a percentage for each day
worked there.
</P>
<P>
   California is not alone in hitting up visiting pro athletes.
There are city taxes to pay in Kansas City, Philadelphia, Detroit
and Cleveland and more state taxes in Missouri, Wisconsin,
Minnesota, New York, Illinois and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said he had to file 13 forms on his
taxes last year just to cover them all.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, the Rangers will have to hire a traveling
CPA, just to keep up with the various tax laws. HURT FEELINGS If
Juan Gonzalez has one grievance with the Rangers it's that they
didn't try to sit down with him personally and get something done
long-term before trading him to Detroit in November.
</P>
<P>
   If Gonzalez had known he might be traded, he might have softened
his stance and been willing to sign for less than the Rangers
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never talked to me,'' Gonzalez said, remembering how Ivan
Rodriguez avoided being traded with a one-on-one with club
president Tom Schieffer.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Doug Melvin says his hands were tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't call up a player and say, `I'm thinking about trading
you.' We had to get something done quickly,'' Melvin explains, ``or
we would have been in a situation where the agent says you better
not trade him because he's not going to sign with anybody
long-term, like Scott Boras did with Alex Rodriguez.'' GAMBLE ON
HISTORY This Cowboys' coaches junket to Las Vegas last week is a
return to the pre-Chan Gailey years. The tradition began when Jimmy
Johnson used to take his coaches down to the Bahamas to gamble and
frolic for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   It continued with occasional trips to Vegas with owner Jerry
Jones and coach Barry Switzer after Johnson left, but basically
came to a standstill when Gailey arrived with strong religious
convictions. TWO WEDDINGS AND... On the same weekend that Emmitt
Smith was married a few weeks ago, Cowboys coach Dave Campo
attended not one, but two weddings.
</P>
<P>
   First came Smith's, with many, many Cowboys players and coaches
in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when longtime locker-room attendant Al Walker was
married in south Dallas, Campo was one of just three Cowboys'
employees in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just as excited to go to Al's wedding,'' Campo says,
``as I was to Emmitt's.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's who Dave Campo is. GO EAST, YOUNG MAN Here's a vote
against the Players Association's plan for realignment. While it
would unite the Rangers and Astros in the same division, it leaves
the Rangers in the American League West. That won't do.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has told the Rangers they will be able to finally
escape the West after all these years of bad travel and
late-starting games. It's a promise that needs to be kept.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Rangers need a good rival like the Astros, but in a
newly revamped Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Either league will do just fine. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817)
390-7760 \Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
 &LR; subheds:REVO'S RIMSHOTS
TASTES BETTER Beer vendors at Wrigley Field, writes the ``Chicago
Tribune's'' Steve Rosenbloom, are wearing T-shirts under their
uniforms with the word ``Scapegoat'' emblazoned across the front
after the bullpen fiasco with the Dodgers a couple of weeks ago.
POSTED Hold it! Ray Bourque shoots again and ... it hits the post!
BATS IN THE BELFOUR I don't know what's scarier, Eddie Belfour on
medication in Game 1 or Eddie Belfour off medication in Game 2 and
still dropping his stick to dive for a puck 10 feet outside the
crease.
MR. TOUGH GUY You'd have thought Roy Firestone had grilled Bobby
Knight unmercifully the way he was talking with Dan Patrick on ESPN
radio the day after his hour-long interview with Indiana coach
Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how tough you get 24 hours after the show's over.
IN THE BOONDOCKS A spokesman for Myles Brand, the man who granted
Knight a reprieve, said the Indiana president ``was out of state''
and didn't have access to a TV, so he didn't watch the ESPN report.
</P>
<P>
   Must have been in Arkansas.
SAFETY FIRST You think if Ray Lewis is acquitted of murder in
Atlanta and returns to the Baltimore Ravens, the NFL will install
metal detectors for players to pass through on their way to the
field?
ROCKET'S RED GLARE How would you like to be the guy that had to
tell Roger Clemens they put the wrong number on his World Series
ring?
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, how'd you like to be the guy who had to tell George
Steinbrenner?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the little bald guy, George Costanza.
PERFECT EVIDENCE Don't know about you, but it didn't take a
radar-gun reading or a signed note from his doctor to tell me that
Darren Oliver has a dead arm. I just turned the TV set on and there
it was.
{Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.} nn
</P>
