American side to demand action on problems that lower levels of the
Russian bureaucracy weren't responding to.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians also agreed to a plan to shutter three nuclear
reactors, and the United States has begun a program to purchase 500
megatons of weapons grade uranium that the Russians are converting
to low-grade fuel. One of the commission's least publicized but
perhaps most important accomplishments was the creation of two
institutes that have channeled Russia's leading weapons scientists
into private sector employment, much of it in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts also see the commission as a missed
opportunity. It produced few big breakthroughs and failed to
generate the kind of business investments that many in Russia
expected it would. Some agreements, such as Russian cooperation in
the international space station, proved hollow: The Russians are
two years late on a crew module for the station that was supposed
to have been launched next month.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that Gore's close relationship with Victor
Chernomyrdin, Russia's controversial former prime minister and
Russia's designee to the commission, also blinded him to mounting
evidence of Chernomyrdin's possible involvement in Russian
corruption and the country's sudden economic collapse in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long period of time, (Gore) was the administration's
point man on Russia policy,'' said Lee Hamilton, director of the
Woodrow Wilson International Center and a former Democratic
congressman from Indiana. ``He, I think, deserves some of the
credit for the achievements of the policy, but likewise deserves
some of the criticism for the failures.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Chernomyrdin held their first meeting in Moscow in
1993. At the time, U.S. officials were anxiously seeking a way to
rid nuclear weapons from the newly independent nation of Ukraine,
which held the world's third largest stockpile of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot, Gore suggested that then-Defense Secretary William
Perry, who was on the trip, fly to Ukraine with Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott to negotiate with the Ukrainians. Chernomyrdin
volunteered to send his deputy foreign minister, and the team left
for Kiev in Perry's plane.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators stayed up late into the night with the
Ukrainians. The next month, the United States and Ukraine issued
the so-called trilateral agreement which de-nuclearized the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big deal,'' said Ashton Carter, a Harvard
University professor who was then an assistant secretary of defense
to Perry and the defense staffer assigned to the commission.
``Getting the Ukrainians to go along with us did not by any means
look like a sure thing, and Al Gore was very involved in that. That
was his baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter also said the commission became extremely helpful to the
Defense Department in trying to implement the Nunn-Lugar Act, named
for former Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn and Sen. Richard Lugar (R-Ind.),
which has appropriated more than $1.2 billion toward dismantling
Russian nuclear stockpiles and ensuring the safety of nuclear
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important that we be able to bring to the very, very
top some of the problems that developed,'' Carter said. ``You could
always tell your Russian counterpart, listen, if we don't get off
the stick on this issue, we'll take it to Gore-Chernomyrdin.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter participated in eight of the commission's 10 summits. He
described Gore as businesslike and well-read on the nuances of
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extraordinarily well briefed and a devourer of
knowledge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL VULNERABILITY?
</P>
<P>
   In the meetings, Gore and Chernomyrdin would sit opposite from
one another and move through agenda items prepared in giant
briefing books. When the two couldn't agree, Carter said, they
would often disappear in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have private dinners and they were quite
productive,'' he said. ``The vice president would come back and
report that he had managed to get through to Chernomyrdin the
importance of an issue, or that somebody on the Russian side was
holding up progress. For us who were trying to make security
programs work, this was a terrific mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's close relationship with Chernomyrdin caused him to
turn a blind eye to reports of the former prime minister's
involvement in Russian corruption, critics say. Gore ignored a CIA
warning about Chernomyrdin, said Keith Bush, Russian and Eurasian
program director at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area where I think Gore is vulnerable,'' said Bush.
``The U.S. side didn't want to see the corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic collapse has also led to finger-pointing in
Russia over the commission's lack of effectiveness in promoting
U.S. investment in Russia. Viktor Kremenyuk, deputy director of the
Institute of USA and Canada at the Russian Academy of Sciences,
said economic issues took a back seat to disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was that it was regarded more as a ritual thing
than . . . a good tool to advance the economic relations,'' said
Kremenyuk. ``Unfortunately, almost 10 years have been simply spent
or wasted without any growth in the economic relationship. The vice
president has simply either misunderstood the importance of this
job, or he simply did not manage it.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
