<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elliott wrecks No. 2 start
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ A blown right-front tire has blown Bill Elliott's
position on the front row for today's MBNA Platinum 400.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who was to start next to pole-sitter Rusty Wallace,
crashed during Saturday morning's Winston Cup practice session at
Dover Downs International Speedway. The extensive damage to the
rear of the No. 94 Ford caused the team to roll out its backup
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the switch of cars, Elliott will still be officially
credited with his second outside pole of the year. However, at the
completion of the three warmup laps before the start of today's
event, he will have to retreat to the back of the 43-car field.
It's NASCAR's rule whenever a team goes to a backup car after
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't worried,'' Elliott said. ``I just hate starting in the
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 94 crew put new tires on the Taurus before the early
practice. Elliott ran 65 laps, and then motored into the pits for a
quick check of all parts, including the tires. He returned to the
track for about 25 more laps before disaster struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming out of (the second turn) and I could feel (the
car) starting to shake,'' Elliott said. ``I thought I was going to
be OK, but the tire went going into three. I might have run over
something or whatever, but it's kind of an unfortunate thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second tough break in as many race weekends for
Elliott. At last Sunday's Coca-Cola 600, Elliott started at the No.
3 position but finished last after blowing an engine.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Elliott was not injured in Saturday's wreck, which
banged up his primary car. The crew quickly pulled out the backup
ride, nicknamed ``Awesome.'' It is the same car that debuted
earlier this year at Texas, where Elliott was caught up in a wreck
and landed on the top of Jeff Gordon's hood.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott had the chance to drive ``Awesome'' around the one-mile
oval before the early practice ended. He got more time in ``Happy
Hour'' practice after the Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good car,'' Elliott said. ``We ran it just as good as
we ran in practice earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mishap, Elliott did not seem to be very upset. He
and his team members managed to find positive things to say about
starting last today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think will affect us at all because it's a long
race,'' co-crew chief Kevin Cram said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fastest cars always find their way to the front. And
you've got to have luck on your side like any other race. This
(mishap) just got us a little behind, but not a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
