r a BC-ENERGY-PRICES-KAN &LR;      06-03 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMERS CAN EXPECT MUCH HIGHER HEATING BILLS NEXT WINTER  
</HEADLINE>
 BC- ENERGY-PRICES -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BY STEVE EVERLY, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Gasoline prices reached another record last
week, upsetting motorists once again.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly overlooked, however, was the soaring price of natural
gas, which could cause similar outcries when people see their
heating bills in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Most noticeably, unleaded gasoline jumped a dime last week, to
$1.59 a gallon at many area pumps. Prices for natural gas and
propane have also been on the rise, doubling from a year ago. And
if they stay up, the average household's heating bills could be
$200 to $300 higher in the course of a normal winter.
</P>
<P>
   The worst could still be avoided if prices dropped by the
heating season. Utilities and propane companies, however, have had
to start building up inventories for winter now with the
higher-priced fuel. Since higher gas costs are passed on to
customers without needing regulatory approval, utilities have begun
warning consumers to expect higher heating bills this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Gas Service last week alerted regulators to its deepening
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to express Kansas Gas Service's concerns about
the very real possibility that natural gas prices this winter will
reach all-time highs,'' Eugene Dubay, the utility's president, said
to members of the Kansas Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns are widespread. Paul Snider, a spokesman for
Missouri Gas Energy, called higher heating bills a sure bet. And
across the country there are worries that three years of relatively
mild gas prices have set up consumers for a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a scary winter,'' said Jack Zekoll, a
deputy director at the New York State Public Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on larger customers could be particularly chilling.
Bob Courtney, energy manager for the Olathe, Kan., School District,
said the district had budgeted about $380,000 for natural gas
during the next school year. Now those costs could reach $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even electric utilities could get dented, because they are using
increasing amounts of natural gas to generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of the spike in natural gas prices was unexpected.
Early this year wholesale gas could be had for $2.20 per thousand
cubic feet. Last week it was about $4.40 before settling down to
around $4.15 by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on? Like gasoline, supplies for natural gas are
tighter than normal. That in turn has caused jitters in the futures
market, where contracts for future delivery are bought and sold,
and which reacts swiftly to any news, good or bad.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Costello, an economist for the federal Energy Information
Administration, said demand for natural gas had been higher than
expected in large part because of the amount of natural gas being
used by the electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for a hot summer have helped to drive natural gas
prices higher because of gas-generated electricity needed to power
air conditioners. And this all comes as gas utilities have to buy
gas to store for use in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Costello said that supplies were catching up to demand, but that
it could be too late for much relief this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the higher gas prices are already having some
effect. Snider said Missouri Gas Energy utility usually stockpiled
a third of the gas it needed for the winter and was now buying the
fuel _ and paying the higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Johnson, a spokesman for Kansas Gas Service, said his
utility also was buying gas to put into storage. The utility is
asking regulators for some changes to pay for its ``hedging''
program, which provides some protection against price spikes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the hedging programs used by Missouri Gas Energy and
Kansas Gas Service will be in for a test this winter. A hedge
allows the utility to cap the cost of gas that is passed on to
customers. Last year the cap was just above $3 per thousand cubic
feet.
</P>
<P>
   With gas costs now above $4, any hedge would probably provide
protection only above $5 _ unless gas prices fall before the hedge
is purchased.
</P>
<P>
   So, the utilities and their customers could see higher prices
than they saw during the price spikes of the winter of 1996-1997,
which spurred regulators to approve the hedging programs.
</P>
<P>
   The propane industry, which primarily serves small towns and
rural areas, is also raising concerns.
</P>
<P>
   George Koloroutis, a vice president for Ferrell North America in
Houston, a subsidiary of FerrellGas in Liberty, said there was
still hope for some relief in time for the heating season. But
propane prices have now topped 58 cents a gallon; a year ago they
were about 26 cents. That sort of price in June is unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe propane prices will be higher this winter than
last,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Platte-Clay Electric Cooperative, which also sells propane, a
customer with an energy-efficient home uses about 800 gallons of
propane, while more inefficient dwellings can nearly double that
amount. That means even a 25 cent per gallon increase can amount to
hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have an impact on our customers,'' said Bill Estes,
the cooperative's manager of customer service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
