r a BC-BILLS-MEDICAL-KAN &LR;      06-03 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLS-MEDICAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH INSURERS FRUSTRATE DOCTORS, PATIENTS  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY PAUL WENSKE and JULIUS A. KARASH, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Terry and Lori Geise don't hide their
frustration with the nation's health-care insurance system.
</P>
<P>
   The Shawnee, Kan., couple's youngest son, Austin, was born two
years ago, and the anesthesiologist's bill was not paid by their
insurer until last fall. Other doctor bills more than a year old
still have not been paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I get a statement, I have to call the doctor to
verify the service, then call the insurer to see why the bill
wasn't paid,'' said Terry Geise. ``I really think the system is
designed to put more of the costs on the backs of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The Geises, who have three other sons, say they spend hours
translating medical statements and tracking claims. ``We don't have
time for this Mickey Mouse stuff. I'll bet many people don't even
question these bills. They just go ahead and pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers increasingly are voicing pent-up anger with an
unwieldy health insurance system that frustrates them with unpaid
bills, exasperating delays and liability for claims they do not
owe.
</P>
<P>
   Many are joining with doctors who accuse insurers of
deliberately delaying paying health claims so they can profit off
the interest on money withheld. Doctors say slow-paying insurers
are forcing them to take out loans to pay their own bills.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers deny they intentionally delay payments. They say most
delays are caused by medical providers filing incorrect or faulty
claims. They also point out that the complexities, in part, result
from providing the array of health-care choices consumers demand.
</P>
<P>
   Few experts, however, defend the nation's system of health
payments. Most agree the system is sluggish, clogged and
inconsistent. In 15 years health-care costs have nearly quadrupled.
And experts say added administrative expenses account for 30
percent of the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may enjoy top-notch health care, but in terms of
processing its bills ``no country is as backward as the United
States,'' said Uwe Reinhardt, a Princeton University health
economist and former member of the Physician Payment Review
Commission, which advises Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And consumers may be getting the worst of it. Patients tested
</P>
<P>
   Consider the ordeal of Kevin Carril.
</P>
<P>
   In July he went to Medical Plaza Consultants to have stitches
removed from a foot wound he suffered when he stepped on broken
glass. The bill came to $50. Carril paid a $12 co-pay, and Blue
Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City was billed for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Months went by, and the bill was not paid. In December, Blue
Cross asked him to indicate whether he had other coverage. He did
not. And the specified reply form was not in the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Medical Plaza billed him for $38. Kathy Vance, office
administrator for the Medical Plaza, said: ``In January, after
trying for five months to bill Blue Cross, we closed the bill, so
that it was no longer pending in our system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just nothing else we can do but pull the patient in at
that time and say, `Your insurer isn't paying.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials declined to be interviewed. Instead they
sent a release explaining conversion to a $35 million computer
system to speed the processing of claims.
</P>
<P>
   Carril said that in the third week of May, he called the insurer
and said he was going to tell The Kansas City Star about his
problem. On June 1, Carril received notice from Blue Cross the
claim was paid.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor's office is often the consumer's introduction to the
health-care gantlet.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first place a glitch can happen. Wrong insurance
information can be typed into a computer. A patient may have
forgotten or lost his or her insurance card. A diagnosis code may
be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Coding errors are among the most common problems that hold up
claims, said Kathy Turnell, a medical-claims analyst for Concentra
Preferred Systems. For that reason medical groups now train
technicians to track insurance claims.
</P>
<P>
   One recent morning at Midwest Ear, Nose and Throat in Olathe,
Kan., Pam Miles was on hold for 12 minutes before reaching a claims
clerk at HealthNet. (HealthNet declined to be interviewed). But
that wasn't bad. She has been simmering on hold for as long as 40
minutes with some insurers.
</P>
<P>
   A big irritation is being told by the insurer the claim was not
received, said Debbie Winters, office billing supervisor for the
Olathe specialists. ``It's just the claim game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Walker, chief financial officer for St. Luke's-Shawnee
Mission Medical Group, said you cannot always blame the insurer. He
said that some practices lacked sophisticated systems and that
technicians needed to handle intricate claims.
</P>
<P>
   His 75-doctor practice bought a $175,000 software program to
analyze and edit claims. The claims are examined at a
clearninghouse before being zapped to insurers, including
HealthNet. Walker said the program had significantly reduced errors
and cut the time it took to hear back.
</P>
<P>
   Other providers, however, say that even when claims are sent
electronically, glitches happen and insurers say they did not get
them.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one practice coded a patient's claim to show
treatment for a heart ailment. By the time it reached the insurer,
it showed the patient was treated for obesity. Since the patient
was not covered for obesity, the claim was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Gaughan, one of the physicians in the Olathe office,
said that it could take some insurers six months to a year to pay
claims and that other claims were reported lost.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Jantsch, a physician and past president of the
Metropolitan Medical Society of Greater Kansas City, said the
system suffered a lack of standardization.
</P>
<P>
   If doctors and insurance companies have trouble tracking claims,
consider how hard it is for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   After Kristin McDaniel's husband was diagnosed with cancer, she
began trying to keep track of the claims. But as the bills grew to
more than $150,000, she couldn't keep up. ``I became exasperated.''
Ultimately her bills were paid, but she said the process was
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to become an astute participant, as a consumer of
health goods,'' said Rob Mahoney, an employee benefit consultant
with Haake Benefits Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should at least make sure whether their health plan
doctors can bill them when the insurer will not pay. Most HMO plans
ban this kind of billing. Some other plans allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Who is responsible for those complexities is part of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 15 years of heightened managed health care, the
cost of health care has grown from around $350 billion to more than
$1.2 trillion. And as baby boomers age, the cost is going up.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt, the Princeton health economist, says that the health
insurance industry has never had an incentive to make coverage
simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you looked at a lot of them, they make more money on the
float,'' said Reinhardt, referring to the time from when the
insurer receives a claim to payment. During that time, he said, the
insurance company can invest the money.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry officials strongly rebut that allegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't play the float,'' said Tom Bartlett, a vice
president at Concentra Preferred Systems, of Napier, Ill., which
resolves disputes between insurers and providers.
</P>
<P>
   He said most insurers made 3 percent to 5 percent profit.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone complains about the system.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Holland, vice president of compensation and benefits at
Sprint Corp., said his company helped ensure swift payment of
claims by motivating insurers with whom it did business.
</P>
<P>
   If insurers pay on time or before, they are paid more money by
Sprint. If they lag, Sprint docks them money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
