</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERS VS. PLAYERS: RUINOUS RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Interleague play has run its course, creating
maybe a tenth of the excitement it did when it was introduced four
years ago. It was the brainstorm of short-sighted folks who fail to
understand good teams, not manufactured rivalries, sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're trying to figure out a way to manipulate it so fans
will again be interested. And next month the brainiacs who run
baseball will vote on realignment. Again, ticket sales and
generating revenue are the only reasons it's being contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   But if the owners, the commissioner's office, the players
association, the agents and anyone else who thinks the game needs
changing to increase popularity really want to do something to help
the fans, maybe they should listen to the game's top attraction and
ticket seller.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year there's been quiet talk throughout the
industry of a work stoppage after the 2001 season. The
aforementioned parties should get in a room and hammer out an
agreement that will ensure there won't be a strike, or a lockout or
whatever other term they can use that translates into screwing over
the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Because if baseball does stop, if the leather and ash are traded
in for arbitrators and bargaining positions, this generation could
get cheated of seeing the most coveted individual record chased.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Mark McGwire entered Saturday 212 homers shy of Hank
Aaron's record of 755. If his work stops after the 2001 season
because baseball becomes too greedy once again, he's vowed it won't
continue whenever, if ever, the sides agree on a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a lockout or strike after next year, you won't see
me in uniform as a player ever again,'' McGwire said. ``I don't
care what they try to do. I will walk away. I don't care to go
through that again. What we did to the game in 1994 was absolutely
horrendous. To do that to the game again, I would be embarrassed. I
would think the other players think that way. I hope the owners
think the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   By past experience, it's debatable if there's much thinking
going on by anyone regarding this issue.
</P>
<P>
   You remember 1994?
</P>
<P>
   The small-market Expos, with current Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone the GM in Montreal, on their way to a possible
showdown with the Yankees in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   They played games one day as summer was running late, then
didn't play again until spring. They canceled the World Series.
That's like canceling Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball has come back nicely. Cities, for the most part,
are building new ballparks. And cities like Cleveland are being
rejuvenated by incorporating baseball into revitalization projects.
</P>
<P>
   Players are fairly paid, most would surmise. Owners are making
money, unless they let emotion rule over business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it,'' McGwire said. ``There is nothing going wrong with
the game of baseball. The owners are making money. The players are
making money. Listen, this is the greatest game of all time. Look
at the new stadiums. Look at the attendance. The bottom line is,
it's common sense. Life is common sense. But do a lot of people use
common sense? No. That's where the game has been embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is too good for two parties to ruin it.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has proven that. Any other enterprise that treats its
customers the way baseball has for the past two decades would have
been out of business for at least a decade.
</P>
<P>
   However, baseball continues strongly because fans spent a
childhood playing it, and the rest of their life wishing they were
a hint better at it so they could play it more. And that has
nothing to do with money.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be a breaking point. Fans won't stop coming all
together, but they'll scale back. When Toronto was winning
championships in the early '90s, it was selling out SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Those who played in Toronto after the 1994 ``work stoppage''
said the fans haven't recovered from it, and thus the Blue Jays
draw dismally. Another work stoppage would be brutal for everyone,
especially the fans.
</P>
<P>
   So baseball should do the right thing. Worry about interleague
and realignment later. Get any labor strife settled now before it
becomes an issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
