<HEADLINE>
LOPES HOPES BREWERS CAN FIX ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took former Los Angeles Dodger Davey Lopes a
while to land a big-league managing job, and would still argue
whether he's done so. One thing he's finding out is just how
difficult it is managing a mediocre, also-ran like the Milwaukee
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee is 22-32, has the fourth-worst winning percentage
(.407) in the National League, and the only thing keeping the
Brewers out of last place in the Central Division is the Chicago
Cubs and Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to change the mindset of the players and how they
approach the game,'' Lopes said. ``How they go about their
business, their expectations. You have to get them to take the
field every night expecting to win. It starts there. You have to
get them to believe in their talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep reiterating it, because there's been a losing
environment here for the last six or seven years. Not only just
here, but throughout the minor leagues, too. I kind of anticipated
what needed to be done, but you don't really see how engrossed you
need to be until you're in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to change the attitude, the Brewers have changed
personnel and, despite being a small-market team, have gobbled up
salary to get rid of players they don't feel will help.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the Brewers released pitcher Jamie Navarro, even
though they had to eat most of his $5-million salary this season.
Lopes also sent opening-day starter Steve Woodard to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lopes) has been great,'' Brewers outfielder Geoff Jenkins
said. ``He's been around the game forever. He knows the game, and
he treats us like professionals. It's been awesome having him.''
</P>
<P>
   Snake-bit Diamondbacks: Arizona survived the start of the season
with closer Matt Mantei and third baseman Matt Williams on the
disabled list. Now, the Diamondbacks will try to hold on to their
West Division lead with first baseman Erubiel Durazo and
right-hander Todd Stottlemyre on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre had trouble with his right forearm, and Durazo has
torn cartilage in his right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago when I got an MRI, I came out with two tears in my
shoulder,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I went in thinking worst-case
scenario. So if going on the DL is ever good news, this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   The losses are huge, though. Stottlemyre was 8-3 with a 4.38
ERA. Durazo was hitting .287 with six homers and 24 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Helton: Is it too early to talk about hitting .400? Well,
maybe, but already opposing teams are showing extra caution
pitching to Colorado Rockies first baseman Todd Helton.
</P>
<P>
   Helton, a former University of Tennessee quarterback who is
hitting .420 with 17 homers and 54 RBI, will have his patience
tested because he might not see too many strikes. When Houston
faced the Rockies last week, Astros manager Larry Dierker gave
explicit instructions not to throw Helton a strike - even in the
eighth inning with the bases loaded in a tie game. It was his third
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mind walking him,'' Dierker said. ``I minded the
pitch he got (a double) on and the pitch he got the sacrifice fly
on. I'd rather have walked him all five times. I didn't want to
walk him with the bases loaded, but one run is less than we
would've done if we threw him one down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Randy Johnson had 10 strikeouts Wednesday,
putting him past Cy Young and into 14th place all-time with 2,824.
... The losing in Chicago continues, and the Cubs are trying
everything to put an end to it. With two roster moves in midweek,
the Cubs have used 39 players through 55 games. ... Mets lefty Mike
Hampton was 2-3 with a 6.99 ERA in April and was 4-0 with a 1.72
ERA in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
