<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA: KEY GAMES IN DIVISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Interleague play is upon us again, and as
usual, many of the participants are whining about it. To them, it's
a nuisance, something they want to get over with so they can get on
with the season with games in their own league, in their own
division.
</P>
<P>
   However, as long as Bud Selig is commissioner, interleague games
are here to stay. The fans say so as well, as attendance is up
overall during interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia longs for the days when he played,
when a team played 18 games vs. its division foes, and 12 vs. the
teams in the other division in the same league. Expansion has
wreaked havoc on a symmetrical schedule, but it isn't all bad,
Scioscia says. In fact, he likes playing the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it, it makes sense when you have natural rivalries
based on geography,'' he said. ``It's something the fans can enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't like what I'm hearing about flip-flopping
divisions as far as who you play, like the AL West playing the NL
Central. That defeats the whole purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   What Scioscia would like to see is playing more games within the
division. The Angels will be making their second trip to Tampa Bay
and Baltimore in the next week, but they still haven't been to
Oakland or Texas in their own division. They won't play at Texas
until after the All-Star break, July 24-26.
</P>
<P>
   ``That for me is an absolute,'' Scioscia said of more
inter-division games. ``When I was playing, the entire final month
of the season was against your own division. If you went into
September six games out, you knew you still had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   You ain't seen nothing yet: In the span of two weeks, the
Indians put five pitchers on the disabled list - Charles Nagy,
Ricardo Rincon, Paul Shuey, Jaret Wright and Paul Rigdon. Earlier
in the season, Bartolo Colon made a trip to the DL.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley is one Indians pitcher who has been able to avoid
injury problems, but he is no stranger to such things, having spent
14 seasons with the Angels when he watched the team get destroyed
by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to think it was me,'' Finley joked. ``This is
like a baby ward compared to over there. We had guys having heart
transplants. Not only were guys out, they were out for four or five
months, with something broken or something that needed to be
reattached. It was happening every other week over there.''
</P>
<P>
   E-4: Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch can't seem to get
over his mental problem when it comes to making the easiest throw
in baseball - from the second-base position to first base.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Knoblauch's throws have been incredibly bad, as he has
thrown the ball into the ground. Steve Sax had the same problem
years ago with the Dodgers and got over it. Knoblauch, though,
doesn't know whether he'll be able to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a breaking point,'' Knoblauch said, adding he is
``pretty close'' to his.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch declined to see a sports psychologist about the
problem last winter but said recently he'll try anything now.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have reportedly expressed interest in Twins second
baseman Todd Walker, who is playing in Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: New Angels shortstop Kevin Stocker didn't make a
good impression in his Angels debut. In the first inning of
Stocker's first game, the first batter of the game - Dodgers
leadoff hitter Todd Hollandsworth - hit a pop fly to shallow left
that Stocker dropped for an error. The reason the Angels signed
Stocker? Defense. ... Again, it's the media's fault. Even though
Orioles starter Mike Mussina has rebounded from a poor start, he
hasn't changed his personal policy of not speaking to reporters.
With Albert Belle also playing for the Orioles, it must be an
awfully quiet clubhouse. ... Speaking of the Orioles, they again
are the biggest disappointment in baseball when you factor payroll.
Their 2000 payroll is $83.1 million, third in baseball behind only
the Yankees ($92.9 million) and Dodgers ($90.7 million). Their
winning percentage (through Friday) ranked No. 24 of 30 teams. The
best team in baseball related to payroll is the White Sox. Their
2000 payroll of $31.1 million ranks No. 26, but their winning
percentage (through Friday) ranked No. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
