<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-BRAVES-NY     06-03 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES BEAT YANKEES, 11-7 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Maddux against Roger Clemens was supposed to be
landmark. It turned out to be landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens and Maddux couldn't get anybody out on Saturday, the
Yankees couldn't catch the ball, John Rocker couldn't throw
strikes, and after watching the Yankees blow three separate leads
and lose by 11-7, Manager Joe Torre couldn't take it any more,
blistering the shoddy performance in a team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Torre's hat was cocked to the side of his head,
his expression vacant. He had just watched 3 hours 57 minutes of
atrocious baseball on a hot and muggy afternoon. He was tired and
angry.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked Torre if he thought Shane Spencer's long fly ball
with two outs in the ninth was going to carry over the wall for a
game-tying grand slam. ``I don't know,'' Torre said. ``I saw so
much today, I don't know what I was looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre's postgame tirades are rare, and he was not specifically
upset with the fact that the Yankees made four errors _ ``They're
part of the game,'' he said _ or that Bernie Williams failed to
catch a fly ball, or that the Yankees failed to score more runs and
bury Maddux when they had the chance. Torre was mad because the
Yankees had lost a game they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly,'' he said. ``I don't know any other way to
describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had a small sense of relief because injuries that
forced two important players out of the game did not appear to be
serious. Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher, sustained a bruised
right knee after Maddux fouled a ball off the joint in the second
inning; Posada's knee guard was split in two, and he could not
immediately put any weight on his right leg. But X-rays indicated
Posada had no fractures, and he may be able to play within the next
couple of days, Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill strained the right side of his right calf running
the bases in the first inning, but did not expect to miss much
time.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player will be in the lineup Sunday against the Braves
left-hander Terry Mulholland, when the Yankees (29-22) play the
final game of their three-game series against Atlanta (36-18).
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill singled in the first inning against Maddux, the third of
four consecutive hits _ the first time in Maddux's career that he
allowed four hits to begin a game. The Yankees had two runs in,
runners at second and third and nobody out against Maddux. Clemens
was coming off his 13-strikeout outing against Pedro Martinez. It
looked as if the Yankees might have a chance to sweep the team with
the best record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees failed to add to their lead in that inning,
Clemens allowed a single to the first batter he faced and the whole
thing turned into a mess. Clemens again had great speed, throwing
97 miles an hour, but ineffectively; he allowed six hits, four
walks, six runs _ four earned _ in five innings and remains a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't very good,'' Torre said. ``I don't know the reason
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens and Maddux have 479 victories and nine Cy Young Awards
between them, but they labored to compile exactly one scoreless
half-inning each. The Yankees scored at least one run in their
first four innings, the Braves scored in each of the first three
innings, and the lead changed hands repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens retired the Braves in order in the fourth, he
raised his arms in mock jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Clemens, you look at Maddux, you think 2-1, 3-2,''
said Pat Corrales, the Braves coach who managed the team for the
day while Bobby Cox attended the high school graduation of his
youngest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter had 4 hits among the Yankees' 13 against Maddux, the
second most Maddux has allowed in his career. But the offense,
which ran aggressively to take advantage of Maddux's slow delivery,
couldn't keep up with the rate at which the Yankees' defense was
giving away runs. Clemens threw wildly toward first on a pick-off
attempt in the first inning, eventually costing himself a run.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch committed another anxiety
throwing error in the second, his ninth error of the season. Jeter
fumbled what should have been a double-play grounder in third, and
when Brian Jordan launched a three-run homer, Jeter flung a piece
of dirt disgustedly, feeling responsible for two of the runs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, the Yankees held a 6-5 lead in the bottom of
the fifth. With two outs and a runner at first, Javy Lopez drove a
ball to deep center, where Bernie Williams sprinted to reach the
ball _ and then missed it, pulling in his glove, perhaps wary of
running into the fence. ``I've got to catch that ball,'' he said
later.
</P>
<P>
   Doggedly, the Yankees regained a 7-6 advantage in the sixth,
Chris Turner slapping a run-scoring single against Maddux; Turner,
who had homered and walked earlier after replacing Posada, was the
last batter Maddux faced.
</P>
<P>
   But with two outs and no one on base in the bottom of the
seventh, Tino Martinez flubbed a throw to Jason Grimsley, allowing
Jordan to reach base. Grimsley (1-1) hit the next batter with a
pitch, and both runners scored when Lopez lined a double into the
gap in left-center field. Shoddy infield defense has plagued the
Yankees all year, with the shortstops committing 7 errors, the
second basemen making 11, the third basemen 13. The Yankees have
surrendered 30 unearned runs, only 7 fewer than they did during the
entire 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by four runs in the ninth, the Yankees had one last
chance when Rocker sprinted out of the bullpen to pitch the final
inning. With the Turner Field fans roaring, Rocker's on-field
control abandoned him, the way it abandoned Mark Wohlers two years
ago. Rocker walked Scott Brosius. He hit Jim Leyritz with the count
no balls and two strikes. He walked Jeter, loading the bases. He
fell behind Spencer. Leo Mazzone, the Atlanta pitching coach, threw
the bullpen phone in disgust. After almost four hours, the
situation was absurd. So was the game.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer swung at a high fastball, and the ball soared toward
left field, through a slight wind, to where Gerald Williams backed
against the fence, reached up and made the catch.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Braves' first home victory against the Yankees since
Game 2 of the 1958 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was at that game, a teenager rooting for his older brother
Frank, who was the first baseman for the Milwaukee Braves. But he
wasn't thinking about that as he trudged into the clubhouse
Saturday evening. He had some things to say. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
