r s BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     06-03 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIP DOWN MEMORY LANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until I figure out how to digitally morph a harmless photograph
into something capable of compromising the integrity of a new
employer, this will be my final NBA column.
</P>
<P>
   Save your wild applause until the finish.
</P>
<P>
   With only one big swing left to take at the David Stern Planet,
using it to knock the cover off of the league's little sins would
be too predictable. OK, we'll take a cut at one disturbing item:
Where did they find the stunt double who impersonated Shaq so
unconvincingly in Game 6?
</P>
<P>
   Now on to the maudlin stuff.
</P>
<P>
   (Those of you allergic to Memory Lane should choose to jump off
here.)
</P>
<P>
   At this time, the columnist would like to thank Elgin Baylor and
Jerry West for allowing pro hoops to flourish in Southern
California. The columnist also would like the reader to save any
Clipper-woe-related spit-takes for the reactionary stage of talk
radio.
</P>
<P>
   Without Baylor and West offering up the Lakers as America's Team
in the hearts and ears of most Americans who reside west of Boston,
Chick Hearn might have been forced to build his fortune on
``Bowling For Dollars.'' But the Lakers did have Baylor and West,
providing a stellar launch for the type of history that can propel
a franchise for a few decades.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, nobody chants ``Beat Port-land!''
</P>
<P>
   As a general manager, West has blended this archival success,
the largesse of a rather generous owner and his own knack for
shrewd observation into a personal genius predicament.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Lakers lose Game 7 today, Phil Jackson's ability to
slalom past public self-actualization will turn an angry mob's
attentions on the roster. And the no-power-forward blame will be
passed to West, whose boss while very accommodating is not the
luxury-tax-snubbing Paul Allen. Missing will be culpability for
Jackson, the first king of geometry to believe you can have a
triangle without points.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has suffered the dings and errors of uncanny misfortune
(an injury roll call for Derek Smith, Danny Manning, Norm Nixon,
Marques Johnson, Ron Harper and the knee-tummy tribulations of
Stanley Roberts), while weaving them into a history that's
hamstrung by the odious allowance limitations imposed by Donald T.
Sterling. He also has permitted his knowledge of the game to be
diluted by the personal whining of Clipper head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   West had an owner who paid to liberate Shaquille O'Neal from
central Florida, a bold move made possible by the preamble of
acquiring young Kobe Bryant. Baylor and the Clippers worked out
Bryant before the 1996 draft, adored him, but were employing a
coach Bill Fitch whose interest in winning a few games NOW left him
in furious opposition to drafting a high school guard with the
seventh overall pick. Because Fitch campaigned for the 1995
draft-night trade that brought center Brian Williams, Rodney Rogers
and Brent Barry for Antonio McDyess, a big forward with star
potential, he still required the services of a large player after
deciding his sensibilities could stomach no more than one season of
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch's man in the 1996 NBA Draft was the mighty Lorenzen
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers thanks to their history and willingness to spend also
had enough talent to absorb Bryant's early growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, West has made many great decisions while the Clippers were
inspiring bouts of head-scratching. But even West as he freely
admits - has had a few misses. For example, the 1998 draft yielded
three Lakers rookies Tyronn Lue (acquired from Denver in the Nick
Van Exel trade) at 23, Sam Jacobson at 26 and Ruben Patterson at
31.
</P>
<P>
   The 32nd pick was 6-foot-10 high school star Rashard Lewis, who
will become very wealthy if he chooses to leave Seattle this
summer. Lewis can't handle Rasheed Wallace down low, but would have
provided enough juice to help Shaq and Kobe put Portland away by
now.
</P>
<P>
   And with him, the Lakers' future would be ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   But without Baylor and West to help the NBA reach the days of
Abdul-Jabbar, the TV grip of Magic and Bird and global stranglehold
of Jordan, L.A. might have been forced to become a town that gave
track stars more love.
</P>
<P>
   I've freed my mind enough to like track, but still can't dig
it. &QL; 
Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing trade rumor involving Dikembe Mutombo has the
Hawks center going to Toronto for three clubhouse foes of Raptors
coach Butch Carter Doug Christie, Charles Oakley and Antonio Davis.
Their combined salaries will just about equal Mutombo's $14.2
million for next season, but a Hawks source says the team would
prefer clearing cap space for future free-agent raids. Christie's
current contract won't expire for four seasons; Davis is locked up
for three; Oakley is a two-year investment. ... Lakers pre-draft
workout dates have included high school guard DeShawn Stevenson
(Fresno) and junior college post man Ernest Brown (Indian Hills,
Iowa). Brown, at 6-foot-10, 230 pounds, has been defined by one
scout as the post-millennial edition of Houston Rocket Carlos
Rogers. Brown, like Stevenson, also worked out for the Clippers,
who were impressed with his potential, which is far from immediate.
Stevenson, based on testimonials from several personnel smarties,
will be drafted in the middle of round one, if not sooner. ...
</P>
<P>
   According to one former NBA star and longtime coach, Jason
Kapono (UCLA, Artesia High) would be a top five pick with two more
seasons of college ball behind him. But if the early buzz for the
good ol' year 2000 is to be believed, the expert young marksman
will be off the board for the Lakers at 29 and Clippers at 30. ...
The ``wow'' quotient is being floated by witnesses to the exploits
of combo guard Jamal Crawford, a 6-4 freshman from Michigan who
worked out for the Clippers three days ago. The easily mocked
Internet draft experts have excluded the Seattle product from their
first-round grids, but real NBA snoops believe the skinny Crawford
(he goes about 185) will be in the hunt for a lottery spot. One
scout likens the kid to Penny Hardaway; another dropped his name in
the same sentence with that of Eddie Jones. Disparate comparisons,
but possible evidence of Crawford's versatility. ... The agent for
21-year Iakovos Tsakalidis, the lottery suspect who has a long-term
contract with AEK Athens in the Greek League, refers to his client
as ``a freaking monster.'' Most monsters, even those at 7-2, 220,
figure to average more than nine points and seven assists in
Greece. But the shortage of card-carrying centers figures to make
the player formerly known as Tsakalov (in Soviet Georgia) a lottery
lock. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' traveling party for this week's Chicago pre-draft
camp is scheduled to include Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, who will become a
former assistant coach if and when that decision is made by the new
head coach. But the Clips will pay for Kareem's expenses while he
and every other coach with job questions ``networks'' in the Windy
City. Well, Kareem doesn't really network; he's more like
not-so-public access. ... Voting by writers and broadcasters has
placed Jason Kidd on the first team among NBA All-Stars, a list
that excludes Grant Hill, Kobe Bryant and Allen Iverson. That's a
foolish result, but a great marketing opportunity for Nike, which
employs the white-capped Kidd: ``Just Do Or Dye It.'' ... Doc
Rivers and the Orlando Magic may not land San Antonio free-agent
prize Tim Duncan, but they have hired Spurs assistant coach Paul
Pressey. According to a league source, Orlando's shopping list also
may include (sit down for this one) Spurs video coordinator Joe
Prunty. Magic execs must be hoping Prunty can rewind that 1999
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to the Clips: Draft Stromile Swift, hypnotize Sterling,
borrow his checkbook, make an offer Rashard Lewis can't refuse,
point Lamar Odom in the direction of the weight room and then make
other teams worry about matching up with all of them (except
Sterling). Two more things: Sign Jacque Vaughn (another team can't
rip out your hearts until you have at least one) and hire Dennis
Johnson because he's seen defense in person and really wants the
job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
