<SLUG> BC-BBN-FRANCO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCO: METS' MAN IN A PINCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Matt Franco walked into the clubhouse, a
teammate shouted across the room, asking if Franco wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Playing time is something Franco constantly seeks as a reserve
with the New York Mets and he does almost anything to get it. He
has a work ethic that makes him one of the first out to the field
and he can start at almost any position - he even pitched twice
last year - but his ability as a pinch hitter is what gets the
Westlake High graduate into most games.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation as one of the game's most effective pinch hitters
keeps the Mets going to him even though he was batting just .182
entering this weekend's series against Tampa Bay. His five career
pinch-hit home runs rank fourth on the club all-time list. He is in
the top three in Mets career pinch hits and he drew a
major-league-record 20 walks as a pinch hitter in 1999. He tied for
fourth in the majors last year with 14 pinch hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of huge hits in the past off the best
pitchers,'' Mets hitting coach Tom Robson said. ``He's done it
before. You throw someone out there that's never done it before,
it's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him. He's the one that comes up late in the game. He
always has to face the closer or the setup guy and he has to do
something when he comes up. It's definitely not an easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   The slow start doesn't worry Franco, who said he traditionally
does better after the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've started off slow every year pinch hitting,'' he said.
``I'm not really sure why. It's a long year, we'll see where I am
at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Low batting averages can be deceptive and not indicative of a
pinch hitter's value. They are not unusual, according to Robson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start off slow, you usually start pressing more,''
Robson said. ``You go through the whole cycle. It comes back to `I
don't don't care anymore' and then it starts coming together. Guys
that are in the lineup every day can get out of that sooner; guys
like Matt, they might have to wait a week for their next at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately he's been better. He's getting more hits and he sees
the ball better now, but he's had some bad luck. He's hit the ball
hard but right at 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco, 30, played in a career-high 112 games in 1997 but has
never had more than 163 at-bats in a season.
</P>
<P>
   First and third base are Franco's primary positions, but this
year alone he has played three infield positions and in the
outfield. If he's not already in the game, Franco begins to stir
late in the game as he senses an opportunity, coaches said. By the
ninth inning of close games, getting him to sit still on the bench
can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Franco said. ``Obviously I wish I could play
more. I'm sure every bench player would say the same thing, but
that's what I get paid to do. It's my job and I've just gotta make
the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always envisioned being an everyday player, but I'm sure
there's a lot of guys who wouldn't mind being a bench player in the
major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   His upbeat but determined attitude are as encouraging to
Franco's coaches as the left-handed hitter's ability to hit to all
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player, especially him, wants to play every day,''
Robson said. ``That's where the money is and that's where you get
your timing better. He does it once every three days and has to be
ready. He doesn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want that job. You're usually the goat. If you get
three or four hits out of 10 - which is really good - you still
fail seven times. ... It's not an easy job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
