<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MICHAEL-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN GETS A BROTHERLY SUGGESTION: WALK AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Irvin, whose retirement after a dozen seasons with the
Cowboys looms more and more apparent each day, should count his
blessings and walk away from the game while he still can.
</P>
<P>
   That's the advice of his older brother, Willie ``Buck'' Dudley,
a 50-year-old high school principal in Irvin's hometown of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see Michael consider his health first, and I
believe Michael will do that,'' said Dudley, a second-year
principal at Boyd Anderson High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to speak for Michael,'' Dudley emphasized. ``I'm
his older brother, but I'm certainly not speaking for him. But if
Michael can't go out there and be Michael, I don't think he will go
out there again. There's too much pride inside of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always an unpredictability about Michael. But from
what I know, and he was here just last week, I think he's leaning
toward giving it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin returned to Fort Lauderdale purely as a favor to Dudley,
who asked the Cowboys' all-time leading receiver to be the keynote
speaker at the school's May 24 all-sports awards banquet, held at a
hotel and attended by about 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving a small, glass plaque _ a token of the students'
appreciation _ Irvin seemed to cherish the gift as he left the
hotel that night, Dudley noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do feel that Michael knows he can walk away from the
game with his head held sky-high,'' Dudley said. ``He can look back
and reflect on all that he has accomplished, especially coming from
where he came. We grew up on 27th Avenue \Rin Fort Lauderdale\S. We
didn't have much. He truly has been blessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I say he should be able to say `thank you' to the
Good Lord and be happy with that, then go on to the next chapter in
his life. That would be the advice I'd give him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley and Irvin, especially close despite their 16-year
difference in age, didn't have this conversation when they were
together recently because Dudley knows this is Irvin's decision,
even to the point of ``when'' it will be made. The Cowboys have
moved ahead as if Irvin will retire.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old receiver last played on Oct. 10, when he
suffered a spinal contusion and more than 30 minutes of paralysis
after making a routine catch at Philadelphia. The injury occurred
when Irvin landed head-first on the artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching it on TV,'' Dudley recalled. ``Football is
immaterial and highly irrelevant at that point. I felt so helpless.
I thought Michael was paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley began noticing a change in his younger brother in March
when Irvin came to South Florida for his induction into the
University of Miami Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed Michael talking about family more than I ever heard
him before,'' said Dudley, referring to Irvin's wife, Sandi, and
their four children. ``I think Michael can make the transition
because he sees himself as a father now. I see a certain level of
maturity with him that wasn't always there before.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, whose work ethic as a player was legendary, hasn't been
working out, although Dudley described him as ``looking very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley cautioned that Irvin's transition from football won't be
easy, especially when the training camp opens next month and he
won't be in a Cowboys uniform for the first time in 13 summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you leave the camaraderie of the guys and the limelight
and all that ..,'' Dudley said, stopping himself. ``Michael loved
playing the game. He was a throwback. A lot of people don't
understand that. Michael would've played the game for a nickel. He
loved it that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's father, Walter, has been deceased since Michael's senior
year in high school. But the 69-year-old mother of both men, Pearl,
is still the matriarch of a strong family unit that includes 17
children and nearly 50 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very supportive of Michael,'' Dudley said. ``But I think
Michael will be fine, I really do. He's thrilled to have his health
after all he's been through, and he wants to raise those children
and be a father for those two boys \Rboth under 3 years old\S.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley said he is aware that ESPN has expressed an interest in
bringing Irvin aboard as a studio analyst for NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's something that would make Mike happy,'' Dudley
said. ``As everyone knows, he has a gift for gab.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin overcame controversy and scandal during his Cowboys
career, including serving a five-game suspension for violation of
the NFL's substance-abuse policy in 1996. He also helped win three
Super Bowls. He has had a potential Hall of Fame career with a
franchise-record 750 catches for 11,904 yards, ranking him 10th and
ninth in NFL history, respectively], among NFL receivers of
all-time].
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has learned a lot from his problems and has picked
himself up each time,'' Dudley said. ``Even now, he can walk away
from the game with all his faculties. When you think about it,
there's no reason to be unhappy.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
