<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICASCUP-CONNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYYC ENLISTS CONNER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's Cup fans doubtless would agree that the best story
line of any of the last 30 Cups, sailed over 149 years, came in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   That's the year Dennis Conner, the first sailor in history to
lose the Cup for the New York Yacht Club, charged down to
Fremantle, Australia, to win it back.
</P>
<P>
   And win it he did, in the huge style that had come to mark the
Conner circus. Lose it big. Win it back bigger. However, he did not
win it for New York but for San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   So what would be more fitting than Conner, on the 20th
anniversary (sort of) of losing the Cup in that excruciating
light-air Race 7 against Australia II in 1983, winning the
America's Cup back for the New York Yacht Club and sending us all
back to Newport?
</P>
<P>
   A deal agreed to Thursday night in New York could bring that
scenario to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Team Dennis Conner, which left Auckland in February, spinnaker
billowing with credibility after a terrific one-boat challenge
against the big-money boys, is finally back in the NYYC house.
</P>
<P>
   A deal that was talked about in 1985, and again before the last
Cup, has finally come to pass. According to NYYC officials, Conner
will head its syndicate and bring with him much of the sailing team
that came in third among 11 challengers who began racing last
October for the most recent Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important member is Tom Whidden, president of
North Sails, who has been with Conner from the start and uses his
vast experience to be a player/coach on the water. Though he
started late with Stars &AMP; Stripes in the last campaign, Whidden was
largely credited with the tremendous surge that put the boat in the
quarterfinal round and made it a real threat in the semis.
</P>
<P>
   The other high-profile member is Ken Read, Conner's talented
helmsman who did much of the bush-beating in the last few weeks
trying to promote the deal with New York.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to a vote of the NYYC Board of Trustees, the
betting was all over the place. One club member assured me last
weekend, ``There's no way New York is going to get into it again.
They got too badly burned.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate hashed over all the negatives: the huge money,
effort, hassle, exposure, and risk required to put on a Cup
campaign, especially among the lineup of international billionaires
these days. Another consideration was that a Cup campaign may draw
resources away from other waterfront activities.
</P>
<P>
   But one speaker apparently touched a vein of sentiment when she
argued that the America's Cup was the pinnacle of a sport in which
the continuum begins with kids' dinghy programs. ``I think we ought
to go sailing,'' she told the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just delighted with the direction we have taken,'' said
trustee Charles Dana. ``It is a courageous position for each
member, and the decision was nearly unanimous.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many questions at this point. Though the two boats of
Young America _ considered by many the fastest challenger boats
developed for the 2000 race _ were bought by Prada's Patrizio
Bertelli, the intellectual property is still owned by Young
America.
</P>
<P>
   The name of Young America CEO John Marshall has not been floated
by New York, but no possibility is off the table, according to
Dana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we still have a lot of questions in front of us,'' he
said. ``We certainly don't go into this with all the answers. The
only thing that was clear to all of us to a member is that time is
of the essence. We either had to sit it out or we had to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always a lot of reasons not to get in, but we knew
if we were going to get into it, another four weeks would be too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the last two weeks, New Zealand has been making
itself an ever-more attractive target for challengers. The
juggernaut that looked invincible for at least another couple of
Cups began to unravel when big money came a-knocking in Auckland
and proved that even the pristine Kiwis are human.
</P>
<P>
   Skipper Russell Coutts, who vowed that money would never break
up Team New Zealand, was one of the first to fall. A reported $4
million-$5 million offer by a Swiss pharmaceutical company cleared
out Coutts and veteran tactician Brad Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   Then chief designer Laurie Davidson bolted for the North
American syndicate taking shape in Seattle, headed by Craig McCaw.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, who headed the design team that produced the last two
America's Cup winners, apparently was miffed at receiving equal
billing as ``principal designer'' with Clay Oliver, an American
from Annapolis, Md., who worked on the design team.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson was never quite assuaged after the 1995 New Zealand
victory when American designer Doug Peterson got equal billing and
seemingly more publicity than Davidson, who is in his 70s.
</P>
<P>
   So between discord in camp and billionaire dollars stalking the
world's sailing markets looking for talent, it's a fair guess that
Team New Zealand will have lost a bit of its air of invincibility
heading into the fall of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very fluid time for everyone,'' said another New
Zealand player. ``Right now the deals are being made. There's going
to be a lot more of this going on before another month goes past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
