<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-CHAVEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADLY, THERE'S NO QUIT IN CHAVEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They never know when to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Never.
</P>
<P>
   If the rumors are true, not even Rocky Marciano really knew when
to quit, because some will tell you he was planning a comeback
after retiring at 49-0 but died in a plane crash before he could
get back into the ring and embarrass himself the way his idol, Joe
Louis, had against him not so many years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   That being the nature of boxing, it came as no surprise last
week that perhaps Mexico's greatest champion was all but on his
knees begging for the opportunity to get a beating one last time.
</P>
<P>
   That is the state Julio Cesar Chavez found himself in Thursday
in Phoenix as he pleaded with members of the Arizona Boxing
Commission to OK a July 29 ritual assassination by World Boxing
Council junior welterweight champion Kostya Tszyu.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez will turn 38 the night of that fight, and a beating is
not normally what you'd be looking for on such a day, but Chavez
needs the money despite having made millions in his career. So he's
ready to accept what he has to know is coming from the division's
hardest puncher, in exchange for $1.2 million. Gross, by the way,
not net.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Chavez took a beating at the hands of Willy Wise,
a journeyman who would have had a hard day's work as Chavez's
sparring partner _ let alone his opponent _ when Chavez was Chavez.
But Chavez is a shadow of that fighter, one who went before
commission members in Arizona after hearing the Nevada State
Athletic Commission rule him unfit to be competitive against Tszyu.
For a man who fought so many big fights in Las Vegas, that had to
be a terrible indignity, but a time comes in the life of too many
fighters that allows them to accept anything just to battle on for
one more paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Cesar Chavez is now in just such a dangerous place.
</P>
<P>
   The Chavez-Tszyu fight originally was scheduled for July 15 at
the MGM Grand in Las Vegas, but everyone involved understood Chavez
would not be having ``a Grand day'' there. So the fight's promoter,
Don Majeski, bowed to the Nevada Commission's refusal and the MGM
Grand's desire to make the whole thing go away, and he shifted the
mismatch to Phoenix, where Chavez went and embarrassed himself last
week by asking the commissioners, ``Let me go out with dignity and
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chavez's definition of that is going out on his shield, he
could have quit after Oscar De La Hoya gave him two harsh beatings.
But Chavez continued on because he needed the adrenaline rush of a
big fight as much as he needed the money. Or nearly as much. So he
fought on, although not well or often.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a record of 103-4-2, he wants to face the killer
puncher of the 140-pound division, and the WBC made it possible by
awarding him one of the phoniest No. 1 rankings ever. The WBC
officials didn't even try to justify it based on Chavez's recent
performances. They just sort of called it a lifetime achievement
award.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain is a friend of the sport and he opposed
the fight coming to Arizona and told the governor so, but in the
end no one listened. McCain created and then pushed through
Congress the Muhammad Ali Reform Act because he hated to see what
was happening to fighters all too often. How much his bill actually
will do to reform boxing is subject to debate, but if he had done
no more than stop this debacle in the desert, he would have done
more for the sport's image (and Chavez's bridgework) than is done
by most people who spend a lot more of their lives around boxing.
</P>
<P>
   But not even McCain could stop the inevitable. The fight was
approved Friday by the commissioners because Arizona doesn't have
many big fights and they mistakenly believe that this is one
because a name like Chavez is part of it. Problem is, that's all
he's got left now. His name.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't really matter what they did in Arizona, because
Chavez was hell-bent on fighting and eventually he would have found
some place to make his final stand. Officials in some other state
would have approved the fight because they, too, wouldn't know any
better or they would have a memory of a different Chavez or they
simply would be willing to ignore the fact that he weighed 166
pounds a month and a half before he's supposed to fight at 140.
</P>
<P>
   They would have ignored what Nevada could not: The simple fact
that this guy may still be called Julio Cesar Chavez but he's
somebody else now. He's a guy who's going to get a beating on his
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   All that will prove is that Sonny Liston was right when he once
described how it ends for a fighter. It ends with a blues song,
Sonny said, not the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield, whose fight with John Ruiz was postponed
until late August or September because of a rib injury, is another
aging champion probably headed for a bad night before it's over. A
week ago, Holyfield claimed that if he'd beaten Lennox Lewis and
become unified champion, he would have retired; but here he is, so
what does that tell you? ``It has eluded me every time I have come
close to it,'' Holyfield said of being unified champion. ``As long
as that's my goal, there's no reason for me to quit. I am not
quitting until I obtain that goal.'' But few who know him believe
that Holyfield would just walk away after accomplishing that.
Holyfield, like Ray Leonard, Thomas Hearns, Ray Robinson, Louis,
and nearly all the great fighters before them, has the delusion and
he has it bad. He has the delusion that winning championships now
is about destiny, not youth and skill and bravery. He still has the
bravery and enough of the skill to beat most heavyweights and go
the distance twice with Lewis, who truly is the undisputed champion
whether he controls the World Boxing Association belt or not. What
he lacks is the youth and the perspective to see that everyone's
time comes and then it goes. In boxing, either you go with it or
you go out trying. Sadly, it sounds as though Holyfield is making
that bargain with the devil of destruction who rules the boxing
ring. ``If I become undisputed heavyweight champion of the world,
then it would be time to retire,'' he said. ``If the decision would
have gone my way in the second Lewis fight, that would have been it
because I would have obtained my goal. I would have written to the
boxing federations to see if they would have allowed me to travel
around the world as the undisputed heavyweight champion of the
world and put on exhibitions. Having boxed for 30 years, I know if
I'm not working hard enough and not willing to make the sacrifices.
I would know that before I get into the ring. It's not about the
payday. It's about the goals I have set. When you set goals,
everything comes together. I have a plan and I'm in charge of that
plan.'' Sure he is . . . Holyfield had this to say about
International Boxing Federation No. 1 contender David Tua, who is
stalking Lewis: ``Tua is a version of (Mike) Tyson. Tyson has very
quick hands for a big man. Tua also has quick hands but is not as
quick. Tua possesses the same impact and power as Tyson and goes to
the body a lot. Tua fights guys going backward better than I do.
Tua has the right style for me. I will fight anybody that will help
me to reach my goal. I always put myself in a neutral position. If
Tua wins the heavyweight belts, I would love to fight him. If he
doesn't win the belts, I would not like to see him.'' . . .
Holyfield also had an interesting perspective on his stablemate,
Michael Grant, who was destroyed in less than two rounds by Lewis
on April 29. ``I truly believe Michael Grant would beat all of the
young heavyweights,'' Holyfield said. ``It does not mean he's a
zero because he lost to Lewis. It just means he's not better than
the heavyweight champion of the world.'' . . . WBA bantamweight
champion Paulie Ayala was hoping to get a shot at a $600,000 payday
vs. World Boxing Organization featherweight champion Prince Naseem
Hamed, but Hamed's brothers, who manage and promote him, must have
seen Ayala fight. Now he's out, even though the deal was nearly
done and Ayala had agreed to all the terms. A new list of three
more likely victims for a summer fight on HBO has been formed, with
Angel Vasquez, who just fought on ESPN's ``Friday Night Fights,''
among the leading contenders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Maskaev (20-2) put himself back on the periphery of the
heavyweight picture when he coldcocked Derrick Jefferson (22-2),
while Hasim Rahman (33-2) kept his fading title hopes alive by
coming back from an early knockdown to stop World Boxing Union (who
cares?) champion Corrie Sanders with what witnesses describe as
nearly 40 unanswered punches. What was Rahman hitting Sanders with?
Pillows? Turned out Jefferson broke his ankle in his loss to
Maskaev. Give him an A for effort, but more and more it is evident
that Maskaev may be the best of the B division heavyweights . . .
Why do you think Andrew Golota fights Orlin Norris June 16 in Las
Vegas and Frans Botha gets another shot at the heavyweight title
vs. Lewis July 15 in London? Can you spell ``pigmentation''? . . .
As much as the world loves the heavyweights, junior middleweights,
and welterweights at the moment, boxing's most competitive division
could well be the junior lightweight (130-pound) class, with newly
crowned WBA champion Joel Casamayor, WBC champ Floyd Mayweather
Jr., and IBF titleholder Diego Corrales as well as former champion
Roberto Garcia and top challengers like Acelino Freitas and Jesus
Chavez. Casamayor is in line to make his first title defense
against Garcia for one reason: promoter America Presents has
contracts with both men. That means no arguing with anyone else and
a safe conclusion for the promoter no matter the outcome. Garcia's
only loss, by the way, came against Corrales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
