<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHIC     06-03 2066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK SERIOUS ABOUT DISCIPLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Football players are funny but they're not stupid. They get it,
as one old coach around here used to say, although they don't
always like it and often try to ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells took the Patriots from the NFL's cellar to the
Super Bowl in four years but by the end of his reign he was being
called ``too critical,'' ``too tough to get along with,'' ``too
likely to treat grown men like little boys.'' At least that's what
the boys said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll took the Patriots from the Super Bowl to the toilet
bowl, out of the playoffs in three years despite coming into the
job with a reputation for being ``a players' coach,'' whatever that
is. By the end of his reign he was being called ``too soft,'' ``too
nice a guy,'' ``too likely to treat little boys like grown men.''
At least that's what the grown men said.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Bill Belichick, who has already fired one player for
acting like a jerk, cut some high-priced veterans who were past
their prime, and threatened a handful of others for not adhering to
his way of thinking. He is, frankly, more Parcells than Pete,
although perhaps a little more balanced than Parcells (with
emphasis on ``little'').
</P>
<P>
   Yet the same kind of Parcellsian outlook that the Patriots' boys
found so off-putting four years ago they now appear to welcome.
When it was announced that often-wayward defensive back J'Juan
Cherry had been fired after becoming involved in an incident at a
financial district bar _ allegedly throwing a nutty, as well as a
bottle _ not one of his teammates uttered a word of protest. When
Belichick threatened, in understated tones, veteran defensive
tackle Henry Thomas for not reporting for two days of ``voluntary''
workouts, only Thomas pointed out that he thought the word
voluntary meant to Belichick what it meant to Noah Webster, which
is ``done of one's own accord.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Thomas's teammates had further comment. Under Carroll,
they made more further comments than they made further progress
through the playoffs. Three years of not only having your backfield
in motion but also your whole team in reverse has a way of focusing
the mind, and so the hard ways of Bill II are not viewed as harsh
but merely firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys have a serious outlook a whole lot earlier than we did
last year,'' said veteran special teams captain Larry Whigham.
``The message we're getting is it's his way or the highway. By this
time, if you're not doing it his way, you're on the plane leaving
for somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in and of itself, does not guarantee the Patriots any
victories, but it does guarantee their fans one thing _ maximum
focus on winning.
</P>
<P>
   Football can be a difficult and painful undertaking in the best
of circumstances. Often the pain that must be endured is mental,
not physical. It is the mental pain of staying home or staying late
at practice to watch tape of your opponents or to study your own
duties over and over again. It is the mental pain of denying
yourself nights on the town when you would be better served
studying what will be asked of you on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When Willie McGinest stood up last year and blasted some of his
teammates for their apparent zealous search for every party in
town, he was right. The parties come after the victories, not
before them, if you want to party hearty. Or if you want to party
for long in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that a Parcells-coached team or a
Belichick-coached one should resemble a room full of monks. No one
in history went out more than Lawrence Taylor _ often to places
visited only by drug addicts or law enforcement officials _ but
Taylor was a special player, one blessed with skill and courage and
physical abilities that allowed him to abuse his body while also
abusing his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, there are very few players who could get away with
that. Most must work harder at what they do and take better care of
themselves to last for long. The same is true of talented teams,
which the Patriots have been for a while despite a record to the
contrary. The Patriots needed to work harder under Carroll but,
frankly, did not. They had no choice under Parcells because he
would make them miserable if they didn't. And so, in 1996, a team
not as talented as several of its peers but a bit luckier and a lot
more focused went to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With a more liberal approach to discipline and responsibility,
and a string of personnel errors after the departure of Parcells
and Charley Armey, the Patriots went home earlier and earlier each
year despite having arguably a better team in 1997 and one that was
playing against more watered-down competition by 1999. By the end
of last season, that left them with a lame duck head coach who
admitted he was happy just to win his final game so he didn't have
a losing season.
</P>
<P>
   Happy, in other words, to be 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick will not be happy to be 8-8. Nor will he be bending
over backward to understand the motivations and angst of his
players. He will treat them like men, as he did Cherry. Like real
men, meaning just what Whigham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm payin' the cost to be The Boss,'' has replaced ``Come
along and sing our song and join our family, M-I-C-K-E-Y-
M-O-U-S-E'' as the club's theme song.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new day dawning in Foxborough. Cherry found that out
too late. A few more fellows, like the portly Ed Ellis, may be on
the way to learning the same hard lesson.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually the grown men of the Patriots will understand
that Bill I was right most of the time, and Bill II will be, too.
Pro football is a hard-hearted game. It is not won very often by
boys wanting to be treated like men but rather by men willing to
pay the price for glory.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, that price can be high. At times it means a loss of
some dignity, enduring a personal slight for a larger purpose.
Sometimes it even means accepting that Noah Webster's dictionary
and Bill Belichick's don't always agree on the meaning of the word
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it means you are treated the way the game demands.
Pro football is a harsh game with a clear bottom line. Hence the
coaches who win invariably act that way.
</P>
<P>
   If you want understanding, go to a psychiatrist every week. If
you want to win in the NFL, go to work every day. It is clear
already that Belichick will not ask for that _ he will demand it.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets it, maybe this edition of the Patriots will get what
they've wanted all along. Maybe they'll win as often as they think
they should.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, it will be because they've become like a popular
singing group: Boyz II Men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slade to move forward
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see linebacker Chris Slade used far more often as a
pass rusher under Belichick's system than he was under Carroll's.
Belichick believes Slade's talents were misused by the previous
administration, which often had him dropping off into pass
coverages that were not his strong suit . . . Tampa Bay executive
Rich McKay was among the group of NFL coaches and front office
personnel that devised the new code of conduct banning certain
celebrations. One was the controversial throat-slashing gesture.
McKay found the most damning evidence of the influence of such acts
on young people on a presentation video that showed many of the
more outrageous celebrations by NFL players. ``We don't want to go
back to being the No Fun League, but at the end of the tape was a
high school tape in which we saw direct copies of our acts,'' McKay
said. ``It showed me that as a league we've got to be concerned
about these acts.'' Added Vikings coach Dennis Green, who also was
on the committee, ``What we don't like is any act demeaning an
opponent.'' . . . Although no substantive work has been done on
renegotiating the contract of Patriot quarterback Drew Bledsoe,
agent Leigh Steinberg said recently, ``It's a situation where we
feel Bob Kraft has always taken care of Drew Bledsoe since he's
been there, so we're not concerned about that. Drew wants to do
what's best for the team. He understands this is a team sport. The
whole thing is not in his hands. His cap number is so high, it
makes sense.'' With upcoming cap numbers of $8.6 million and $9.3
million, Steinberg is right and Kraft knows it. It is unclear when
the sides will do something about it, but judging by the uncertain
nature of the offensive line in front of Bledsoe, it might be wise
to do something before he gets whacked around a few more times. But
Steinberg insisted, ``Drew likes Boston, and the nature of his
personality is such that he wants to spend his whole career in New
England. No one has a more vested interest in having a better cast
around than Drew does.'' . . . Armey finally signed the five-year
contract he was long ago offered to become the Rams' general
manager. Armey will not be directly involved in working out salary
cap problems _ that will fall to club president Jay Zygmunt _ but
that's no problem, because, as Armey pointed out, ``We have a good
triangle with Jay, myself, and (coach) Mike (Martz). It's a good
working group. We try to make everything we do in personnel a
three-way deal.'' Armey remains a strong believer in the draft even
in this day of free agency because, as we will see in the next few
days, yesterday's free agency bargain is today's released failure.
``If you draft well, you close the free agency hole,'' Armey said.
``The only way you can shrink it is to draft well and with a plan
for your team.'' A case in point was the Rams' decision to let
offensive tackle Fred Miller sign a big contract with the Titans
rather than destroy their salary cap position. They believe young
Ryan Tucker can step in with no dropoff. So when Tucker signed an
offer sheet as a restricted free agent, the Rams matched it at far
less than it would have cost to retain Miller. ``Tucker and Miller
are so close to being the same player we felt with the salary cap
difference we had no decision to make,'' Armey said. ``The key with
the salary cap is not spending the money. Anybody can do that. It's
managing the money, and Jay does that very well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Status quo in St. Louis
</P>
<P>
   Some may wonder why the Rams chose not to trade high-priced
quarterback Trent Green after the emergence of Kurt Warner last
season. With Warner leading the Rams to a Super Bowl victory, he is
in line for a huge raise despite being an exclusive-rights free
agent (meaning, in essence, that he's free to go nowhere but St.
Louis). Yet Armey and Zygmunt agreed that the Rams needed to keep
Green at least through the 2000 season. ``This is a horse we put a
lot of bets on,'' Armey said. ``If we jump the horse now, we
accelerate a lot of those bets. Our best avenue is to keep Trent in
place behind Kurt for now and deal with it next year when there's
less of a salary cap implication.'' . . . Pushing the free agency
period back from Feb. 15 to March 1 next year comes as welcome news
to most teams. Belichick said, ``It's always helpful to have the
most time possible before you have to make these kind of decisions.
This has become such a rushed situation. The season is barely over
and you're right into free agency and the (college scouting)
combine and then right into preparing for the draft. There really
isn't much time for reflection about your team.'' Tennessee general
manager Floyd Reese agreed. ``It's a little extra time to review
what you're going to do,'' Reese said. ``It will keep us from
having to make a decision in the middle of February that we might
regret later. Days are helpful at that time of year, let alone two
weeks. It was particularly difficult if you went deep into the
playoffs.'' . . . Remember this name: Quentin Spotwood. He is an
undrafted free agent who has become the talk of the Dolphins'
minicamps. That doesn't mean he'll do it when the hitting starts,
but so far head coach Dave Wannstedt has been impressed . . . Pity
poor Carolina quarterback Steve Beuerlein. The 35-year-old
Beuerlein had his first Pro Bowl season last year but has paid a
price for it. He has had five operations since January, including a
recent one for a torn abductor tendon. That's on top of hernia
surgery, two scopes (knee and ankle), and a shoulder operation to
shave a bone spur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
