<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3817 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-RICE-BOS &LR;      06-03 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-RICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE STRICTLY A SIDE DISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He was supposed to be the third component. The
Lakers had two-thirds of the millennium's new Big Three in
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant. The sweet-shooting Glen Rice was
a natural for the other spot.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to the Lakers last season, it was considered a fait
accompli. Rice would be the ideal complement to O'Neal's inside
game and Bryant's slashing to the basket. There may be no better
spot-up shooter in the game.
</P>
<P>
   As Portland coach Mike Dunleavy noted, ``You have to admit that
every time Glen Rice is open, I don't care what he has shot or done
before, your heart goes to your throat. Or your stomach. Or
someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Or someplace.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, 33, hasn't made many coaches swallow hard since arriving
here for the now-steep price of Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell. He
didn't find his niche in Kurt Rambis's system and he certainly
hasn't found it in Phil Jackson's triangle offense. In other words,
it hasn't quite worked out the way it was planned.
</P>
<P>
   Rice tends to get lost in the offense and ends up as Just
Another Player on the floor, along with Robert Horry and Rick Fox.
He had the worst scoring season since his rookie year, shot a
career-worst 43 percent from the field, and has had even lower
numbers in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the drama, he will be a free agent this summer. As
they say, timing is everything, and Rice's timing, on and off the
court, is way off. Where once his ubiquitous agent and henchman,
David Falk, was heralding Rice as an obvious ``maximum guy'' (read:
$14 million per year and up), it now looks more and more that Rice
won't get nearly that much and could even end up going elsewhere
for a more Jackson-friendly player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen has been used to playing basketball a certain way and at
a certain level for a number of years,'' Jackson said. ``It's an
old dog/new trick kind of thing. I've encouraged him to find a way
to play in our system.''
</P>
<P>
   That, perhaps, is the most bizarre part of this square peg/round
hole story. Who better than Rice for this system of constant motion
and open shooting? Who better to be Mr. Outside to Shaq's Mr.
Inside?
</P>
<P>
   Rice has kept his cool and his poise, whether it's after a
disappearing act (as in Game 5 of the Portland series) or after a
rare scoring outburst (Game 4).
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that I'm not really doing the type of things I'm
normally doing,'' he said, ``but at the same time, we're winning,
so that's an all-time high right now. But under the circumstances,
when you look at the makeup of this team, the role I have to play
is not to go out and score 30 or 40 points. I have to be there when
I'm needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he wonder why he doesn't get more touches?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a loaded question,'' he said. ``If I answer that, it
could get me in trouble. The thing I have to do is go out there and
be ready when the ball's kicked out. Whatever comes along down the
road, comes along. We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The architect of Jackson's triangle offense, the venerable Tex
Winter, sees it mainly as an inability of Rice to get to where he's
supposed to be. That comes, Winter says, from a career-long custom
of not moving the way the triangle wants you to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggle with this all the time as a coaching staff,''
Winter said. ``We feel we're doing things that should make him a
very effective basketball player. We just haven't gotten the
results. I think he knows where to go. Can he be a weapon? Good
Lord, yes. People know who he is. But it's his inability to play
without the basketball. He hasn't done a lot of that in his career.
Basically, he's a stand-alone, spot-up shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice once was also a stand-alone, spot-up, automatic 20-point
scorer. His career average is 20.2. He entered the season as the
third-most prolific 3-point scorer in NBA history, a one-time
All-NBA second-team selection, and the MVP of the 1997 All-Star
Game. Dunleavy was right about that Glen Rice: A coach swallowed
something when he spotted up on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Rice averaged only 15.9 points a game. He
attempted 404 fewer shots in just two fewer games than in his last
full season in Charlotte. He did score 20 or more points in more
than one-third of the Lakers' games, and LA was 24-4 in those
games.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 16 games of the playoffs, Rice is averaging
only 12.8 points and shooting 41.1 percent. He had one memorable
game, a 21-pointer in Game 4 of the Portland series. He followed
that up with a 1-for-8, 4-point submission in 33 lost minutes in
Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's future could well be tied to the Lakers' performance.
Would they be inclined to break up the team if it won an NBA title?
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable speculation that Los Angeles would embrace
a sign-and-trade deal that might bring them someone like Toni Kukoc
or Charles Oakley. That would entail giving Rice no more than a
modest 15 percent raise over his current $7 million contract. That
would be far less than what he might once have envisioned, but
still enough to keep his family (three children) with food on the
table and a roof over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought his market value had been irreparably
damaged, Rice shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about that,'' he insisted. ``People around the
league know what I can do, so I'm not worried about that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Good shooters tend to find good work in the NBA. It may be that
this is simply an uneven fit, or it may be a case of a player on
the downside of a once-prolific career.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, a championship ring would go a long way toward
making up for the least productive season of Rice's 11-year career.
That should be plenty for most players. Only time will tell whether
it will be so for Rice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
