<HEADER>
A3818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-BBNOTES-VALENTIN-     06-03 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-VALENTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX RUB SALT INTO VALENTIN'S WOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been here before. A top Red Sox player suffers a
devastating, season-ending injury, and is faced with surgery that
is likely to have a drastic impact on his future.
</P>
<P>
   As if that is not enough, he also is faced with censure from the
ball club, which is unhappy at the choices he made about his
medical care.
</P>
<P>
   On the day John Valentin had surgery to repair a ruptured tendon
in his left knee _ an injury that left the 33-year-old third
baseman wondering whether his career was over _ a team spokesman
said the club had not authorized him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, we were back to last summer and the ugliness that
surrounded Tom Gordon's case, when general manager Dan Duquette and
Gordon's agent battled over the pitcher's diagnosis and the choice
of doctor who would perform surgery on his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, according to club spokesman Kevin Shea, was not
willing to discuss Valentin's case. But apparently he was disturbed
at the sequence of events that led to Valentin's decision to have
Dr. David Altchek perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin rejected an offer from team medical director Arthur
Pappas to have the Sox staff perform the surgery. According to
Valentin's agent, Dick Moss, three surgeons were considered:
Altchek, the Mets' orthopedist who performed Valentin's earlier
knee surgery and also reconstructed Bret Saberhagen's shoulder;
James Andrews, the Birmingham, Ala., orthopedist who has operated
on dozens of high-profile athletes; and Richard Steadman, the US
Olympic ski doctor who performed Butch Henry's knee surgery and
also operated on Picabo Street.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin decided to have Altchek do the surgery. Moss said he
informed Pappas of the decision, and according to Moss, the doctors
had a conversation shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' position? It was not as combative as it was in Gordon's
case, when they rejected Andrews in a messy exchange in which
Duquette questioned Andrews's integrity by raising
conflict-of-interest issues (Andrews is Tampa Bay's medical
director) and the players' union and commissioner's office had to
be brought in to broker an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The team apparently had no objection to Altchek. But,
apparently, Duquette felt that Valentin and Moss should have sought
the club's permission before making their decision.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking baseball official said these disputes seem to
arise only with the Red Sox. Last year, to cite another example,
Brian Rose was not reimbursed when he went to see Andrews for a
second opinion on his troublesome elbow.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem a dangerous signal for the Sox to send out,
especially in such a highly charged setting, that players at their
most vulnerable must be wary of clashing with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're doing,'' said Moss, who had not
heard from Duquette or any other Sox official expressing any
concern about an unauthorized action.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette called Valentin on Friday, shortly after the player was
discharged from the New York hospital in which Altchek repaired the
tendon. Moss railed at the idea that the Sox could dictate who
would perform Valentin's procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to the patient, when the doctor is someone listed on
the second-opinion list,'' he said. ``What an outrageous
proposition to suggest otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gauging their position
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who have the 22d pick in Monday's draft of high
school and college players, would love to take Rocco Baldelli, the
outfielder from Bishop Hendricken in Warwick, R.I. But Baldelli,
who was the state's indoor sprint champion and a terrific
volleyball player good enough to be considered for the junior
national team, may not be around when it's the Sox' turn. There are
rumblings that Baldelli, ranked the top high school athlete
available by Baseball America, could go as early as the fourth
pick, which is held by the Royals. The Sox, who love to go local,
also like West Roxbury High pitcher Manny Delcarmen, a righthander
who has registered 94 miles per hour on scouts' radar guns, but
they may have to weigh whether Delcarmen can still be had on the
second round . . . So, you liked what you saw of Johnny Damon, the
swift Royals outfielder who helped lead Kansas City to a series win
over the Sox last week? So do the Yankees. Superscout Gene Michael
was in town last week tracking Damon, who fits the Bombers' need
for another lefthanded bat. Royals GM Herk Robinson says there have
been some inquiries regarding Damon, and the Royals probably would
be willing to part with him, since he wants a five-year deal and
they'll need to free up money to sign slugging right fielder
Jermaine Dye and eventually splendid center fielder Carlos Beltran.
Robinson said there's nothing imminent . . . Drayton McLane, the
Astros owner who justifiably is taking some heat for blowing up
what had been a terrific team in salary-driven deals, acknowledged
in an interview last week that he may have erred. ``Hindsight is
always the best way to judge what you were thinking,'' he told a
Houston paper. ``It's like when you get your test paper back and
when you know the answer but put the wrong one down. There are some
decisions, sure, we would have done differently. Which ones, I'm
not sure.'' Carl Everett has homered in every home series the Sox
have played, but the Astros, of course, weren't the first team to
ship him out. The Yankees, Marlins, and Mets, in that order, also
let him go, the Yankees in the expansion draft. ``The kid was a
late bloomer,'' said one baseball man. ``Can you imagine George
(Steinbrenner) having the patience to wait for him to develop? I
don't think so.'' Everett, who grew up in Tampa, said he has met
Tampa resident Steinbrenner on a couple of occasions. ``I met him
once at a boxing match in Tampa,'' said Everett. ``My agent was
managing the fighter. He introduced us.'' . . . Tampa Bay GM Chuck
LeMar had to wince when he released shortstop Kevin Stocker, who
had made 11 errors in 40 games with the Devil Rays. Stocker came to
the Rays from Philadelphia in an expansion-draft day deal for Bobby
Abreu, who has blossomed into a star for the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Division revision
</P>
<P>
   The Players' Association is on the right track with its proposal
for realignment that would transfer the Astros from the NL Central
to the AL West, creating two 15-team leagues. But it isn't going to
happen. McLane has no intention of leaving the NL, and except for
the expansion owners (Arizona and Tampa Bay), clubs retain veto
power. The notion of having one league with 16 teams, the other
with 14, one with a wild card, one without, is ludicrous, which is
one reason commissioner Bud Selig has delayed a vote on the issue
until next month at the earliest . . . There's a difference between
being petty and being principled, and Major League Baseball's
decision to keep Pete Rose from attending the Reds' 25th
anniversary celebration of the 1975 team Saturday night in
Cincinnati was petty. Rose, such an immense part of the Big Red
Machine, would not have tarnished the event by his presence. He
belonged there as much as he did at last October's ceremony
honoring the All-Century team . . . A Chicago alderman, Edward
Burke, is drawing support for his proposal to limit beer sales at
pro sports events in town. Burke's plan would stipulate that the
Cubs, White Sox, Bulls, Blackhawks, and Bears could sell beer no
earlier than 30 minutes before a game. The baseball teams would be
required to stop pouring in the bottom of the fifth inning, the
others by the start of the third period. This is in response, of
course, to the ugliness in Wrigley Field, when fans brawled with
Dodgers players after a spectator grabbed the cap of Dodgers
catcher Chad Kreuter in the bullpen. The opposition to Burke's
proposal? Not surprisingly, the beer vendors' union has voiced
objections, calling the proposal an overreaction . . . Add the name
of Steve Trachsel, the Devil Rays righty who beat Pedro Martinez,
1-0, last month in Fenway Park, to the list of pitchers who could
be available before the July trading deadline. There isn't a player
on the Devil Rays who can't be had in a deal . . . At the same
time, subtract the name of Sterling Hitchcock, the Padres' lefty
that the Sox were hot after last winter. Hitchcock was due to
undergo Tommy John tendon-transfer surgery in his left elbow, which
will end his season . . . The next month should tell us more about
the Yankees. In the next 24 days, the Bombers play 17 games against
teams that began the weekend in first place: the Braves, Red Sox,
and White Sox . . . Ken Griffey, benched one game last week by Reds
skipper Jack McKeon, was in an 0-for-14 funk and had just 4 hits in
39 at-bats. Junior has only one three-hit game this season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Better Red
</P>
<P>
   Cuban defector Osvaldo Fernandez, who originally signed with the
Giants after a much-publicized lottery in which he was an entry
with Livan Hernandez, was on his way out of baseball after elbow
surgery kept him out of the big leagues since '97. But Gary Hughes,
who was one of Fernandez's first hosts when he came to the States
and rode in Marlins owner Wayne Huizenga's airplane, recommended on
the eve of training camp that the Reds sign him. GM Jim Bowden gave
him a shot, and Fernandez has been a godsend to the Reds' rotation.
The Reds had won all four of his starts since he replaced the
disabled Pete Harnisch, and in his last outing he held the Expos to
two hits in seven innings, retiring the last 19 batters he faced .
. . Damon Buford has 10 home runs _ four more than he hit all of
last season for the Red Sox _ and came into the weekend batting
.292 for the Cubs. But perhaps the biggest surprise: Buford, who
was strictly a platoon player in Jimy Williams's scheme, had played
in each of the Cubs' first 55 games . . . Who says you can't teach
an old Hit Dog new tricks? When Mo Vaughn hit 40 home runs for the
Sox in 1998, two-thirds of them went to either center or left
field. Now that he's no longer taking aim at the deep porches in
right field in Fenway Park, Vaughn has hit 17 of his first 18 home
runs between the right-field foul line and straightaway center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
