<HEADLINE>
VENUS COMING INTO VIEW AT FRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Venus sightings have been infrequent this year. Maybe
too much cloud cover? Not even the Palomar Mountain telescope could
have picked her out vegetating in Florida while her tender,
tendinitis-ized wrists took their time in healing.
</P>
<P>
   Venus was under cover. Under wraps. Under daily icings. And
under a fluffy cloud of nothingness floated by her playful, foxy
papa, Richard Williams, who said she was through with tennis at the
tenderest age of 19. Retired as a teenager? With this world yet to
conquer?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the shining Venus of this planet is Venus Ebone Starr
Williams, who has unretired fast, and descended on Stade Roland
Garros perhaps to save American tennis from ignominy at the French
Open. Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   The guys have wimped out. With Andre Agassi as drum major,
they've paraded like lemmings off a cliff, making one of the worst
showings since Yanks first tested the crimson earth in 1926. That
year, one of two male entries, New Yorker Vinnie Richards, did OK,
a semifinalist to the homeboy champ, Henri Cochet.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's left to the US women to salvage something: Williams, an
easy winner Saturday, plus Monica Seles and Chanda Rubin. With the
preliminaries over, they're in with a spiky crowd. It includes the
favorite, Martina Hingis, who would give several of her Swiss bank
accounts to add the only major jewel missing from her tiara;
three-time champ Arantxa Sanchez Vicario; Mighty Mary Pierce; the
sinewy native heroine, Amelie Mauresmo; ever-troublesome Conchita
Martinez; and the Paraguayan paragon, Rossana De Los Rios.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me?
</P>
<P>
   Has anybody ever seen a female Paraguayan tennis player?
Especially one with a 3-year-old daughter? Not I. Not until
Saturday when 24-year-old Rossana, the only mother on the tour,
cramping in the last set, gamely survived an established gamer,
ninth seed Amanda Coetzer, 7-5, 6-7 (5-7), 6-4, in 2 hours 39
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is the most remarkable story in years. The junior champ
here in 1992, she lost interest and quit for five years, then
``awoke one day last year wanting to play again.'' This was her big
league debut, for which she won enough computer points in the
minors to reach No. 151, and enter the qualifying tournament.
Rossana, ``the sole support'' of her husband, Gustavo Neffa, an
unemployed pro soccer player, and their redheaded child, Anna
Paola, was ``given heart'' by their cheering her from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible dream,'' she said in Spanish. ``I am the
only good woman player ever from Paraguay. I was coached as a
junior by (countryman) Victor Pecci'' _ finalist in the French 21
years ago, loser to Bjorn Borg.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Paris, she felt her chances were as distant as Earth
from the other Venus. Williams has trucked along an easy-street
boulevard to the fourth round, where the female tournament really
commences. And ``that's good,'' said Williams, ``not to be pushed
too much'' (yielding 11 games to three foils). ``I need to just get
out there and find my rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still missing. But with France's Emilie Loit across the
net, a wild card ranked No. 156, and an obvious lover of home
cooking, who needed rhythm to win, 6-2, 6-2? ``I'll need it next''
_ against 11th-seeded Anke Huber _ ``and I think I'll raise the
level of my game. When I have to fight, against the better players
I do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind this was only Williams's seventh start since losing
in the semis of the season-closing Chase Championships to Hingis.
After a superb 1999 (six titles, 61-13, finishing No. 3), she was
sidelined six months. Hibernating, she watched TV, attended classes
at the Art Institute in Fort Lauderdale (``fashion illustration,
math, psychology''), tended her wrists, and left the playing to
little sister Serena, the US Open champ. Serena, obviously
unprepared after her grand Flushing Meadow success, and
experiencing a nothing season, has gone underground herself.
</P>
<P>
   Where is she? ``Home,'' says Venus. Why? ``Injured.'' What's the
injury. ``I don't know. I don't ask her. We don't talk about that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the obfuscating but winsome Williamses. They delight in
keeping us all off-balance, milking ink from whatever they do or
don't do.
</P>
<P>
   Williams concedes, ``I don't have the muscle mass I did. I lost
a little bit. I will get stronger eventually. Give me a couple of
months.''
</P>
<P>
   She has only a couple of days at the moment, but Williams is
such a terrific athlete and so competitive that she may steal a lot
of vital points with her speed, and rediscover the shotmaking
rhythm that Martina Navratilova predicts ``should bring her a major
title before long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe my daddy thought I should retire,'' she said with a
laugh. ``He told me to stay home six more weeks, to make sure of
the wrists. But he also wants Serena and me to make our own
decisions.'' Really? ``And I had to get out here and start playing.
So here I am. I know a lot of people don't believe us when we say
we can't play _ but they can write whatever they want.''
</P>
<P>
   What she wants for them to write most next weekend is that big
sister has caught up with little sister and stashed another major
championship in the family vault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
