<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SIMMONS-     06-03 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SIMMONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMONS OUT TO FIND HIS OPENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ We know Terry Glenn is No. 1. We know Troy Brown
will be the main inside receiver and third-down guy. And right now
it looks as though Tony Simmons is the heir apparent to Shawn
Jefferson as the Patriots' outside speed receiver, barring the
signing of a receiver before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Will this be enough weaponry for Drew Bledsoe and the new
spread-out offense?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a few pieces left to the puzzle,'' said Glenn.
``But I think everyone's clicking so well with Drew right now that
I think it's going to be very productive once we get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, they say, used to run routes like Richard Simmons, but
now he has a clue. What the Patriots don't want their outside
receiver to do is run to spots where Bledsoe isn't expecting him to
be.
</P>
<P>
   It appears Simmons is now on the same page. With his speed and
two years of NFL experience, it's time for him to show it. If he
doesn't, the loss of Jefferson to the Falcons in free agency will
be felt deeply. After all, the thinking in letting Jefferson go was
that Simmons could at least act as a decoy downfield, but he knows
he needs to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm really playing the role of Shawn, but I have
to prove I can play his role or a backup role or whatever role they
see me at right now,'' said Simmons. ``I have two years under my
belt now, so it's about time that I should be a factor in this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what the Patriots are thinking. Last year,
Simmons seemed to be buried on the depth chart behind Glenn,
Jefferson, Brown, and Vincent Brisby. He rarely saw the field in
the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation where they used me as needed,'' said
Simmons. ``I wouldn't call it a wasted year because I learned a
lot. Shawn taught me an awful lot about the game and he also taught
me about things off the field as well. I'll miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is Jefferson's departure that could put Simmons in a
starting role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that losing Shawn helped me,'' said Simmons.
``It's too bad that has to be the way it is, but now it's up to me
to take advantage of the situation. I have a great chance in a
great offense to show I can be a major factor. It's all up to me,
and I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he constantly works on his speed with coach Mike
Morris, who used to compete against Wisconsin track coach Richard
Hackett. Morris and Hackett have conferred on methods to keep
improving Simmons's running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still do all of my track stuff,'' said Simmons, a former
sprinter at Wisconsin who won the Big 10 100-meter title over
Falcons receiver Tim Dwight. ``Speed is my game and I can never
lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons doesn't know whether he's faster now than he was then,
but he knows he's made strides in his route running and feels he
has decent enough hands to make the tough catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The route running is something I have to constantly work on,''
he said. ``I didn't come from a passing offense at Wisconsin, so
that's been the toughest part for me. I still don't run the
crispest routes, but I think I've improved and I'll keep
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, too, has noticed an improvement in Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can make an impact because he's so fast,'' said Glenn.
``It's all a matter of confidence. A young receiver has to develop
that by catching the ball. It would be nice to have a game-breaker
on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be good for Glenn, who will draw the majority of
attention from defenses. For the Patriots' sake, they'd better have
Simmons, Brown, or Brisby getting open when Glenn is in double
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to beat my man,'' said Simmons. ``I have to use my
speed the right way on the field. That's what I'm constantly trying
to do and that's what I have to show the coaches I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
