<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WEST-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS SPENT AFTER CLOSING THE DEFICIT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Their task is still a daunting one. The Portland
Trail Blazers have improbably taken the Western Conference finals
to a seventh game Sunday night. The odds, however, still are
stacked against them.
</P>
<P>
   Given up for dead a week ago _ Lakers coach Phil Jackson said
the Blazers were at ``death's door'' after falling behind, 3-1 _
Portland is very much back in the picture. But the Blazers have to
do what only two teams in NBA history ever have done: win a seventh
game on the road after trailing, 3-1. Their historical inspirations
are the 1968 Celtics (against Philadelphia) and the 1995 Rockets
(against the Suns). Six teams overall have come back from a 3-1
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting,'' said Blazers guard Steve
Smith. ``Once we get there, anything can go. It's not about record
or home-court losses. It's about one game and seeing what we're
made of.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Blazers looked as though they were made of
straw. But two stirring wins have forced Sunday's winner-take-all
affair at Staples Center, where the Blazers already have inflicted
two losses on the Lakers in this series. They're also responsible
for three of the last four LA losses in the building.
</P>
<P>
   But getting there is only half the story. The Lakers, while a
bit wounded, have history on their side. New and old. They have not
lost three straight games all season and they are 9-1 in seventh
games at home, winning their last seven. The only loss came in 1969
to Bill Russell's Celtics. By contrast, Portland has appeared in
just one seventh game in its 23-year playoff history, a home game
in 1990 against the Spurs (Portland won in overtime).
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, ever the mind-game man, started the posturing after
Portland's 103-93 win Friday night by deciding he would have his
team practice Saturday at Staples Center. The Lakers never practice
there; they have their own facility in El Segundo. By taking over
Staples Center, Jackson forced the Trail Blazers to push their
practice time back to late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, any edge apparently is worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not shocked it has come to this,'' Jackson said, although
he would have been stunned a week ago if told it would go the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the rough stuff. Shaquille O'Neal was called for a
flagrant foul on Scottie Pippen in Game 6, although Jackson didn't
agree with the call. Pippen said the Lakers are trying to distract
the Blazers with gratuitous cheap shots and physical play. Rick
Fox, for goodness sakes, has even taken on the role of provocateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are hitting me after the whistle and things of that
nature,'' Pippen said, ``but I know what it is about when you get
this far in the playoffs. I'm sure they're going to try everything,
but it can't work on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about O'Neal's foul, Pippen said, ``He hit me hard. It was
obvious what he was trying to do. He never made any attempt to go
after the ball. So I'm going to see if that's going to cost him
$10,000.'' Pippen was fined $10,000 for an elbow in Game 4. The
Lakers thought he should have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will need a breakout game from Shaq, who was hounded
and harassed in Game 6. He finished with 17 points, his lowest
total ever against Portland in a playoff game. He normally abuses
Arvydas Sabonis, but the Lithuanian leviathan stayed out of foul
trouble Friday night, playing 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because they weren't calling anything,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Lakers' other breadwinner, Kobe Bryant, is
playing on a sore foot. He did score 33 Friday, but 12 came in the
fourth when the Lakers were hoisting treys everywhere. A third
option (Glen Rice, perhaps?) would be nice for LA.
</P>
<P>
   The odds, the venue, and hoop history are all in the Lakers'
favor. Portland has the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we all got what we came for, a Game 7 between two
great teams,'' Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``It all comes
down to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-03 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD GAVE PACERS A WILL AND A WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It really happened.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Walsh is happy to verify the story. ``Basically,'' says
the Indiana Pacers president, ``he told me that if I hired him, he
could get us to the Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He,'' of course, is Larry Bird, and he, of course, has kept
his word. There was an agonizing near-miss in 1998 and there was a
disappointing ending in 1999, but now there is naught but joy and
happiness in a land where basketball runs an extremely close 1-2
with Godliness. Larry Bird is taking his Indiana Pacers to the 2000
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   He has done it his way. Two assistants, and two assistants only.
How about that? ``I don't think you need more than that,'' he said
at the time. ``I'd rather have two assistants and pay them better.
If it turns out I need a third one, I'll get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Two assistants. Dick Harter handles the defense. Rick Carlisle
handles the offense. Harter is old enough to be Bird's father and
then some, and Bird is 43. Carlisle could be a younger brother.
Bird didn't know Harter beyond a handshake and a howdoyado before
hiring him. Harter is the wise old head who has coached at every
level and who knew how to manage a game. Carlisle is the rising
star whippersnapper coach who someday will have his own team to
run. They provide the perfect balance for Bird in every way.
</P>
<P>
   Two assistants! Everybody else has at least three, and Don
Nelson has _ what is it? _ 29? The players loved it from the
beginning, because it told them that Bird could see through all the
b.s. Why do you need all these guys walking around with clipboards?
Two assistants. One for the defense and one for the offense. Two
assistants. What a novel thought.
</P>
<P>
   But Bird always has been about eliminating the clutter. You
should see his house. You leave a glass on a table, and _ bang! _
it's heading for the sink. You leave a newspaper or magazine on the
couch and _ bang! _ it's heading for the trash. Bird is about one
heartbeat shy of being labeled a neat freak.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at the Pacers and saw a team that had the necessary
components to win. ``A playoff team that didn't make the playoffs''
was the assessment of someone at the time, and it was true. There
were injuries in the 1996-97 season, and there was friction between
many of the players and Larry Brown. The players quit on him and he
even admitted that he had grown weary of coaching them. It was
clearly time for a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   But the core was OK. This was a team that had gone to the
Eastern Conference finals in 1994 and 1995, losing seventh games to
New York and Orlando. There was a lot of experience and there was
Reggie Miller, a legitimate marquee player. Oh, there were flaws,
too, and there still are. This team is no threat to the memory of
the '83 76ers, '86 Celtics, '87 Lakers, or '97 Bulls. But the
positives far outweighed the negatives, then and now.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been a smooth ride. In the beginning the
players listened to him because he was Larry Bird. But it doesn't
take long for Larry Legend to become Larry the (expletive) Coach
when things get a bit rocky, and the Pacers aren't exactly the most
stable team from the eyebrows up. As recently as last Wednesday
morning there was trouble in Indiana's paradise, as players went
public with their displeasure over Bird's (and Harter's) chosen
defensive methods.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any moaning now. The Pacers stuck with Bird's
program and won both Games 5 and 6. They will be going to the
Finals and they will be in the hands of a good coach, or coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two games ago, players were questioning what I was doing and
all I told them was, `You've got to believe and you've got to get
up and play harder, and if you lay it on the line, it will work,'
'' Bird says. ``If you are soft, they will take advantage of you.
They stuck with it and believed in it, and when they were down 18
points at Conseco Field House, it worked for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of being down 18 points in the first quarter of Game 5
in your own building, is it possible that said dire circumstance,
or the reaction to it, turned out to be the making of a
championship team? Bird thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back from 18 down the other night, we became a
different team,'' Bird maintains. ``This is the best I've seen us
since I've been here. We're tougher. We fought. We scrapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Toughness and scrappiness have not been words one would attach
to the Pacers, who have been regarded as the quintessentially soft
finesse team, Miller excepted. Rik Smits is hopeless. He is 33 and
isn't going to change. Jalen Rose is a work in progress. Mark
Jackson is limited and nowhere near as good as he thinks he is. But
in the last seven periods of play, the entity known as the Indiana
Pacers has acquired a new collective persona.
</P>
<P>
   It may be as simple as this: They finally have come to
understand, without the shred of a doubt, that their coach knows
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really excited when he was hired,'' recalls Travis Best,
the little point guard out of Springfield, Mass., who was
magnificent in the last two games. ``We needed a change, and I knew
what kind of a warrior he was. It was not about X's and O's. He
doesn't even have to say anything. You just want to play for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry has done a lot for the game, whether playing, coaching,
whatever the case may be. We have respect for him. When he says
something, we go out there and try to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't necessarily saying that last Wednesday morning, but
now they have further reason to believe in the leadership of Larry
Bird. They plugged into his thought process and his will and now
they are going to the NBA Finals. It took three full regular
seasons, two failed playoff tries, and now three playoff series in
the year 2000, but it has come to pass: The Indiana Pacers finally
have become a reflection of their coach. They always had the
talent. Now they have the will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
