<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-NORMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARK LOSING COMPETITIVE BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being Greg Norman is a huge undertaking. He's designing golf
courses in all corners of the world. He's making his own wine. He's
got his own turf. He's involved in the clothing business. A
personal Web site (www.shark.com), naturally, and all the toys _
yacht, helicopter, jet _ need constant attention, too. All the
while, of course, he's attempting to keep tabs with his powerful
political friends on both sides of party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Whew. No wonder there's no time for golf. At least, not a
full-time, full-conscience effort.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, Norman cut short his commitment to the
Memorial Tournament to keep a scheduled meeting with Florida Gov.
Jeb Bush. He withdrew instead of taking part in Monday's final
round of the rain-plagued event, which is certainly his
prerogative. It's a free world, and he needs more money like you
and I need car problems. Not a huge deal, perhaps, but it was
inconsiderate and smacks of elitism that the Tour does not need.
</P>
<P>
   He's 45 and the competitive fires are no longer there _ the ones
that need to burn inside the ropes, that is. Business endeavors?
He's got plenty of passion for those, and good luck to him. He's
fabulously rich, and unlike his on-course experience, which has
included his share of hard luck, everything he touches in the
business world turns to gold.
</P>
<P>
   During a pre-Memorial press conference, he said that golf
remains his No. 1 priority besides his family, but you would have a
hard time finding people who believe that. Then, when he walks away
rather than finish a tournament he had committed to, it looks
lousy.
</P>
<P>
   Norman has done this before, at the Tour Championship in 1996
when that prestigious event was extended until Monday. Everyone
else in the field stuck around to play, even those 15 shots behind,
but Norman couldn't be bothered.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour is one of the most grueling ways to make a living,
a way of life that is far different from what the public perceives
it to be. The travel is tough, the hours are long, the mental
strain enormous. You have a couple dozen guys who truly stand out _
Tiger Woods, Davis Love, Phil Mickelson, Colin Montgomerie, David
Duval _ and could hop out of bed at 2 a.m. and place top 10
anywhere. But the majority of players grind away week in and week
out, always trying to make a cut, constantly concerned about exempt
status. To these players, berths in tournaments are like gold, and
most of them are genuinely grateful for the chance to be on the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes Norman's action even more disturbing. When
you enter a tournament, you should do so with a serious commitment.
There is a serious financial stake, and the fans deserve nothing
but a total effort by the players.
</P>
<P>
   If it rains, you get wet. If it is cold, you freeze. If the
course is tough, you shoot a high number. If someone burns it up,
you don't win. Low 70 and ties get into weekend play, so you know
there's a chance you'll go home empty-handed. If serious weather
kicks in, you know Monday finishes are part of the landscape, if
that's what it means to get in 72 holes.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Doug Ford at the Masters, shooting 89 and going on
his merry way. Ford's lifetime exemption _ a reward for having won
the Masters _ does not get passed on to someone else if he chooses
not to play.
</P>
<P>
   Not so at the Memorial. The people who run that event are set on
a field of 105, so if Norman were to turn down his spot (which
comes via his status as a former champion), it would go to someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   If he wants to play, wonderful. He has earned the right and
there are plenty of people who still want to see him beneath that
shark hat. But if he can't respectfully commit 100 percent to the
event, please step aside, and let someone else into the field.
</P>
<P>
   Monday and Tuesday, at 12 sites, hundreds of golfers ranging in
stature from unheralded amateur to former Masters champion (Craig
Stadler) will agonize over shots for 36 holes in an effort to
secure a spot in the US Open at Pebble Beach. Each of them has
committed to this experience knowing the weather could turn nasty,
the rough will be tough, the greens rock-hard, the challenge
fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and they know that if there's a tie at the end of 72 holes,
the playoff is Monday. Norman, who has a free pass via a generous
exemption from the USGA, may want to factor that into his business
plans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping good company
</P>
<P>
   Olin Browne is one of those Tour guys who takes his job
seriously, and he'll be grinding away Monday in hopes of making it
into the US Open. Browne will be at Woodmont CC in Rockville, Md.,
which could be considered a PGA Tour stop with the caliber of
players involved: Robert Allenby, Billy Andrade, Woody Austin, Rich
Beem, Jay Don Blake, Greg Chalmers, Brandel Chamblee, Stewart Cink,
John Cook, Glen Day, Chris DiMarco, Brad Faxon, Harrison Frazar,
David Frost, Bill Glasson, Scott Gump, Jay Haas, Gabriel Hjerstedt,
Scott Hoch, Mike Hulbert, Jonathan Kaye, Shigeki Maruyama, Scott
McCarron, Joey Sindelar, Kirk Triplett, Scott Verplank, and Kevin
Wentworth. Browne, 40, is a two-time PGA Tour winner and one of the
most forthright players you'll meet out there. He spent a year at
The Country Club and learned a lot of the game's finer points from
former head pro Don Callahan. And Browne has quietly turned into a
solid player _ 100th on the money list in 1996, but 94th, 47th, and
51st since. Currently, he is 97th with $237,658 . . . James
Driscoll, the University of Virginia senior from Chestnut Hill, was
unable to defend his title at this weekend's Hornblower Memorial at
Plymouth CC, competing instead in the NCAA Championship at Auburn
University in Alabama. Driscoll also will be at Woodmont, trying to
earn a ticket to Pebble Beach, where he fared so well in the US
Amateur last summer. Jason Caron, the PGA Tour rookie from South
Yarmouth, heads a list of New Englanders trying to get past the
sectional. Others include: Billy Downes of Hampden; Michael Flynn,
the Rochester, N.H., native who went to Texas Christian University;
P.H. Horgan of Newport; Ron Philo Jr. from the CC of Vermont; Brett
Quigley of Barrington, R.I.; BUY.com Tour regulars Kevin Johnson of
Pembroke, Geoff Sisk of Marshfield, and Fran Quinn of Northborough;
Andy Morse of Needham and Peter Morgan of Harwich, those ultimate
road-travelers; and Mark Brown, the Milton native and former
assistant pro at Presidents GC in Quincy who now works at Tam
O'Shanter on Long Island . . . Proving that there is a strong
appeal to a US Open at Pebble Beach, here are some blasts from the
past who are going into competition at sectional qualifying: Ben
Crenshaw, Mark McCumber, Mac O'Grady, Mike Nicolette, Jack Renner,
Gary Hallberg, D.A. Weibring, Andy Bean, Bob Gilder, Wayne Grady,
Richard Zokol, Fuzzy Zoeller, Peter Jacobsen, and Mike Donald, who
would be working on the last ride in a 10-year exemption had he not
fallen down at Medinah and lost to Hale Irwin in 1990 . . . Stadler
and son Kevin are in the same qualifier in Cincinnati; Weibring and
son Matt are at different locales; and Johnny Miller will be in the
gallery (or perhaps caddying) for son Andy, who will tee it up at
Lake Merced in Daly City, Calif. Think Johnny would get up for his
NBC duties at Pebble Beach (his favorite course) if his son made it
in? . . . Per-Ulrik Johansson is taking time out from his European
Tour duties to try to qualify, while Chan Song Wongluekiet _ whose
13-year-old twin sisters Aree and Naree have gotten quite a bit of
publicity this year by playing in LPGA Tour events _ is trying to
make it in at age 17 . . . His father has an exemption, but Gary
Nicklaus will try to qualify at Bear Lakes in West Palm Beach,
where the field also includes David O'Kelly, the former head pro at
Willowbend . . . The Kuehne Brothers _ Hank (the pro) and Trip (the
amateur) are at the same site in Houston . . . And, yes, that is
former major league pitcher Shane Rawley entered at Settindown
Creek CC in Atlanta . . . As for New Zealand's Michael Campbell, he
avoided the qualifying nightmare by accepting a last-minute special
exemption from the USGA, joining Norman, Jack Nicklaus, Tom Watson,
Curtis Strange, and Aaron Baddeley on the VIP list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reading the fine print
</P>
<P>
   Here are the names: Valerie Van Ryckeghem, Raquel Carriedo,
Sandrine Mendiburu, Sofia Gronberg, Samantha Head, Elisabeth
Esterl, Caroline Hall, Lora Fairclough, and Marina Arruti. Now, who
are they? They are currently in the top 15 in Solheim Cup points
standings, and if you have heard of any of them, then you are a
serious reader of golf agate in the weekly publications. These
women play strictly in Europe, where the women's pro tour is not
nearly as extensive as the LPGA Tour, and truth be told perhaps
just one or two of these women will make the team. Laura Davies and
Trish Johnson, both of whom are locks, are 1-2 in the standings,
and European captain Dale Reid is committed to taking just the
first seven. After that she gets five wild-card picks . . . Before
shooting 69 in the third round of last week's Corning Classic,
Grace Park had gone 17 rounds without breaking 70. This from the
1998 US Women's Amateur champ who was widely expected to have a
banner rookie season on the LPGA Tour. It still could happen,
despite her slow start. Park shot 66 to open this week's Kathy
Ireland Greens.com Classic in Murrells Inlet, S.C., and if that
signals a turnaround, it would be wonderful for the Tour. Park is a
brilliant talent who could pump life into the circuit . . . John
Daly continues to be a lightning rod for bad luck. He was 4 over
playing the 17th hole in the second round of the Memorial
Tournament when his approach hit playing partner Mark Brooks's ball
on the green. Brooks got to place his ball in its original spot,
while Daly had to play from where his ball stopped, which was about
50 feet from the pin. Had it not struck Brooks's ball, no doubt
Daly's shot would have drawn back and been within 15-20 feet. Daly
made par at 17, then double-bogeyed the 18th, apparently thinking
that 4 over was no good. Alas, 4 over just got in under the cut . .
. There was a pretty good breeze as Alisdair Watt stood off to the
18th green at Waverly Oaks GC in Plymouth, though truthfully he
didn't pay much attention. And why should he? He polished his game
at Royal Troon in his native Scotland, where it wasn't out of the
ordinary for him to go out for a match with Montgomerie. Watt, 33,
the assistant pro at Farm Neck on Martha's Vineyard, shared
medalist honors with a 69 in a Mass. Open qualifier at the course
in Plymouth, and revealed afterward that a certain golf enthusiast
from Washington, D.C., was a student of his on the Vineyard a
couple of summers ago. Did he improve President Clinton's game?
Such a silly question to ask a professional instructor. ``Of course
I did,'' said Watt, smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
