<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-RICHARD-     06-03 1990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-RICHARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AU REVOIR TO THE ROCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those of us too young to have seen Maurice Richard play
(virtually everyone born after, say, 1955), his greatness has been
documented and understood through word and photograph since his
retirement from the NHL in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Like almost every picture of the inimitable Rocket, the stories
often focused on his haunting dark green eyes. He had steely
vision, tiny licks of flame perpetually dancing in his pupils,
spreading into a raging fire as he approached the net.
</P>
<P>
   He was, by all accounts, fierce and unyielding, a man who
internalized doubts others shared about his abilities early in his
career _ when he was thin of frame and often injured _ and
transformed that doubt into an obsessive rage to succeed. The
Rocket was laid to rest last week, carried from the Notre Dame
Basilica in Montreal with a blanket of yellow roses, a touch of
beauty and delicateness, spread over his mahogany casket. He died
of abdominal cancer at age 78, more than 40 years after scoring his
final goal for the glorified Canadiens, and after having spent most
of his life being a provincial deity.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins Hall of Famer Milt Schmidt was tending to flowers last
week, taking advantage of a gorgeous late-spring day to plant
geraniums and impatiens around his home in suburban Boston. In the
10-plus seasons they opposed each other, Schmidt recalled, he was
never exposed to what he called Richard's vicious side.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was that one time he broke my nose,'' said the
82-year-old Schmidt. ``We were both racing for the puck, as I
recall, and he came up with his arms and elbows. Of course, I've
got a lot of nose to hit, and he caught me. When the doctor told me
it was broken, I said, `OK, fine, Doc, but not a word to anyone.' I
just didn't want (Richard) to have the satisfaction that he'd
broken it.''
</P>
<P>
   When they next met, Schmidt spotted Richard cutting cross-ice in
a switch and made certain he was crissing when the Rocket was
crossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I got him,'' said Schmidt. ``I got him with a good,
legitimate knee and elbow _ if you could call that legitimate. He
turned right around on me and said, `Why you do that?' And I said,
`Well, Maurice, you were turning one way, and I turned that way,
and . . .' Then he said again, `Why you do that?' I think then I
said, `Look, forget it, let's just play.' And that was it. We got
along fine, really; I respected him and he respected me.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard's strength was in his legs and arms. He was a fast
skater, but the rink always has been flooded with the fleet.
Richard, though, made a habit of using that speed to gain a slight
positioning edge and then he would almost straight-arm past
opposing forwards or defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would ward you off with his arms,'' said Schmidt. ``Those
were his strengths, his legs and his arms. But if you're asking
what made him such a special talent, well, you had to have
something else to score all the goals (544) he did. He just had a
fantastic way of finding the opening in a net. He always had his
head up, which you're supposed to do, of course, when you've got
the puck, and he'd see exactly where he wanted to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture of Richard that may be best remembered, and perhaps
cursed, by Boston fans came in the moments after what many consider
his greatest goal. It was April 8, 1952, Game 7 of the Stanley Cup
semifinals against the Bruins, at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Knocked unconscious early in the action, the woozy Richard spent
most of the game in the dressing room before returning to the bench
in the third period, his vision still too impaired for him to read
the scoreboard. Stories of the day had him asking Elmer Lach, one
of his brothers on the fabled Punch Line with Toe Blake, what the
score was and how much time remained as he sat on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   With about four minutes to go, Richard hurdled the boards,
gained possession of the puck, charged in, and beat Bruins goalie
Sugar Jim Henry with the winner. The lasting picture is that of a
bloodied, seemingly dazed Richard exchanging a postgame handshake
with Henry, whose own eyes were blackened from a broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``That beautiful bastard,'' wrote Elmer Ferguson of the Montreal
Herald, ``scored semi-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Help wanted
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant GM Mike O'Connell said that he and Peter
Laviolette, head coach in Providence (AHL) the last two years,
talked 7-10 days ago about Laviolette filling the assistant
coaching job left open in Boston by Ken Baumgartner. ``And we'll
talk again,'' said O'Connell. ``Peter's expressed an interest in
doing it, and I think he's talked to Pat Burns about it, too. We'll
see where it goes.'' O'Connell said the Bruins also might keep a
goaltending consultant on staff next year, a position not filled
since the early 1990s when ex-Harvard netminder Joe Bertagna helped
players such as Reggie Lemelin and Andy Moog stay in tune. ``Our
goalies are open to the idea,'' said O'Connell. ``It would be
someone to help them with the technical part of it, work with
videos, talk with them.'' Gerry Cheevers wouldn't be among the
candidates for the job, said O'Connell, because the club values his
efforts in the pro scouting department . . . Everyone expects that
Jacques Lemaire will be the Minnesota Wild's head coach, provided
he and GM Doug Risebrough can work out the money. Had Risebrough
remained in Edmonton, where he was Glen Sather's right-hand man, he
likely would be the Oiler GM now that Sather has signed on as the
Rangers' Mr. Fix-It (for a reported $15 million over five years) .
. . If Kevin Lowe decides to join Sather and be the Rangers' head
coach (John Muckler was canned in March), then ex-Bruin Craig
MacTavish undoubtedly would be promoted as the Oilers' new head
coach. It could happen anyway if Lowe stays put and assumes
Sather's GM duties . . . Sather said it was the Ray Bourque trade
in March that underscored to him that it was time to leave
Edmonton. When he saw Boston boss Harry Sinden talking trade during
the GM meetings prior to the deadline, it was frustrating for
Sather to realize there was no way his skimpy Oiler budget allowed
him to join the bidding _ ultimately won by the Avalanche, one of
the Oilers' top rivals. Sather: ``I knew the deal was coming down.
You're sitting there knowing something was going to happen, and
there was absolutely zero you could do about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plots thicken
</P>
<P>
   Not sure if Thomas Harris is a true hockey fan, but the author
of ``The Silence of the Lambs'' caught my attention in that story
when his central character, heinous murderer Hannibal Lecter, wore
a restraining mask that had to be stolen from a goalie's equipment
bag. And now, in the gripping sequel, ``Hannibal,'' Lecter flees
Europe by joining a tour group on a flight to Detroit. To make sure
that Lecter mixes into the group, Harris has him wearing warmups
that ``bear the insignia of the Toronto Maple Leafs.'' I wouldn't
want to be the guy who belted out ``Game On'' with the not-so-good
Dr. Lecter within earshot . . . The rumor mill has Tampa Bay
shipping both Vincent Lecavalier and netminder Dan Cloutier to
Ottawa for the rights to Alexei Yashin. ``Not going to happen,''
said Bolts GM Rick Dudley . . . Ex-Bruin Wayne Cashman, whose stint
as head coach in Philadelphia was mercifully short (61 games,
'97-98), last week requested permission from the Flyers to talk to
Tampa Bay about moving back there as an assistant coach. Cash held
that job for four seasons before spending a year with San Jose
prior to his arrival in Philly . . . The Islanders profited by the
luck of the draw and copped the No. 1 pick in the June draft,
rocketing up from the No. 5 spot in the lottery last week. ``We're
doing a jig,'' said ex-Bruins defenseman Mike Milbury. It could
make for some interesting orchestrations on draft day, because of
ex-BU netminder Rick DiPietro. The Islanders already have their
franchise netminder in Roberto Luongo. If someone with a lower pick
truly covets DiPietro _ such as, say, Chicago with picks No. 10 and
11 _ they could offer to swap picks and toss in a roster player for
the right to go first. The Islanders held only an 8 percent chance
of winning the lottery . . . Another ex-Bruin, Al Sims, is among
the candidates to fill the assistant coaching job left vacant in
Toronto with the departure of Alpo Suhonen to Chicago. Sims coached
the last two years in Milwaukee, the Nashville Predators' top
affiliate . . . Kirk Muller, once a Montreal captain, wore No. 9
once during an All-Star game. Richard, who wore that No. 9 to its
retirement in Montreal, made a point of quizzing Muller about why
he wore it. ``And he told me, `You're a Canadien, don't make a
habit of it,' '' said Muller. The Rocket wasn't kidding . . .
Woonsocket's Brian Boucher is in for some kind of pay raise after
blossoming into the Flyers' No. 1 backstop. He earned $450,000 last
season, while John Vanbiesbrouck, dumped from the top job, was on
the books at $3.75 million . . . Jean Beliveau, now battling cancer
himself, was among the Rocket's ex-Canadien pallbearers. The
others: Henri ``Pocket Rocket'' Richard, Dickie Moore, Butch
Bouchard, and Dollard St. Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cup is his baby
</P>
<P>
   ESPN once more has delivered a series of clever spots to promote
hockey, focusing this spring on where individual members of the
Stars took the Stanley Cup after winning it last spring. When
Schmidt last held the Cup, as Bruins general manager in 1972, the
league had not yet begun the practice of having the winners carry
it hither and yon. When Schmidt brought it home following the
victory banquet, he felt a degree of anxiety over being the
trophy's keeper. ``They didn't have guards carrying it around like
today,'' said Schmidt. ``As the manager, I was responsible.'' Once
home, Schmidt scouted around for a suitably safe resting spot,
ultimately deciding to tuck it into his daughter's bed, covering it
over with a blanket. ``Nancy was small then,'' said Schmidt, ``she
found somewhere else to sleep.'' Schmidt's name is engraved in the
Cup four times with the Bruins, twice as a player and twice as a
member of management. ``I'm proud of that,'' he said, ``to be
included with so many players past, present, and future. There are
so many great players who don't get their names on it _ like Ray
Bourque again this year. Same thing happened to Bill Gadsby _ such
a great, great defenseman, but it just never happened for him.'' .
. . The Leafs were denied a request for a special exemption for
Bryan Berard so that they would not have to protect him in the
expansion draft later this month. Berard is still recovering from
an eye injury and may not play again, which would have made the
exemption the right thing to do. The Flyers, likewise, don't know
whether Eric Lindros, after suffering multiple concussions, will be
able to play again. Shouldn't they, too, be able to claim that
L'Enfant Terrible is a special situation? Meanwhile, Flyers
chairman Ed Snider said last week that the club expects to offer
Lindros the qualifying $8.5 million it takes to retain his rights,
rather than simply allow him to depart as an unrestricted free
agent . . . Wayne Gretzky _ that's owner Wayne Gretzky _ has this
to look forward to in Phoenix. The troika of Keith Tkachuk, Jeremy
Roenick, and Teppo Numminen will see their collective salaries jump
from $7.25 million to $17.5 million. No. 99 will find out that it's
harder to score from the owner's box than it has ever been . . .
Bruins training camp is about 90 days away _ enough time for the
good folks in Wilmington to finish the steel cage that will house
tough guy Martin Grenier, who has amassed 983 penalty minutes over
the last three years in the Quebec League. Are you ready to
rummmmmbllllle?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
