<HEADER>
A3827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-LAKERS-B     06-03 1779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-LAKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS PRIME TIME BUT NOT ALL-TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do we make of the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   Well, after watching them for a week, it's easy to see why Phil
Jackson should have been Coach of the Year. They may be the best of
this NBA, but they also may be the worst 67-15 team in history.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles became the eighth team to win 67 or more games in a
season. Four of those teams accomplished the feat in the last 10
years, and of the previous seven, six won NBA championships, the
1972-73 Celtics being the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the six champions, only the 1991-92 Chicago Bulls had
as hard a time in the postseason as these Lakers are having.
Although they may have looked unbeatable in the regular season, the
Lakers appear to be anything but in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: They needed five games to put away the eighth-seeded
team in the West, the Sacramento Kings. None of the other post-1984
champions (when the playoffs were expanded to 16 teams) had such a
problem. In fact, all three Chicago teams (1991-92, 1995-96,
1996-97) as well as the 1985-86 Celtics swept their first-round
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The Lakers already have lost two in a row at home, and
we haven't even started the NBA Finals. The 1995-96 Bulls and the
1985-86 Celtics went undefeated at home in the postseason (10-0).
The 1996-97 Bulls lost once at home. Only the 1991-92 Bulls were
worse at home, losing thrice, once each in the second, third, and
final rounds.
</P>
<P>
   This is happening in a league that has never been more diluted.
In the 1980s, you needed three Hall of Famers to win a title. Now
you need two dominant players. The Lakers are getting it done with
two starters who should be retired (Ron Harper, A.C. Green) and
with a reserve who basically was retired (Brian Shaw). We won't
even get into John Salley. Yes, Rick Fox, Robert Horry, and Derek
Fisher were starters on a 61-win team, but that, too, speaks
volumes about the lack of depth in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are very good _ for their time. It's a 29-team league
with the players coming in at a younger age and the ESPN-ization of
the game getting stronger with each episode of ``SportsCenter.''
It's a league that can create a star (Vince Carter) simply because
he dunks spectacularly. Never mind that he has never won a playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson took the LA job knowing exactly what the situation was:
He had a team with the dominant talent in the game (Shaquille
O'Neal) who, like Michael Jordan a decade earlier, was frustrated
by an inability to win. He knew which buttons to push and he
succeeded. You look at his roster and you have to marvel at the job
he did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't call him coach
</P>
<P>
   It has been months since Danny Ainge left the Phoenix Suns
coaching job, and he says he is still quite happy with his
decision. Ainge interviewed recently for the since-filled (Rod
Thorn) job of director of basketball operations for the Nets. But,
he said, it was more of a pro forma interview; figures were not
discussed, nor were the parameters of control. ``I was in New
York,'' said Ainge. ``I figured I couldn't lose anything by going
for the interview.'' As for coaching, he said, ``I've had phone
calls from three different teams asking me if I was interested in
coaching. I turned them all down. I have no interest in coaching,
none whatsoever. I can't stress that enough. It's the last thing I
want to do right now. I have turned down every inquiry and will
continue to do so.'' Ainge said he still has a standing offer from
Suns owner Jerry Colangelo to rejoin the franchise in some
capacity, but he is quite happy with his TNT gig and doesn't want
to become another scholarship guy with the Suns. They have a few .
. . Thorn, meanwhile, steps back into the team executive role for
the first time in more than 15 years. He is one of the league's
true good guys, so we know he won't take umbrage if we at least
note his drafting record as the Bulls' general manager. Yes, he did
select Jordan. That was a no-brainer; MJ fell into his lap. That
would be like giving Rick Pitino credit for drafting Paul Pierce.
But he also drafted ``San'' Quintin Dailey (after his assault
problems), Ronnie Lester (after he blew out his knee), and such
other luminaries as Mitch Wiggins, Sidney Green, and Ennis Whatley.
He also fired Jerry Sloan, one of the best coaches the Bulls ever
had. Thorn was toast once Jerry Reinsdorf purchased the team in
1985. But, as we noted, he's such a good guy that he won't care
and, clearly, neither do the Nets. And Jersey had some company over
the years. Thorn also turned down an overture from Charlotte to
become its rainmaker . . . One theory as to why Larry Bird doesn't
want to stay in Indiana: He wants to run the whole show. Although
he's been given that option, Bird may still feel that he wants to
be the sole decision-maker and that might not be the case as long
as Donnie Walsh is still there and the owners are actively
involved. Bird may simply go back to Naples, Fla., and wait to see
whether his investor group can persuade Paul Gaston to sell the
Celtics . . . Jerry Stackhouse went on ESPN Friday and said he
thought Grant Hill's chances of returning to Detroit were 70-30. At
the same time, Stackhouse said if Hill did bolt Motown, the Pistons
might be able to find two players who would make them better while
Stackhouse himself would become the man. ``It would be a great
opportunity for myself,'' he told Gary Miller on ``Up Close.''
``But we need more than one player, more than two players.'' When
Miller mentioned Glenn Robinson as a possibility, Stackhouse's eyes
lit up. ``I'd love to play with the Big Dog. Any time of the day,''
he said. When the Pistons were bounced from the playoffs,
Stackhouse said he thought the team needed a true center and a
point guard. Asked how incumbent point guard Lindsey Hunter might
have taken those remarks, Stackhouse did not back off. ``Lindsey's
more of a shooter who looks to score,'' Stackhouse said. ``We need
more of a distributor, someone to get us the ball.'' As for the
next Pistons coach, Stackhouse gave his blessing to George Irvine:
``We already have a rapport with him.'' . . . Speaking of coaches,
the Grizzlies settled on Sidney Lowe, who must have had a great
interview because his resume isn't exactly dazzling. In Lowe's
defense, he coached a bad (as in pre-Garnett) Timberwolves team (he
replaced the fired Jimmy Rodgers) and was 33-102 over 1 1/2 years.
He is a Timberwolf original, starting as a player for the late Bill
Musselman and then becoming a broadcaster and an assistant coach in
two separate stints, including last season under Flip Saunders. He
also was an assistant under Mike Fratello for five years in
Cleveland. But is he an improvement over the dismissed Lionel
Hollins, who at least had the support of many of the key Vancouver
players? Don't be surprised if Lowe lasts a couple years and
basketball boss Dick Versace moves into the coaching position
when/if the team improves. By that time, it also could be headed to
any number of new locales, none of them in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hornets stirring
</P>
<P>
   The clock is ticking in Charlotte and it's not at the pace that
the Hornets want. Ray Wooldridge, the executive trying to get a new
arena built, had hoped to have some idea of his chances by the end
of this month. But the people who make those decisions in Charlotte
told him he'd be lucky to get anything by the end of July, or one
month into free agency. With Eddie Jones considering a move, that
is not good news for the Hornets because it will be hard to
guarantee they won't be moving if the arena falls through. Teams
can start courting free agents as of July 1 . . . The Magic, who
have three lottery picks, reportedly have offered two of them (Nos.
5 and 10) to the Nets for the first pick. Maybe that's why Orlando
coach Doc Rivers and possible No. 1 pick Kenyon Martin were seen
together at an Orlando Miracle WNBA game this past week. But the
Nets may want to hold on to the pick if for no other reason than to
see what it will fetch. It's also a valuable chip for a team
looking to rebound with a new coach and management team . . .
Speaking of the Nets, you will hear Lenny Wilkens's name mentioned
there because of his longstanding relationship with Thorn. The two
go back more than 30 years and Thorn once was an assistant under
Wilkens in Seattle in the early 1970s. That happens also to be the
decade in which Wilkens last won a meaningful playoff series . . .
You have to wonder why the Celtics, as well as a lot of other
teams, are so ridiculously covert about whom they bring in for
predraft workouts. To divulge the identity of these lads might
actually give them some publicity at a time when they are off the
map. The idea that another team might ``find out'' whom they're
working out is ludicrous given that the first two questions a
player is asked are almost always, ``Where have you been?'' and
``Where are you going next?'' . . . Let me get this straight. John
MacLeod leaves the bench in Phoenix as an assistant to ``make
himself available'' as a head coach somewhere else? Seems to me he
could still have done that and stay where he was. More likely,
there probably was the realization on MacLeod's part that he
wouldn't be back as an assistant to Scott Skiles . . . Fox was the
subject of a Page 1 story this past week in the Wall Street
Journal. The piece focused on the extracurricular pursuits of the
Lakers, ranging from Fox's movie career to Shaq's forgettable
cinema history to Kobe Bryant's upcoming hip-hop CD. According to
the story, the current Laker roster has accumulated 17 film
credits, 50 television appearances, and four CDs. In addition,
Salley has hosted a show on the Fox Family Channel (that,
apparently, is not an oxymoron) and produced a film in which Jerry
Springer will appear . . . Just a name to think about as the NBA
draft approaches: Olumide Oyedji. He's a 6-foot-9-inch native of
Nigeria who played for Dirk Nowitzki's old team this past season in
Germany. He is an ath-a-lete. He was MVP of the German All-Star
Game and also won the slam dunk title. At 19, he's a work in
progress, but he has, as scouts love to say, a big upside . . .
Hubert Davis has opted out of his contract, which, given his
playing time in Dallas, might seem ill-advised. But coach-for-life
Don Nelson said he not only wants Davis back, but that he
encouraged him to opt out because he felt Davis was underpaid.
That, apparently, no longer is a problem with moneybags Mark Cuban
writing the checks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
