<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT NOT PAYING OFF FOR POOR TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The purpose of the amateur draft is simple: to give bad teams a
chance to get better. The problem is, it simply doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of baseball's economics is that, as a general rule,
bad teams are bad because they don't have the money to spend on
talent. In other words, they are small-market teams.
</P>
<P>
   These days, that also means they don't have the money to spend
on huge signing bonuses for first-round draft picks. Consequently,
some clubs at the top of the First-Year Player Draft _ which begins
tomorrow _ don't take players according to talent; they take them
according to affordability.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us up there at the top of the draft _ and we've been
up there too many years _ sometimes don't have the ability to pick
the guys we'd like to pick,'' Twins general manager Terry Ryan
said. ``Draft day ought to be an exciting day for the whole
organization. But when you have players you say you can't take
because of the money, I think that's bad for the industry. The bad
clubs ought to get the good players. And that doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It used to happen that way. In 1987, the Mariners chose Ken
Griffey Jr. with the first pick, and signed him for a $160,000
bonus. But last year's top choice, Josh Hamilton, cost Tampa Bay
$3.96 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Major League Baseball summoned scouting directors two
weeks ago for what they called ``negotiating training.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a meeting to remind people that signing bonuses have
been out of control for the last `x' number of years,'' Major
League Baseball executive vice president Sandy Alderson said.
``Given the system we have, there's really no reason for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The system seemingly gives the players little leverage. If they
don't sign, they can't re-enter the draft for another year.
</P>
<P>
   But three years ago, J.D. Drew became a rich man despite the
system. He was drafted by the Phillies with the second overall
selection, but didn't sign. After playing in an independent league
for a year he was back in the draft, and was taken fifth overall by
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Drew had no leverage, the Cardinals gave him a $8.5
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of stories have baseball officials contemplating a
change to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to a point where you'd like to see some kind of salary
scale for younger players, or some kind of restructuring of the
draft to give those lesser clubs or smaller-market clubs some
advantage,'' Rangers GM Doug Melvin said. ``But as the bonuses go
higher, they're all of a sudden losing the advantage the draft had
given them in previous years.''
</P>
<P>
   Even clubs that can afford big bonuses don't always get value
for their money. The Rangers gave 1995 first-round pick Jonathan
Johnson a $1.1 million signing bonus. Mike Lamb, their
seventh-round pick in '97, got $50,000. Johnson remains in the
minors, while Lamb is the starting third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, something's got to be done because there's just too
big of a gap between signing bonuses of players when there's not
that big of a gap between the player talents,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   One solution that has been discussed is an NBA-style salary cap.
But for the present, the small-market teams will have to draft
according to signability instead of talent.
Tim Johnson John Rocker leaves after walking the three batters he
faced in the in the ninth inning last weekend against Houston.
Rocker: from out of control to losing his control The Braves once
had a dominating closer with an outstanding fastball, a guy who
looked like he could rack up 30-save seasons for years to come. But
suddenly, Mark Wohlers couldn't throw strikes. Two years later,
he's attempting a comeback in the low minors with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   History could be repeating itself with John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Tuesday's game against the Cubs with a 5-2 lead in
the ninth, but couldn't finish it. He was pulled after walking two
and giving up a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, he faced the Yankees with an 11-7 lead in the ninth
and loaded the bases, hitting a batter and walking two, before
getting out of the inning, barely, when Shane Spencer flew out to
the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The walks yesterday were the 14th and 15th he has issued in his
past 91/3 innings. He has walked 25 in 171/3 innings this season;
he walked 37 in 721/3 innings last year.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Javy Lopez suggested that the pressure from fans, media
and players because of Rocker's controversial off-season remarks
and subsequent suspension is getting to him.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Leo Mazzone said part of Rocker's problem is
mechanical, and he plans to work with Rocker on keeping his head up
and watching the ball into the catcher's mitt.
</P>
<P>
   But Mazzone conceded the bigger problem is mental. Mazzone has
talked with Rocker about focusing solely on the catcher's mitt and
not allowing fans or opposing players to disturb his focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concentration is the word used in this case,'' Mazzone said.
``I want him to make sure the only thing he sees is the catcher's
target. Closers have a history of going through periods like this,
especially if you're a power guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For the present, Rocker remains the closer. But if he continues
to have trouble throwing strikes, Mike Remlinger or Kerry
Ligtenberg could take over.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops
\Nsubheds:Voice of common sense Hard-headed, greedy owners and
union officials might accomplish something that pitchers seem
unable to do: stop Mark McGwire's pursuit of the career home-run
record. McGwire is threatening to retire if there is a work
stoppage after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a lockout or strike after next year, you won't see
me in uniform as a player ever again,'' McGwire said. ``I will walk
away. I don't care to go through that again. What we did to the
game in 1994 was absolutely horrendous. To do that to the game
again, I would be embarrassed. I would think the other players
think that way. I hope the owners think the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it. There is nothing going wrong with the game of
baseball. The owners are making money. The players are making
money. Listen. This is the greatest game of all time. Look at the
new stadiums. Look at the attendance. The bottom line is, it's
common sense. Life is common sense. But do a lot of people use
common sense? No. That's where the game has been embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is too good for two parties to ruin it.''
\Nsubheds:Weird stat of the week Four triple plays were turned in
the major leagues last year, three in the National League and one
in the American League. There have been four already this season,
including two last week.
</P>
<P>
   The latest came Wednesday, in a matchup between the best pitcher
and best slugger in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was up with the bases loaded and no one out against the
Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson. McGwire hit a fly to shallow center.
Steve Finley threw home to easily nail Placido Polanco. After
making the tag, catcher Damian Miller threw to third to get Edgar
Renteria, who was trying to move up on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of my head, standing on the mound, I was thinking
if I got McGwire to hit into a triple play, I'd be all right,''
Johnson said. ``That was the critical point of the game. I've only
seen those on highlight films.'' \Nsubheds:Something's rotten in
Montreal The only thing that seemingly could save baseball in
Montreal was a new ballpark, which was supposed to be ready for the
2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   However, problems between owner Jeffrey Loria and some of his
partners could spell doom for both the ballpark and the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary plans called for a open-air stadium that would cost
about $200 million. But now, Loria reportedly wants a covered, or
partially covered, stadium that would cost as much as $270 million.
</P>
<P>
   Loria wants his partners to pay the difference, and the partners
are balking.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the first-year owner contend his plan when he
purchased the team was to move it, and this is a way of forcing
that to happen. \Nsubheds:As good as advertised The Red Sox-Yankees
game in New York last Sunday had all the makings of a classic. Two
bitter rivals playing before 55,000 at Yankee Stadium, nationally
televised on ESPN, and with Cy Young Award winners Pedro Martinez
and Roger Clemens on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The game lived up to the hype. Both pitchers took shutouts into
the ninth inning before Boston's Trot Nixon broke up the duel with
a two-out, two-run homer off Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez finished with a four-hit shutout, one walk and nine
strikeouts. Clemens allowed five hits, walked none and struck out
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love baseball, you had to love that game _ both
sides,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said. ``I don't think it
gets any better, especially in this era of the home run. You see
two guys like that out there, full house, national TV ... pretty
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's game-winning homer came eight innings after Clemens
struck him out with a fastball on the outside corner. When Nixon
questioned the call briefly with home-plate umpire Ed Rapuano,
Clemens shouted at Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he wanted to go ahead and let me know it was a
strike,'' Nixon said. ``I guess you could call it a lack of respect
for me. I respect that guy as a pitcher, but that fired me up as
much as anything.''
\Nsubheds:Around the NL Everman High School graduate Ellis Burks
has homered in 35 ballparks after going deep in Pacific Bell Park
on Wednesday. Mark McGwire and Fred McGriff are tied for the
all-time lead with 36 each. Burks has a chance to tie them when the
Giants visit Enron Field in Houston on June 23-25. Reds first
baseman Sean Casey looked like a rising superstar when he hit .332
with 25 homers, 42 doubles and 99 runs batted in last year, his
first full season in the majors. But, entering last night, he's
batting only .230 with two homers and 11 RBI. ``I'm out there
battling, and I'm going to keep battling,'' Casey said. ``I'm going
to have a great season. That's the bottom line. That's the way I
feel. You go through little ruts like this.'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker wasn't happy when Rockies first baseman Todd Helton hit two
homers Monday, including the game-winner in the eighth inning.
``That was the whole idea, not throw him any strikes,'' Dierker
said. ``We couldn't be any more explicit. But we throw it right
down the middle. Twice. It would be one thing if Larry Walker was
hitting behind him. But they don't really have anybody behind
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Helton walked with the bases loaded in the eighth
inning, forcing in the winning run. ``I didn't want to walk him
with the bases loaded, but one run is less than we would've done if
we threw him one down the middle,'' Dierker said. The Phillies felt
good about their chances this season because they had three
pitchers in their starting rotation who were on the All-Star team
last season. But the trio of Curt Schilling, Andy Ashby and Paul
Byrd were a combined 4-14 with a 6.57 earned-run average going into
Schilling's start last night. Dodgers reliever Jeff Shaw, who has a
sore right shoulder, lost his role as closer after allowing three
runs without retiring a batter in a 10-5 loss to the Mets on
Tuesday. Shaw has 11 saves but has blown five chances. He is 2-3
with an ERA of 7.84 and an opponent's batting average of .316.
Manager Davey Johnson said he'll use a committee of Terry Adams,
Mike Fetters and Antonio Osuna until Shaw gets it together. The
Cubs' attempt to improve their existing nucleus by trading for
Ismael Valdes, Eric Young and Damon Buford and signing Ricky
Gutierrez in the off-season didn't work. Instead of a contender,
they have an aging team with a poor record. It's almost time to
blow it up and start over. ``Everybody wants to win, but eventually
this team might have to be restructured,'' manager Don Baylor said.
``We haven't gotten there yet, but you have to think about the
future of this club.'' After striking out 10 batters in 72/3
innings against the Cardinals on Wednesday, Diamondbacks ace Randy
Johnson is on pace to fan 382 batters. The major-league record is
383 by Nolan Ryan in 1973. The NL record is 382 by Sandy Koufax in
'65. Rockies third baseman Jeff Cirillo's average dropped from .371
to below .320 this week, and he blames the slump, in part, on
ongoing discussions about a four-year contract extension. ``It is a
distraction, and it is getting done,'' he said. Now that the Mets'
Mike Hampton is pitching well again, he has become the biggest
double threat in the game. He's batting .321 and hits well enough
that Diamondbacks scouts recently prepared a report on him. ``I
can't remember the last time we spent so much time talking about
how to pitch to the other pitcher,'' Arizona manager Buck Showalter
said.
\Nsubheds:Around the AL Even though the White Sox took two out of
three from Cleveland last weekend to remain in first in the
Central, Indians manager Charlie Manuel was unimpressed. ``Are they
improved? Yeah,'' he said. ``But I think we're the stronger team on
the field.'' Cal Ripken hit his 10th home run of the season on
Tuesday night, the first time the Orioles third baseman has reached
10 homers in May since he had 12 before June 1 in 1991. That was
the year he won his second MVP award. The White Sox averaged 4.3
runs in May after averaging 7.2 runs per game in April. They batted
.304 as a team in April but only .236 in May. ``The league has made
some adjustments to us,'' manager Jerry Manuel said. ``People find
ways to pitch to you. As a young club, you can talk about
adjustments, but we have to make adjustments. We just have to
readjust.'' When Orioles reliever Buddy Groom surrendered a two-run
homer to Fred McGriff in the eighth inning of a 4-3 loss to Tampa
Bay on Wednesday _ the 14th blown save by the bullpen _ it
continued a season of frustration for Mike Mussina. Mussina dropped
his ERA to 3.92 by allowing only two runs in seven innings, but
remains 2-6. The Orioles haven't scored more than five runs in any
of his 12 starts and have scored three or fewer in six of them.
``I've probably pitched well enough to win seven games,'' he said.
``If you really take away my wins and losses, most of my numbers
are identical to last year. One year, I'm 7-2; the other, I'm
2-6.'' With John Valentin out for the season and perhaps his career
because of a catastrophic knee injury, Wilton Veras will get the
bulk of the playing time at third base for the Red Sox. Valentin
was a postseason hero last year, but the Sox have survived without
him in the regular season before. Entering last night, the Sox were
34-19 in the past 53 games started by Veras. Ten Indians have
suffered injuries since May 18, seven of which required trips to
the disabled list. ``That MRI might be a good stock to check out,''
Charlie Manuel said. Tigers reliever Doug Brocail allowed five runs
(four earned) while not retiring a batter in an 8-2 loss to the
Blue Jays last weekend. The next day he pitched 12/3 scoreless
innings and was the winning pitcher in a 4-3 victory. ``That's the
way it goes for those late-inning guys, either the outhouse or the
castle,` manager Phil Garner said. Replied Brocail: ``It's tough to
sleep in the outhouse. I prefer the castle.` David Cone is having a
horrible season. The erstwhile Yankees ace fell to 1-5 with a 6.24
ERA after giving up six earned runs in 31/3 innings against the A's
on Wednesday. Cone's velocity has declined the past few seasons,
but he got by with a good slider and with guile. Even that is
failing him now. ``David couldn't throw a strike,'' catcher Jorge
Posada said. ``He tried everything.'' White Sox starter James
Baldwin improved to 15-1 in domes when he beat the Mariners with
the Safeco Field roof closed Tuesday. ``I can't explain it,'' he
said. Randy Velarde's unassisted triple play against the Yankees on
Monday was only the 10th in a regular-season game in big-league
history, but the second of his career. The A's second baseman once
did it in spring training while playing for the Yankees.
\Nsubheds:The week ahead The first round of interleague play
includes two of the best matchups, with the Mets and Yankees and
Cubs and White Sox playing for bragging rights in their cities. The
Mets play in Yankee Stadium and the Cubs at Comiskey Park next
weekend.
\Nsubheds:The last word ``At first I thought it was one out, then
it was like, `Oh gosh.' That's just great, great. It's something to
be proud of.'' _ Yankees outfielder Shane Spencer after hitting
into an unassisted triple play
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
