<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRAFT-HARRINGTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMDALE'S HARRINGTON HIGHLY PRIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ Sometime early Monday, the news will become
official and Matt Harrington will know for sure he's a soon-to-be
multimillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Most other 18-year-olds, you would figure, would be waiting by
the phone. Not him.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, of Palmdale High, is the No. 1 prospect in Monday's
major-league draft, according to Baseball Weekly, and No. 2 in
Baseball America. He has a 98 mph fastball and an assortment of
breaking pitches that zoom in at various unhittable angles.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes to plan, he'll get that phone call and sign for a
bonus perhaps as large as $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   And precisely because Harrington isn't like most kids, he'll be
in third-period civics class, maybe fourth-period geometry, when
the call comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking forward to this forever, but I have to be in
school,'' Harrington said. ``The truth is, I'm not nervous at all.
I'm excited, I'm anticipating what's going to happen, but I'm not
nervous because there's nothing to be nervous about - it's out of
my control.''
</P>
<P>
   That maturity comes from Harrington's parents, Bill and Sue, who
say all they've ever wanted was for Matt to have as much poise in
real life as he does on the pitching mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say Matt's a very mature person,'' Sue said. ``The
people closest to him mean everything to him. He's always gone out
of his way to be kind and loyal. I think it goes without saying
we're very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, a right-hander, was always a prospect based on his
fastball velocity and the fact he is 6-foot-4. However, injuries
interfered with his performances in 10th and 11th grades, and it
wasn't until this season that he proved utterly dominating.
</P>
<P>
   He led regional large-school pitchers in victories (11-0), ERA
(0.53) and strikeouts (125 in just 65 innings), carrying underdog
Palmdale to the Golden League championship and the second round of
the Division II playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a routine where Matt would pitch every Friday and I
always knew we were going to win the game,'' coach Lance Pierson
said. ``As a coach, that was a very comforting feeling having Matt
Harrington on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   There were instances, Pierson admits, when he genuinely felt
sorry for opposing hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must have been 15 times this season when guys went up
there against Matt and simply took three straight called strikes,''
Pierson said. ``They just shrugged and walked back to the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Highland, Palmdale's main rival, went 0-2 against Harrington,
averaging two runs against him and almost 10 runs against its other
25 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Harrington was a guaranteed win for them,'' Highland
coach Mike Van Cheri said. ``He just outclassed everybody. When
you've got the kind of stuff Matt Harrington has, you overmatch any
high school team. I've been coaching 15 years and he's absolutely
the best I've ever seen, no doubt about it. He's just leaps and
bounds ahead of everyone else and this year he just matured so much
on the mound. You couldn't rattle him. I really hope he's the No. 1
pick in the draft. He's earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Pierson is taking the day off to be with Harrington's
family when that phone call comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Matt's always been just Matt,'' Pierson said. ``But the
other day I got the new issue of Baseball America in the mail, and
there he was on the cover. That's when it really hit me for the
first time, how special he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Harrington says he'll never forget this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some games, it just felt like I was untouchable out there,
that I was throwing the ball right by every guy in the lineup,'' he
said. ``But even the times when I wasn't doing as well, I just
tried to go out there with that same attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a confident young man, but he feels no sense of
entitlement. He knows the road to the majors is long and filled
with curves, even for a bonus baby with commas in his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Is he really planning on waiting all the way until school's over
Monday before finding out what happened?
</P>
<P>
   He smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well ... my last class is baseball. Since the season's already
over, maybe I will go home just a little bit early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
