<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS: PRESSURE ON L.A., NOT US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They're enjoying all this, make no mistake. This
back-from-death's-door routine, this new-life-from-the-darkness
bit.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the Trail Blazers have risen to push the Lakers to
this unexpected edge, Portland is curious how L.A. will react to
now being the one at death's door.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, and maybe even eager. The Blazers can't help wondering,
even thinking, the Lakers might not handle the pressure as well as
they did in winning the last two games to force a decisive Game 7
in their Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they're a little bit of a fragile team,'' Blazers
forward Scottie Pippen said. ``They don't have the experience. They
don't truly believe in the triangle system. They've already talked
(about it). Once you catch guys like that, you tend to think things
are working in your favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Only six teams in NBA history have come back after trailing 3-1
in a best-of-seven series, and the Blazers believe they are now
poised to make it seven. And just maybe, the Lakers are starting to
feel the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the team that's had to win the last couple of games,''
Blazers forward Bonzi Wells said. ``Now we want to see how they
take the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers first stayed alive when they won their second
consecutive at Staples Center in Game 5 and then forced a final
game with their fairly easy 103-93 victory Friday in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last two games we came out aggressive, took it right to
them and really never gave them a chance to get going on either end
of the floor,'' Portland guard Damon Stoudamire said. ``It will be
interesting to see how they respond, especially on their home
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen maintains the truth is the Blazers weren't really the
team under all that pressure - despite Lakers coach Phil Jackson's
comment the 3-1 deficit put them at death's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been under pressure,'' Pippen said. ``We've been in
the best position we could have been in. There's no pressure when
you're down 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is when you're up 3-1, trying to close a team
out. We're in a great position. We're in a position to beat this
team three times in a row. And we're up for the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who coached Pippen to six NBA titles while with the
Bulls, had been playing mind games with the shooting forward all
series. Jackson said it was up to Pippen to lead the Blazers and
said he should have been suspended for throwing a forearm at John
Salley's head in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Jackson was declaring the Lakers had to stop Pippen's
penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of it has come as a surprise to Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Phil has already told them, the only way you're going
to beat this team is to cut their heads off,'' Pippen said. ``They
feel like I'm the head, and they need to cut me off. That's his
philosophy and that's just how he's telling them to go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've tried it all series, and it hasn't worked. I'm sure
tomorrow they're going to try and come out and complete their
mission. But my mindset is just to go out and stay focused on what
I have to do in the game and allow the officials to take care of
all the rest of the stuff going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy would rather the Blazers didn't
concern themselves with anything the Lakers are feeling or even
consider they have an edge from already surviving two elimination
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think about it,'' he said. ``Don't worry about it.
That's not our problem. Our problem is staying alive tomorrow and
playing our game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get caught up in any other type of feelings but the
ones we've had these last two ballgames, with the same kind of
mindset, the same kind of determination.''
</P>
<P>
   The past two games, the Blazers have played like a team that has
figured the Lakers out. Their post players are killing the Lakers,
their outside shooters are hitting, their pick-and-roll with center
Arvydas Sabonis keeps burning Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, they've collapsed well on O'Neal and forced the
Lakers into an outside shooting game that has mostly failed.
</P>
<P>
   And they're promising to come aggressively again today.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, you don't want to come in and wait for their
punches,'' Blazer Steve Smith said. ``You want to come out throwing
punches. Like a boxing match, you'd rather throw punches and maybe
run out of gas instead of waiting and waiting, and then maybe it's
too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
