<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS SAVOR TITLE, BUT BEST SETS SIGHTS ON LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was only one problem when Travis Best was asked
about the upcoming NBA Finals and started talking about boyhood
memories of Larry Bird against the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers aren't facing Bird's Indiana Pacers just yet.
</P>
<P>
   While most of his Pacers teammates were measured in their
predictions Friday after winning the Eastern Conference title over
the New York Knicks, Best said he had no doubt they will face the
Lakers in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the thought reminded him of his youth in
Springfield, Mass., watching the NBA's top two teams, Bird's Boston
Celtics and the Lakers of Magic Johnson and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the way Shaq is playing, with the way Kobe is playing and
the guys around them, that is the challenge,'' said Best, Indiana's
point guard. ``Not taking anything away from Portland. But if
you're going to win the championship, why not go through the best
team.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the league's best regular-season record, the Lakers
lost their Game 6 to the Trail Blazers and have blown a
three-games-to-one lead in the Western Conference finals. Game 7 is
this afternoon at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   For now, only the Pacers can celebrate. The postgame lockerroom
after Friday's 93-80 victory over the Knicks was bedlam. Indiana
never has been to the Finals, falling short several times despite
often-heroic efforts by veteran Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit has been given to Bird, who says he will step
down as coach despite a 147-67 record in three seasons on the job.
Bird won three NBA titles as a player and was the league's MVP for
three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But after a quiet series against the Knicks, Miller took over
the spotlight Friday night, scoring 17 of his game-high 34 points
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who refused to bite on the thought of a Pacers/Lakers
final despite growing up in Southern California and attending UCLA,
has played some of his greatest games in Madison Square Garden. But
his best work Friday might have been a pregame pep talk to his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell by the look in his eyes before the game and
what he said, that he was going to be on,'' teammate Dale Davis
said. ``I definitely thought that he wasn't going to be denied.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lakers-Pacers?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time to reflect on what we've done,'' Davis said.
``We'll have plenty of time to think about that in the days ahead.
There are a lot of guys who have been here a long time and known a
lot of pain. This is a proud moment for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   A Lakers/Indiana matchup also would be of interest because
former Laker Sam Perkins now plays for the Pacers. Mark Jackson
also played one season in Los Angeles, although he did it with the
Clippers and left after demanding a trade.
</P>
<P>
   But Lakers-Pacers?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make a difference,'' Jackson said. ``Either way it
is going to be a war.''
</P>
<P>
   That left Best to lend a Bird/Lakers showdown some historical
perspective and show that players can be fans, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember those games like they were yesterday,'' said Best,
who is in his fifth season from Georgia Tech. ``Those games were
intense. Everyone would get on the couch, and you couldn't help but
keep a ball in your hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Celtics were huge in Springfield, but they were only my
third favorite team. Larry was everything, but my favorite teams
were Philly and the Lakers. James Worthy? That was my guy. And
Magic? Every game was so hard. Larry has brought that to this team.
It is going to be an incredible series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0210 </DOCNO>
