<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEWITT-60MINUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`60 MINUTES' PRODUCER AIMS BITTER BLAST AT EX-COLLEAGUE
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The simmering five-year debate over the way ``60
Minutes'' handled a controversial report about the tobacco industry
heated up again on Saturday as the show's executive producer
attacked Lowell Bergman, a former ``60 Minutes'' producer and
longtime investigative reporter, in a speech to more than 1,000
journalists in New York. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt, the executive producer, said that Bergman should not
be allowed ``within a hundred miles of a newsroom.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hewitt opened the floor to questions, supporters of Bergman
responded angrily to Hewitt's comments, sparking a spirited debate
that continued after the speech. Matters came to a head when David
Fanning, a friend of Bergman, confronted Hewitt and Mike Wallace,
the ``60 Minutes'' correspondent, as a thick crowd knotted around
the men.
</P>
<P>
   Fanning argued that Bergman should have been given a chance to
respond to Hewitt's comments, especially since they came at the
annual meeting of Investigative Reporters and Editors, an
organization to which Bergman has belonged essentially since its
inception in 1975. After several minutes of debate, Wallace and
Hewitt broke off from Fanning and left.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt's criticism stems from the way he and Wallace were
portrayed in ``The Insider,'' a 1999 movie about the way the CBS
program handled the report on the tobacco industry in 1995. Bergman
consulted on the film, which cast him as a principled reporter who
eventually quit his job over CBS's handling of the report, while
portraying Hewitt as more concerned with CBS's stock price than the
truth. Bergman has been a respected investigative reporter for a
generation, and is a contract freelancer and consultant for The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy highlights the potential for corporate
censorship in journalism at a time when a handful of major media
companies control much of what is seen and heard by consumers, as
well as the responsibility that reporters have when Hollywood
fictionalizes their stories.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, Hewitt said that
``The Insider'' portrayed him dishonestly and that Bergman had a
responsibility to make sure that the story the movie told was
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt said he had stood up to his bosses at CBS for the report,
and that it would only have been broadcast in the form Bergman
preferred if Hewitt and Wallace had hired ``a band of guerrillas''
to take over a CBS television station and broadcast the report
themselves. By turning himself into a hero and portraying Hewitt as
a toady, Bergman lied, destroying his credibility as a journalist,
Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home in Berkeley, Calif., Bergman said he did not
have control of ``The Insider,'' but he said he believed Hewitt had
``gotten off lightly'' in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman said he believed self-censorship and advertiser pressure
on television news is a serious and growing problem, but said that
fact did not excuse Hewitt's actions on the tobacco industry
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he couldn't have'' gotten the story to run, Bergman said
of Hewitt, but ``he didn't try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
