<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT FIELD FOR DODGERS, ANGELS MIGHTY FINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ I whiled away the early innings of a quiet
Saturday-afternoon cross-towner at Edison Field playing Jimmy the
Greek with the lineups.
</P>
<P>
   I penciled check marks on the Los Angeles Dodgers' half of the
scorecard next to the positions where they have the edge - second
base, shortstop, right field, catcher, bench and starting pitching
- and on the Anaheim Angels' side where they're stronger - first,
third, center, bullpen and team speed. A small check for
``intangibles'' went to the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Left field became a very pleasant problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield or Darin Erstad? Darin Erstad or Gary Sheffield?
Which would you rather have? Could you go wrong either way?
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-area teams haven't enjoyed two players this good
at the same position at the same time since Rod Carew of the Angels
and Steve Garvey of the Dodgers were holding down first base jobs
circa 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'd get much argument from whoever picked
second,'' said Angels manager Mike Scioscia, imagining a two-player
draft. ``The answer is that Erstad is the perfect fit for this
club, and Sheffield is the perfect fit for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need Sheffield in the middle of the lineup. I need Erstad
at the top of the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, their dissimilar skills were displayed for 34,580 fans
at the season's second clash of the Dodgers and Angels, and
Sheffield got the edge.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his 16th and 17th home runs, driving in four runs, and
added a sharp single and run scored as the Dodgers beat Brian
Cooper and the Angels 8-3. Erstad settled for three singles and an
RBI in five at-bats, raising his American League-leading average to
.377.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield pulled a shoulder-high fastball into the left-field
foul pole to make it 3-0 before Cooper retired a batter, and drove
a hanger 425 feet to straightaway left to make it 5-0 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who doesn't have Sheffield's power, showed his speed,
collecting his third hit by beating out a bouncer to first baseman
Eric Karros in the eighth inning. When's the last time you saw a
leg single to first?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, baseball players at the same position never actually
duel. Hitters and pitchers duel.
</P>
<P>
   One left fielder might watch the other with slightly keener
interest. But it's unlikely Sheffield and Erstad have even thought
about how special it is to have players of such class sharing a
corner of the local ballfields.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to fans - and daydreaming club officials - to think
about which they'd choose.
</P>
<P>
   Angels officials make the case that Erstad is younger (he turns
26 today), is more versatile (Scioscia bats him leadoff but could
as easily slot him third), and is too intense to let down when the
rest of the team is going flat.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Sheffield (32) is any less of a gamer. He plays hurt,
as he did during the Florida Marlins' World Series championship run
in 1997, Sheffield's only sub-.300 season in the past five, and
when he's healthy he's the kind of big hitter who'll carry a team.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't healthy Saturday and he carried a team anyway.
Sheffield sprained his right ankle for the third time this season
with an awkward slide at Dodger Stadium on May 22 and still feels
the effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not near 100 percent,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``But I'll take him however he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield said he was sore after going 2 for 5 - matching Erstad
swing for swing - in the Angels' 12-5 victory Friday night. So he
switched to rubber spikes Saturday. Improvement noted.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of the way through the season, he's on a pace
for 50-plus homers and 140 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in the middle of the lineup have to pick it up a
notch with some guys (injured),'' Sheffield said. ``We have to make
a difference in the ballgame every time we come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield made a difference in the second interleague game of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And, for now, it's the difference between two outstanding left
fielders brought together in time and space. Saturday the edge went
to Sheffield. But I'll be checking again today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
