<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NY     06-03 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT TAMPA, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is amazing, Al Leiter said after his last start, the way one
bad pitch can turn a good game into a bad one. That day, his bad
pitch turned into a grand slam by the Dodgers' Shawn Green, and the
Mets lost for the first time this season with Leiter pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter made several bad pitches against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
Saturday night, but none of them hurt. He allowed five walks, his
most in any start since last August, and the Devil Rays had a
runner in scoring position in five of his seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter was tough when it mattered most, and he shut out the
Devil Rays for six and two-thirds innings on the way to a 1-0
victory. Dennis Cook, John Franco and Armando Benitez preserved the
shutout as the Mets won for the 11th time in their last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays were hitless in six at-bats against Leiter with
runners in scoring position; three times, he retired the former
All-Star Vinny Castilla to end an inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Leiter allowed a single to pitcher Steve
Trachsel, the leadoff hitter. After two outs, he walked Greg Vaughn
for the fourth time, this time on four pitches, and Cook came in to
retire Fred McGriff on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter allowed only four hits _ all singles _ and had eight
strikeouts. He improved his record to 6-1 and his earned run
average to 3.23.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel, meanwhile, continued a quirky trend by pitching
heroically against a top starter. The right-hander has beaten some
of the American League's best pitchers _ Pedro Martinez, Orlando
Hernandez and Brad Radke _ but entered the game with a 3-5 record
and a 5.54 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Leiter, whose first nine starts were Mets victories,
Trachsel was stingy, allowing only six hits over seven innings.
After giving up a leadoff double to Matt Franco in the third _
Franco's first extra-base hit of the year _ Trachsel left him
stranded, striking out Leiter, who was trying to bunt, retiring
Melvin Mora on a flyout and freezing Derek Bell on a third-strike
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel did his job again in the fourth, but Vaughn didn't do
his. After permitting a leadoff double to Edgardo Alfonzo, Trachsel
got two ground-ball outs. Then Todd Zeile lofted a high pop to
left. With a slight wind blowing, Vaughn tried in vain to follow
the ball's flight, roaming around the warning track before seeing
the ball skim off the wall. Zeile got a double and the Mets had a
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game was the Mets' 55th; after 55 games last
year, General Manager Steve Phillips fired three coaches, and Bobby
Valentine suggested he should no longer be the manager if the team
did not improve over the next 55. The team did improve, of course,
and Valentine stayed.
</P>
<P>
   In their 55th game last season, the Mets' lineup included only
three players who are currently active with the club. Rickey
Henderson and John Olerud now play for Seattle, Roger Cedeno for
Houston and a trimmer Bobby Bonilla for Atlanta. Brian McRae is
retired and shortstop Rey Ordonez is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's team was 27-28 after 55 games; this year's team is
31-24. Valentine brushes off comparisons, believing them unfair to
players and, probably, irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But this team is playing better, and there is more stability in
the starting rotation, with four of the Mets' five starters turning
in solid performances with relative consistency. The bullpen has
not been dominant, but it is again a strength. The lineup and bench
are works in progress. Valentine is constantly tweaking with the
parts Phillips gives him.
</P>
<P>
   Mora has batted leadoff in all four games since returning from
the disabled list, but Valentine has not committed to any leadoff
man since the release of Henderson in mid-May. He said Saturday
that he used the process of elimination based on who else was
playing; the only two players on the roster he has used there on
consecutive days are Mora and Joe McEwing.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Ordonez, the Mets essentially have five
everyday players and three positions where the starters can change
daily, which can sometimes be confusing. The nameplates in the
lineup posted in the clubhouse do not include positions, and when
Matt Franco saw his name in the lineup Saturday afternoon, he was
not sure where he was playing _ it was left field, his first start
there this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been carried by a few players _ Mike Piazza and
Alfonzo most prominent among them _ and the bench could become a
concern if it continues to struggle. Darryl Hamilton, the starting
center fielder, and Ordonez are not expected back until around the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips shook up the mix this weekend by adding the left-handed
hitters Lenny Harris, who joined the team Saturday, and Ryan
McGuire, and designating for assignment Jon Nunnally, who had 26
strikeouts in 74 at-bats. Catcher Vance Wilson was optioned to
Norfolk to make room for Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a contact guy, not a high-walk guy, but he puts it in
play,'' Phillips said of Harris, acquired from Arizona for Bill
Pulsipher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
