<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT STARS, 2-1. 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Devils were a good road team in the first three
rounds of these Stanley Cup playoffs and they continued the trend
Saturday night in Game 3 of finals against the Dallas Stars. After
splitting the first two games back home at Continental Arena, the
Devils took a 2-1 victory over the defending champions Saturday
night on the slushy ice of Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the best game so far in the series, and it improved the
Devils' road record to 8-2 in the postseason. Leading by two games
to one in the four-of-seven-game final round, which resumes here on
Monday night, the Devils are two games away from winning their
second Stanley Cup championship. They won their first in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The game began at a fast pace, with both teams aggressively
pushing the tempo. The first period, which ended in a 1-1 tie, was
the best yet in this series. Scoring for Dallas on the power play
was Sylvain Cote. Scoring at even strength for the Devils was Jason
Arnott.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was just as intense, with little of the slow
and cautious strategy that marked the second game, a 2-1 Dallas
victory on Thursday night. The Devils got the only goal of the
period when Petr Sykora scored on the power play and gave his team
a 2-1 lead going into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Cote scored after intercepting a clearing pass by Scott Stevens,
the Devils' defenseman, who tried to move the puck out of danger
after goalie Martin Brodeur had made a save on Jere Lehtinen.
Brodeur was pulled to the right and Stevens was over him when Cote
sent the puck into the open net from the right-wing circle at 13
minutes 8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   That power play was the first of three consecutive penalties
against the Devils, two of which overlapped by 49 seconds. The
Devils killed off that two-man advantage and got the equalizer at
18:06 when Arnott broke clear, took a pass, split the defense, beat
goalie Eddie Belfour with a low shot and fell in celebration. Brian
Rafalski and Colin White got the assists.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden, the Devils' penalty killer, was asked in a
television interview at intermission if the special-teams
performance had inspired the Devils. ``I think so,'' he said. ``We
killed off a five-on-three situation. They had the momentum
going.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of action aside from the goals. The Devils'
Randy McKay sent Joe Nieuwendyk into the boards with a check that
left Nieuwendyk slow to get off the ice. Claude Lemieux of the
Devils, penalized for slashing earlier, took advantage of a shove
from Dallas defenseman Darryl Sydor to fall over Belfour while
charging the net for a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:27 of the second period, Sykora scored after taking a long
slap shot from the left side, near the blue line. The puck may have
deflected off the stick of Dallas defenseman Derian Hatcher before
it glanced off Belfour's glove and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, much was made of the ice conditions. Late in
periods, the surface tends to get mushy and chippy here,
particularly in June with its high temperatures. Because the Stars
play here regularly and the Devils visited only once during the
regular season, this was thought to be an advantage for the home
team.
</P>
<P>
   Devils Coach Larry Robinson was not one to use that as a
preconceived explanation for whatever was to transpire later. When
asked how the ice was after Saturday morning's practice, he said:
``Ice is fine. It is frozen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
