<SLUG> BC-TRASH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'VE GOT WAY TOO MUCH STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Richard Buffington knows he has too much stuff. It's
piled in the two-car garage, the storage roomand the spare bedrooms
of the ranch house he and his wife have shared for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Seems his neighbors have the same problem. Recently, he put
castoffs on the curb that were too big for the trash can _ and the
pile grew.
</P>
<P>
   `Someone else put their stuff there,` said Buffington, 66, a
retired dentist, looking over the mound. `See that light fixture?
And there was even some kind of toy. That's not even ours.`
</P>
<P>
   Like Buffington's heap, the evidence is mounting: We have too
much stuff.
</P>
<P>
   In this booming economy, we are buying and replacing and
throwing away like never before. Nationally, people bought 40
percent more stuff _ cars, armchairs, toasters and computers _ last
year than four years ago,the U.S. Department of Commerce says.
</P>
<P>
   And in this Phoenix area of few basements and fewer attics, we
must confront our stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill donations are up 40 percent nationally in the past five
years. At least half of all new homes built in the Phoenix area
have three-car garages, while most people only have two cars.
Storage companies boast of doubling business in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   You can even buy more stuff _ books, even a new magazine _
telling you how to get rid of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But the most obvious sign of our overstuffed society may be our
own front yards. Simply look at the curbs on the day the city hauls
away bulk trash. Note the ugly sofa Goodwill won't take, the old
swamp cooler and the patio chairs Dad meant to fix.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix collectors picked up 90,000 tons of it, including the
usual palm fronds and lawn clippings, last year. That's a 50
percent increase from eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   `We've just got a lot of stuff,` says Dean Schwindt, operations
manager for Waste Management Inc., which picks up trash in north
Phoenix. `We see everything including the kitchen sink.`
</P>
<P>
   During the quarterly bulk trash pickup, going on now in Phoenix,
once-tidy neighborhoods turn junky. Everything that can be hidden,
squirreled away in a back closet, pushed to the back of the garage
or crammed into the shed is put in plain view. You can see a toilet
sitting in front of your neighbor's house. It's like showing your
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   A tan couch sits outside a brick bungalow in central Phoenix.
Beside it are twin mattresses, a busted playpen and a baby swing.
</P>
<P>
   David Hovorak, 19, is sweeping the patio outside the home,
finishing the cleanup. He surveys the pile, a little bigger than a
van.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm just glad it's not in the house,` he says.
</P>
<P>
   This is the stuff that even the Salvation Army doesn't want. But
more and more, it's dropped off anyway.
</P>
<P>
   `Someone will give us an old chair, and we can't take it. We
don't have time to upholster it,` says Maj. Barry Lucas of the
Salvation Army, who adds that donations are up 5 percent over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   `They'll say, `You can give it to a homeless person.' But whose
doorstep will it go on? You can't put it under a tree.`
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army spends about $10,000 a month getting rid of
unusable goods.
</P>
<P>
   But even as we crave simplicity, we make room for more. Many
times, stuff put out on the curb is picked through before it gets
to the landfill. Neighbors bet each other on how long it will take
for someone to take a broken ceiling fan or console television.
</P>
<P>
   `Aluminum chairs, they go fast,` Buffington says, adding that
even he, trying to streamline his own stuff, has eyed neighborhood
castoffs.
</P>
<P>
   `Like one time there were some nice couches on our street. I
wanted to put on a mask and go get them,` he says. `But my wife
wouldn't let me.`
</P>
<P>
   In the neighborhoods near Central and Glendale avenues, sidewalk
shoppers nicknamed city goats prowl through the stuff, picking and
hauling away lamps, bikes or furniture before the city picks them
up.
</P>
<P>
   The city says the stuff still belongs to the property owners, so
people should ask before taking.
</P>
<P>
   `But it is outside, it is trash,'' says Brian Yingling,
solid-waste foreman for Phoenix. He does tell his crews not to take
anything, though. `We don't want anyone to misconstrue what we're
doing,` he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Cejas, who helps pick up the bulk trash for Phoenix, says
not to worry. Stuff is picked through as soon as it's put out.
</P>
<P>
   `By the time we get here, everything good has been hauled
away,`Cejas said. `They leave us the bad stuff.` &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Laura.Trujillo(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8891. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
