<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-PHILLIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX COME UP EMPTY IN PHILADELPHIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Just a week ago, the Red Sox were making their
case that with Pedro Martinez, they feared no team, including the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Without Martinez, scratched from his start Saturday night
because of a sore muscle in his side, the Sox have lately been
propagating the notion they're no match for any team, including the
Phillies, who own the second-worst record in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who were 12 games over .500 May 19, were clobbered by
the Phillies, 9-3, which assured them of losing a series for the
fourth time in their last five sets. They've lost two out of the
three to the Tigers, Blue Jays, and Royals, and dropped their
second straight to Philadelphia in another of those interleague
exercises detested by manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, who outhit the Sox, 10-3, were not ashamed to
admit they were happy to have dodged Martinez, who was not around
to put an end to a Sox losing streak that stands at four games,
matching their longest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro's the best pitcher in the world,'' said Phillies second
baseman Alex Arias, who messed with the Sox' travel plans from the
outset with a winning, 11th-inning pinch hit Friday night off John
Wasdin, who was shipped to Pawtucket the next afternoon. ``Any time
you don't have to face him, it's a good feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys you probably don't even watch the
video, because you've seen him so much on SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   By night's end, the Sox were still in first place, tied with the
Bombers, the only team they've beaten in a series the last two
weeks, but the record (29-22) was now just seven games above the
break-even point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a well-pitched game, we need a clean game, get some
guys in scoring position and get some hits,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Those elements were absent Saturdy night. Tim Wakefield, the
knuckleballer working on a day's rest, would have been better off
staying in bed than in Veterans Stadium, where the Phillies
celebrated their liberation from Martinez by exploiting every quirk
in Wakefield's unpredictable repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies scored one run on an error by rookie third baseman
Wilton Veras, two more after a botched pitchout and a third-strike
passed ball, one on a home run by catcher Mike Lieberthal, another
on a sacrifice fly, and one more on a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I gave up only two hard-hit balls all night,'' said
Wakefield, who was taking the bullet for an overworked bullpen.
``The home run and the line drive by the pitcher (Randy Wolf). I
felt strong. I could have pitched some more, but the results didn't
dictate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Veras allowed Lieberthal's slow roller to pass through his legs
undisturbed in the first, the rookie's team-leading ninth error in
33 games and second costly miscue since John Valentin's
season-ending knee injury. It was the start of a dreadful night for
Veras, who went 0 for 4 and whiffed thrice, the last time on three
pitches in the eighth inning, when the Sox had scored once and
still had two men on base.
</P>
<P>
   Is the kid feeling the pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' Williams said. ``Not for me. I think he's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies put the game out of reach in the eighth inning,
when Lieberthal crushed a three-run home run off Rob Stanifer, the
reliever recalled Saturday from Pawtucket in place of Wasdin, who
apparently left his ``Way Back'' nickname behind. The home run was
the second of the game for Lieberthal, who drove in five runs, or
two more than Sox catcher Jason Varitek has knocked in since May 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not hitting at the right time, we're not pitching at the
right time,'' said Varitek, who was charged with two passed balls,
saw his throw go wide right on the pitchout attempt, and struck out
twice and popped out, leaving four runners on base. ``We were in a
situation where we had chances today, and I was one who didn't
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, who has 23 RBIs in his last 17 games, drove in two
runs. Nomar Garciaparra, who has 12 hits in 17 at-bats in his last
five games, knocked in the other with the 100th home run of his
career. Mike Stanley, who flied out twice and just missed a
three-run home run in the eighth when his drive down the left-field
line went foul, was the only other Sox starter to hit the ball out
of the infield. The Sox went down on strikes 11 times against the
lefthanded Wolf (9 whiffs) and reliever Chris Brock.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' frustration revealed itself on the final out. Darren
Lewis, who went hitless in five at-bats out of the leadoff hole,
flung his helmet at the feet of first base umpire Jim Joyce after
being called out on a borderline play. Joyce instantly ejected
Lewis, who had to be kept from the umpire by first base coach Tommy
Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game can turn this around real quick,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   For it to be quick, it will have to come from someone other than
Pedro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-00 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000603.0223 </DOCNO>
