<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4047 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-03 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ANOTHER LIFE: A Memoir of Other People &LR;  By Michael Korda.
Delta, $14.95. A perpetually optimistic book editor recalls his
many years at Simon &AMP; Schuster and his encounters with nearly
everybody who is anybody, from Richard Nixon to Joan Crawford.
``Korda's tone of voice is affectionate and urbane, his manner that
of the accomplished raconteur who never spoils the story with a
heavy-handed moral,'' Lewis Lapham wrote in The New York Times Book
Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAYOVER &LR;  By Lisa Zeidner. Perennial, $13. Claire Newbold is a
successful middle-aged saleswoman who, after the death of her
3-year-old son and her husband's infidelity, simply refuses to go
home one day. Instead, she embarks on an odyssey of lust,
seduction, forbidden desire and furtive hotel hopping. ``The novel
rocks with a lot of great, sexy scenes, in which Zeidner's fine
writing is on glorious display,'' Karen Karbo wrote in The New York
Times Book Review in 1999. ``With `Layover,' Zeidner joins the
ranks of Doris Lessing, Margaret Atwood and Fay Weldon, all of whom
have written in the women-spiraling-into-madness genre.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEVIL TAKE THE HINDMOST: A History of Financial Speculation &LR;  By
Edward Chancellor. Plume, $13.95. The author employs ballads,
newspaper articles and gossip in this tour of speculative manias, a
long trail of wild dreams, burst bubbles and lost fortunes
stretching back to the 17th century. Last year the reviewer Adam
Smith praised the book's ``admirable scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIPPING THE VELVET &LR;  By Sarah Waters. Riverhead, $13.95. The
heroine of this erotic first novel is a wide-eyed girl who falls
for a music-hall actress in late Victorian England. This
infatuation leads to heartbreak and a harrowing (if ultimately
redeemed) life as a cross-dresser and kept woman in the back alleys
and elegant homes of London. ``If lesbian fiction is to reach a
wider readership ... Waters is just the person to carry the
banner,'' Miranda Seymour wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY PILGRIM'S PROGRESS: Media Studies, 1950-1998 &LR;  By George W.S.
Trow. Vintage, $13. This book-length essay is not so much about
media as it is a social history of the decline of patrician New
York and the loss of authority once wielded by traditionally
civilized people like the author. Trow is ``an inspired close
reader of all the stuff we gloss, graze and glance at,'' Gerald
Marzorati wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SEA CAME IN AT MIDNIGHT &LR;  By Steve Erickson. Perennial, $14.
This apocalyptic novel revolves around a girl with a twisted past
who hooks up with an obsessive millennial freak; other plot lines
involve a creator of improbable maps and an illicit trade in time
capsules. ``The various stories mesh together at the level of
verbal echo and poetic metaphor,'' Geoff Nicholson wrote last year.
``Erickson also writes brilliantly sentence by sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LADIES FROM ST. PETERSBURG: Three Novellas &LR;  By Nina
Berberova. New Directions, $12.95. This posthumous collection
revolves around themes of flight and exile from Mother Russia, and
is steeped in an unromantic view of the author's homeland. In 1998
the reviewer Ken Kalfus admired ``the lucidity of ... Berberova's
prose and the deftness of her characterizations.''
</P>
<P>
   New Directions has also reissued  &UR; THE BLUE LANTERN: And Other
Stories &LR; , by Victor Pelevin ($12.95), in which irony, dark humor
and existential musings are given free rein in the strange
landscape of post-Soviet Russia. Pelevin continues to ``gnaw at our
confidence in conventional reality, like a dog worrying a bone,''
Kalfus wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROME AND A VILLA &LR;  By Eleanor Clark. Steerforth Italia, $18.
This series of rapturous sketches of postwar Rome and its people,
originally published in 1952 and updated in 1974, displays Clark's
``genius for attention, observation and recording'' and ``a true
sense and love of the grand, the tragic, the beautiful,'' Katherine
Anne Porter wrote in The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE MIRACLE OF CASTEL DI SANGRO &LR; , by Joe McGinniss
(Broadway, $14.95), the author of ``Fatal Vision'' travels to a
remote Italian village to chronicle the efforts of the local soccer
team to recreate its Cinderella season of a year earlier. The
result is ``an engaging tale well worth telling, rich in comic
incidents, delightful characters and dramatic surprises,'' Bill
Barich wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDNIGHTS: A Year With the Wellfleet Police &LR;  By Alec Wilkinson.
Ruminator, $14. At the age of 23, the author spent a year as a
rookie policeman on the nine-man force in a small town on Cape Cod.
His account of the trials and tedium of life in uniform ``enchants
the reader into caring about the subject and wanting to read on,''
Peter Benchley wrote in 1982. ``His perceptions of and compassion
for his fellow officers are profound.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAST OF THE MOUNTAINS &LR;  By David Guterson. Harvest/Harcourt,
$14. A Seattle heart doctor who is dying of cancer sets out for the
high deserts and canyons of eastern Washington with his two dogs to
commit suicide. ``When Guterson is at his best, the story and the
landscape nearly become one,'' Robert Sullivan wrote in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
